WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.720
[Amit Varma]: When I started the Scene and the Unseen four years ago, I could not have imagined what

00:00:09.720 --> 00:00:14.080
[Amit Varma]: the show would become. At that time, I thought I will do 20 minute episodes on the unintended

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:19.520
[Amit Varma]: consequences of public policy. Today, this is a show that features long form conversations,

00:00:19.520 --> 00:00:24.140
[Amit Varma]: sometimes longer than three hours on subjects that range from politics to history to economics

00:00:24.140 --> 00:00:28.960
[Amit Varma]: to society and culture. And along the way, I discovered truths about the nature of audio

00:00:28.960 --> 00:00:34.600
[Amit Varma]: and the power of podcasting that ran contrary to what I had earlier believed. Also, I built

00:00:34.600 --> 00:00:39.360
[Amit Varma]: a listenership that was far more engaged and that cared more about what I was putting out

00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:45.120
[Amit Varma]: than any readership I could have imagined as a writer. We are 200 episodes old today.

00:00:45.120 --> 00:00:53.080
[Amit Varma]: What a journey it's been. Maybe it's time to sit back for a moment and take stock.

00:00:53.080 --> 00:00:59.040
[Unknown]: Welcome to the Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:05.200
[Amit Varma]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:05.200 --> 00:01:09.040
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the Scene and the Unseen. In fact, welcome to episode 200 of the Scene and the

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:15.240
[Amit Varma]: Unseen. This is a special episode for me for a number of reasons. One, 200 is a nice round

00:01:15.240 --> 00:01:20.280
[Amit Varma]: number and it feels appropriate to celebrate it in a way that one won't celebrate, say,

00:01:20.280 --> 00:01:26.160
[Amit Varma]: episode 196 or episode 203. But still, it's nice to have these milestones that allow you

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:32.200
[Amit Varma]: to celebrate or to take stock. Two, I'm using this episode to launch the Scene and the Unseen

00:01:32.200 --> 00:01:37.000
[Amit Varma]: books. Along with the publishers Westland, I'm bringing out a four-volume anthology of

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:41.760
[Amit Varma]: the Scene and the Unseen with curated excerpts from the 200 episodes of the Scene and the

00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:46.760
[Amit Varma]: Unseen so far. These four volumes, which will be out early next year, will be divided across

00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:53.880
[Amit Varma]: the themes of politics, history, economics, and society and culture. Three, I'm also launching

00:01:53.880 --> 00:01:58.520
[Amit Varma]: the Scene and the Unseen merchandise, beginning with designer mugs that you can browse at

00:01:58.520 --> 00:02:04.560
[Amit Varma]: sceneunseen.in slash stuff. And four, my good friend and frequent guest, economist Shruti

00:02:04.560 --> 00:02:09.840
[Amit Varma]: Rajagopalan has put together a special episode in which she got 22 guests and fans of the

00:02:09.840 --> 00:02:15.600
[Amit Varma]: show to ask me questions. So the tables have turned and I'm in the firing line. We ended

00:02:15.600 --> 00:02:20.280
[Amit Varma]: up recording a five-hour conversation and I consider splitting it up into two episodes.

00:02:20.280 --> 00:02:25.840
[Amit Varma]: But then I figured that me talking about myself felt a little bit self-indulgent. So it was

00:02:25.840 --> 00:02:31.520
[Amit Varma]: best to just release it as one bumper episode. So this is therefore the longest episode ever

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:36.800
[Amit Varma]: on the Scene and the Unseen and regular programming resumes next week. Before we get to the conversation,

00:02:36.800 --> 00:02:41.360
[Amit Varma]: I need to express my gratitude to those who made the show possible. Four years ago, I

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:46.480
[Amit Varma]: didn't listen to podcasts and therefore didn't understand why this was such a special medium.

00:02:46.480 --> 00:02:52.080
[Amit Varma]: Then a friend of mine called Amit Doshi approached me. Amit ran the podcast network, IVM podcast,

00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:56.160
[Amit Varma]: and he asked if I'd be interested in doing something with them. I met up with Amit and

00:02:56.160 --> 00:03:01.360
[Amit Varma]: his then creative director, May Thomas, at a restaurant in Juhu called Fable and decided

00:03:01.360 --> 00:03:06.680
[Amit Varma]: to take a shot at this show. May soon went her own way and my partnership with IVM ended

00:03:06.680 --> 00:03:11.840
[Amit Varma]: last year as I went solo. But without Amit Doshi's initiative, you would not be listening

00:03:11.840 --> 00:03:17.960
[Amit Varma]: to this. Almost all of my 200 episodes have had one editor, Vijay Doifode. Vijay's been

00:03:17.960 --> 00:03:23.280
[Amit Varma]: a silent partner in crime, often fighting a valiant battle to salvage shaky audio. And

00:03:23.280 --> 00:03:29.280
[Amit Varma]: I continue to feel so reassured that he remains by my side as I go down this path. The artwork

00:03:29.280 --> 00:03:34.320
[Amit Varma]: of the show is done by the brilliant artist, Alekha Gupta, whose wonderful work adds to

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:38.160
[Amit Varma]: the character of the Scene and the Unseen. While Vijay and Alekha are the two people

00:03:38.160 --> 00:03:42.960
[Amit Varma]: I work with every week, I also want to thank those who've played a part in this show in

00:03:42.960 --> 00:03:48.400
[Amit Varma]: the past. Josh Thomas, Swati Bakshi, Abbas Mohamed, and Jude Weston helped produce it

00:03:48.400 --> 00:03:54.600
[Amit Varma]: back in the IVM days. Madhu Menon built the website sceneunseen.in and took the podcast

00:03:54.600 --> 00:03:57.880
[Amit Varma]: of photographs, which are actually pretty good photographs if you take the podcaster

00:03:57.880 --> 00:04:03.560
[Amit Varma]: out of them. And May Thomas and Sean Fanthorne helped me with advice and support at crucial

00:04:03.560 --> 00:04:09.200
[Amit Varma]: times. I also want to thank the many, many guests I've had over these 200 episodes who

00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:14.480
[Amit Varma]: have trusted me and have been generous with their time and insights. It takes two people

00:04:14.480 --> 00:04:19.640
[Amit Varma]: to have a good conversation, and I'm blessed to have been able to learn so much from so

00:04:19.640 --> 00:04:23.920
[Amit Varma]: many wonderful people. And I also want to thank you, the listener, for making me feel

00:04:23.920 --> 00:04:29.600
[Amit Varma]: that someone is listening and that this matters. I've often had lonely moments where I've wondered

00:04:29.600 --> 00:04:34.880
[Amit Varma]: if this was worth it. And your constant validation and support has meant a lot to me. Also, since

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:40.080
[Amit Varma]: I opened the show up for support in April this year, many of you have made generous

00:04:40.080 --> 00:04:44.320
[Amit Varma]: financial contributions to keep the show going. I feel guilty that I haven't been able to

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:48.880
[Amit Varma]: write to each of you personally to thank you for this. But it's been heartwarming and even

00:04:48.880 --> 00:04:54.080
[Amit Varma]: moving for me. The show remains independent because of you. More than that, it remains

00:04:54.080 --> 00:04:59.040
[Amit Varma]: meaningful to me because of you. So thank you for that. Over to the conversation now

00:04:59.040 --> 00:05:03.400
[Amit Varma]: where Shruti unleashes one surprise after another. But you know the drill. Before we

00:05:03.400 --> 00:05:30.880
[Amit Varma]: get there, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:05:34.400 --> 00:05:39.240
[Amit Varma]: And I do many, many hours of deep research for each episode. Besides all the logistics

00:05:39.240 --> 00:05:45.360
[Amit Varma]: of producing the show myself, scheduling guests, booking studios, paying technicians, the travel

00:05:45.360 --> 00:05:50.120
[Amit Varma]: and so on. So well, I'm trying a new way of keeping this thing going. And that involves

00:05:50.120 --> 00:05:55.400
[Amit Varma]: you. My proposition for you is this. For every episode of the scene and the unseen that you

00:05:55.400 --> 00:06:00.840
[Amit Varma]: enjoy, buy me a cup of coffee, or even a lavish lunch, whatever you feel it's worth. You can

00:06:00.840 --> 00:06:06.400
[Amit Varma]: do this by heading over to seen unseen.in slash support and contributing an amount of

00:06:06.400 --> 00:06:12.240
[Amit Varma]: your choice. This is not a subscription. The scene and the unseen will continue to be free

00:06:12.240 --> 00:06:19.320
[Amit Varma]: on all podcast apps and at seen unseen.in. This is just a gesture of appreciation. Help

00:06:19.320 --> 00:06:31.320
[Guest]: keep this thing going. Seen unseen.in slash support.

00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:55.960
[Guest]: And I'm frankly a little bit tired of being the conduit to fangirls and fanboys and listeners

00:06:55.960 --> 00:07:00.160
[Guest]: everywhere. And I thought it might also be a little bit of fun to turn the tables on

00:07:00.160 --> 00:07:05.960
[Guest]: Amit and ask him to be the guest for three and a half hours, right so that he knows how

00:07:05.960 --> 00:07:13.120
[Guest]: the rest of us feel. Just FYI, for this episode, I am prepared with energy bars, caffeine and

00:07:13.120 --> 00:07:19.280
[Guest]: water. I have only not come with like a pack for like survivorship or survivahood. But

00:07:19.280 --> 00:07:24.280
[Guest]: other than that, I'm fully prepared. So this is why I've taken over the show and Amit,

00:07:24.280 --> 00:07:25.280
[Guest]: welcome to the show.

00:07:25.280 --> 00:07:28.400
[Amit Varma]: Thank you for having me on your on my show. It's a great honor.

00:07:28.400 --> 00:07:33.080
[Guest]: Yeah, the other reason I sort of took over is I have known Amit long enough that I can

00:07:33.080 --> 00:07:39.160
[Guest]: be pushy and obnoxious and do things like invite myself over for the 200th episode at

00:07:39.160 --> 00:07:44.320
[Guest]: the 100th episode. So we did you know, like a sort of big reflections episode 100 episodes

00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:49.320
[Guest]: ago. And that was a little bit more fun because we got to have lunch at Oh Calcutta just before

00:07:49.320 --> 00:07:54.360
[Guest]: we recorded that. So this time all the yummy food is missing and it's the pandemic and

00:07:54.360 --> 00:07:58.440
[Guest]: we're not in the studio together. But other than that, it feels really, really nice to

00:07:58.440 --> 00:08:01.440
[Guest]: celebrate this big sort of, you know, milestone.

00:08:01.440 --> 00:08:06.800
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, I do. I don't know how we reached episode 200 dude. For what it's worth, I live

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:12.960
[Amit Varma]: and record in Mumbai and Shruti is in NYC and we record most of our episodes remotely.

00:08:12.960 --> 00:08:17.360
[Amit Varma]: But you happen to be down in Mumbai that time. So we had lunch at Oh Calcutta and then recorded

00:08:17.360 --> 00:08:20.920
[Amit Varma]: the 100th and here we are at the 200th. And I don't think you invited yourself in the

00:08:20.920 --> 00:08:25.200
[Amit Varma]: sense that it feels perfectly natural to, you know, do a milestone episode with you

00:08:25.200 --> 00:08:29.520
[Amit Varma]: because you know, I don't know if you remember, but you know, before the show started, you

00:08:29.520 --> 00:08:35.360
[Amit Varma]: know, we did a bunch of sort of pilot episodes. And you were my guinea pig for those and listeners

00:08:35.360 --> 00:08:40.640
[Amit Varma]: may not be aware of this. But before we launched the show, when I was partnering with IBM,

00:08:40.640 --> 00:08:45.200
[Amit Varma]: the way we conceptualize the show was something of a produced show where I go on a theme and

00:08:45.200 --> 00:08:49.800
[Amit Varma]: then we have soundbites from various people coming in and all of that. And later on at

00:08:49.800 --> 00:08:52.720
[Amit Varma]: some point we realized that's too much of a pain and what the hell and let's just do

00:08:52.720 --> 00:08:57.240
[Amit Varma]: a straight interview show because much easier to kickstart it and I had a good sense of

00:08:57.240 --> 00:09:01.240
[Amit Varma]: it and the show of course went on to evolve massively from there. But Shruti was the guinea

00:09:01.240 --> 00:09:02.960
[Amit Varma]: pig for many of those.

00:09:02.960 --> 00:09:07.920
[Guest]: Yeah, not only was I a guinea pig, I must fess up here to all your listeners. I was

00:09:07.920 --> 00:09:14.040
[Guest]: also someone who didn't think this was a great idea. I was like, why will people listen to

00:09:14.040 --> 00:09:18.720
[Guest]: us? What is the point of recording this conversation? Really, the two of us are going to talk about

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:22.360
[Guest]: minimum wage or something like that. You know, one of the guinea pig episodes was I think

00:09:22.360 --> 00:09:26.140
[Guest]: on minimum wage and I was like, who the hell is going to care about what we have to say

00:09:26.140 --> 00:09:32.560
[Guest]: about this? So I was a big time naysayer. I'm really glad Amit did not take my advice

00:09:32.560 --> 00:09:37.680
[Guest]: and he went with this. Otherwise, there would be no 200th show. So that's my mini confession.

00:09:37.680 --> 00:09:42.280
[Guest]: But I became a big cheerleader for the show soon enough. This was just in the very, very

00:09:42.280 --> 00:09:43.280
[Guest]: initial period.

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:48.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, initially, like right now, for example, if you speak to me, I have a very

00:09:48.600 --> 00:09:52.240
[Amit Varma]: good sense of what I'm doing and great conviction and what I'm doing and why I'm doing it. But

00:09:52.240 --> 00:09:56.060
[Amit Varma]: at the start, it was just an experiment. It was like, let's do it. The show was nothing

00:09:56.060 --> 00:10:01.920
[Amit Varma]: like what it is now. And, you know, from there, it's kind of evolved. And I mean, really one

00:10:01.920 --> 00:10:06.760
[Amit Varma]: of the sort of the turning points in my thinking about the medium was episode 26, which we

00:10:06.760 --> 00:10:10.480
[Amit Varma]: did together on the right to property, which was, you know, more than an hour. And, you

00:10:10.480 --> 00:10:15.440
[Amit Varma]: know, early on in the show, my conception of podcasting, my conception of media in general,

00:10:15.440 --> 00:10:19.000
[Amit Varma]: because I didn't listen to podcasting, my conception of this kind of media in general

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:23.400
[Amit Varma]: was that people have short attention spans, and you have to hook them in the first 15

00:10:23.400 --> 00:10:27.120
[Amit Varma]: seconds. And no matter how long you make it, it should not be longer than 20 minutes, which

00:10:27.120 --> 00:10:30.960
[Amit Varma]: was all rubbish. And I'll, you know, maybe get a chance to elaborate later in the episode

00:10:30.960 --> 00:10:36.840
[Amit Varma]: why I feel that way. But as we sort of when we did episode 26, which was more than an

00:10:36.840 --> 00:10:42.040
[Amit Varma]: hour, I thought, okay, this is my best episode so far. And it happens to be my longest. So

00:10:42.040 --> 00:10:46.840
[Amit Varma]: what is going on here? And I really enjoyed this and listeners seem to enjoy it. And it

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:50.600
[Amit Varma]: took a new life. And now of course, one hour is like a ridiculous miniature, I would never

00:10:50.600 --> 00:10:57.400
[Amit Varma]: do something so hopelessly shallow. But what I'll do on social media, by the way, is release

00:10:57.400 --> 00:11:02.080
[Amit Varma]: sort of without the numbers, I'll show you a list of my top 25 episodes in popularity

00:11:02.080 --> 00:11:05.400
[Amit Varma]: because so many people discover the show and they're like, what should I listen to first?

00:11:05.400 --> 00:11:08.640
[Amit Varma]: So I'll share the top 25. And you'll see that I think more or less all of them are more

00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:13.880
[Amit Varma]: than two hours. And there's a very good correlation between sort of length and popularity.

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:17.560
[Guest]: I don't think it's a correlation between length and popularity. I think it's between quality

00:11:17.560 --> 00:11:22.840
[Guest]: and popularity. You tend to engage more with guests who are very, I mean, I don't mean

00:11:22.840 --> 00:11:26.240
[Guest]: some of your guests are not high quality. But you know, sometimes when the conversation

00:11:26.240 --> 00:11:31.120
[Guest]: is going really well, you tend to go longer. And that is why the listener is hooked longer

00:11:31.120 --> 00:11:36.320
[Guest]: because it is that good. So you know, it's this funny thing, Jerry Seinfeld, in one of

00:11:36.320 --> 00:11:42.340
[Guest]: his shows, he talked about how a length and quality are just substitutes for each other.

00:11:42.340 --> 00:11:46.680
[Guest]: And I think this was with Patton Oswalt. He said, you know, there are three second cat

00:11:46.680 --> 00:11:52.960
[Guest]: and ad videos on YouTube that he can't tolerate two seconds off. But there are other things

00:11:52.960 --> 00:11:56.720
[Guest]: which you know, you're willing to watch for hours, people are willing to watch the directors

00:11:56.720 --> 00:12:01.880
[Guest]: cut a lot of rings back to back and things like that. So I really think it's not that

00:12:01.880 --> 00:12:07.600
[Guest]: people enjoy the length per se, but it is the amount of quality packed in per minute,

00:12:07.600 --> 00:12:11.480
[Guest]: which you have managed to sustain for three hours, I just cannot imagine how.

00:12:11.480 --> 00:12:15.000
[Amit Varma]: No, no. And also what happens is, and I'm sure you'll, you know, I don't know what questions

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:18.280
[Amit Varma]: you have lined up for me with, you know, it's going to be a wonderful surprise as we go

00:12:18.280 --> 00:12:22.420
[Amit Varma]: along. And we'll probably talk about interviewing. But one of the things that I do during an

00:12:22.420 --> 00:12:27.080
[Amit Varma]: episode is always calibrate how long it should be, according to a number of factors, such

00:12:27.080 --> 00:12:30.640
[Amit Varma]: as if I'm really enjoying it, and if it is a stimulating conversation, and there's enough

00:12:30.640 --> 00:12:35.440
[Amit Varma]: dope to talk about, and the other person is willing, which is key, then I go on as long

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:39.200
[Amit Varma]: as I feel like, but sometimes the conversation may be great, but maybe the other and the

00:12:39.200 --> 00:12:42.040
[Amit Varma]: other person also feels as great, but they just don't have the time they've given me

00:12:42.040 --> 00:12:46.200
[Amit Varma]: three hours. So we have to end before that. That's fine. And sometimes there aren't, you

00:12:46.200 --> 00:12:50.480
[Amit Varma]: know, enough things to talk about. And they kind of wind down. And sometimes I just feel

00:12:50.480 --> 00:12:54.760
[Amit Varma]: that they're getting tired, they want to talk, they want to be kind, but they are just getting

00:12:54.760 --> 00:13:00.040
[Amit Varma]: tired, they haven't sort of stacked up with energy bars and caffeine as you have. So at

00:13:00.040 --> 00:13:03.760
[Amit Varma]: that point, I just, you know, I have to make the call that I have to be kind to this person

00:13:03.760 --> 00:13:08.320
[Amit Varma]: and let them go. So they live to see another day and maybe another episode someday.

00:13:08.320 --> 00:13:12.200
[Guest]: I have been told by my husband that I get hangry. I mean, he didn't have to tell me

00:13:12.200 --> 00:13:18.200
[Guest]: I know this about myself. I didn't want to unleash the crazy demon version of me on you

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:23.880
[Guest]: and hence the snacks and the caffeine. So if I can begin right after this long prelude,

00:13:23.880 --> 00:13:28.240
[Guest]: I mean, let me tell you the plan for the show, since you don't know what's going on, you

00:13:28.240 --> 00:13:35.120
[Guest]: have a rough, vague idea. So we did something, we went behind your back, and we asked a group

00:13:35.120 --> 00:13:41.320
[Guest]: of guests and fans, and this is not, you know, it's just a random ordering of people I know

00:13:41.320 --> 00:13:45.480
[Guest]: you have enjoyed having on your show. And some of the fans I have interacted with on

00:13:45.480 --> 00:13:49.640
[Guest]: Twitter, and I know that, you know, they're huge fans of yours. So those who are not on

00:13:49.640 --> 00:13:54.280
[Guest]: this list, this is entirely my fault. Um, it had nothing to do with it. Right. So this

00:13:54.280 --> 00:13:58.960
[Guest]: is just like a group of people who thought it would be great to ask you some questions.

00:13:58.960 --> 00:14:05.600
[Guest]: So what we did was I just asked them to record a question in their voice and send it to us.

00:14:05.600 --> 00:14:11.840
[Guest]: So Vijay, who is your sound guy, and amazing and my life savior, and who have traumatized

00:14:11.840 --> 00:14:16.520
[Guest]: over the last, say, two to three weeks, has been very helpful in putting this together,

00:14:16.520 --> 00:14:20.160
[Guest]: making sure we get all the recordings, they're of good quality. So I'm going to play the

00:14:20.160 --> 00:14:25.720
[Guest]: question. And you have to answer the question. So for the listeners, this is pretty spontaneous,

00:14:25.720 --> 00:14:29.640
[Guest]: because Amit doesn't know what's coming. Right. And I have a whole bunch of questions in the

00:14:29.640 --> 00:14:35.320
[Guest]: middle that that, you know, I will have, I'm sure. And, you know, just as there is always

00:14:35.320 --> 00:14:40.840
[Guest]: with your episodes, no fixed plan, no fixed script, we just take this where the conversation

00:14:40.840 --> 00:14:46.720
[Amit Varma]: goes. Well, I'm really scared and excited, but a little scared, because normally I'm

00:14:46.720 --> 00:14:51.080
[Amit Varma]: at the other end. I mean, it's very relaxing to be a guest, because I don't have to prepare

00:14:51.080 --> 00:14:55.360
[Amit Varma]: and I don't have to wrack my brain about what do I ask next? And where do I take the conversation?

00:14:55.360 --> 00:15:00.720
[Amit Varma]: And you're constantly on sort of focusing hard when you're the host being a guest is

00:15:00.720 --> 00:15:04.120
[Amit Varma]: much easier. However, I don't know what's coming at me. So this is interesting. Where

00:15:04.120 --> 00:15:11.080
[Guest]: are we starting? Okay, so we are gonna start with Manu Pillai, who has been definitely

00:15:11.080 --> 00:15:16.240
[Guest]: one of your most popular guests, right? He also, I think, packs in the most number of

00:15:16.240 --> 00:15:21.920
[Guest]: words per minute. And he is really one of my favorite authors, one of my favorite historians.

00:15:21.920 --> 00:15:27.000
[Guest]: I love reading his books. So thank you, Manu, for your question. And here goes.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:33.440
[Unknown]: Hi, Amit. You know, my question for you is quite simple. Because I've been on your show

00:15:33.440 --> 00:15:39.680
[Unknown]: three times, and I've heard you discuss various things with various experts and writers and

00:15:39.680 --> 00:15:46.400
[Unknown]: others ever since. And one of the things I've noticed is that you always spend a good amount

00:15:46.400 --> 00:15:51.920
[Unknown]: of time right at the start, trying to get them to open up about themselves, their pasts,

00:15:51.920 --> 00:15:58.240
[Unknown]: their childhood years, the kind of intellectual inspirations they've had, where they studied,

00:15:58.240 --> 00:16:04.360
[Unknown]: what brought them to these junctures where they currently are. And I've always thought,

00:16:04.360 --> 00:16:09.000
[Unknown]: what about you? You know, where did you grow up? What are the books you read? What made

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:14.920
[Unknown]: you this complete podcast guru? You know, this figure who's able to sort of woo other

00:16:14.920 --> 00:16:20.000
[Unknown]: people and get them to talk about things that they may not necessarily otherwise relate

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:24.480
[Unknown]: to a public audience, but you managed to extract that kind of information. And I wonder if

00:16:24.480 --> 00:16:30.160
[Unknown]: you let us extract a little bit of information about you as well, about your background and

00:16:30.160 --> 00:16:35.880
[Unknown]: the things that make you who you are. I hope, you know, Shruti will ask you and prod you

00:16:35.880 --> 00:16:38.760
[Unknown]: in this direction and get you to open up a little bit.

00:16:38.760 --> 00:16:43.880
[Amit Varma]: Wow, that's such a lovely question. So, you know, before I get down to answering it, like,

00:16:43.880 --> 00:16:47.200
[Amit Varma]: first of all, of course, we link all these episodes from the show notes, I must say that

00:16:47.200 --> 00:16:52.360
[Amit Varma]: I've done three episodes with Manu and they were all a super hit. And he's been doing

00:16:52.360 --> 00:16:57.360
[Amit Varma]: this lovely thing. Just be a guest. Yeah, no, but I have to, I have to say these things

00:16:57.360 --> 00:17:01.440
[Amit Varma]: about these very kind guests of mine who have asked these questions that, you know, Manu

00:17:01.440 --> 00:17:06.240
[Amit Varma]: has been on Twitter recently reading out from Hindi and Marathi translations of his books

00:17:06.240 --> 00:17:11.840
[Amit Varma]: and just absolutely lovely. It shows you why he's like the resident chick magnet of Twitter.

00:17:11.840 --> 00:17:16.400
[Amit Varma]: And he's got a great voice, you should totally get into podcasting, though, as I often keep

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:20.240
[Amit Varma]: saying that this is not radio, so voice does not matter. And I can elaborate on that separately

00:17:20.240 --> 00:17:25.360
[Amit Varma]: if you want. But to sort of, before I get to answer this question, because I am a guest,

00:17:25.360 --> 00:17:29.320
[Amit Varma]: I can ramble as much as I want, and the host cannot interrupt. That's the rule of the show.

00:17:29.320 --> 00:17:33.400
[Amit Varma]: So I'd also like to talk about why I get people to open up. It's a conscious decision. It's

00:17:33.400 --> 00:17:37.440
[Amit Varma]: not a decision at all, I have to reach three hours, how do I do it, spend one hour talking

00:17:37.440 --> 00:17:42.440
[Amit Varma]: about them, but it's a conscious decision. But you know, not the intended reason, but

00:17:42.440 --> 00:17:46.480
[Amit Varma]: part of why it works is the tactical thing is that it gets a guest to relax, and then

00:17:46.480 --> 00:17:49.800
[Amit Varma]: they're more likely to trust you and open up and all of that. But the real reason I

00:17:49.800 --> 00:17:55.280
[Amit Varma]: do it is for the listeners to sort of give them a sense of the flesh and blood person

00:17:55.280 --> 00:17:59.680
[Amit Varma]: behind the ideas and the work that we're going to hear about. Because too often, I think

00:17:59.680 --> 00:18:05.200
[Amit Varma]: that in the world, we and I've been thinking a lot and talking a lot about this recently,

00:18:05.200 --> 00:18:09.420
[Amit Varma]: that we focus on abstract things and not enough on concrete things. So if you're talking about

00:18:09.420 --> 00:18:14.220
[Amit Varma]: somebody's work and somebody's ideas, and you can go into all these abstract areas.

00:18:14.220 --> 00:18:19.480
[Amit Varma]: And it's also interesting to me to get a concrete sense of who is this person? What is the journey

00:18:19.480 --> 00:18:23.560
[Amit Varma]: where does she come from? What are the, you know, and I'm not referring to Manu as a her,

00:18:23.560 --> 00:18:29.680
[Amit Varma]: I'm just, it's a generic pronoun. And so which is why I do that. But to sort of, and I think

00:18:29.680 --> 00:18:34.360
[Amit Varma]: I actually talk enough about myself in little bits and pieces here that readers should already

00:18:34.360 --> 00:18:40.240
[Amit Varma]: feel they know me. But basically, I was sort of, my dad is Punjabi, my mom is Bengali,

00:18:40.240 --> 00:18:44.080
[Amit Varma]: my dad was an IAS officer. So I was born and brought up in Chandigarh, where I was still

00:18:44.080 --> 00:18:49.800
[Amit Varma]: I think the eighth standard. And then my dad sort of shifted to Pune, where he was a director

00:18:49.800 --> 00:18:55.480
[Amit Varma]: of the Film and Television Institute of India in the late 80s. In fact, he was a person

00:18:55.480 --> 00:19:00.840
[Amit Varma]: who took the decision to expel Sanjay Leela Bhansali from the Institute, who was an editing

00:19:00.840 --> 00:19:05.200
[Amit Varma]: student and demanded that his graduation film should be one that he's allowed to direct.

00:19:05.200 --> 00:19:08.640
[Amit Varma]: And my father was like stickler for rules and know what are you saying you are an editing

00:19:08.640 --> 00:19:13.400
[Amit Varma]: student and all of that. So I would have expelled him for aesthetic reasons alone. But I don't

00:19:13.400 --> 00:19:17.840
[Amit Varma]: think my dad thought along those lines, I could have seen the future monstrosities that

00:19:17.840 --> 00:19:23.320
[Amit Varma]: would come out of there. So, but I mentioned that as an important point, because I, you

00:19:23.320 --> 00:19:26.760
[Amit Varma]: know, as a child, I basically grew up watching a lot of world cinema and thinking of it as

00:19:26.760 --> 00:19:31.200
[Amit Varma]: something completely normal, not a separate genre, like world cinema or something, not

00:19:31.200 --> 00:19:34.880
[Amit Varma]: as you know, a different kind of cinema, but as something completely normal, I would watch

00:19:34.880 --> 00:19:39.360
[Amit Varma]: two, three films a day, that was a big influence on me. I was also fortunate because my dad

00:19:39.360 --> 00:19:45.520
[Amit Varma]: is a reader and loved collecting books. And we had 1000s of books at home, literally many

00:19:45.520 --> 00:19:49.840
[Amit Varma]: 1000s. So I would read I would just pick up whatever I came across and serendipity helped

00:19:49.840 --> 00:19:54.780
[Amit Varma]: me when I was about the age of 10. And I saw this book, I still remember, it was a hardback

00:19:54.780 --> 00:20:00.880
[Amit Varma]: modern library edition. And the book had the intriguing title of House of the Dead. So

00:20:00.880 --> 00:20:05.800
[Amit Varma]: I thought, okay, this will be some really funky, nice, you know, thrilling book zombies

00:20:05.800 --> 00:20:09.900
[Amit Varma]: and all that, whatever, I don't know, let's check it out. And it was a book by Dostoevsky

00:20:09.900 --> 00:20:14.600
[Amit Varma]: about his years when he was in a prison in Siberia. And I was just blown away, my whole

00:20:14.600 --> 00:20:17.680
[Amit Varma]: world was blown open, though I haven't read it since then. So I need to go back and read

00:20:17.680 --> 00:20:22.800
[Amit Varma]: it. So I read all of Dostoevsky and then I read all the Russians. And then I got to Shakespeare.

00:20:22.800 --> 00:20:29.160
[Amit Varma]: I read all of Shakespeare when I was 10. Though my I must say that while my reading was prolific,

00:20:29.160 --> 00:20:32.640
[Amit Varma]: my tastes weren't very evolved. Because if I remember correctly, my favorite Shakespeare

00:20:32.640 --> 00:20:37.400
[Amit Varma]: play was Titus Andronicus and kind of moved on from there. And then as I entered my teenage

00:20:37.400 --> 00:20:41.920
[Amit Varma]: years, I kind of read less and less. My reading habits sort of went off into adulthood. But

00:20:41.920 --> 00:20:47.160
[Amit Varma]: there was that early base where I had kind of read a lot and so on. And at this point,

00:20:47.160 --> 00:20:53.640
[Amit Varma]: I had no sort of ideological sort of leanings. I was sort of probably mildly left liberal,

00:20:53.640 --> 00:20:57.600
[Amit Varma]: like many people tend to be in college. And then I went to college and I decided, okay,

00:20:57.600 --> 00:21:01.840
[Amit Varma]: I want to be a writer. So what do I do? How does one write and it seemed made sense to

00:21:01.840 --> 00:21:08.680
[Amit Varma]: be to say, okay, I'll be an advertising copywriter. And right. So I did my BA in English literature

00:21:08.680 --> 00:21:14.120
[Amit Varma]: in Ferguson College. And I did not then know of a story past. You know, it was in Ferguson

00:21:14.120 --> 00:21:20.640
[Amit Varma]: College in I think 1892 or 1893 that Gopal Krishna Gokhale and who had one of the founders

00:21:20.640 --> 00:21:25.240
[Amit Varma]: of the college met Mahatma Gandhi for the first time and they went for a walk on the

00:21:25.240 --> 00:21:30.000
[Amit Varma]: grounds of Ferguson College and had a long chat. And it had a history of atheism. It's

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:34.600
[Amit Varma]: also in Ferguson College where Gopal Ganesh Agarkar, one of the great figures of our independence

00:21:34.600 --> 00:21:38.840
[Amit Varma]: who sadly died too young, a great classical liberal, once while teaching a biology class,

00:21:38.840 --> 00:21:43.120
[Amit Varma]: he asked all his students, if a donkey had God, what would that God look like? And then

00:21:43.120 --> 00:21:48.800
[Amit Varma]: he held both his hands up above his ears. And brilliant. And I remember in, you know,

00:21:48.800 --> 00:21:52.720
[Amit Varma]: Gokhale's biography by B.R. Nanda, there's an anecdote about how Gokhale tells someone

00:21:52.720 --> 00:21:56.720
[Amit Varma]: about Ferguson College and that person says something to the effect of, oh, you come from

00:21:56.720 --> 00:22:03.560
[Amit Varma]: that hotbed of atheism. Anyway, I wasn't aware of any of these in when I was in college and

00:22:03.560 --> 00:22:08.640
[Amit Varma]: nor was I an atheist then. Like I said, I was mildly left liberal and mildly very fuzzy

00:22:08.640 --> 00:22:13.040
[Amit Varma]: about God. And I thought spirituality and there is some bigger force out there and we

00:22:13.040 --> 00:22:18.360
[Amit Varma]: cannot give it a name and all of that complete rubbish. Now, of course, I'm an atheist, but

00:22:18.360 --> 00:22:21.960
[Amit Varma]: defined as the absence of belief. So I don't believe that there is no God. It's simply

00:22:21.960 --> 00:22:26.600
[Amit Varma]: that I don't believe that there is a God. So this is a complete digression. But I remember

00:22:26.600 --> 00:22:32.000
[Amit Varma]: a letter I did to the economist once said that, you know, saying that atheism is a belief

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:37.720
[Amit Varma]: system or a religion is like saying that not collecting stamps is a hobby. So that's kind

00:22:37.720 --> 00:22:43.200
[Amit Varma]: of that's kind of how I look at it. But also what happened was then I went to Delhi from

00:22:43.200 --> 00:22:49.920
[Amit Varma]: there. And in Delhi, I joined this place called HTA Hindustan Thompson Associates, where I

00:22:49.920 --> 00:22:55.320
[Amit Varma]: spent a few months. And for whatever reasons, I wasn't happy advertising wasn't doing it

00:22:55.320 --> 00:22:59.600
[Amit Varma]: for me. And at that time, you know, channel V had just started and they had come out with

00:22:59.600 --> 00:23:05.520
[Amit Varma]: the quick gun Murugan commercials and all of that. And, and my then girlfriend now wife

00:23:05.520 --> 00:23:09.400
[Amit Varma]: was in Pune, and she was planning to go to Bombay to study, although she didn't end up

00:23:09.400 --> 00:23:12.720
[Amit Varma]: studying, she said she would study, but she was trying to go to Bombay and the long distance

00:23:12.720 --> 00:23:19.040
[Amit Varma]: thing wasn't working out. So I said, TK, I'm going to go to Bombay. And that's the best

00:23:19.040 --> 00:23:24.480
[Amit Varma]: decision you have made. It was so so I went to Bombay, I can I think I landed in Bombay

00:23:24.480 --> 00:23:30.600
[Amit Varma]: on a Friday. And in Monday, I was employed at channel V. I worked in channel V for a

00:23:30.600 --> 00:23:35.040
[Amit Varma]: couple of years, I worked for a couple of years more in MTV after that, you know, spent

00:23:35.040 --> 00:23:40.160
[Amit Varma]: kind of five years between those two places. And then sort of moved on and did a bunch

00:23:40.160 --> 00:23:44.560
[Amit Varma]: of things. I've spoken about that journey in other places. But basically, I sort of

00:23:44.560 --> 00:23:50.160
[Amit Varma]: did. I tried to be an entrepreneur for a very short while, which was right after the dot

00:23:50.160 --> 00:23:55.600
[Amit Varma]: com bubble burst. So not the best of timings that didn't work, then I joined wisdom, which

00:23:55.600 --> 00:24:01.000
[Amit Varma]: bought Cricinfo. And I became managing editor there, did that for a few years. And because

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:05.480
[Amit Varma]: I didn't want to write only about cricket started a blog called India uncut, which,

00:24:05.480 --> 00:24:09.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, back in the day became kind of fairly popular, wrote that a lot. I call that my

00:24:09.240 --> 00:24:13.600
[Amit Varma]: writing gym. Like, you know, when I sort of teach my writing course, now I tell people

00:24:13.600 --> 00:24:17.600
[Amit Varma]: about how important it is to write regularly. And India uncut was great, because I was writing

00:24:17.600 --> 00:24:22.440
[Amit Varma]: five posts a day. And because my attitude was it is just a blog, I wasn't paralyzed

00:24:22.440 --> 00:24:26.520
[Amit Varma]: by the fear of anxiety that what will other people think of my writing, and so on and

00:24:26.520 --> 00:24:31.120
[Amit Varma]: so forth. So I ended up doing some 8000 posts in five years. Then I moved on to sort of

00:24:31.120 --> 00:24:36.360
[Amit Varma]: playing poker professionally for a living. And after five years of that, I decided that

00:24:36.360 --> 00:24:41.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, it was taking a toll on my lifestyle, I had saved up enough to kind of not have

00:24:41.160 --> 00:24:44.920
[Amit Varma]: to work for a while. So I thought, let me be a writer again, left that then I kind of

00:24:44.920 --> 00:24:49.840
[Amit Varma]: became editor of the online magazine Pragati for a while, started the scene and the unseen

00:24:49.840 --> 00:24:54.960
[Amit Varma]: around the same time. And now I can safely say that I'm either a professional podcaster

00:24:54.960 --> 00:25:00.280
[Amit Varma]: or a professional educator, none of which I would have, you know, expected five years

00:25:00.280 --> 00:25:05.680
[Amit Varma]: ago, but like, here we are, it's, it's, it's, yeah, it's a wild journey.

00:25:05.680 --> 00:25:09.840
[Guest]: You know, one of my favorite things about you, and especially because I have seen about

00:25:09.840 --> 00:25:16.560
[Guest]: the last 15 plus years of this, this transition in your life, is that you never wait for there

00:25:16.560 --> 00:25:23.640
[Guest]: to be this infrastructure or this institutional system. I say this specifically, because I

00:25:23.640 --> 00:25:29.240
[Guest]: have students who asked me, how do I do this? How do I become a lawyer? Or how do I become

00:25:29.240 --> 00:25:33.880
[Guest]: so and so? How do I start writing a column? And if I were to give them your example, it

00:25:33.880 --> 00:25:37.960
[Guest]: would be just start doing it. And it will figure itself out and something will come

00:25:37.960 --> 00:25:44.600
[Guest]: of it. Most people wait to be asked to do something. Most people wait for a job to exist

00:25:44.600 --> 00:25:50.080
[Guest]: before actually doing what they care about. You are one of those few people who's just

00:25:50.080 --> 00:25:55.400
[Guest]: like, I really enjoy doing this, and I'm going to do it. And that's the end of that. And

00:25:55.400 --> 00:25:59.320
[Guest]: it's one of my favorite things about you. So what is your attitude about that? Were

00:25:59.320 --> 00:26:03.920
[Guest]: you always like this as a kid? Does it come from having certain amount of privilege and

00:26:03.920 --> 00:26:09.240
[Guest]: also certain amount of self knowledge that you know, you do something long enough, you

00:26:09.240 --> 00:26:13.720
[Guest]: know, it's going to turn into something valuable? Where does this unique, you know, sort of,

00:26:13.720 --> 00:26:18.360
[Guest]: it's not even entrepreneurial, it's really like, it's entrepreneurial, it's experimental.

00:26:18.360 --> 00:26:21.400
[Guest]: It's really interesting characteristic of you that I have observed.

00:26:21.400 --> 00:26:24.640
[Amit Varma]: Look, I think the privilege is always there. Because obviously, you know, I've had the

00:26:24.640 --> 00:26:29.440
[Amit Varma]: good fortune of not really having to worry about my next meal is going to come from though,

00:26:29.440 --> 00:26:34.720
[Amit Varma]: at the same time, I have essentially been completely self made got nothing from elsewhere.

00:26:34.720 --> 00:26:39.120
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, been working since I was 20. And all, all of that. But my approaches, you

00:26:39.120 --> 00:26:43.080
[Amit Varma]: know, it seems like it's planned. And there's a grand philosophy behind it. I do have a

00:26:43.080 --> 00:26:47.800
[Amit Varma]: sort of, not a grand philosophy, but a way of thinking about these things now. But a

00:26:47.800 --> 00:26:51.840
[Amit Varma]: lot of it when it happened was that I just felt enamored with something and I went ahead

00:26:51.840 --> 00:26:58.160
[Amit Varma]: and did it. And I was always sort of an idealistic fool. And I never sort of thought about is

00:26:58.160 --> 00:27:03.520
[Amit Varma]: there a market for this? Is this going to make money? Is this going to sort of lead

00:27:03.520 --> 00:27:08.280
[Amit Varma]: to short term results and validation and all of those things. I just jumped into it. Having

00:27:08.280 --> 00:27:11.680
[Amit Varma]: said that the one thing I wanted to do all my life, which is write novels is something

00:27:11.680 --> 00:27:16.640
[Amit Varma]: I've just written one bad novel. So I haven't done enough of that. So actually, I haven't

00:27:16.640 --> 00:27:19.960
[Amit Varma]: done what you're saying I've done, which is jump into what I love. But I've done a lot

00:27:19.960 --> 00:27:23.880
[Amit Varma]: of other things which have interested me because I wanted to do them. Now my broad sort of

00:27:23.880 --> 00:27:27.760
[Amit Varma]: advice to people would be whenever you're doing something two pieces of advice. One

00:27:27.760 --> 00:27:31.720
[Amit Varma]: is don't overthink it. I think there is a trade off between getting it done and getting

00:27:31.720 --> 00:27:37.400
[Amit Varma]: it right. And wherever there is a conflict between those two, you should privilege getting

00:27:37.400 --> 00:27:42.240
[Amit Varma]: it done. And in fact, getting it done as a way to get it right, because you get it done

00:27:42.240 --> 00:27:45.880
[Amit Varma]: once and then you keep doing it, doing it, doing it, you keep iterating, it becomes something

00:27:45.880 --> 00:27:50.200
[Amit Varma]: else and event that's actually the only way to get it right. Like, even the scene and

00:27:50.200 --> 00:27:54.320
[Amit Varma]: the unseen, for example, like I'm really proud of the episodes that I've done since say maybe

00:27:54.320 --> 00:27:59.560
[Amit Varma]: episode 8090. And, you know, the last the last 100 episodes, so to say, but I don't

00:27:59.560 --> 00:28:03.360
[Amit Varma]: like the early episodes at all. Because the conception of the show was very different.

00:28:03.360 --> 00:28:07.440
[Amit Varma]: And as you keep doing it, you know, you sort of keep learning, you keep growing, you discover

00:28:07.440 --> 00:28:11.280
[Amit Varma]: new things, and then it becomes a different kind of beast. So my first piece of advice

00:28:11.280 --> 00:28:15.080
[Amit Varma]: is don't overthink it, where there's a you see that trade off between getting it done

00:28:15.080 --> 00:28:18.700
[Amit Varma]: and getting it right air on the side of getting it done, just start and see where it goes

00:28:18.700 --> 00:28:22.280
[Amit Varma]: throw things at the wall. My other way of looking at it, which is something I've come

00:28:22.280 --> 00:28:26.400
[Amit Varma]: to realize this year, and maybe we'll get a chance to speak about it at length later

00:28:26.400 --> 00:28:31.360
[Amit Varma]: in this episode is that, and this is a piece of advice I give creators that I think much

00:28:31.360 --> 00:28:36.400
[Amit Varma]: as they say about futurists and science fiction writers, that they tend to overestimate the

00:28:36.400 --> 00:28:40.660
[Amit Varma]: short term and underestimate the long term. I think creators do this as well, that many

00:28:40.660 --> 00:28:44.560
[Amit Varma]: creators will start creating something and they'll overestimate the short term and what

00:28:44.560 --> 00:28:49.160
[Amit Varma]: it will get them in terms of validation and financial rewards. And they'll say, my podcast

00:28:49.160 --> 00:28:52.880
[Amit Varma]: will be so popular and it'll get so many hits and I'll make so much money and they overestimate

00:28:52.880 --> 00:28:57.480
[Amit Varma]: that and they could get disheartened by that and stop doing it. But you might underestimate

00:28:57.480 --> 00:29:01.520
[Amit Varma]: the long run because what will happen in the long run is something that you don't really

00:29:01.520 --> 00:29:04.480
[Amit Varma]: know. I mean, look at someone like Joe Rogan, he's been podcasting for donkey's years and

00:29:04.480 --> 00:29:08.360
[Amit Varma]: now he gets 100 million deals from Spotify. And obviously, there's a little bit of survivors

00:29:08.360 --> 00:29:15.480
[Amit Varma]: bias at play there. But regardless, I think those who succeed in creative enterprises

00:29:15.480 --> 00:29:19.200
[Amit Varma]: will be people who do it for the love of it. And of course, you have to be practical and

00:29:19.200 --> 00:29:22.360
[Amit Varma]: you have to think about how you want to make money and so on. But there are people who

00:29:22.360 --> 00:29:26.960
[Amit Varma]: do it for the love of it, and then it works out and then they sort of start thinking of

00:29:26.960 --> 00:29:32.080
[Amit Varma]: all of these other aspects, many of which fall into place. So I won't say that I didn't

00:29:32.080 --> 00:29:36.240
[Amit Varma]: want to make money of this. But I started seeing in the unseen, obviously, I wasn't

00:29:36.240 --> 00:29:41.600
[Amit Varma]: like the first 108 episodes made nothing. And till I went independent, in fact, and

00:29:41.600 --> 00:29:45.640
[Amit Varma]: broke with my as well partners, it was making very negligible money. And now for the last

00:29:45.640 --> 00:29:50.360
[Amit Varma]: few months, it's better partly because, you know, and again, this is something which in

00:29:50.360 --> 00:29:54.320
[Amit Varma]: the context of creators, I can speak about later that as creators, you have to think

00:29:54.320 --> 00:29:58.120
[Amit Varma]: of what you do for each and what you do for revenue. And they may not often coincide and

00:29:58.120 --> 00:30:03.980
[Amit Varma]: you may do something to build your brand which which then pays off in other ancillary ways.

00:30:03.980 --> 00:30:08.940
[Amit Varma]: So there's a sort of now post facto of figuring out a lot of stuff. But the bottom line is

00:30:08.940 --> 00:30:14.080
[Amit Varma]: that there was a long, long period when the show wasn't, you know, making any money, and

00:30:14.080 --> 00:30:18.840
[Amit Varma]: it was a labor of love. And especially when it became the long form conversation thing,

00:30:18.840 --> 00:30:24.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, I would often read many, many books to sort of prepare for it. And for each episode,

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:28.280
[Amit Varma]: and it became really hard work. So I remember once I was going to an episode recording,

00:30:28.280 --> 00:30:31.920
[Amit Varma]: and I was feeling very low that day, I was saying like, what's the point, you know, it's

00:30:31.920 --> 00:30:36.320
[Amit Varma]: there's no money, there's nothing. Again, you know, one more time in my life, like India

00:30:36.320 --> 00:30:40.800
[Amit Varma]: uncut, I'm doing something which is very popular, but there's nothing in it. And then at the

00:30:40.800 --> 00:30:44.200
[Amit Varma]: end of the recording, I was like walking on air, I just felt so elated. And I thought

00:30:44.200 --> 00:30:48.760
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, it's worth it for its own sake, it doesn't matter the other stuff can

00:30:48.760 --> 00:30:52.280
[Amit Varma]: come or not come, but it's worth it for its own sake. And the recording for those who

00:30:52.280 --> 00:30:56.440
[Amit Varma]: want to know though, it could have been many recordings, because I've, you know, made almost

00:30:56.440 --> 00:30:59.200
[Amit Varma]: all the recordings I've done in the past couple of years are worth it for their own sake.

00:30:59.200 --> 00:31:04.800
[Amit Varma]: But this was episode 150, which was with VK Kartika. And we were talking a lot about books.

00:31:04.800 --> 00:31:07.920
[Amit Varma]: So that's sort of something that I enjoyed.

00:31:07.920 --> 00:31:13.000
[Guest]: We have VK Kartika coming up later in some questions. But I want to go on to one of your

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:18.660
[Guest]: more recent episodes with Rajat Ubhiyankar. Right? This was this lovely episode on his

00:31:18.660 --> 00:31:25.240
[Guest]: book on how he traveled across India with truck drivers. And he's asked a really interesting

00:31:25.240 --> 00:31:29.600
[Guest]: question about influence of your parents, your father in particular. So just give that

00:31:29.600 --> 00:31:30.600
[Unknown]: a click.

00:31:30.600 --> 00:31:35.480
[Unknown]: Apologies if this question is a bit personal. But I recently found out that Amit's father

00:31:35.480 --> 00:31:41.000
[Unknown]: was an IAS officer. Now I have several friends who are children of civil servants, IAS, IPS

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:46.640
[Unknown]: and so on. And so many of them are now committed vocal libertarians. So anecdotally, there

00:31:46.640 --> 00:31:51.960
[Unknown]: seems to be a pattern at work here. So my question for Amit is, what role, if any, did

00:31:51.960 --> 00:31:56.840
[Unknown]: witnessing the workings of the Indian state growing up play in you later becoming a libertarian?

00:31:56.840 --> 00:32:02.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's such a great question. Great, perceptive question. You know, to really speculate,

00:32:02.960 --> 00:32:06.880
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I don't know too many other libertarians and I don't even like to use that label now

00:32:06.880 --> 00:32:12.800
[Amit Varma]: because I think labels make people think in tribal ways. So what I would kind of say is,

00:32:12.800 --> 00:32:17.400
[Amit Varma]: if I may speculate on why it may be the case that children of bureaucrats might tend to

00:32:17.400 --> 00:32:21.840
[Amit Varma]: distrust the state a little bit more is that they don't think of the state in abstract

00:32:21.840 --> 00:32:26.760
[Amit Varma]: terms anymore, that they have seen some concrete effect of it because in a sense, they are

00:32:26.760 --> 00:32:31.960
[Amit Varma]: part of it and beneficiaries of it in indirect ways. So perhaps that could be a reason but

00:32:31.960 --> 00:32:36.880
[Amit Varma]: I never actually consciously thought about it. As it happens, my father was a remarkably

00:32:36.880 --> 00:32:41.800
[Amit Varma]: honest IAS officer and known for that and perhaps even suffered for that. But regardless

00:32:41.800 --> 00:32:45.480
[Amit Varma]: of that, I think the state is all around you. But I would like to think that, you know,

00:32:45.480 --> 00:32:50.680
[Amit Varma]: just growing up in those times, even if my father wasn't who he was, I would probably

00:32:50.680 --> 00:32:58.120
[Amit Varma]: have, you know, grown to think the way that I do. Because in fact, I was not like a libertarian

00:32:58.120 --> 00:33:02.520
[Amit Varma]: in childhood or something. Like I said, I was mildly left liberal if there's any problem

00:33:02.520 --> 00:33:07.280
[Amit Varma]: my, you know, I'd want the state to step in and solve it. And, you know, all my intent

00:33:07.280 --> 00:33:10.480
[Amit Varma]: for everything would be compassionate. And I would not think about outcomes and the way

00:33:10.480 --> 00:33:15.680
[Amit Varma]: the world really works. And it's really much later in adulthood that I kind of turned away

00:33:15.680 --> 00:33:20.680
[Amit Varma]: from that. But I would say that, you know, what you call libertarianism is, I think,

00:33:20.680 --> 00:33:24.680
[Amit Varma]: a common human decency that all of us share. And this is something I want to elaborate

00:33:24.680 --> 00:33:28.880
[Amit Varma]: on at book length at some point. But the point of it is that in the concrete in our personal

00:33:28.880 --> 00:33:33.160
[Amit Varma]: lives, most of us behave in ways that you would call libertarian, we respect the consent

00:33:33.160 --> 00:33:37.880
[Amit Varma]: of others, we don't try to coerce others, we won't force somebody else to pay for our

00:33:37.880 --> 00:33:42.120
[Amit Varma]: preferences. If we go to a restaurant with a bunch of friends, you know, we won't force

00:33:42.120 --> 00:33:46.400
[Amit Varma]: everyone to order exactly what we're ordering, and so on and so forth. But when we go beyond

00:33:46.400 --> 00:33:50.080
[Amit Varma]: the concrete and talk about the abstract, and we talk about the state, suddenly these

00:33:50.080 --> 00:33:57.000
[Amit Varma]: values go for a toss. And we, you know, because we don't see the cost of the sort of coercion,

00:33:57.000 --> 00:34:02.640
[Amit Varma]: and the other things that we then begin to recommend. So I would say that in our personal

00:34:02.640 --> 00:34:07.240
[Amit Varma]: lives, most of us, if we are decent human beings, we are by default, what you are calling

00:34:07.240 --> 00:34:12.720
[Amit Varma]: libertarians. I mean, I use the term in a shorthand way. And, you know, I'm just wary

00:34:12.720 --> 00:34:18.240
[Amit Varma]: of using terms like these, because they're so tribal, but all of that. So I say that,

00:34:18.240 --> 00:34:23.160
[Amit Varma]: so I don't know what part that played in my life. And I know the kids of a handful of

00:34:23.160 --> 00:34:29.880
[Amit Varma]: bureaucrats and none of them think like me. So I think maybe Rajat's experience is different.

00:34:29.880 --> 00:34:33.440
[Amit Varma]: I wonder how, you know, I should have asked him this during the episode, but it never

00:34:33.440 --> 00:34:39.280
[Amit Varma]: came up. I wonder how truck drivers feel about sort of the state, because they are actually

00:34:39.280 --> 00:34:44.160
[Amit Varma]: constantly victims in so many different ways of the oppressiveness of the state. So given

00:34:44.160 --> 00:34:49.480
[Amit Varma]: how so many of us normalize that, perhaps they don't think about it at all.

00:34:49.480 --> 00:34:54.520
[Guest]: The next question I want to ask you comes from another one of my favorite episodes on

00:34:54.520 --> 00:35:00.400
[Guest]: your show, which is Chinmay Tumbe. And you know, his wonderful book and work on migration

00:35:00.400 --> 00:35:05.160
[Guest]: that you talked about. And it just, you know, some of these stories, like whether it's Rajat's

00:35:05.160 --> 00:35:10.120
[Guest]: book or Chinmay's book, to me, when I heard the episode, it didn't feel like it was about

00:35:10.120 --> 00:35:15.640
[Guest]: truck drivers or it was about migration. It felt like it was this broad story about India

00:35:15.640 --> 00:35:20.960
[Guest]: and Indians. And there is like this universality to these themes, like whether it's migration,

00:35:20.960 --> 00:35:25.760
[Guest]: whether it's driving, that each one of us can immediately connect to what it is that's

00:35:25.760 --> 00:35:31.680
[Guest]: going on. So big shout out to both of them. And I'm going to play Chinmay's question for

00:35:31.680 --> 00:35:32.680
[Unknown]: you now.

00:35:32.680 --> 00:35:37.880
[Unknown]: Hi, Amit. This is Chinmay Tumbe here. Congrats on your 200th episode. As you know, I love

00:35:37.880 --> 00:35:41.680
[Unknown]: migration. And so my question for you is tell us something about your own migration story.

00:35:41.680 --> 00:35:42.680
[Unknown]: What are your roots?

00:35:42.680 --> 00:35:48.720
[Amit Varma]: Oh, yeah, my own migration story. So I mean, there are two ways in which I can tackle this

00:35:48.720 --> 00:35:53.120
[Amit Varma]: question. And one, I've already kind of spoken about my background born and brought up in

00:35:53.120 --> 00:35:59.080
[Amit Varma]: Chandigarh and then moved to, studied in Pune for a few years, was in Delhi where I worked

00:35:59.080 --> 00:36:04.520
[Amit Varma]: in HTA for a year and then Bombay since then, the last 25 years, more than that. But before

00:36:04.520 --> 00:36:09.560
[Amit Varma]: that, if you kind of look at where my parents are from, my mother was, you know, a Calcutta

00:36:09.560 --> 00:36:16.040
[Amit Varma]: person, a hardcore Bengali, a Bhattacharya as it were. And my father was born in 1941

00:36:16.040 --> 00:36:22.080
[Amit Varma]: in what is now Pakistan in Sheikhupura, which is a place in Lahore. And as a kid shifted

00:36:22.080 --> 00:36:28.200
[Amit Varma]: to Calcutta, and he and my mom, you know, met in college and had a roaring love affair,

00:36:28.200 --> 00:36:33.000
[Amit Varma]: which was the talk of the town and parental opposition, and all of that nonsense. And

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:37.080
[Amit Varma]: I guess fortunately, or unfortunately, for me, they kind of battled through. In fact,

00:36:37.080 --> 00:36:42.440
[Amit Varma]: it's an interesting story. My father had, you know, when he graduated, he had sort of

00:36:42.440 --> 00:36:48.040
[Amit Varma]: options where he had, he had private sector offers, I think from Clarion Advertising,

00:36:48.040 --> 00:36:52.480
[Amit Varma]: which was then the number one to join the then editor of EPW. And this would have been

00:36:52.480 --> 00:36:57.120
[Amit Varma]: the mid to early 60s. The then editor of EPW loved something he did. And he said, come

00:36:57.120 --> 00:37:01.240
[Amit Varma]: and work with me. And one day you will be the editor and all of that. He also I think

00:37:01.240 --> 00:37:05.840
[Amit Varma]: got a scholarship to Cambridge, Cambridge and whatever, for further studies, but he

00:37:05.840 --> 00:37:10.040
[Amit Varma]: wanted to marry my mother. And my mother's father said the boy must have a job and a

00:37:10.040 --> 00:37:14.640
[Amit Varma]: proper job, not some silly private sector job. And what is this going on over the place

00:37:14.640 --> 00:37:20.560
[Amit Varma]: for studying? So my, so my father decided that, okay, he'll try for the IAS. So without

00:37:20.560 --> 00:37:26.880
[Amit Varma]: really preparing for it, he gave the entrance exam and go through and voila. And, and the

00:37:26.880 --> 00:37:31.800
[Amit Varma]: interesting thing is when I asked him about his past, and in fact, at one point, I thought

00:37:31.800 --> 00:37:35.800
[Amit Varma]: that I should record these memories. So I sat down with a recorder and recorded a couple

00:37:35.800 --> 00:37:39.160
[Amit Varma]: of hours of me talking to him not for the purpose of publishing anywhere, but just for

00:37:39.160 --> 00:37:44.120
[Amit Varma]: my own sort of personal memories. And he doesn't really kind of care about his past. Like,

00:37:44.120 --> 00:37:47.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, when I was going to Pakistan for the cricket tour in 2006, I said, where were

00:37:47.360 --> 00:37:51.240
[Amit Varma]: you born? You know, should I probably go there? And he said, No, no, don't bother. I don't

00:37:51.240 --> 00:37:56.200
[Amit Varma]: even remember. It doesn't mean anything to me. So, you know, that's kind of how it was.

00:37:56.200 --> 00:38:00.680
[Amit Varma]: And I once I've asked him a couple of times about counterfactuals about how his life would

00:38:00.680 --> 00:38:04.520
[Amit Varma]: have been had he say gone to Cambridge or done this or done that or whatever. And he

00:38:04.520 --> 00:38:11.160
[Amit Varma]: always kind of hedges and doesn't really give an answer to that. And but anyway, I mean,

00:38:11.160 --> 00:38:15.560
[Amit Varma]: here I am. So all's well that ended well. The other way to answer that migration question

00:38:15.560 --> 00:38:21.600
[Amit Varma]: is to also think about it in terms of the mental geographies we inhabit. That while

00:38:21.600 --> 00:38:25.680
[Amit Varma]: I have, of course, been born and brought up in India and have lived here all my life,

00:38:25.680 --> 00:38:29.680
[Amit Varma]: the mental geographies I have inhabited, and this would be true much more for millennials

00:38:29.680 --> 00:38:34.680
[Amit Varma]: here today than perhaps would be people of my generation. But the mental geographies

00:38:34.680 --> 00:38:39.800
[Amit Varma]: were always Western, in some senses, all the books I read were in English, and they were

00:38:39.800 --> 00:38:45.080
[Amit Varma]: from all across the world. And all the music I heard was largely American and rock and

00:38:45.080 --> 00:38:51.080
[Amit Varma]: all of that. And my mental landscapes were mental, my Western, my ways of thinking about

00:38:51.080 --> 00:38:58.480
[Amit Varma]: the world were Western. So I think that, you know, people in India are a kichri in more

00:38:58.480 --> 00:39:04.440
[Amit Varma]: ways than just their physical geographies may indicate. And by the way, I want to say,

00:39:04.440 --> 00:39:09.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, whenever someone asked me to recommend a book that they should read about India,

00:39:09.080 --> 00:39:13.360
[Amit Varma]: I don't recommend some of the famous books that I've done episodes on, I recommend India

00:39:13.360 --> 00:39:16.920
[Amit Varma]: Moving by Chinmay Tummey, because I think it's a masterpiece, one of the best books

00:39:16.920 --> 00:39:21.800
[Amit Varma]: of the last decade. And people haven't heard of it. And that's just such a blooming tragedy.

00:39:21.800 --> 00:39:25.480
[Amit Varma]: So kindly go and listen to my episode with him because it tells us so much about who

00:39:25.480 --> 00:39:31.220
[Amit Varma]: we are. It has so many TIL moments. Like, for example, you know, the biggest TIL moment

00:39:31.220 --> 00:39:37.000
[Amit Varma]: in that episode for me while reading the book, in fact, for me was when he spoke about how

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:41.800
[Amit Varma]: the highest amount of migration in India happens when women get married and they leave their

00:39:41.800 --> 00:39:45.960
[Amit Varma]: parental homes and they go to their marital homes. And most of us won't even and it's

00:39:45.960 --> 00:39:50.560
[Amit Varma]: invisible, it's invisible. Most of us because we have such a male centric view of the world

00:39:50.560 --> 00:39:56.240
[Amit Varma]: wouldn't even think of that as migration, right? You know, it just seems so natural.

00:39:56.240 --> 00:40:00.400
[Amit Varma]: You're going from one home to another home, but it is migration and what are the influences

00:40:00.400 --> 00:40:06.560
[Amit Varma]: that has and what happens. So it's a wonderful book. I'm sorry, I can't help plugging past

00:40:06.560 --> 00:40:08.360
[Amit Varma]: episodes and books that I have enjoyed.

00:40:08.360 --> 00:40:13.200
[Guest]: No, I'm thrilled because part of why I wanted to do this with you is also reflect on these

00:40:13.200 --> 00:40:17.760
[Guest]: episodes, right? And the wonderful moments that have taken place. I want to take Chinmay's

00:40:17.760 --> 00:40:22.600
[Guest]: question one step further and ask you some of the counterfactuals, right? Are there places

00:40:22.600 --> 00:40:29.560
[Guest]: you chose not to migrate to where you had maybe job offers or, you know, family or school

00:40:29.560 --> 00:40:32.800
[Guest]: or, you know, what were the parts you did not take?

00:40:32.800 --> 00:40:37.560
[Amit Varma]: Well, so like I said, when I was a kid, you know, growing up as a kid in the FBI, where

00:40:37.560 --> 00:40:42.120
[Amit Varma]: my father was director, I used to watch movies all the time. And at that point, you know,

00:40:42.120 --> 00:40:45.720
[Amit Varma]: I wanted to be a writer since I was like, four or five years old. But at that point,

00:40:45.720 --> 00:40:51.120
[Amit Varma]: I said, I also want to be a filmmaker. And my father through his connection said, Listen,

00:40:51.120 --> 00:40:54.600
[Amit Varma]: you know, after you're done with whatever I can get you admission into the French Film

00:40:54.600 --> 00:40:58.760
[Amit Varma]: Institute because a director there is a friend and blah, blah, blah, and we can do something

00:40:58.760 --> 00:41:03.080
[Amit Varma]: and you want to go and I was a lazy bum. I said, I left to learn French. He said, Yes,

00:41:03.080 --> 00:41:09.080
[Amit Varma]: I said, forget it. I'm cool here. And I didn't go. So, which I have actually not thought

00:41:09.080 --> 00:41:13.360
[Amit Varma]: about since the time that conversation happened. But since you asked me, I suppose that is

00:41:13.360 --> 00:41:17.840
[Amit Varma]: one counterfactual. And for what it's worth, I'm still passionate about cinema, but I decided

00:41:17.840 --> 00:41:22.720
[Amit Varma]: not to follow that path because your creative product is dependent on too many other people

00:41:22.720 --> 00:41:26.480
[Amit Varma]: and too many things falling into place. And I said, with my writing, I can just turn out

00:41:26.480 --> 00:41:29.920
[Amit Varma]: books on my own, it doesn't matter. Now it so happens I've been a lazy bum. And I haven't

00:41:29.920 --> 00:41:34.160
[Amit Varma]: actually written the 15 books I should have by now, though there is time to make up for

00:41:34.160 --> 00:41:40.720
[Amit Varma]: that. But I don't really have any big counterfactuals. Apart from that, the fact is, I was, you know,

00:41:40.720 --> 00:41:44.920
[Amit Varma]: if you want to look at counterfactuals, it would not be in terms of opportunities that

00:41:44.920 --> 00:41:51.000
[Amit Varma]: came to me, but parts that I chose not to chase. So I could have gone, you know, I'm

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:56.280
[Amit Varma]: sure I could have gone the IIT IIM way if I wanted to. But I wanted to do arts because

00:41:56.280 --> 00:42:01.800
[Amit Varma]: I wanted to write at some point. I'm sure if I really wanted to, I could have gone abroad

00:42:01.800 --> 00:42:06.240
[Amit Varma]: and studied there and made a life there. But when I was young, I had this very rebellious

00:42:06.240 --> 00:42:09.640
[Amit Varma]: attitude of why should I go abroad, I will do things on my own. And I was very anti the

00:42:09.640 --> 00:42:17.640
[Amit Varma]: education system, and just anti just all those traditional paths that people take. And, and

00:42:17.640 --> 00:42:21.240
[Amit Varma]: I don't regret any of that. I mean, if I have any regrets is that I haven't worked hard

00:42:21.240 --> 00:42:26.200
[Amit Varma]: enough at what I set out to do. But I am convinced that I set out to do the right thing.

00:42:26.200 --> 00:42:31.600
[Guest]: No, absolutely. Now, the next part, you know, I mean, since we were talking about the parts

00:42:31.600 --> 00:42:38.360
[Guest]: that you have taken, and you haven't taken, these are two of not just your guests, you

00:42:38.360 --> 00:42:43.600
[Guest]: know, that I whom I have loved in the episodes, and so on. But also two of my favorite people

00:42:43.600 --> 00:42:49.280
[Guest]: who've come on your show. One of them I know well, and it's Prem Panikkar. The other one

00:42:49.280 --> 00:42:54.680
[Guest]: I don't know at all, Joy Bhattacharya, but I feel like I know him through your episode

00:42:54.680 --> 00:42:58.800
[Guest]: through a number of other things he does. Also, because I'm a cricket widow. And you

00:42:58.800 --> 00:43:04.360
[Guest]: know, he's kind of around in the background if you're a cricket widow. And I love him

00:43:04.360 --> 00:43:09.520
[Guest]: on Twitter. I love everything that he does. So I'm going to play you first Prem Panikkar's

00:43:09.520 --> 00:43:14.120
[Guest]: question and then Joy Bhattacharya's question and you will know why in a minute that they

00:43:14.120 --> 00:43:15.120
[Guest]: are coming together.

00:43:15.120 --> 00:43:23.880
[Unknown]: Hey, Amit. Congratulations on the double hundred and here's the triple and beyond. You've had

00:43:23.880 --> 00:43:29.720
[Unknown]: a storied career. You've been a cricket writer, editor, fiction writer, columnist, a two-time

00:43:29.720 --> 00:43:37.880
[Unknown]: winner of the Bastiat, a poker player, pioneering podcaster, writing coach. I may have left

00:43:37.880 --> 00:43:44.240
[Unknown]: out a couple of things, but that's quite a comprehensive CV as it stands. So which of

00:43:44.240 --> 00:43:50.440
[Unknown]: these gives you the greatest satisfaction? And what is that one thing or things that

00:43:50.440 --> 00:43:53.920
[Unknown]: is on your bucket list of things that you still want to do?

00:43:53.920 --> 00:44:00.960
[Unknown]: Hi, Amit. Congratulations for 200 incredible episodes. So this is my turn to ask you a

00:44:00.960 --> 00:44:05.800
[Unknown]: question. And here's my question. You've had many of that, from being a cricket writer

00:44:05.800 --> 00:44:12.360
[Unknown]: to working in MTV as a producer, to being a poker player, to being an award-winning

00:44:12.360 --> 00:44:18.960
[Unknown]: business journalist, and now a podcast host. So if you had to make a choice, which one

00:44:18.960 --> 00:44:23.640
[Unknown]: of these previous professions or vocations would you have avoided? If you had to lose

00:44:23.640 --> 00:44:26.640
[Amit Varma]: one of them, which one would it be?

00:44:26.640 --> 00:44:30.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. Lovely questions by both of them. And they're both people who are personally close

00:44:30.560 --> 00:44:35.120
[Amit Varma]: to me. I respect them a lot and I'm really fond of them. And Prem has been on a couple

00:44:35.120 --> 00:44:41.160
[Amit Varma]: of episodes and Joy was on a very memorable episode about sports ecosystems where I, you

00:44:41.160 --> 00:44:45.080
[Amit Varma]: know, the second half of that episode with Joy where he talks about, you know, all the

00:44:45.080 --> 00:44:49.280
[Amit Varma]: work he did setting up the football under 17 World Cup and all of that was just made

00:44:49.280 --> 00:44:53.800
[Amit Varma]: me so happy. And it was so inspiring because, you know, I was like, here is another idealistic

00:44:53.800 --> 00:44:57.520
[Amit Varma]: fool. So someone who's making much more of a difference to the world than I managed to,

00:44:57.520 --> 00:45:02.760
[Amit Varma]: but just absolutely wonderful people and wonderful episodes. To answer that question, I, you

00:45:02.760 --> 00:45:06.920
[Amit Varma]: know, the tragedy is, I think none of them mentioned the one thing that I really thought

00:45:06.920 --> 00:45:11.440
[Amit Varma]: of myself all my life as and which I haven't really done enough of, which is writing novels,

00:45:11.440 --> 00:45:15.120
[Amit Varma]: writing fiction or literature or whatever. And I haven't done enough of that. And I will

00:45:15.120 --> 00:45:21.600
[Amit Varma]: at some point do more of that. I've just written one shitty book, as I said, long ago and which

00:45:21.600 --> 00:45:26.360
[Amit Varma]: was, yeah. So, you know, but out of all of these, look, the early years, like I don't

00:45:26.360 --> 00:45:30.520
[Amit Varma]: even mention advertising or television on my CV because it just doesn't mean anything

00:45:30.520 --> 00:45:35.280
[Amit Varma]: to me. It didn't enrich my life, didn't teach me anything. You know, as I think I enjoyed

00:45:35.280 --> 00:45:41.520
[Amit Varma]: my blogging a lot, because sort of the more you write, you know, writing forces you to

00:45:41.520 --> 00:45:46.640
[Amit Varma]: think. And, you know, there's something that I talk to my writing students about when I

00:45:46.640 --> 00:45:50.560
[Amit Varma]: teach writing these days is that there is a two way causal relationship between clear

00:45:50.560 --> 00:45:54.680
[Amit Varma]: writing and clear thinking. That not just that if you're, you know, it's obvious that

00:45:54.680 --> 00:45:59.600
[Amit Varma]: if you're a clear thinker, you're more likely to write clearly. But equally, if you force

00:45:59.600 --> 00:46:03.640
[Amit Varma]: yourself to write clearly in simple language about complex things, you have to think that

00:46:03.640 --> 00:46:09.600
[Amit Varma]: much deeper about whatever you're writing. And that just improves the way that you think.

00:46:09.600 --> 00:46:14.000
[Amit Varma]: So I think all that prolific writing that I did in my blogging years was useful to me.

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:18.360
[Amit Varma]: I'm kind of, I'm happy with that. But you know, I used to say until recently that there

00:46:18.360 --> 00:46:24.840
[Amit Varma]: is nothing I have done in my life that I can really be proud of. I think to some extent,

00:46:24.840 --> 00:46:30.040
[Amit Varma]: now when I think about it, I think the scene in the unseen is I think I've created value.

00:46:30.040 --> 00:46:33.040
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, it's an ongoing journey, but I'm proud of some of the conversations that

00:46:33.040 --> 00:46:40.840
[Amit Varma]: I've done. I also think that in what is a very new field, I've been able to sort of

00:46:40.840 --> 00:46:45.400
[Amit Varma]: gather a certain understanding about a medium which did not exist there earlier, like I'm

00:46:45.400 --> 00:46:50.440
[Amit Varma]: teaching a podcasting course now. And while preparing for it, so I had a whole bunch of

00:46:50.440 --> 00:46:54.200
[Amit Varma]: insights, I wrote that down, structured it. And then I thought, let me see what others

00:46:54.200 --> 00:46:58.360
[Amit Varma]: have taught. And I tried started going through other podcasting courses. And they were all

00:46:58.360 --> 00:47:03.000
[Amit Varma]: like your basic dummies guide to podcasting kind of thing. These are the kind of mics,

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:08.000
[Amit Varma]: this is how you edit, this is how you do and none of the conceptual stuff that I had gathered

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:12.720
[Amit Varma]: over all this time. Like why is audio so different as a medium which people don't get so many

00:47:12.720 --> 00:47:17.340
[Amit Varma]: people think of it as video with visuals, but it is incredibly different in every way.

00:47:17.340 --> 00:47:22.240
[Amit Varma]: Why are podcasts so different from radio podcast is not just radio on demand. Like people think

00:47:22.240 --> 00:47:28.400
[Amit Varma]: of Netflix as TV on demand, and that's correct. But podcasts are much more than radio on demand.

00:47:28.400 --> 00:47:34.200
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, and some of that also came from my realizing the insane level of engagement

00:47:34.200 --> 00:47:40.600
[Amit Varma]: with which my listeners have with the show, and the sense that many of them have that

00:47:40.600 --> 00:47:46.600
[Amit Varma]: this means something to them that they have a stake in it, you know, and all of that.

00:47:46.600 --> 00:47:52.440
[Amit Varma]: So in that sense, I think that, you know, I've kind of the podcasting journey is very

00:47:52.440 --> 00:47:58.200
[Amit Varma]: interesting, and it's an ongoing one. And I'm sort of enjoying it. But at some point,

00:47:58.200 --> 00:48:02.440
[Amit Varma]: if I had to give up any of them, look at give up the poker years, not because I mean, I

00:48:02.440 --> 00:48:06.920
[Amit Varma]: took it up because it was a an intellectual challenge and be unlike my other great passion

00:48:06.920 --> 00:48:10.880
[Amit Varma]: until then, which was writing, I actually saw I could make money off poker. And I did.

00:48:10.880 --> 00:48:15.200
[Amit Varma]: And one of the reasons I left was that I thought I'd played for a while make a few money and

00:48:15.200 --> 00:48:19.680
[Amit Varma]: then you know, do my thing. And I found it doesn't really scale that way. You know, you

00:48:19.680 --> 00:48:24.520
[Amit Varma]: get to a certain point. And after that, it becomes a question of access to bigger games.

00:48:24.520 --> 00:48:30.720
[Amit Varma]: And it becomes very political in that respect. And also, it destroys your lifestyle because

00:48:30.720 --> 00:48:34.160
[Amit Varma]: you're playing like, you'll play a 15 hour session, come back, sleep for eight hours,

00:48:34.160 --> 00:48:37.640
[Amit Varma]: go play another session. And I also found that during those years, I felt like I was

00:48:37.640 --> 00:48:42.520
[Amit Varma]: getting dumber. Because poker, you have to be obsessive to be good at poker, and you

00:48:42.520 --> 00:48:46.880
[Amit Varma]: can't do anything else. So I stopped reading books, I stopped hanging out with friends

00:48:46.880 --> 00:48:50.680
[Amit Varma]: apart from the people I played poker with. And you know, I was reading the biography

00:48:50.680 --> 00:48:54.840
[Amit Varma]: of some famous poker player of the 70s. And there was a story about how for 20 and he

00:48:54.840 --> 00:48:58.400
[Amit Varma]: was an American player. And there was a story of how for 20 years, he didn't know who the

00:48:58.400 --> 00:49:03.680
[Amit Varma]: president of the US was. And I could understand that, because it was just constricting my

00:49:03.680 --> 00:49:07.840
[Amit Varma]: whole whole world. And I felt my brain and I felt I have to get out. So even though I

00:49:07.840 --> 00:49:14.320
[Amit Varma]: am not knocking, kind of what I did, going back, if I had to give a piece of advice to

00:49:14.320 --> 00:49:19.480
[Amit Varma]: my younger self in 2009, it would be no, no, no, don't don't play poker, just just just

00:49:19.480 --> 00:49:24.720
[Amit Varma]: focus on writing and do your thing. But poker also taught me a lot about the world that

00:49:24.720 --> 00:49:28.360
[Amit Varma]: I think enriched the way I think about the world. For example, I think of the world much

00:49:28.360 --> 00:49:33.800
[Amit Varma]: more in probabilistic ways, I recognize the impact of luck in our lives much more, which

00:49:33.800 --> 00:49:40.160
[Amit Varma]: most people don't. Most people give too much credit to their agency and what they have.

00:49:40.160 --> 00:49:43.960
[Amit Varma]: You know, they imagine they are responsible for their successes and their failures. And

00:49:43.960 --> 00:49:48.520
[Amit Varma]: that's true to a very small extent, you know. So when we succeed, we'll tend to let it get

00:49:48.520 --> 00:49:52.120
[Amit Varma]: to our heads and become arrogant. And when we fail, we let it get ourselves down and

00:49:52.120 --> 00:49:56.800
[Amit Varma]: it will hurt our self image. And the truth is, in both of those is a lot of luck involved.

00:49:56.800 --> 00:50:02.680
[Amit Varma]: And part of what you have to do as you go through life is become equanimous about the

00:50:02.680 --> 00:50:07.040
[Amit Varma]: outcomes of the things that you do and the and the cards that life deals you like in

00:50:07.040 --> 00:50:11.920
[Amit Varma]: poker, you you know that, you know, it's a game of skill, but the quantum of luck is

00:50:11.920 --> 00:50:16.360
[Amit Varma]: much higher than in other sports or games of skill. So any single hand will be mostly

00:50:16.360 --> 00:50:21.280
[Amit Varma]: luck. It's over a long period that the edge, the skill plays out. So you play a hundred

00:50:21.280 --> 00:50:25.760
[Amit Varma]: thousand two hundred thousand hands. The tragedy is that in life, you cannot do that. In life,

00:50:25.760 --> 00:50:30.480
[Amit Varma]: you get the cards that you get and it is what it is. But it is still important not to sweat

00:50:30.480 --> 00:50:35.280
[Amit Varma]: what you cannot control and instead to focus on what you can control, which is you focus

00:50:35.280 --> 00:50:40.320
[Amit Varma]: on the process or as that great poker player Lord Krishna once said, you know, just do

00:50:40.320 --> 00:50:44.600
[Amit Varma]: the right thing and don't worry about the fruits of your action.

00:50:44.600 --> 00:50:48.760
[Guest]: So before you continue on this, because, you know, you keep anticipating the questions,

00:50:48.760 --> 00:50:54.400
[Guest]: which is very frustrating for me as a host, because you you can almost see what's coming

00:50:54.400 --> 00:51:01.560
[Guest]: next. I have a question for you from Akshaya Mukul, also, who has been on your show. He

00:51:01.560 --> 00:51:07.040
[Guest]: wrote this fantastic book about the Gita Press. Once again, you know, it was one of those

00:51:07.040 --> 00:51:12.360
[Guest]: books that just opened my eyes to this entire world and subculture that I didn't know existed.

00:51:12.360 --> 00:51:16.960
[Guest]: And Akshaya Mukul has really become one of my favorite thinkers. So, you know, I'm just

00:51:16.960 --> 00:51:19.960
[Guest]: going to play his question for you and then we can continue talking about poker.

00:51:19.960 --> 00:51:25.800
[Unknown]: Hello, Amit. Akshaya Mukul here. Good to see my favorite podcaster being interviewed by

00:51:25.800 --> 00:51:31.760
[Unknown]: my favorite columnist, Shruti. Can you tell listeners about your life as a poker player?

00:51:31.760 --> 00:51:36.480
[Unknown]: Thanks, Shruti, for this opportunity. See you both in person soon.

00:51:36.480 --> 00:51:41.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's a lovely episode and Akshaya is such a wonderful, warm person and I can't

00:51:41.280 --> 00:51:44.720
[Amit Varma]: wait to see him soon as well. And that's a great book. Again, I'll say that that's again,

00:51:44.720 --> 00:51:48.760
[Amit Varma]: you know, I don't I don't in this age of hyperbole when you use terms like masterpiece, it almost

00:51:48.760 --> 00:51:54.240
[Amit Varma]: feels like, you know, it's but again, as in the case of Chinmay's book for Akshaya's book,

00:51:54.240 --> 00:51:59.040
[Amit Varma]: I absolutely mean it. The book he's written on the Gita Press is just incredible and so

00:51:59.040 --> 00:52:04.000
[Amit Varma]: eye opening for someone like me. So my life as a poker player would, you know, this gets

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:08.680
[Amit Varma]: into odd territory because poker is illegal in India and it's only legal in the offshore

00:52:08.680 --> 00:52:14.520
[Amit Varma]: casinos of Goa, which is where I first started playing. I think in 2009, I took a holiday

00:52:14.520 --> 00:52:21.280
[Amit Varma]: to Goa and we went to Casino Royale, the offshore casino there, played a little bit of poker,

00:52:21.280 --> 00:52:25.640
[Amit Varma]: had beginner's luck, and then decided this is what I want to do. And of course, I didn't

00:52:25.640 --> 00:52:29.480
[Amit Varma]: know anything about the game then. But as I studied the game, the intellectual challenges

00:52:29.480 --> 00:52:34.640
[Amit Varma]: overtook me and I kind of loved getting into the math and the game theory and all of that

00:52:34.640 --> 00:52:40.040
[Amit Varma]: and that sort of changed the way I think about it. And I used to write a column on poker

00:52:40.040 --> 00:52:45.440
[Amit Varma]: for the Economic Times as well, which I think I wrote 42 installments for them and stopped

00:52:45.440 --> 00:52:50.920
[Amit Varma]: it at exactly the point where I decided to leave poker. And one of the interesting things

00:52:50.920 --> 00:52:55.920
[Amit Varma]: about poker is that it is on the intersection of being a serious sport slash science and

00:52:55.920 --> 00:53:01.680
[Amit Varma]: gambling. So, you know, you might be treating it as a serious sport and a serious science,

00:53:01.680 --> 00:53:06.520
[Amit Varma]: but there are people who are sitting with you who are essentially just addicted to gambling.

00:53:06.520 --> 00:53:10.480
[Amit Varma]: They're playing it for the dopamine rushes. And I wrote columns about this as well. It's,

00:53:10.480 --> 00:53:15.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, the way the, I mean, gambling addiction in biochemical terms is, you know, the same

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:21.440
[Amit Varma]: as addiction to alcohol or cigarettes or whatever you take a puff or you drink a peg, you get

00:53:21.440 --> 00:53:28.920
[Amit Varma]: that dopamine rush. It's a similar thing with sort of gambling. And that led to this period

00:53:28.920 --> 00:53:33.080
[Amit Varma]: of frustration where I felt that what is the point of my skill? It's I'm not playing against

00:53:33.080 --> 00:53:38.120
[Amit Varma]: other people who are also treating it as a serious skill and as a game theoretical thing.

00:53:38.120 --> 00:53:43.160
[Amit Varma]: I am playing it with people. And by this, I mean, in the underground cash games that

00:53:43.160 --> 00:53:48.040
[Amit Varma]: I used to play in Mumbai and around who are just sitting off, you know, have no idea what

00:53:48.040 --> 00:53:51.880
[Amit Varma]: they're doing. And eventually, it's all going to come to us. And I remember there was me

00:53:51.880 --> 00:53:56.520
[Amit Varma]: and a very close friend of mine who's also pro and a really good player and who's gone

00:53:56.520 --> 00:54:02.080
[Amit Varma]: on to do phenomenally well in the last five years since I left, though not because I left,

00:54:02.080 --> 00:54:06.800
[Amit Varma]: but in general. So he and I were at a game together in Vashi. And there was a third person

00:54:06.800 --> 00:54:10.240
[Amit Varma]: in the game after the whole game had wound up and he was a big builder there and he was

00:54:10.240 --> 00:54:15.280
[Amit Varma]: high on cocaine and he will just every hand he would just, you know, push a ton of chips

00:54:15.280 --> 00:54:19.840
[Amit Varma]: and huge amounts of money blind without looking at his cards. So it's only a matter of time,

00:54:19.840 --> 00:54:25.560
[Amit Varma]: right? And then we are driving back and both my friend and I, his name is Jagdeep and both

00:54:25.560 --> 00:54:29.600
[Amit Varma]: Jagdeep and I were, we didn't feel good about the whole thing. And we were like that, what

00:54:29.600 --> 00:54:34.000
[Amit Varma]: is the difference between us and drug dealers? It almost feels like we're exploiting someone's

00:54:34.000 --> 00:54:38.160
[Amit Varma]: addiction. So there was that aspect of it where, as you would know, I keep talking about

00:54:38.160 --> 00:54:43.120
[Amit Varma]: all how all human interactions are positive, some interactions, right? So if I create a

00:54:43.120 --> 00:54:47.600
[Amit Varma]: podcast and someone listens to it, and like every interaction that takes place is a double

00:54:47.600 --> 00:54:51.440
[Amit Varma]: thank you moment, both people benefit, which is why they say thank you to each other. Poker

00:54:51.440 --> 00:54:55.480
[Amit Varma]: is not like that, right? It's a zero sum game. And you know, considering that if you're playing

00:54:55.480 --> 00:55:00.280
[Amit Varma]: at a place where the game is being great, it's actually a negative sum game. And you

00:55:00.280 --> 00:55:04.360
[Amit Varma]: only win when someone else loses. And someone else losing is not just someone else losing

00:55:04.360 --> 00:55:10.160
[Amit Varma]: someone else losing means their sort of lives could just fall apart. And I've seen that

00:55:10.160 --> 00:55:14.600
[Amit Varma]: happening to people. I've tried to make interventions in the case of two friends of mine who were

00:55:14.600 --> 00:55:21.520
[Amit Varma]: addicted to gambling. And I remember, you know, I mean, there are just very sad stories.

00:55:21.520 --> 00:55:25.440
[Amit Varma]: I don't want to get into them right now. But one thing you realize is that interventions

00:55:25.440 --> 00:55:29.720
[Amit Varma]: don't help. And people might rationally realize that they're addicted to something, but they

00:55:29.720 --> 00:55:33.840
[Amit Varma]: can't help themselves. You know, and I, for example, see that, like, I think I might be

00:55:33.840 --> 00:55:38.680
[Amit Varma]: addicted to social media, for example. So, you know, or maybe addicted to distraction

00:55:38.680 --> 00:55:41.920
[Amit Varma]: if they can be such a thing. But the bottom line is, I think all of us know this, that

00:55:41.920 --> 00:55:45.760
[Amit Varma]: we know that I should not, you know, go on Twitter now, or I should not start watching

00:55:45.760 --> 00:55:49.880
[Amit Varma]: a YouTube video now, because I will go down a rabbit hole and watch 50 of them. But then

00:55:49.880 --> 00:55:54.800
[Amit Varma]: you just start and, you know, and most of the time, the sort of the impact of harmless

00:55:54.800 --> 00:56:00.000
[Amit Varma]: addictions like that, as it were, is not such a big deal. Like, when I was trying to wean

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:03.840
[Amit Varma]: friends of mine of poker, I'd say just play online chess here, you know, you know, that's

00:56:03.840 --> 00:56:07.680
[Amit Varma]: a better thing to get addicted to, because you're not losing money, you're losing time.

00:56:07.680 --> 00:56:12.080
[Amit Varma]: And I've just seen horrendous consequences of this. And it all happens below the surface,

00:56:12.080 --> 00:56:15.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, the families of people realize what has happened to them, they may try to help

00:56:15.880 --> 00:56:19.920
[Amit Varma]: them, there's really nothing you can do. It's a downward spiral. And it's horrendous. And

00:56:19.920 --> 00:56:23.920
[Amit Varma]: that's why, you know, when I started playing poker, I had the impression that the winners

00:56:23.920 --> 00:56:28.440
[Amit Varma]: stay in the game, the losers leave the game. And over a period of time, what I realized

00:56:28.440 --> 00:56:32.560
[Amit Varma]: when I was leaving, is that it's the other way around that it's the winners who eventually

00:56:32.560 --> 00:56:36.640
[Amit Varma]: leave the game, but the losers are addicted, they cannot leave the game. So there are all

00:56:36.640 --> 00:56:40.680
[Amit Varma]: these aspects. So while I was an evangelist of poker once upon a time, because it's so

00:56:40.680 --> 00:56:47.360
[Amit Varma]: intellectually stimulating, and all of those things, there is also this other dark, seamy

00:56:47.360 --> 00:56:52.960
[Amit Varma]: side to it. And you cannot, you know, rationalize that by saying that this is, you know, the

00:56:52.960 --> 00:56:56.440
[Amit Varma]: voluntary action of consenting adults and all of that, which of course it is, which

00:56:56.440 --> 00:57:02.160
[Amit Varma]: is why the state should not ban it. But it is nevertheless a social problem. And you

00:57:02.160 --> 00:57:06.760
[Amit Varma]: would hope that, you know, solutions emerge from within society.

00:57:06.760 --> 00:57:12.720
[Guest]: Yeah. And this actually brings me to another really lovely question that Karthika has asked

00:57:12.720 --> 00:57:19.800
[Guest]: almost exactly on this aspect of, you know, you nurturing your love for poker and then

00:57:19.800 --> 00:57:23.280
[Guest]: walking away from it. So I'm going to play Karthika's question now.

00:57:23.280 --> 00:57:30.320
[Unknown]: Hi, Amit. This is Karthika. Congratulations on this fabulous milestone of 200 episodes.

00:57:30.320 --> 00:57:34.800
[Unknown]: And here's my question for you. It's a bit personal, actually. I know you were really

00:57:34.800 --> 00:57:38.720
[Unknown]: involved with poker at one time, you played poker, you wrote about it, then at some point

00:57:38.720 --> 00:57:43.760
[Unknown]: you decided no more. I was reading about addictive personalities the other day. And I wondered,

00:57:43.760 --> 00:57:48.480
[Unknown]: is that how you would describe yourself? What's it like nurturing a love for something and

00:57:48.480 --> 00:57:51.400
[Unknown]: then killing it? I really want to know.

00:57:51.400 --> 00:57:55.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's such a lovely question. And I should say my episode with Karthika is of

00:57:55.040 --> 00:57:59.460
[Amit Varma]: course one of my favorites. And I'm and I kind of mentioned why for sort of those reasons.

00:57:59.460 --> 00:58:03.440
[Amit Varma]: But also, I mean, it's a great episode by itself. But also, she is the publisher at

00:58:03.440 --> 00:58:09.400
[Amit Varma]: Westland. And as I mentioned in the introduction that they are publishing the four volumes

00:58:09.400 --> 00:58:14.000
[Amit Varma]: of the scene and the unseen, you know, selected excerpts from conversations I have had, you

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:18.120
[Amit Varma]: will have to wait a while Shruti to see if your conversations get featured or not. But

00:58:18.120 --> 00:58:21.080
[Amit Varma]: yeah, that's, that's a really good question. And it's something that I thought a lot about

00:58:21.080 --> 00:58:26.360
[Amit Varma]: like, number one, I would venture that many more of us are prone to addiction than we

00:58:26.360 --> 00:58:32.040
[Amit Varma]: think, except that, you know, in some cases, it may manifest in very overt addiction to

00:58:32.040 --> 00:58:36.520
[Amit Varma]: either alcohol or drugs or whatever. But there are so many other things that we can get addicted

00:58:36.520 --> 00:58:41.680
[Amit Varma]: to, like when I, you know, I've done a bunch of episodes with about the Mughal period with

00:58:41.680 --> 00:58:48.000
[Amit Varma]: say, Manu and Manimugdha and Ira Mukherjee and I need to record with her again soon.

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:53.680
[Amit Varma]: She's incredible. And one of the things that keeps coming up again and again, Parvati Sharma

00:58:53.680 --> 00:58:58.000
[Amit Varma]: also, and one of the things that keeps coming up, Supriya Gandhi recently, and one of the

00:58:58.000 --> 00:59:02.320
[Amit Varma]: themes that keeps coming up again and again, and all the wonderful books is how so many

00:59:02.320 --> 00:59:06.960
[Amit Varma]: of these Mughal princes and all that died of alcohol addiction. And the thing is that

00:59:06.960 --> 00:59:10.360
[Amit Varma]: it just strikes me thinking aloud that that is the only thing you would get addicted to

00:59:10.360 --> 00:59:13.640
[Amit Varma]: what else are you there's no social media, there's no Twitter, there's no poker, there's

00:59:13.640 --> 00:59:18.720
[Amit Varma]: no chess. So alcohol is going to be one of the most common ways for affluent people who

00:59:18.720 --> 00:59:23.960
[Amit Varma]: can afford enough alcohol to get addicted to. But to come back to it, I think, you know,

00:59:23.960 --> 00:59:28.960
[Amit Varma]: when I was sort of playing poker, I the thought crossed my mind when I decided to leave that

00:59:28.960 --> 00:59:33.640
[Amit Varma]: I'm a winning player, but it could be the case that I am an addict and a winning player.

00:59:33.640 --> 00:59:38.400
[Amit Varma]: And what will happen if that is the case, and I am glad to report it wasn't the case.

