[Unknown]: about that, though. My question is about poker players. Do you find that people who play

01:05:10.120 --> 01:05:14.840
[Unknown]: poker and who therefore are playing the bluff almost every day and playing it with a lot

01:05:14.840 --> 01:05:20.300
[Unknown]: of skill? Do they live life like that as well? Are they do they take chances? Are they gamblers

01:05:20.300 --> 01:05:25.000
[Unknown]: in life? Are they a little edgy? Or is that a persona they put on when they get on to

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:29.120
[Unknown]: the on to the poker table? Hmm. Love to know.

01:05:29.120 --> 01:05:33.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's such a lovely question. And I really enjoy, I've got to, you know, again,

01:05:33.240 --> 01:05:38.680
[Amit Varma]: a few words about Harsha before I answer this question. My first introduction to audio as

01:05:38.680 --> 01:05:43.920
[Amit Varma]: someone who did audio, my first attempt at audio was, I was, you know, I traveled to

01:05:43.920 --> 01:05:48.720
[Amit Varma]: Pakistan with, you know, following the Indian cricket team in 2006. And I was covering it

01:05:48.720 --> 01:05:52.880
[Amit Varma]: for the Guardian and also writing about it for Crick Info, where I was actually employed

01:05:52.880 --> 01:05:58.720
[Amit Varma]: at the time. And I also got a side gig where for one of the BBC channels every day, I would

01:05:58.720 --> 01:06:02.800
[Amit Varma]: have to give a one minute update on what was happening at the time they called me. And

01:06:02.800 --> 01:06:06.280
[Amit Varma]: if at that, and so I would have my narrative prepared, so many wickets have fallen and

01:06:06.280 --> 01:06:09.960
[Amit Varma]: all that. But I'm actually watching the match at that point. And if something happened right,

01:06:09.960 --> 01:06:14.000
[Amit Varma]: then I would have to weave it in, which I found difficult. So I was struggling with

01:06:14.000 --> 01:06:19.400
[Amit Varma]: that. So Harsha was on the tour as a broadcaster. And at one point, I, you know, I mentioned

01:06:19.400 --> 01:06:22.800
[Amit Varma]: that I had this problem. And he was so kind. I think if I remember, he sat with me for

01:06:22.800 --> 01:06:28.920
[Amit Varma]: half an hour told me about the sort of the all the basics of what to do for radio and,

01:06:28.920 --> 01:06:32.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, really calmed me down and gave me great advice, all of which I have completely

01:06:32.080 --> 01:06:36.480
[Amit Varma]: forgotten. And I didn't do audio after that for many years. But it speaks to his kindness

01:06:36.480 --> 01:06:41.600
[Amit Varma]: that he was also such a huge superstar at the time, like you correctly said, and, and

01:06:41.600 --> 01:06:45.560
[Amit Varma]: such a, you know, a warm and helpful human being. To answer the question, there are different

01:06:45.560 --> 01:06:51.560
[Amit Varma]: aspects to it. Number one is that as far as what are poker players like, do they also

01:06:51.560 --> 01:06:58.440
[Amit Varma]: bluff their way through lives? I think the the people who are addicts to poker are also

01:06:58.440 --> 01:07:03.400
[Amit Varma]: people who are doing all kinds of other gambling. So there would be people who would be constantly

01:07:03.400 --> 01:07:07.440
[Amit Varma]: on the phone call with bookies betting on cricket betting on this betting on that. And

01:07:07.440 --> 01:07:14.240
[Amit Varma]: that's the way that they are. The people who were treating it like me were not like that,

01:07:14.240 --> 01:07:20.680
[Amit Varma]: number one. But number two, the thing about bluffing is that has the sort of has a deal

01:07:20.680 --> 01:07:25.960
[Amit Varma]: that when you're bluffing, you're playing a game of probabilities. For example, I hope

01:07:25.960 --> 01:07:30.040
[Amit Varma]: I don't get too technical here, but I'll try and kind of explain the way to think about

01:07:30.040 --> 01:07:36.600
[Amit Varma]: bluffing. Let's say that if there is a pot on the river with 1000 rupees, right? So I

01:07:36.600 --> 01:07:42.640
[Amit Varma]: bet 500 rupees into it. Okay, now there's 1500 in the pot to win that 1500 you have

01:07:42.640 --> 01:07:49.400
[Amit Varma]: to call 500 bucks, right? So you are getting three to one odds, which means that you have

01:07:49.400 --> 01:07:56.560
[Amit Varma]: to be right one in four times for your call to be correct. Right? Which means that optimally,

01:07:56.560 --> 01:08:01.760
[Amit Varma]: I have to be bluffing there one in four times. And the rest of the time I have to have value

01:08:01.760 --> 01:08:06.560
[Amit Varma]: bets. If either of us deviates from these percentages, they are making a mistake and

01:08:06.560 --> 01:08:12.420
[Amit Varma]: they will lose in the long run. So the result is that if you do not, if somebody never bluffs

01:08:12.420 --> 01:08:18.360
[Amit Varma]: and they are betting a value hand 100% of the time, two things happen. One is you don't

01:08:18.360 --> 01:08:23.160
[Amit Varma]: get enough value hands in poker, so you will not win enough hands. But more importantly,

01:08:23.160 --> 01:08:27.400
[Amit Varma]: your opponent will see that you are never bluffing and therefore they will always fall

01:08:27.400 --> 01:08:31.920
[Amit Varma]: to your bet. So you're never going to make enough money. So therefore, bluffing is not

01:08:31.920 --> 01:08:37.440
[Amit Varma]: something that is any different from any other kind of bet that you're trying to fool someone.

01:08:37.440 --> 01:08:43.040
[Amit Varma]: It's just something that mathematically you have to throw in for your poker to be profitable

01:08:43.040 --> 01:08:48.360
[Amit Varma]: in the long run. And you throw it in depending on a variety of factors like how you are building

01:08:48.360 --> 01:08:56.120
[Amit Varma]: your ranges and how your sort of whole thinking about the game is. In fact, you know, what

01:08:56.120 --> 01:09:00.720
[Amit Varma]: is known as like there are two and this is another interesting thing to note is that

01:09:00.720 --> 01:09:05.720
[Amit Varma]: people think that tells count that, you know, in movies they'll show that somebody bluffs

01:09:05.720 --> 01:09:09.800
[Amit Varma]: and then he's completely still all over and the other guy looks at him and he'll see a

01:09:09.800 --> 01:09:14.720
[Amit Varma]: vein popping somewhere and he'll be like, ha, he's bluffing, call, call. But in real

01:09:14.720 --> 01:09:21.000
[Amit Varma]: life, actually, that once you pass a certain level of poker, it doesn't matter. Good players

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:24.560
[Amit Varma]: won't even look for tells. It's all about the math. And there are two things come in

01:09:24.560 --> 01:09:29.840
[Amit Varma]: in poker. There are two kinds of sort of poker that you can play. One is exploitative poker,

01:09:29.840 --> 01:09:35.320
[Amit Varma]: where you try to exploit a mistake the other person is making. So if they call too much,

01:09:35.320 --> 01:09:40.520
[Amit Varma]: you value bet more. If they fold too much, you bluff more, you adjust according to that.

01:09:40.520 --> 01:09:44.840
[Amit Varma]: The other is game theory optimal poker, like in the example I pointed out, where it doesn't

01:09:44.840 --> 01:09:49.800
[Amit Varma]: matter what he does, you get your frequencies right. So if you bet 500 into 1000 to a river

01:09:49.800 --> 01:09:55.440
[Amit Varma]: and you give him 3 to 1 odds, you build your range in such a way that you have that percentage

01:09:55.440 --> 01:10:00.500
[Amit Varma]: of bluffs and that percentage of value hands. And then in the long run, you cannot lose.

01:10:00.500 --> 01:10:04.840
[Amit Varma]: If he deviates, he loses by either calling too much or folding too much, but you cannot

01:10:04.840 --> 01:10:09.480
[Amit Varma]: lose. So if you play game theory optimal poker, it doesn't matter what the opponent does.

01:10:09.480 --> 01:10:13.120
[Amit Varma]: You don't need to look at him. It doesn't matter what his tendencies are. Now, obviously,

01:10:13.120 --> 01:10:17.480
[Amit Varma]: game theoretical optimal poker is a theoretical construct. No human being can possibly play

01:10:17.480 --> 01:10:23.640
[Amit Varma]: it perfectly. But the better you have an idea of what GTO poker might be, the better you

01:10:23.640 --> 01:10:29.120
[Amit Varma]: will be at spotting mistakes that the other person makes and therefore exploiting them.

01:10:29.120 --> 01:10:32.560
[Amit Varma]: Now, the fascinating thing, in fact, about this duck poke versus Daniel Negrano match

01:10:32.560 --> 01:10:37.640
[Amit Varma]: that I'm kind of talking about is duck. So Daniel Negrano is an old school poker player

01:10:37.640 --> 01:10:41.400
[Amit Varma]: who plays exploitative poker. He'll sit at the table and he'll stare at your neck and

01:10:41.400 --> 01:10:46.080
[Amit Varma]: he'll look for bluffs and he'll kind of do all of that. And it's all a lot of psychology

01:10:46.080 --> 01:10:50.480
[Amit Varma]: and all that. Duck poke is a new computer generation player who basically at one point

01:10:50.480 --> 01:10:55.840
[Amit Varma]: in time was the best heads up cash game player in the world. And he's completely into GTO

01:10:55.840 --> 01:11:00.160
[Amit Varma]: stands for game theory optimal. And he's completely into game theory optimal poker. And he had

01:11:00.160 --> 01:11:05.920
[Amit Varma]: an incredible video channel, which sadly started after I left poker, where he would, you know,

01:11:05.920 --> 01:11:11.000
[Amit Varma]: talk about different hands from a GTO perspective and just really mind blowing and educative.

01:11:11.000 --> 01:11:15.640
[Amit Varma]: Though he retired from poker at a particular point in time, but he had once mocked Negrano

01:11:15.640 --> 01:11:19.760
[Amit Varma]: and they had this feud going on. And it was a feud about ideas. Like one of them said

01:11:19.760 --> 01:11:22.840
[Amit Varma]: rake is good. The other one said too much rake is bad. There should be a limit. This

01:11:22.840 --> 01:11:27.600
[Amit Varma]: guy said no more rake is good and blah, blah, blah. So they had a battle over ideas, but

01:11:27.600 --> 01:11:32.120
[Amit Varma]: being macho, they decided to settle it over the field. And so therefore, they are now

01:11:32.120 --> 01:11:37.520
[Amit Varma]: having a challenge match, which is 25,000 hands. And at the time of speaking, I think

01:11:37.520 --> 01:11:44.680
[Amit Varma]: only 1000 hands are over and poke is already up. I think $250,000 or something. And the

01:11:44.680 --> 01:11:48.200
[Amit Varma]: other board deposited a million each to begin with, though I think if Negrano goes all the

01:11:48.200 --> 01:11:53.480
[Amit Varma]: way, he'll end up depositing more and losing more. So it's like new school versus old school.

01:11:53.480 --> 01:11:58.400
[Amit Varma]: But anyway, regardless, I think the idea that most people have of poker that is that is

01:11:58.400 --> 01:12:03.960
[Amit Varma]: a of exploitative poker. And B, I think they overplay the psychological and the tell aspects

01:12:03.960 --> 01:12:07.800
[Amit Varma]: and the bluffing aspects. And as far as bluffing is concerned, the way you think of it is you

01:12:07.800 --> 01:12:12.440
[Amit Varma]: have a range for every particular situation, whether you're calling or you're betting,

01:12:12.440 --> 01:12:17.840
[Amit Varma]: and you play with that range. And that range will include both value hands and bluffs.

01:12:17.840 --> 01:12:21.400
[Amit Varma]: So when you psychologically when you think about it, you're betting with that range and

01:12:21.400 --> 01:12:26.760
[Amit Varma]: it doesn't really matter, you're playing correctly. And, you know, equally when somebody else

01:12:26.760 --> 01:12:30.920
[Amit Varma]: is playing against me, if that person is a competent person, I'm thinking of their range

01:12:30.920 --> 01:12:38.000
[Amit Varma]: in my range in that spot. And, you know, playing accordingly and all of that and I don't really

01:12:38.000 --> 01:12:43.080
[Amit Varma]: want to get into poker theory here. But I'll say that those typical popular culture stereotypes

01:12:43.080 --> 01:12:50.520
[Amit Varma]: of poker players are, you know, where those stereotypes are of these dynamic people wearing,

01:12:50.520 --> 01:12:54.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, sunflower shirts and dark glasses and doing flamboyant things and all of that.

01:12:54.920 --> 01:12:58.040
[Amit Varma]: I think that's completely false. But where it comes to geeks who are sitting in front

01:12:58.040 --> 01:13:02.920
[Amit Varma]: of a computer and, you know, I have known of people who play 24 hour sessions and they'll

01:13:02.920 --> 01:13:06.520
[Amit Varma]: have a bottle near them so they can pee into it because they're playing 20 tables at a

01:13:06.520 --> 01:13:09.840
[Amit Varma]: time and they don't want to get up to go to the loo. That's true.

01:13:09.840 --> 01:13:16.280
[Guest]: Oh, wow. No, there is one interesting element to what you said, which is the difference

01:13:16.280 --> 01:13:20.680
[Guest]: between when you do this in a repeated game, not just necessarily with one person, but

01:13:20.680 --> 01:13:24.520
[Guest]: also with yourself, like, you know, when you play lots and lots of hands versus if you

01:13:24.520 --> 01:13:29.280
[Guest]: were sort of, you know, playing with your family, you know, over Thanksgiving or on

01:13:29.280 --> 01:13:32.640
[Guest]: Diwali, you play Tash, something like that. You're just hanging out and you're playing

01:13:32.640 --> 01:13:38.360
[Guest]: a game. Right. So to me, it seems like the element of surprise or bluff can have a lot

01:13:38.360 --> 01:13:44.280
[Guest]: of value there in this one time game or in a new interaction. But in the repeated game,

01:13:44.280 --> 01:13:49.200
[Guest]: it doesn't. Right. As you just pointed out, that other things take over. So now I'm going

01:13:49.200 --> 01:13:54.440
[Guest]: to ask you, Harsha's question from that point of view, when you meet people the first time,

01:13:54.440 --> 01:13:59.440
[Guest]: do you hold your cards close to your chest? Are you able to like sort of, you know, bluff

01:13:59.440 --> 01:14:03.000
[Guest]: easily? Not in the sense of telling lies, but in the sense of, you know, just being

01:14:03.000 --> 01:14:07.400
[Guest]: polite and not getting too much into it or not letting them know exactly what you're

01:14:07.400 --> 01:14:13.440
[Guest]: thinking. But with people over a long period of time, people who are close friends, collaborators,

01:14:13.440 --> 01:14:17.680
