01:20:40.840 --> 01:20:45.000
[Amit Varma]: I can't think of anything. Listen, I have this interesting idea for which I could thought

01:20:45.000 --> 01:20:48.960
[Amit Varma]: I'll someday do a YouTube show of called the seed and the unseen, which is about the unintended

01:20:48.960 --> 01:20:53.400
[Amit Varma]: consequences of public policy. So he liked the name, he liked the concept, he said, Let's

01:20:53.400 --> 01:20:57.120
[Amit Varma]: do that. And that's that was really the concept behind the show that you take a little bit

01:20:57.120 --> 01:21:01.880
[Amit Varma]: of piece of public policy and you talk about that. In fact, we we did pilot episodes on

01:21:01.880 --> 01:21:06.240
[Amit Varma]: the minimum wage, but I never ended up ever doing an episode on the minimum wage, which

01:21:06.240 --> 01:21:12.040
[Amit Varma]: is interesting because it moved away from public policy and became more about, you know,

01:21:12.040 --> 01:21:17.880
[Amit Varma]: these deep dive interviews into ideas and lives and history and so on and so forth.

01:21:17.880 --> 01:21:21.760
[Amit Varma]: So what what really happened then was that over a period of time, it just evolved along

01:21:21.760 --> 01:21:27.160
[Amit Varma]: with my own intellectual curiosity and the journeys I wanted to take. And I figured out

01:21:27.160 --> 01:21:32.920
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, longer is better. And I learned a number of different things about audio along

01:21:32.920 --> 01:21:38.400
[Amit Varma]: the way, which, you know, I've explored a great length in my podcasting course, but

01:21:38.400 --> 01:21:42.480
[Amit Varma]: I'll briefly sort of go over some of that. One is that audio is different from other

01:21:42.480 --> 01:21:46.520
[Amit Varma]: mediums because of the way people consume it. Like if you're watching a YouTube video,

01:21:46.520 --> 01:21:49.880
[Amit Varma]: it's probably on your laptop or phone and you can click away to another tab or look

01:21:49.880 --> 01:21:54.360
[Amit Varma]: away or press the back button or whatever. People will typically consume audio when they

01:21:54.360 --> 01:22:00.560
[Amit Varma]: are either commuting, working out or doing errands, like washing dishes, for example,

01:22:00.560 --> 01:22:05.400
[Amit Varma]: which was a use case for so many of us during the lockdown. Now, what that means is that

01:22:05.400 --> 01:22:09.880
[Amit Varma]: either a captive audience have chosen to be a captive audience and not going to be distracted.

01:22:09.880 --> 01:22:14.560
[Amit Varma]: The primary thing they are doing is something else, but it's automatic. It doesn't require

01:22:14.560 --> 01:22:20.800
[Amit Varma]: the brain. So therefore they are sort of listening. Secondly, which is very different, right?

01:22:20.800 --> 01:22:25.180
[Amit Varma]: Because in no other thing, you have a captive audience like this. It's only audio. Secondly,

01:22:25.180 --> 01:22:29.800
[Amit Varma]: people are listening at higher speeds. And the reason for this is that while our brain

01:22:29.800 --> 01:22:35.680
[Amit Varma]: can allow us to speak at a natural rate of between 150 to 200 words up to 225, we can

01:22:35.680 --> 01:22:41.440
[Amit Varma]: listen from 275 to 500, which is why, you know, it's difficult to hold someone's attention

01:22:41.440 --> 01:22:45.720
[Amit Varma]: when you're talking to them because they've got spare attentional capacity and they can

01:22:45.720 --> 01:22:49.440
[Amit Varma]: do other things while they're listening to you, which is also why people can listen at

01:22:49.440 --> 01:22:52.640
[Amit Varma]: higher speeds because they can actually take it in. So it's not like squeaky squeaky. It

01:22:52.640 --> 01:22:58.560
[Amit Varma]: normalizes very fast. People will take it to 1.25, 1.5 and it will just normalize. And

01:22:58.560 --> 01:23:01.680
[Amit Varma]: so these two things are coming together. It's passive listening. They're listening while

01:23:01.680 --> 01:23:05.260
[Amit Varma]: doing something else. So they're a captive audience and they're listening at double speed.

01:23:05.260 --> 01:23:08.920
[Amit Varma]: So when you do a 20 minute episode, by the time the guy has put his shoelaces on to go

01:23:08.920 --> 01:23:14.320
[Amit Varma]: jogging, which might take 10 minutes, the episode is over. Right. So when I started

01:23:14.320 --> 01:23:18.680
[Amit Varma]: kind of working out and listening to podcasts at the same time, I realized that if I'm out

01:23:18.680 --> 01:23:23.820
[Amit Varma]: for an hour, a two hour episode is perfect for me. The third sort of learning that comes

01:23:23.820 --> 01:23:29.400
[Amit Varma]: from this is that people have great hunger and desire to for deep content that typically,

01:23:29.400 --> 01:23:34.620
[Amit Varma]: you know, first of all, it is true in a sense that we live in the age of short, the short

01:23:34.620 --> 01:23:38.640
[Amit Varma]: attention span, but the opposite is also true. And it is not true that there are shallow

01:23:38.640 --> 01:23:43.120
[Amit Varma]: people and there are deep people. It is that we contain multitude. So within each of us,

01:23:43.120 --> 01:23:47.880
[Amit Varma]: there is a shallow me and a deep me. And you know, so the shallow me might be surfing TV

01:23:47.880 --> 01:23:52.620
[Amit Varma]: channels or, you know, I'll have 50 tabs open on Chrome at the same time. But the deep me

01:23:52.620 --> 01:23:57.160
[Amit Varma]: also craves deep learning and deep knowledge. Now, the thing is, many of us may not have

01:23:57.160 --> 01:24:01.360
[Amit Varma]: the time to actually listen to books in our daily lives. How much time do we have? How

01:24:01.360 --> 01:24:05.220
[Amit Varma]: much time are we going to devote to reading? But because we listen to audio while doing

01:24:05.220 --> 01:24:10.280
[Amit Varma]: something else, we are more likely to take in knowledge that way, which is why I often

01:24:10.280 --> 01:24:14.760
[Amit Varma]: say that, you know, audio books and printed books are not really competing with each other.

01:24:14.760 --> 01:24:19.680
[Amit Varma]: They're entirely different use cases. So a lot of people, therefore, like getting their

01:24:19.680 --> 01:24:24.080
[Amit Varma]: sort of deep sense or rather fulfill their hunger for depth by listening to audio, whether

01:24:24.080 --> 01:24:28.520
[Amit Varma]: it's audio books or podcasts. Now, this is one aspect of it. Now, the thing is that,

01:24:28.520 --> 01:24:33.200
[Amit Varma]: as I said earlier, podcasts are different from radio. It's not just radio on demand.

01:24:33.200 --> 01:24:37.360
[Amit Varma]: And there's a reason for that as well, which is that let's think about this concept of

01:24:37.360 --> 01:24:42.400
[Amit Varma]: space in media. Let's for a moment, look at visual media, that when you go to a cinema

01:24:42.400 --> 01:24:46.820
[Amit Varma]: theater to watch a movie, there's a certain distance between you and the screen. And similarly,

01:24:46.820 --> 01:24:50.480
[Amit Varma]: on the other side of the screen, there's a certain distance between the camera and the

01:24:50.480 --> 01:24:55.520
[Amit Varma]: actors. You know, they are much further away. Then when you come to the television age,

01:24:55.520 --> 01:24:59.120
[Amit Varma]: you're in your living room and the TV is across the room, it's a couple of meters away, and

01:24:59.120 --> 01:25:02.800
[Amit Varma]: there's a distance between you and the TV. And similarly, the shot on the TV has become

01:25:02.800 --> 01:25:06.920
[Amit Varma]: closer and you have sitcoms and everybody's in a room and it's closer. Similarly, if you're

01:25:06.920 --> 01:25:12.000
[Amit Varma]: watching a YouTube video on your laptop, if it's a made for YouTube video, again, the

01:25:12.000 --> 01:25:16.760
[Amit Varma]: two distances correlate to each other. Now, think of the distance in terms of audio that

01:25:16.760 --> 01:25:19.560
[Amit Varma]: when you're listening to radio, say you're in your car or whatever, and you're listening

01:25:19.560 --> 01:25:23.720
[Amit Varma]: to radio, there is a certain distance, but podcasts are in your head. They're literally

01:25:23.720 --> 01:25:29.100
[Amit Varma]: in your head. It's the most intimate medium that there is. It's a one-on-one conversation.

01:25:29.100 --> 01:25:34.120
[Amit Varma]: And this is a reason, this is a critical reason why, a critical difference between podcasts

01:25:34.120 --> 01:25:39.880
[Amit Varma]: and radio, that in radio, in a sense, you're broadcasting, you're speaking to many people.

01:25:39.880 --> 01:25:43.200
[Amit Varma]: In audio, you're not doing that. You're speaking to one person. So you can take that tone,

01:25:43.200 --> 01:25:48.800
[Amit Varma]: which is why I say that many of the qualities that make for good radio, like, oh, radio

01:25:48.800 --> 01:25:53.520
[Amit Varma]: voice and diction and you must speak like this, do not apply to podcasts at all. You

01:25:53.520 --> 01:25:57.800
[Amit Varma]: don't need a good voice. You don't need an accent. You don't, it's an intimate one-on-one

01:25:57.800 --> 01:26:04.400
[Amit Varma]: conversation, which, you know, makes it such an incredible medium. And, and, and when you're

01:26:04.400 --> 01:26:08.800
[Amit Varma]: listening to people for like two hours a week, three hours a week, or whatever, when you

01:26:08.800 --> 01:26:13.780
[Amit Varma]: do with a long episodes, then you have that sense of relating to that person, also trusting

01:26:13.780 --> 01:26:17.360
[Amit Varma]: that person, respecting that all of those things, you know, all the podcasts that I

01:26:17.360 --> 01:26:21.080
[Amit Varma]: listened to, you know, you and I both, you know, admire someone like Russ Roberts, or

01:26:21.080 --> 01:26:26.440
[Amit Varma]: we'll listen to Tyler Carvin, who you're fortunate enough to work with and meet regularly. And,

01:26:26.440 --> 01:26:30.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, so there is, you feel like you have a stake in those shows. It's not just their

01:26:30.480 --> 01:26:35.920
[Amit Varma]: shows, it's also your show, in a sense of speaking, and they are merely the custodians

01:26:35.920 --> 01:26:41.680
[Amit Varma]: of it in a manner and podcasts have that kind of intimacy, which makes it such a such a

01:26:41.680 --> 01:26:45.000
[Amit Varma]: sort of remarkable and special medium.

01:26:45.000 --> 01:26:49.560
[Guest]: Absolutely. You know, it's, like I said, at the beginning of the show, I was a bit of

01:26:49.560 --> 01:26:55.320
[Guest]: a naysayer initially, because I just couldn't imagine why anyone would find it interesting

01:26:55.320 --> 01:26:59.160
[Guest]: to hear me and Amit speak to each other, because we talk like this with each other all the

01:26:59.160 --> 01:27:03.760
[Guest]: time. And we were like, now we're just recording it. Like, there's no music, there's no script,

01:27:03.760 --> 01:27:08.440
[Guest]: there's no jokes, there's no punchline. So I was a big, you know, critic in the beginning.

01:27:08.440 --> 01:27:14.920
[Guest]: But over the 199 episodes, and I've been on the show more than a dozen times, ha, take

01:27:14.920 --> 01:27:20.720
[Guest]: that Vivek Kaur, but I've been on the show, you know, a number of times. And when I have

