[Guest]: conversation with you. And I don't remember exactly what I said, I've had a couple of

01:27:46.160 --> 01:27:50.880
[Guest]: people correct me, you know, you said this, and we went and looked this up. But you know,

01:27:50.880 --> 01:27:55.800
[Guest]: it's actually that. And I find that really incredible one that someone would care so

01:27:55.800 --> 01:28:00.320
[Guest]: deeply, they would remember things one said they would quote one back to oneself, you

01:28:00.320 --> 01:28:06.560
[Guest]: know, things like that. But the other part of it was also that we live in the information

01:28:06.560 --> 01:28:12.840
[Guest]: age, but there is almost too much information, right. And in that sense, what you bring to

01:28:12.840 --> 01:28:19.440
[Guest]: the table, aside from the intimate conversation is, you are curating, I know that it's the

01:28:19.440 --> 01:28:24.560
[Guest]: other person living in your household, who is the curator, but you are also an intellectual

01:28:24.560 --> 01:28:31.440
[Guest]: curator of sorts, right? Like you, you are really reading so much and cherry picking

01:28:31.440 --> 01:28:36.280
[Guest]: and presenting and saying, Hey, you one really must reach in my book, right? Or one must

01:28:36.280 --> 01:28:40.360
[Guest]: really read this thing about the Gita Press that no one may have heard of before that.

