[Guest]: drafts, I routinely get review copies from book publishers. So you and I get to read

01:29:10.400 --> 01:29:15.240
[Guest]: very differently sample very differently for most people. And that is also something I

01:29:15.240 --> 01:29:21.360
[Guest]: learned about the show that Amit Verma is not just someone they listen to for information.

01:29:21.360 --> 01:29:25.680
[Guest]: It's also someone they listen to, to tell them what is worth listening to what is worth

01:29:25.680 --> 01:29:30.080
[Guest]: reading, what is worth thinking about in the world. And I don't think that can be done

01:29:30.080 --> 01:29:34.680
[Guest]: quite as easily in the written format. You know, you can put out a blog post on India

01:29:34.680 --> 01:29:40.400
[Guest]: uncut tomorrow, 20 books, one must read today, it will have nowhere close to the impact that

01:29:40.400 --> 01:29:46.360
[Guest]: discussing those 20 books over, you know, the podcast medium has, I'll tell you why.

01:29:46.360 --> 01:29:51.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, one reason, of course, is that I'm sort of, I kind of follow my own intellectual

01:29:51.000 --> 01:29:55.080
[Amit Varma]: journey. And, you know, just take the listeners along with that. So I'm not really thinking

01:29:55.080 --> 01:29:59.080
[Amit Varma]: that I'm not thinking of it as a curatorial function, I'm following my own journey. And

01:29:59.080 --> 01:30:04.360
[Amit Varma]: that curatorial thing becomes a default thing. But the other aspect is that, you know, you

01:30:04.360 --> 01:30:08.600
[Amit Varma]: read a book review, what is it, it's 800 words, you know, even if you read a long essay on

01:30:08.600 --> 01:30:14.480
[Amit Varma]: a book, a long read on a book, it's like 3-4,000-5,000, whatever, that's, that's about it. But a scene

01:30:14.480 --> 01:30:19.920
[Amit Varma]: in the unseen episode can be, you know, is usually over 20-25,000 words, which are consuming

01:30:19.920 --> 01:30:23.840
[Amit Varma]: in a short period of time, like my episode with Karthik Muralidharan was not just the

01:30:23.840 --> 01:30:28.000
[Amit Varma]: longest episode of the scene in the unseen so far, maybe this will break that record.

01:30:28.000 --> 01:30:34.720
[Amit Varma]: But it was also, he speaks at 1.5x, right? And so I got that episode transcribed, and

01:30:34.720 --> 01:30:41.600
[Amit Varma]: it was 43,000 words. Now, where are you going to get 43,000 words of directed conversation?

01:30:41.600 --> 01:30:46.840
[Amit Varma]: Not just a person talking, but a conversation that is directed in interesting directions

01:30:46.840 --> 01:30:50.800
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth. And that's, again, something that makes podcasting different

01:30:50.800 --> 01:30:55.720
[Amit Varma]: from radio. Radio, because of all the imperatives, has to stay broad and shallow. You've paid

01:30:55.720 --> 01:30:59.680
[Amit Varma]: a license fee, you've got a radio station, one, you have you recoup your money through

01:30:59.680 --> 01:31:05.080
[Amit Varma]: advertising. So you go for lowest common denominator, which is why FM in India is so horrendously

01:31:05.080 --> 01:31:10.640
[Amit Varma]: bad. But even otherwise, even if there were no entry barriers, you are catering to broad

01:31:10.640 --> 01:31:15.200
[Amit Varma]: audiences. And therefore you can't go too deep, like who's interested in an argument

01:31:15.200 --> 01:31:19.560
[Amit Varma]: on how India's First Amendment came about, and all of those things. You'd rather talk

01:31:19.560 --> 01:31:23.720
[Amit Varma]: about Bollywood and cricket and gossip and all of that. Podcasting allows you to go deep

01:31:23.720 --> 01:31:28.240
[Amit Varma]: to find what Kevin Kelly calls a thousand true fans, that there are plenty of people

01:31:28.240 --> 01:31:31.800
[Amit Varma]: out there who are interested in deep knowledge, interested in books. Maybe they don't know

01:31:31.800 --> 01:31:35.160
[Amit Varma]: where to look. Maybe they don't know there are others like them, you know, and maybe

01:31:35.160 --> 01:31:40.580
[Amit Varma]: they don't. And suddenly you give them access to these kind of discussions with the author.

01:31:40.580 --> 01:31:43.840
[Amit Varma]: And not just those, you know, every author that I've spoken to will probably have videos

01:31:43.840 --> 01:31:47.360
[Amit Varma]: on YouTube where somebody speaks to them for 20 minutes or 30 minutes or even an hour.

01:31:47.360 --> 01:31:51.640
[Amit Varma]: And I find them incredibly shallow. All these lit fests, they have these, you know, these

01:31:51.640 --> 01:31:55.160
[Amit Varma]: panels where you'll have a one hour session and 40 minutes, you'll talk to four authors

01:31:55.160 --> 01:31:59.520
[Amit Varma]: and then have Q&A. And that's incredibly shallow. You're not going deep at all. And the way

01:31:59.520 --> 01:32:03.840
[Amit Varma]: I think of my podcasting is one, I want to go deep and two, I don't want to follow the

01:32:03.840 --> 01:32:07.880
[Amit Varma]: news cycle. Like even if I cover something that is in the news, I'll wait for a period

01:32:07.880 --> 01:32:12.160
[Amit Varma]: of time. And like my two most popular episodes, I was Srinath Raghavan on Kashmir and the

01:32:12.160 --> 01:32:16.760
[Amit Varma]: CAA. And in both of those cases, I didn't release them immediately when the event happened.

01:32:16.760 --> 01:32:21.240
[Amit Varma]: It took a couple of weeks. And I think they're like definitive and classic episodes. You

01:32:21.240 --> 01:32:26.200
[Amit Varma]: can listen to 30 years from now. And my aim with everything that I do is I'm not just

01:32:26.200 --> 01:32:31.520
[Amit Varma]: sort of going across space in terms of people across the world listen to me. I want to go

01:32:31.520 --> 01:32:35.160
[Amit Varma]: across time. I want someone 30 years later to binge on my show. You know, when you were

01:32:35.160 --> 01:32:40.400
[Amit Varma]: starting your Ideas of India podcast, one of the pieces of advice I gave you was that,

01:32:40.400 --> 01:32:44.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, do not think of what your listener will hear on episode one, think of what they

01:32:44.080 --> 01:32:47.920
[Amit Varma]: will binge on episode 100, you know, and you want to create that for them, you want to

01:32:47.920 --> 01:32:54.400
[Amit Varma]: create that body of work. So that was sort of my ethic towards podcasting and, and why

01:32:54.400 --> 01:32:59.680
[Amit Varma]: it is so incredibly, you know, exciting, because, you know, you can do all of these things.

01:32:59.680 --> 01:33:04.720
[Guest]: No, it's, it's amazing. I think one, you've also sort of cracked open the podcast space,

01:33:04.720 --> 01:33:08.880
[Guest]: especially something which is not cricket or Bollywood, you know, the usual suspects

01:33:08.880 --> 01:33:15.100
[Guest]: of mass podcasting. But the other is you have also sort of, I think, set the template or

01:33:15.100 --> 01:33:19.040
[Guest]: become the role model in one sense, right? I'm, of course, in a particularly privileged

01:33:19.040 --> 01:33:23.160
[Guest]: position that if I'm starting a podcast, I can pick up my phone call Amit Verma and say,

01:33:23.160 --> 01:33:27.240
[Guest]: hey, I'm thinking about doing this, what do you think I should do? But for most others,

01:33:27.240 --> 01:33:31.280
[Guest]: they've sort of started many, many of our common friends, in fact, has started their

01:33:31.280 --> 01:33:37.680
[Guest]: podcast. And a lot of their template or the way they think about it has been informed

01:33:37.680 --> 01:33:42.360
[Guest]: by how you think about it or how people engage with you. There were two pieces of advice

01:33:42.360 --> 01:33:48.200
[Guest]: that you gave me three pieces of advice, actually, which really stuck with me. And one was you

01:33:48.200 --> 01:33:54.520
[Guest]: said be yourself, because it is exhausting to be anyone else. And you can't sustain it.

01:33:54.520 --> 01:33:58.880
[Guest]: And that is, in one sense, the only secret sauce that one brings to the table, right,

01:33:58.880 --> 01:34:02.940
[Guest]: which is it becoming, of course, to hear all these different episodes, some are coming

01:34:02.940 --> 01:34:07.400
[Guest]: just for CAA, some are coming to hear Manu Pillai. But the people who are coming over

01:34:07.400 --> 01:34:11.680
[Guest]: and over again are coming for Amit Verma or are coming for Shruti Rajagopalan as, as you

01:34:11.680 --> 01:34:18.040
[Guest]: know, you were talking about me. The second was the thing you said about think about creating

01:34:18.040 --> 01:34:23.040
[Guest]: a bank of knowledge, you know, over a period of time. But the third thing is something

01:34:23.040 --> 01:34:28.200
[Guest]: I have imbibed from you, not because you specifically said it to me, but just by looking at your

01:34:28.200 --> 01:34:33.000
[Guest]: journey. You were talking about how you were frustrated, you know, at various points, is

01:34:33.000 --> 01:34:37.560
[Guest]: this really worth doing? It takes just an enormous amount of work to put together, there's

01:34:37.560 --> 01:34:43.360
[Guest]: no infrastructure, there is no money in it, and so on, so forth. And I realized that,

01:34:43.360 --> 01:34:47.080
[Guest]: you know, many people say you did it for the love of doing it. I think this whole love

01:34:47.080 --> 01:34:55.180
[Guest]: business is, you know, it's a little bit overdone. I think what the reason you did it is that

01:34:55.180 --> 01:35:01.000
[Guest]: you also converted it into a consumption good for yourself. Right? If I do a podcast with

01:35:01.000 --> 01:35:07.000
[Guest]: Karthik Muralidharan, I must inform myself on the education system in India. And that

01:35:07.000 --> 01:35:10.920
[Guest]: is something that's going to broaden the horizon. And then I'll speak with Karthik. And of course,

01:35:10.920 --> 01:35:14.680
[Guest]: Karthik will crack open anyone's brain and, you know, broaden their horizons, and so on,

01:35:14.680 --> 01:35:19.320
[Guest]: so forth. And that is something I follow to the T, I've only done single digit, you know,

01:35:19.320 --> 01:35:23.880
[Guest]: episode numbers so far. But I treat it as a consumption good that even if there were

01:35:23.880 --> 01:35:30.480
[Guest]: zero people listening to the show, I get enough out of doing each show and having each conversation

01:35:30.480 --> 01:35:35.880
[Guest]: that, you know, even if no one tuned in, I would walk away pretty happy. And once again,

01:35:35.880 --> 01:35:39.680
[Guest]: we are in privileged positions where we don't need to do this for money, of course. So there's

01:35:39.680 --> 01:35:44.160
[Guest]: that. But I think these are three bits of advice that I got from you, which, you know,

01:35:44.160 --> 01:35:48.440
[Guest]: for the podcasters who are listening out there, that were just incredibly useful. The fourth

01:35:48.440 --> 01:35:54.040
[Guest]: one came from my producer, Jeff. And you know, this is also a bit of the culture at Mercatus,

01:35:54.040 --> 01:35:59.040
[Guest]: which is that we won't look in metrics. I actually have no clue other than the first

01:35:59.040 --> 01:36:04.480
[Guest]: episode, how many downloads or listens my podcast got, and so on. And the rule is that

01:36:04.480 --> 01:36:09.120
[Guest]: I won't ask and that he won't tell me until we're about, you know, six, seven months in,

01:36:09.120 --> 01:36:13.400
[Guest]: at which point, you know, we can have a little bit of information. And the goal is that,

01:36:13.400 --> 01:36:17.960
[Guest]: you know, the tail doesn't wag the dog, which is also something I learned from you. Don't

01:36:17.960 --> 01:36:22.160
[Guest]: worry about the numbers. Don't worry about what is going on. Even if the numbers are

01:36:22.160 --> 01:36:25.240
[Guest]: very few, you have 1000 genuine fans and so on and so forth.

01:36:25.240 --> 01:36:29.040
[Amit Varma]: No, my approach was the numbers was I don't care about the numbers. Because like I said,

01:36:29.040 --> 01:36:33.820
[Amit Varma]: it's across time and all of that. And the quality and the amount of feedback I get is

01:36:33.820 --> 01:36:38.120
[Amit Varma]: enough to you know, tell me that it's kind of really worth it. Just to sort of elaborate

01:36:38.120 --> 01:36:43.560
[Amit Varma]: on the two other pieces of advice you pointed out. One as far as you know, you know, I tell

01:36:43.560 --> 01:36:46.800
[Amit Varma]: keep telling my writing students don't use jargon and you're just saying consumption

01:36:46.800 --> 01:36:51.720
[Amit Varma]: goods and all of that. No, I think I think one of the byproducts of my podcast is certainly

01:36:51.720 --> 01:36:55.680
[Amit Varma]: that I enrich myself intellectually in terms of what I'm reading and in terms of the knowledge

01:36:55.680 --> 01:37:01.040
[Amit Varma]: I'm taking in. And I appreciate that. But that's not the reason I'm doing it because

01:37:01.040 --> 01:37:07.360
[Amit Varma]: it's a byproduct. And I the reason I do it is to be able to have these great conversations,

01:37:07.360 --> 01:37:11.440
[Amit Varma]: but it's a great byproduct. And it's a good reason to do it if you know that matters.

01:37:11.440 --> 01:37:14.520
[Amit Varma]: But the other one is also so important. Like I'm teaching this podcasting course. And one

01:37:14.520 --> 01:37:18.600
[Amit Varma]: of the things I point out is, you know, people will get too obsessed with, you know, where

01:37:18.600 --> 01:37:23.000
[Amit Varma]: is a gap in the market and what is a hole that I can fill in all of those things. And

01:37:23.000 --> 01:37:27.400
[Amit Varma]: I'm like, don't be market obsessed. Because no matter what you try to do, like, you know,

01:37:27.400 --> 01:37:31.320
[Amit Varma]: there are interview podcasts are a dime a dozen interview podcasts with public policy.

01:37:31.320 --> 01:37:34.800
[Amit Varma]: People are a dime a dozen. There are 7 billion people on this planet. There are already more

01:37:34.800 --> 01:37:39.080
[Amit Varma]: than a million podcasts. Everything's been done. All ideas are out there. Even if you

01:37:39.080 --> 01:37:43.640
[Amit Varma]: find a gap in the market, 20 people will fill it for you. What makes your podcast unique?

01:37:43.640 --> 01:37:47.520
[Amit Varma]: Only one thing makes it unique. And that's you. Because nobody else is you and you are

01:37:47.520 --> 01:37:51.840
[Amit Varma]: you. So what I therefore try to do is I'm following my own intellectual journey. I'm

01:37:51.840 --> 01:37:57.760
[Amit Varma]: thinking aloud, I am almost having no filter, in that sense, that, you know, you can listen

01:37:57.760 --> 01:38:02.160
[Amit Varma]: to something I said in a past episode, which, you know, and say that, hey, but you know,

01:38:02.160 --> 01:38:06.800
[Amit Varma]: that's such a silly line to go down on. And I have often changed my mind while thinking

01:38:06.800 --> 01:38:11.120
[Amit Varma]: aloud over the course of all the episodes that I've done. So yeah, I think that's, you

01:38:11.120 --> 01:38:15.680
[Amit Varma]: know, as far as podcasting advice goes, that's, in fact, number one on my list that be authentic

01:38:15.680 --> 01:38:19.640
[Amit Varma]: to yourself. That's the only thing that gives you a shot. And then what you end up with

01:38:19.640 --> 01:38:23.960
[Amit Varma]: will at least be meaningful and valuable to you to that one person rather than to nobody

01:38:23.960 --> 01:38:24.960
[Guest]: at all.

01:38:24.960 --> 01:38:30.680
[Guest]: And I think this is also why, you know, very often you and I have spoken to the same people

01:38:30.680 --> 01:38:35.880
[Guest]: or discussed the same book. And our shows have been completely different. Because one,

01:38:35.880 --> 01:38:39.960
[Guest]: we haven't coordinated what we're doing, right, except knowing that, hey, what's coming out

01:38:39.960 --> 01:38:43.960
[Guest]: next or something like that. But I have no clue what conversation you had with Dinyar

01:38:43.960 --> 01:38:49.040
[Guest]: Patel, when I had the same conversation or with Viral Acharya more recently. And then

01:38:49.040 --> 01:38:54.000
[Guest]: when I hear your conversation, and I know the one I've had, I'm like, wow, everyone

01:38:54.000 --> 01:38:58.080
[Guest]: would think Amit and I would think along the same lines, but it's just completely different.

01:38:58.080 --> 01:39:00.160
[Guest]: So your advice has helped me in very good stead.

01:39:00.160 --> 01:39:03.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And see, that's a remarkable thing that people would think that in terms of ideas,

01:39:03.920 --> 01:39:09.040
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you're probably, in a sense, ideologically, the closest person to me on the podcast. I

01:39:09.040 --> 01:39:14.720
[Amit Varma]: disagree with everyone, but I disagree with you the least perhaps. And, and yet the episodes

01:39:14.720 --> 01:39:18.720
[Amit Varma]: are so different. Like we and it's not that if one of us records with person X, the other

01:39:18.720 --> 01:39:22.280
[Amit Varma]: one will listen to that episode and then avoid it. No, in fact, what's happened to us is

01:39:22.280 --> 01:39:27.720
[Amit Varma]: you recorded with Madhav Khosla before I did, and my episode came out first, and did to,

01:39:27.720 --> 01:39:34.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, the Viral episodes where I offered to share my lines of inquiry with you. And

01:39:34.000 --> 01:39:37.760
[Amit Varma]: you said, No, no, no, I don't want to be influenced by that, because either I'll try to avoid

01:39:37.760 --> 01:39:42.560
[Amit Varma]: it, or I'll, you know, it might influence what comes to my mind. And so without that

01:39:42.560 --> 01:39:46.560
[Amit Varma]: sort of foreknowledge of what the other has done, we would just go into those episodes

01:39:46.560 --> 01:39:52.080
[Amit Varma]: and, you know, come up with entirely different results, which speaks exactly to that, that,

01:39:52.080 --> 01:39:56.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, don't, don't think of what others will think of your questions or what, you

01:39:56.960 --> 01:40:00.400
[Guest]: know, don't game it, don't game it, don't overthink it, don't think too hard of the

01:40:00.400 --> 01:40:05.760
[Amit Varma]: audience, be authentic to yourself, respect the audience, but don't don't, you know, ultimately,

01:40:05.760 --> 01:40:07.320
[Amit Varma]: you got to be authentic to yourself.

01:40:07.320 --> 01:40:13.280
[Guest]: No, absolutely. And, you know, now I want to talk a little bit about the philosophy

01:40:13.280 --> 01:40:18.080
[Guest]: of the conversation or your philosophy of interviewing people. You spoke about this

01:40:18.080 --> 01:40:21.920
[Guest]: quite a bit with Russ Roberts, which, by the way, I know we're not supposed to pick like

01:40:21.920 --> 01:40:26.880
[Guest]: the most favorite episode. But while listening to a podcast, I mean, if I didn't pick my

01:40:26.880 --> 01:40:32.080
[Unknown]: favorite episode as the one that Russ Roberts did with Amit Verma, I'm going to go to libertarian

01:40:32.080 --> 01:40:36.480
[Guest]: hell, which might be what we're living in. But you know, who knows? Anyway, so I just

01:40:36.480 --> 01:40:44.320
[Guest]: love the conversation you had about discourse, about the way we change, not just ourselves,

01:40:44.320 --> 01:40:49.600
[Guest]: but also what we're putting out there in society. Like, what is it that it takes to have a good

01:40:49.600 --> 01:40:53.040
[Guest]: conversation? That episode, for those, you know, of the listeners who may not have had

01:40:53.040 --> 01:40:59.360
[Guest]: a chance to hear it yet, is one of my absolute favorites in all 200. But aside from that,

01:40:59.360 --> 01:41:04.800
[Guest]: aside from, you know, just the simple art of listening and talking, what is your larger

01:41:04.800 --> 01:41:09.600
[Guest]: philosophy of speaking with someone for the purpose of the interview or the podcast,

01:41:09.600 --> 01:41:14.880
[Amit Varma]: not when you meet them over lunch? Yeah, I think, you know, the thing is, Stephen Covey

01:41:14.880 --> 01:41:20.320
[Amit Varma]: once said that we don't listen to understand, we listen to respond. And I think there's a profound

01:41:20.320 --> 01:41:25.440
[Amit Varma]: point there in the sense that that is almost Kantian in a sense, you know, where, you know,

01:41:25.440 --> 01:41:29.600
[Amit Varma]: Immanuel Kant's categorical imperative warns against treating other people as a means to an

01:41:29.600 --> 01:41:34.560
[Amit Varma]: end. Now, there is a sort of a larger conversation to be had here about do we do that in our lives,

01:41:34.560 --> 01:41:39.040
[Amit Varma]: is everyone a means to a particular end? And I don't have a good answer for that.

01:41:39.040 --> 01:41:43.200
[Amit Varma]: And I think much of the time that is the case, even if we think that should not be the case,

01:41:43.200 --> 01:41:48.720
[Amit Varma]: it is the case. But I think that becoming aware of this can enrich our lives,

01:41:49.360 --> 01:41:55.520
[Amit Varma]: treating other people as people with agency and an individuality and respecting them for that

01:41:55.520 --> 01:41:59.520
[Amit Varma]: can enrich our lives. And part of how you do that is through listening, where, you know,

01:41:59.520 --> 01:42:03.280
[Amit Varma]: if you are listening to respond, you're listening for reasons of self aggrandizement that you want

01:42:03.280 --> 01:42:07.040
[Amit Varma]: to respond because you want to win a point or you want to show people who might be listening,

01:42:07.040 --> 01:42:12.400
[Amit Varma]: how smart you are and all of that. And therefore, I made a conscious decision that I am not going

01:42:12.400 --> 01:42:16.960
[Amit Varma]: to do that I am going to give the person I am talking to maximum respect because it is also

01:42:16.960 --> 01:42:23.600
[Amit Varma]: true that no matter how knowledgeable I might be, or how intelligent I might be, every single

01:42:24.160 --> 01:42:29.120
[Amit Varma]: person in the 7 billion plus in the world knows something that I don't. And therefore,

01:42:29.120 --> 01:42:34.640
[Amit Varma]: my life can be better off if I can get them to share it with me. And so you have to give that

01:42:34.640 --> 01:42:40.640
[Amit Varma]: respect to everyone, even someone you disagree with. So some of the sort of principles that I've

01:42:40.640 --> 01:42:46.960
[Amit Varma]: come up with, therefore, is that you never interrupt, right? You know, I just want them

01:42:46.960 --> 01:42:51.920
[Amit Varma]: to go with the flow of thinking. I don't like to sort of, I will not interrupt them at any point.

01:42:51.920 --> 01:42:56.480
[Amit Varma]: And it's very rare when I do that when there is an interjection that must be made. And I will then

01:42:56.480 --> 01:43:01.040
[Amit Varma]: guide them back to whatever they were talking about or whatever. But I might disagree very

01:43:01.040 --> 01:43:05.520
[Amit Varma]: strongly or I might have something to say, even if they go on for 20-30 minutes, I will write

01:43:05.520 --> 01:43:09.680
[Amit Varma]: down the points I want to make and I will make them sequentially later. So I will often say,

01:43:10.240 --> 01:43:13.840
[Amit Varma]: when my turn comes, that okay, I have three responses to that. And I'll go through them

01:43:13.840 --> 01:43:17.600
[Amit Varma]: one, two, three, because I'm also writing down and taking notes. But I will never interrupt,

01:43:17.600 --> 01:43:23.840
[Amit Varma]: I let them go where they want. The other sort of trick to avoid is sort of when you have a list of

01:43:23.840 --> 01:43:28.240
[Amit Varma]: questions prepared, and then you want to follow that order. So the other person is talking,

01:43:28.240 --> 01:43:32.320
[Amit Varma]: but you've already tuned off and you're thinking of the segue into your next question, and you go

01:43:32.320 --> 01:43:37.280
[Amit Varma]: down to that. And I like the conversation to flow in a natural way. And to make sure that doesn't

01:43:37.280 --> 01:43:42.320
[Amit Varma]: happen. So obviously, I have really exhaustive notes. And I do sort of cover a lot of ground in

01:43:42.320 --> 01:43:46.000
[Amit Varma]: those notes. And I know what are the themes I want to cover, and I make sure I cover them all,

01:43:46.000 --> 01:43:50.800
[Amit Varma]: or as many as I can have the broader themes. But I don't try to force the order, I like to keep the

01:43:50.800 --> 01:43:55.120
[Amit Varma]: flow of the conversation going. If they say something interesting, I can pick up on that and

01:43:55.120 --> 01:43:59.360
[Amit Varma]: we can go a little further. And that's what I aim for. And I've been you know, because I teach this

01:43:59.360 --> 01:44:04.720
[Amit Varma]: podcasting course, and we are recording this on the 10th, this Sunday, on the 15th, a week before

01:44:04.720 --> 01:44:09.520
[Amit Varma]: the episode releases, I'll be giving my second webinar, which is also about talking about

01:44:09.520 --> 01:44:14.320
[Amit Varma]: interviewing at much length. So I've been thinking about how different interviewers do this stuff.

01:44:14.320 --> 01:44:20.080
[Amit Varma]: You know, Joe Rogan, Russ Roberts, Tyler Cowen, Sam Harris, the some of the people I've, you know,

01:44:20.080 --> 01:44:24.240
[Amit Varma]: listened to and admired their craft for different reasons. And it's really interesting. And I think

01:44:24.240 --> 01:44:28.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm most similar, of course, to Russ and I agree with you, that's a beautiful episode, it just

01:44:28.640 --> 01:44:34.560
[Amit Varma]: warmed my heart to record it. And I think, you know, Russ felt similarly about it. And it was

01:44:34.560 --> 01:44:39.680
[Amit Varma]: just a lovely episode on conversation. But that's also partly because I think we have the same sort

01:44:39.680 --> 01:44:44.560
[Amit Varma]: of ethic towards conversation. I wish the shows were much longer, which is, I think, the one

01:44:44.560 --> 01:44:49.760
[Amit Varma]: fundamental difference between us that we're both very respectful of the guest and we are trying to

01:44:49.760 --> 01:44:55.200
[Amit Varma]: unpeel the layers. But you know, while we both go around as deep, I probably go broader, because I

01:44:55.200 --> 01:45:00.880
[Amit Varma]: have that much more time to play with. And Sam Harris is a little different Joe Rogan is, you

01:45:00.880 --> 01:45:07.120
[Amit Varma]: know, extremely different in different ways. And Tyler is brilliant, because he can ask things that

01:45:07.120 --> 01:45:12.320
[Amit Varma]: I can't even think of, which, you know, questions and areas that I can't even conceive of. And I'm

01:45:12.320 --> 01:45:16.720
[Amit Varma]: just wow at the question, you know, the question alone, sort of enlightens you in many ways.

01:45:16.720 --> 01:45:20.960
[Amit Varma]: But I think what he also does is that he doesn't go enough with the flow of the conversation,

01:45:20.960 --> 01:45:26.240
[Amit Varma]: where he will have a sequential list of things he wants to cover. And so that's a style. And it's a

01:45:26.240 --> 01:45:30.480
[Amit Varma]: great show conversations with Tyler, these are different sort of styles. So you have to figure

01:45:30.480 --> 01:45:33.680
[Amit Varma]: out what works for you, because you're being authentic to yourself. And I found that this

01:45:33.680 --> 01:45:38.400
[Amit Varma]: worked the best for me to don't interrupt, give them the space, don't look for gotcha moments,

01:45:38.400 --> 01:45:42.720
[Amit Varma]: right? I don't need to show off how smart I am. So I'm not going to, you know, keep interrupting

01:45:42.720 --> 01:45:46.000
[Amit Varma]: to show off my cleverness or that I have done my research or whatever, I'm not going to look for

01:45:46.000 --> 01:45:49.920
[Amit Varma]: gotcha moments that on, you know, last year, at so and so it's a time you said this, now you're

01:45:49.920 --> 01:45:54.480
[Amit Varma]: saying this, because I don't want the conversation to be adversarial, because I want them to come

01:45:54.480 --> 01:46:00.400
[Amit Varma]: relax to at the level where they are much more open and honest in sharing their thoughts and

01:46:00.400 --> 01:46:05.360
[Amit Varma]: their ideas with me. And it's important not to so even when I, for example, disagree with someone,

01:46:05.360 --> 01:46:09.360
[Amit Varma]: I will, I always state my disagreements, people don't realize this, because I'm being very polite,

01:46:09.360 --> 01:46:13.760
[Amit Varma]: and we're not used to politeness on social media disagreements and all of that. But I state my

01:46:13.760 --> 01:46:18.560
[Amit Varma]: disagreements, but I don't push the point. So you know, in fact, people have, I don't know if you're

01:46:18.560 --> 01:46:22.720
[Amit Varma]: one of them, but people gave me feedback on the Arvind Subramanian episode that I didn't push back

01:46:22.720 --> 01:46:28.000
[Amit Varma]: enough. And the thing is, I stated my disagreements. But then I don't want to push back and say, no,

01:46:28.000 --> 01:46:31.760
[Amit Varma]: you didn't answer this properly. Or what about this? Or what about that? Because I don't want

01:46:31.760 --> 01:46:36.560
[Amit Varma]: it to be adversarial. I'm happy to let the listener make up their own mind about what I asked and what

01:46:36.560 --> 01:46:42.320
[Amit Varma]: he said. But beyond that, I see no point in litigating something beyond the point in time.

01:46:42.320 --> 01:46:47.360
[Amit Varma]: And I also think that it's a little disrespectful that when the person has been generous enough with

01:46:47.360 --> 01:46:53.040
[Amit Varma]: their time and their, you know, with the insights, and you cannot take that generosity for granted,

01:46:53.040 --> 01:46:58.240
[Amit Varma]: to then disrespect that by, you know, taking it into other directions and showing how smart you

01:46:58.240 --> 01:47:02.720
[Amit Varma]: are and all that. I'm saying, my philosophy is you take in all that you can from the conversation

01:47:02.720 --> 01:47:08.080
[Amit Varma]: and whatever the disagreements are, you state them politely, and let the listeners sort of

01:47:08.080 --> 01:47:12.640
[Amit Varma]: make up their own mind, which is why so many people have disagreed with, have come back on

01:47:12.640 --> 01:47:17.040
[Amit Varma]: the show very often, because they enjoy that as well, given the take. So yeah.

01:47:17.760 --> 01:47:21.040
[Guest]: Yeah. And I don't think there's anything wrong with disagreement. But you know, it's a question

01:47:21.040 --> 01:47:27.840
[Guest]: of means and ends, right? Your show is not about holding public officeholders accountable,

01:47:27.840 --> 01:47:33.280
[Guest]: right? This is not primetime television. Or this is not, you know, you are not, as you said,

01:47:33.280 --> 01:47:40.240
[Guest]: litigating. The purpose of your show is to educate, you know, both oneself and, you know,

01:47:40.240 --> 01:47:45.200
[Guest]: the broader audience. And that's, of course, the larger point of it. But also in that immediate

01:47:45.200 --> 01:47:51.840
[Guest]: moment, be in that moment, right? Treat the other person, look in their eye, have that conversation,

01:47:51.840 --> 01:47:58.800
[Guest]: learn something from each other, have the benefit of spontaneity, that the conversation may take

01:47:58.800 --> 01:48:04.080
[Guest]: your mind to a place that you've never been to before. So it's not so much that I think interruptions

01:48:04.080 --> 01:48:08.880
[Guest]: are bad or having prepared questions are bad. It's just that it doesn't fit with the goal that you

01:48:08.880 --> 01:48:14.400
[Guest]: have in mind, right? Which is to see where this conversation might take you. And you can do that,

01:48:14.400 --> 01:48:18.880
[Guest]: because the guests on the show are so high quality, that they need very little, you know,

01:48:18.880 --> 01:48:24.240
[Guest]: direction or interruption and things like that. So I don't know if what you do and what Rusts does

01:48:24.240 --> 01:48:31.120
[Guest]: can be done by many other people with many other guests. But for the kind of purpose that you

01:48:31.120 --> 01:48:38.320
[Guest]: have in mind, I think the format just works beautifully. And also too few people, as you said,

01:48:38.320 --> 01:48:43.840
[Guest]: the end goal is usually to can an episode in a particular way. That's the other thing I learned

01:48:43.840 --> 01:48:49.680
[Guest]: from you. I am exactly like you, I prepare a lot of notes, I go in with like 20 pages of notes for

01:48:49.680 --> 01:48:54.800
[Guest]: each episode. But I actually don't, you know, prep questions or read out questions, I'll usually have

01:48:54.800 --> 01:48:58.720
[Guest]: my first question in mind. But other than that, it's like, you know, usually cracked open. And

01:48:58.720 --> 01:49:05.440
[Guest]: that's another thing I've learned from you. And I think the joy of that, for me, has been leaving

01:49:05.440 --> 01:49:12.080
[Guest]: myself open to be surprised in a way that it is impossible to be surprised if you go with a very

01:49:12.080 --> 01:49:17.840
[Amit Varma]: fixed idea in mind. Yeah, absolutely. I mean, and the thing with research is I always feel under

01:49:17.840 --> 01:49:23.040
[Amit Varma]: prepped. But I always, you know, cover very little of my prep. So here, I have a question,

01:49:23.040 --> 01:49:27.200
[Guest]: since we talked about like, you know, how much you and I prep and the notes, there's another

01:49:27.200 --> 01:49:33.120
[Guest]: question from Akshay Mukul, because he is prolific, not just in his books, but also in his questions

01:49:33.120 --> 01:49:39.120
[Guest]: on on this podcast. So here is Akshay Mukul's second question. I'm always amazed with your

01:49:39.120 --> 01:49:44.080
[Unknown]: research on diverse books, and the manner in which you make conversation freewheeling.

01:49:44.080 --> 01:49:50.560
[Unknown]: Can you tell us what kind of homework goes before each podcast? Yeah, lovely question. So, you know,

01:49:50.560 --> 01:49:55.040
[Amit Varma]: since I got into the long form conversation, I think, see, the thing is, the challenge of doing

01:49:55.040 --> 01:50:01.600
[Amit Varma]: a three hour conversation is exponentially tougher than say, a half an hour conversation.

01:50:01.600 --> 01:50:05.680
[Amit Varma]: It's not that you need six times as much research, it's just exponentially tougher.

01:50:05.680 --> 01:50:10.800
[Amit Varma]: So what I try to do is I try to like, first of all, of course, there is a selection bias

01:50:10.800 --> 01:50:15.040
[Amit Varma]: in that I'm choosing subjects which are already interesting to me. So I'm likely to have already

01:50:15.040 --> 01:50:19.600
[Amit Varma]: read books on them and have a certain amount of background information. But otherwise,

01:50:19.600 --> 01:50:23.920
[Amit Varma]: the thing is, like, if I'm talking to an author, I will obviously read all his books.

01:50:23.920 --> 01:50:29.840
[Amit Varma]: Like last week, my episode 199 was with Ambi Parmeswaran. And so I read five books by him.

01:50:29.840 --> 01:50:33.680
[Amit Varma]: And he's actually written 10. But the other five are like case studies and things like that.

01:50:33.680 --> 01:50:37.600
[Amit Varma]: So I read five books by him, watched a bunch of YouTube videos, took a lot of notes,

01:50:37.600 --> 01:50:41.840
[Amit Varma]: all of that you want to read around the subject. Like for a long time, I wanted to do

01:50:41.840 --> 01:50:46.800
[Amit Varma]: episodes on Gandhi with Ram Guha. And I read more than 30 books on Gandhi. But the thing is,

01:50:46.800 --> 01:50:50.960
[Amit Varma]: many of them are already read, they're not specifically for the episode. So besides his

01:50:50.960 --> 01:50:56.560
[Amit Varma]: own two books on Gandhi, I read a whole bunch else. And some of them I, you know, did a reread

01:50:56.560 --> 01:51:01.760
[Amit Varma]: skim when the time for the episode came about. So I've often had 20-30 pages of notes on

01:51:01.760 --> 01:51:06.080
[Amit Varma]: Microsoft Word for a particular episode. I have just recently discovered this app

01:51:06.080 --> 01:51:10.400
[Amit Varma]: called Roam Research. And that's amazing, because it allows you to

01:51:11.440 --> 01:51:16.160
[Amit Varma]: categorize and have nested queries and bidirectional linking. And so for the last

01:51:16.160 --> 01:51:22.400
[Amit Varma]: two, three episodes, I've used that and really enjoyed that. So which is much better than,

01:51:22.400 --> 01:51:26.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, Microsoft Word, where everything is one long list, and you bolded the parts.

01:51:26.720 --> 01:51:31.680
[Amit Varma]: But when you have 20 pages of notes, it's like, very difficult also that when you're at the start

01:51:31.680 --> 01:51:36.560
[Amit Varma]: of the show, somebody may mention, you know, some subject, which you know, your 25th question is

01:51:36.560 --> 01:51:41.360
[Amit Varma]: about or roundabouts there. So you're quickly scrolling to it, because while it's been mentioned,

01:51:41.360 --> 01:51:45.760
[Amit Varma]: you want to quote that relevant bit from that relevant book. And that's far easier in Roam

01:51:45.760 --> 01:51:52.400
[Amit Varma]: Research. And, you know, all of that. So I put in a lot of research. And the idea is not so much to

01:51:52.400 --> 01:51:56.400
[Amit Varma]: ask about all of those things. But because I think you need that background information,

01:51:56.400 --> 01:52:01.040
[Amit Varma]: that I need, if I'm talking to someone who's going to give me deep knowledge on a subject,

01:52:01.040 --> 01:52:08.960
[Amit Varma]: I need a certain baseline of knowledge myself, to be able to take the conversation to those sort of

01:52:08.960 --> 01:52:14.160
[Amit Varma]: interesting places like in Akshaya's case is not just reading Akshaya's books, but I also have to

01:52:14.160 --> 01:52:19.600
[Amit Varma]: have some awareness of the history of that time and how the Indian freedom movement was shaping

01:52:19.600 --> 01:52:24.000
[Amit Varma]: up. And, you know, all of those other kinds of things. Despite that, I must say that Akshaya's

01:52:24.000 --> 01:52:29.200
[Amit Varma]: book is just such a eye opener for me, because there are so many things that I didn't know in

01:52:29.200 --> 01:52:32.880
[Amit Varma]: that, which is why such a remarkable book, there are very few books, which, you know,

01:52:33.520 --> 01:52:39.520
[Amit Varma]: have so many TIL moments, especially about one's own country. So yeah, so I put in a lot of work

01:52:39.520 --> 01:52:43.200
[Amit Varma]: into research, which is rewarding for its own sake, I feel like I know the subject much better.

01:52:44.160 --> 01:52:52.560
[Amit Varma]: But I often, you know, at my age, I'm in my mid 40s, almost touching 47 next month. So I sort of,

01:52:52.560 --> 01:52:58.240
[Amit Varma]: so I forget a lot. So I forget what I've discussed in, you know, 30 episodes ago with somebody or

01:52:58.240 --> 01:53:02.400
[Amit Varma]: whatever. But the point is that, you know, at some level, you've internalized aspects of the

01:53:02.400 --> 01:53:08.400
[Amit Varma]: knowledge and that informs your worldview and your views on things to some extent. So So yeah,

01:53:08.400 --> 01:53:13.120
[Amit Varma]: but I think I think that in a sense, the one unintended consequence, the unseen effect,

01:53:13.120 --> 01:53:19.120
[Amit Varma]: as it were, of the show on my life, is to just really kickstart my reading habit again, and

01:53:19.120 --> 01:53:23.440
[Amit Varma]: make me read a lot more. And because of that, think much more deeply about knowledge management.

01:53:23.440 --> 01:53:28.480
[Amit Varma]: Like I was, you know, when I was doing the last class for my podcasting course, somebody also said

01:53:28.480 --> 01:53:31.920
[Amit Varma]: I should sort of one day teach a course on knowledge management. I don't know if someone

01:53:31.920 --> 01:53:36.480
[Amit Varma]: will be interested in that or not. But I've been getting into that because I think one of the great

01:53:36.480 --> 01:53:40.800
[Amit Varma]: challenges I face is that when you're exposing yourself to a lot of knowledge, how do you sort

01:53:40.800 --> 01:53:46.640
[Amit Varma]: of say build a second brain, so to say in, you know, Tiago Forte's words so that, you know,

01:53:46.640 --> 01:53:52.400
[Amit Varma]: that knowledge is sort of systemized, and it's not just diffused and lost and all of that. So

01:53:52.400 --> 01:53:56.400
[Amit Varma]: that's, again, something that I've been thinking about. And I don't imagine I would have been

01:53:56.400 --> 01:54:02.560
[Amit Varma]: thinking about it so much, had it not been for the work that the scene in the unseen makes me do.

01:54:02.560 --> 01:54:05.760
[Guest]: You know, knowledge management, there are two parts to it. One is, of course,

01:54:05.760 --> 01:54:09.840
[Guest]: knowledge management in terms of creating a record of what you're doing, right? I think,

01:54:09.840 --> 01:54:14.240
[Guest]: in that sense, what you're doing with the four volumes of the scene and the unseen is going to

01:54:14.240 --> 01:54:20.560
[Guest]: be this incredible, you know, resource, especially because unlike me, you don't put out the full

01:54:20.560 --> 01:54:25.120
[Guest]: transcript, right? So it's hard for people to go back and look up things or, you know,

01:54:25.120 --> 01:54:28.400
[Guest]: they may want to, but if they didn't have a piece of paper, because they were doing chores,

01:54:28.400 --> 01:54:32.880
[Guest]: they couldn't get the name of the book down. So I think it's that kind of knowledge management I

01:54:32.880 --> 01:54:38.080
[Guest]: really believe in, like, you know, just putting a body of work out there. The personal knowledge

01:54:38.080 --> 01:54:43.280
[Guest]: management, I don't believe in that much. You know, I always tell my students this, my students

01:54:43.280 --> 01:54:47.920
[Guest]: are always taking copious notes, you know, they're like, what is the best, you know, is Evernote

01:54:47.920 --> 01:54:53.520
[Guest]: better or Rome research better? By the way, thanks. That's a lifesaver. I just started using it. But

01:54:54.160 --> 01:55:01.280
[Guest]: I always tell them, think about it, internalize it. If you wanted to find it, just have faith

01:55:01.280 --> 01:55:05.520
[Guest]: that you will be able to find it. It might take you an extra five minutes in that moment, but you

01:55:05.520 --> 01:55:10.560
[Guest]: will be able to get it. The reason is now, unlike when you and I were studying in college and things

01:55:10.560 --> 01:55:15.440
[Guest]: like that, everything is available on the internet. Search functions are so good. You know, our own

01:55:15.440 --> 01:55:19.600
[Guest]: personal mobile phones and things have started getting search functions. So I think it's just

01:55:19.600 --> 01:55:25.200
[Guest]: much easier to go back and find something. My worry with knowledge management systems is they

01:55:25.200 --> 01:55:32.080
[Guest]: are so hard to create and maintain for personal use. I don't know if 95% of that crap I'm ever

01:55:32.080 --> 01:55:35.920
[Guest]: going to go back and see. Now, of course, if you're doing it for a project like a book or a podcast,

01:55:35.920 --> 01:55:40.480
[Guest]: it's a little bit different. But I think just like a general personal knowledge management system,

01:55:40.480 --> 01:55:45.920
[Guest]: I'm I'm not a big fan of it. I think just have faith in your brain and your curiosity and your

01:55:45.920 --> 01:55:50.080
[Guest]: ability to internalize concepts. And I think, you know, that'll take you quite far.

01:55:50.640 --> 01:55:54.400
[Amit Varma]: No, I mean, I'll disagree with this. Because I think our brain is not meant to

01:55:55.200 --> 01:55:59.840
[Amit Varma]: our first disagreement on the show. I think our brain is not meant to retain information in

01:55:59.840 --> 01:56:03.600
[Amit Varma]: systematic ways. And all of that our brain is meant to be creative and think about stuff,

01:56:03.600 --> 01:56:08.080
[Amit Varma]: but not really retain information. And I have often find knowledge management to be frustrating. And

01:56:08.080 --> 01:56:13.760
[Amit Varma]: I'll think of something that someone said and simply not be able to find it at all. Right?

01:56:13.760 --> 01:56:19.280
[Amit Varma]: And no matter all the search functions and all that. And what I find is that I actually find

01:56:19.280 --> 01:56:23.200
[Amit Varma]: Rome very helpful. Because what I'll do is every time I come across an interesting quote, maybe in

01:56:23.200 --> 01:56:27.360
[Amit Varma]: something that I'm reading, I'll just do that bi directional think I'll put double brackets and

01:56:27.360 --> 01:56:32.320
[Amit Varma]: quote around it. So now I have a page on Rome called quote, which includes all the quotes I've

01:56:32.320 --> 01:56:37.280
[Amit Varma]: ever, you know, tagged in that way, which is useful. And then within that there'll be other

01:56:37.280 --> 01:56:41.680
[Amit Varma]: similar things. So like, for example, when I was getting my podcasting course ready, I said,

01:56:41.680 --> 01:56:45.920
[Amit Varma]: I have to read books on the history of radio, the history of audio, and blah, blah, blah,

01:56:45.920 --> 01:56:51.920
[Amit Varma]: whole bunch of resources, books, videos, do all of that created a one page for that, then for each

01:56:51.920 --> 01:56:56.640
[Amit Varma]: of them, I had these nested bits where for each book, there's this nested bit, you click it,

01:56:56.640 --> 01:57:01.600
[Amit Varma]: it opens out, I have various insights there, I'm sort of linking them to each other. And

01:57:01.600 --> 01:57:06.240
[Amit Varma]: just in terms of organizing my mind, it was incredibly useful. And during that process,

01:57:06.240 --> 01:57:10.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, part of it turned out to be useless, because most of those insights were not at all

01:57:10.000 --> 01:57:13.840
[Amit Varma]: useful to me. And most of the insights, some of which I've shared here are not something that are

01:57:13.840 --> 01:57:19.600
[Amit Varma]: actually written anywhere. So you know, it's just coming from my experience. But for other subjects,

01:57:19.600 --> 01:57:24.400
[Amit Varma]: like when I research for episodes, like when I did the episode with Ambi, I had sort of like I

01:57:24.400 --> 01:57:28.560
[Amit Varma]: had Ambi Parmeswaran is the name of a page below that I have personal then that's nested, you click

01:57:28.560 --> 01:57:34.160
[Amit Varma]: on that it opens up it has, you know, which room of Godavari hostel in IIT Madras he was, so then

01:57:34.160 --> 01:57:39.200
[Amit Varma]: you use little nuggets like that. And then he also relaxes and it takes a nice personal tone. When

01:57:39.200 --> 01:57:44.240
[Amit Varma]: you bring that in, I had each of his books, I had, you know, separate nested sections for that

01:57:44.240 --> 01:57:48.880
[Amit Varma]: within that conceptually, I have separate nested sections, I come across interesting quotes,

01:57:48.880 --> 01:57:53.600
[Amit Varma]: because he uses quotes a lot in his book, they are now part of my larger database of quotes.

01:57:53.600 --> 01:57:58.240
[Amit Varma]: So it's, so I find it useful for me. But you're right. I mean, you said that is good for projects,

01:57:58.240 --> 01:58:03.040
[Amit Varma]: but not otherwise. I haven't used it long enough to be able to tell. But I think for individual

01:58:03.040 --> 01:58:07.440
[Amit Varma]: projects, like for researching for episodes is great. But one of the things I'm going to do now,

01:58:07.440 --> 01:58:13.760
[Amit Varma]: as I prepare my four anthologies for the seen and the unseen, is the transcripts of all my episodes,

01:58:13.760 --> 01:58:19.200
[Amit Varma]: when they get to me, I'm going to put them all in Rome research, so that then it becomes really

01:58:19.200 --> 01:58:24.560
[Amit Varma]: much easier to do that sort of bi-directional sort of forming connections, like I have asked so many

01:58:24.560 --> 01:58:30.320
[Amit Varma]: times that was a liberal constitution imposed on an illiberal society. And it's very easy for me

01:58:30.320 --> 01:58:35.200
[Amit Varma]: using tools like this to see how many people have asked it to and just bunch all the answers together

01:58:35.200 --> 01:58:40.240
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. So I think my brain struggles with the enormous amounts of knowledge out there.

01:58:40.240 --> 01:58:44.960
[Amit Varma]: And I think finding ways like this to kind of bring it all together is useful.

01:58:44.960 --> 01:58:48.960
[Guest]: By the way, on the whole, you know, saying incentives a number of times or talking about

01:58:48.960 --> 01:58:53.840
[Guest]: a liberal constitution imposed on illiberals. My biggest complaint about the scene and the

01:58:53.840 --> 01:58:58.960
[Guest]: unseen merchandise is that it does not come with short classes, because then your listeners can't

01:58:58.960 --> 01:59:05.040
[Unknown]: play a drinking game every time. Every time I say incentives. Amit Verma says incentives,

01:59:05.040 --> 01:59:09.920
[Unknown]: or every time you say multitudes, we all contain multitudes, or you quote John Lennon,

01:59:09.920 --> 01:59:16.880
[Guest]: or you talk about the liberal versus illiberal constitution. So my next suggestion for the

01:59:16.880 --> 01:59:24.160
[Guest]: merchandise, maybe for episode 250 or 300 is we desperately need short classes to play drinking

01:59:24.160 --> 01:59:31.440
[Guest]: games for the scene and the unseen. Now, I want to I mean, I know you have no trouble booking guests,

01:59:31.440 --> 01:59:36.000
[Guest]: because I mean, of course, you don't have trouble booking guests. But there are a couple of

01:59:36.000 --> 01:59:42.240
[Guest]: questions about, you know, choosing your guests. And the first question comes from someone who

01:59:42.240 --> 01:59:48.960
[Guest]: might be one of my, perhaps one of my most favorite thinkers alive in our time. And that is

01:59:48.960 --> 01:59:54.880
[Guest]: Pratap Bhanu Mehta. You know, I mean, I've read pretty much everything Pratap has written over

01:59:54.880 --> 02:00:00.720
[Guest]: the years, it is just a joy to read him. He's a thinker who once again, contains multitudes,

02:00:00.720 --> 02:00:05.680
[Guest]: right? I mean, the breadth and the depth with which he thinks about any subject is amazing,

02:00:06.400 --> 02:00:11.200
[Guest]: how it is both historical, but it's also abstract. And it's philosophical, but it's also about a

02:00:11.200 --> 02:00:16.800
[Guest]: contemporary issue. It's, you know, he's really one of my favorite thinkers. And I was so thrilled

02:00:16.800 --> 02:00:23.440
[Guest]: when you got him on the scene and the unseen. I heard that episode on, you know, 1x, I didn't

02:00:23.440 --> 02:00:29.360
[Guest]: speed it up, because I wanted it to just go on as long as it does. And like, enjoy every moment of

02:00:29.360 --> 02:00:36.000
[Guest]: it. But Pratap was very generous and instantly responded with a question. So I'm going to play

02:00:36.000 --> 02:00:39.840
[Guest]: Pratap's question for you. And then we'll talk a little bit more about guests on the scene and

02:00:39.840 --> 02:00:49.200
[Unknown]: the unseen. So Amit, congratulations on your double century. And I know this is just the beginning.

02:00:49.840 --> 02:00:55.520
[Unknown]: So one question I've always been meaning to ask you, is you have this great love for literature,

02:00:55.520 --> 02:01:01.200
[Unknown]: and you're one of the most voracious readers of novels that I know of. So if you were doing

02:01:01.200 --> 02:01:08.800
[Unknown]: a seance version of the scene and unseen, and you were inviting back a dead novelist for a

02:01:08.800 --> 02:01:15.200
[Unknown]: conversation, who would that be? And what's the question you would be dying to ask them?

02:01:16.800 --> 02:01:22.320
[Amit Varma]: Wow, what an incredible question. I think, yeah, I mean, that's, you know, like you said,

02:01:22.320 --> 02:01:25.760
[Amit Varma]: like, I love Pratap's writing, and he's incredibly thought provoking with everything

02:01:25.760 --> 02:01:30.640
[Amit Varma]: he writes. And I'm afraid he is thought provoking with his questions as well, because I'll have to

02:01:30.640 --> 02:01:35.520
[Amit Varma]: think a bit to, you know, come up with this, but I'm really glad I could finally get Pratap on my

02:01:35.520 --> 02:01:38.880
[Amit Varma]: show. Because you know, it's, you know, when I first started the scene and the unseen, I remember,

02:01:39.680 --> 02:01:44.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, opening up the notepad on my phone and thinking about who the possible guests would be.

02:01:44.160 --> 02:01:49.840
[Amit Varma]: And I put five names down, and then I couldn't think of any more. And Pratap was there. So I'm

02:01:49.840 --> 02:01:54.640
[Amit Varma]: really glad we kind of crossed that one off. And hopefully, he'll be back on my show at some point

02:01:54.640 --> 02:01:59.760
[Amit Varma]: in time without necessarily having a subject in mind just to sort of shoot the breeze as it were.

02:02:00.320 --> 02:02:04.320
[Amit Varma]: To answer this question, as far as novelists are concerned, well, you know, I'll cheat a bit,

02:02:04.320 --> 02:02:12.160
[Amit Varma]: I'll say George Orwell. But what I really love about George, as I said that Shruti held up a

02:02:12.160 --> 02:02:16.960
[Amit Varma]: piece of paper on which she had written George Orwell, so she guessed it. But again, my admiration

02:02:16.960 --> 02:02:21.360
[Amit Varma]: for Orwell is not so much for his novels, which is why it is a bit of a cheat, but really his

02:02:21.360 --> 02:02:27.360
[Amit Varma]: nonfiction writing, especially his remarkable collected essays, which is just so incredible.

02:02:27.360 --> 02:02:31.040
[Amit Varma]: And every time I'm stuck writing a piece, I'll, you know, open that and read three,

02:02:31.040 --> 02:02:35.680
[Amit Varma]: four essays by him on whatever subject, it doesn't matter. And just the rhythms of the language

02:02:35.680 --> 02:02:41.840
[Amit Varma]: that he uses will get my brain working properly again. So I love Orwell. Now, what would I ask

02:02:41.840 --> 02:02:47.440
[Amit Varma]: him? I think I would ask him that. I mean, he was already, I think by the time he died,

02:02:47.440 --> 02:02:53.840
[Amit Varma]: disillusioned with the extreme left by that time, even though you could call him a man of the left.

02:02:53.840 --> 02:02:58.480
[Amit Varma]: And I would ask him that, you know, if he had, presumably, if he comes back in a seance,

02:02:58.480 --> 02:03:02.400
[Amit Varma]: and as a ghost, he's been witnessing everything that's been happening since in some depth,

02:03:02.400 --> 02:03:08.160
[Amit Varma]: that has that disillusionment deepened, what does he feel now? And, you know, would he be

02:03:08.160 --> 02:03:13.200
[Amit Varma]: more likely to agree with his contemporary higher who I don't think that the two ever would have

02:03:13.200 --> 02:03:17.840
[Amit Varma]: met or known each other or even written about each other. So maybe just use the world because

02:03:17.840 --> 02:03:22.720
[Amit Varma]: it's interesting seeing his views evolve over a period of time. And I think Orwell was one of the

02:03:22.720 --> 02:03:28.480
[Amit Varma]: greatest, you know, he threw his novels, he looked into the future. I mean, the warnings against

02:03:28.480 --> 02:03:35.680
[Amit Varma]: totalitarianism and statism that his novels contain is second to none. And even today,

02:03:35.680 --> 02:03:41.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, especially people keep talking about 1984. And how, you know, this combination of

02:03:41.280 --> 02:03:47.280
[Amit Varma]: state power and technology could be bringing about something that makes what was once a dystopian

02:03:47.280 --> 02:03:53.200
[Amit Varma]: seem not so outlandish after all. And I'd ask a little bit about that, because I think that

02:03:53.200 --> 02:04:00.160
[Amit Varma]: he would have seen clearly enough to sort of, you know, be able to paint that crisp picture

02:04:00.160 --> 02:04:05.680
[Amit Varma]: where you realize that this sort of totalitarianism and statism doesn't come either from the left or

02:04:05.680 --> 02:04:10.880
[Amit Varma]: the right, it comes from both places. And in a sense, it comes from the same instinct of imposing

02:04:10.880 --> 02:04:15.680
[Amit Varma]: your vision of the world on others. And I'd be very interested in seeing how his thinking would

02:04:15.680 --> 02:04:22.480
[Amit Varma]: have evolved over these, you know, these sort of last 70 years. But that's a bit of a cheat,

02:04:22.480 --> 02:04:27.120
[Amit Varma]: because my admiration for Orwell is because of his nonfiction, though I love both 1984 and Animal

02:04:27.120 --> 02:04:33.920
[Amit Varma]: Farm. So give me a moment, let me think about whether this I am so kicked right now, while you

02:04:33.920 --> 02:04:39.760
[Guest]: take a moment that I called it, because as soon as I heard Pratap's question, I said, I'm pretty

02:04:39.760 --> 02:04:44.000
[Guest]: sure he's gonna say George Orwell. And then I'm pretty sure he's gonna hedge and say, you know,

02:04:44.000 --> 02:04:49.120
[Guest]: his fiction writing is great, but you must really read his nonfiction. So I feel like I've gotten to

02:04:49.120 --> 02:04:54.320
[Guest]: know you well, and I'm feeling very smug right now, though, for me, Animal Farm is always going

02:04:54.320 --> 02:04:58.000
[Amit Varma]: to be very special. Yeah, it's very special. I'd love to speak to guys like, for example,

02:04:58.000 --> 02:05:05.680
[Amit Varma]: Solzhenitsyn, or, you know, even someone like Dostoevsky, or, you know, the Japanese guys,

02:05:05.680 --> 02:05:10.800
[Amit Varma]: Mishima, Tanizaki. But I don't know what I would ask them. I mean, for example, my,

02:05:10.800 --> 02:05:16.800
[Amit Varma]: the literary writer at whose altar I worship is actually alive. It's Alice Munro. And I would

02:05:16.800 --> 02:05:20.400
[Amit Varma]: not want to meet her because I would not know what to say, I would not be able to say anything,

02:05:20.400 --> 02:05:26.240
[Amit Varma]: I would be sort of struck speechless. And there's really nothing to say. I mean, what do you say,

02:05:26.240 --> 02:05:30.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, her craft is in a sense beyond imitation. So with novelists, I think that's the

02:05:30.720 --> 02:05:35.680
[Amit Varma]: thing. If you ask about dead intellectuals from the past, who were thinkers or nonfiction writers,

02:05:35.680 --> 02:05:40.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, I'd love to talk to Kant, I'd love to talk to John Locke. You know, I'd love to

02:05:40.160 --> 02:05:45.280
[Amit Varma]: talk to Adam Smith. You know, as I know, you would and Russ Roberts would have.

02:05:45.280 --> 02:05:49.200
[Guest]: Speaking of people from the past and people who might not be around anymore,

02:05:49.200 --> 02:05:54.080
[Guest]: there is another one of our favorite guests, Narayani Basu, who's been on your show,

02:05:54.080 --> 02:06:01.120
[Guest]: who wrote the wonderful book on Menon. And, you know, I want to play her question for you,

02:06:01.120 --> 02:06:06.080
[Guest]: because I think she will give you the out from having to come up with a name other than George

02:06:06.080 --> 02:06:09.040
[Guest]: Orwell and coming up with a question to ask a literary figure.

02:06:09.760 --> 02:06:15.680
[Unknown]: Hi, Amit, this is Narayani. Many, many congratulations on 200 episodes. Thank you

02:06:15.680 --> 02:06:22.160
[Unknown]: so much for making longer conversations fun again. I wanted to ask, is there anyone

02:06:22.720 --> 02:06:28.160
[Unknown]: from any period of history? And this could be anybody, right? It could be a literary figure,

02:06:28.160 --> 02:06:33.520
[Unknown]: a literary figure, an actor, an economist, a social reform activist, you get the picture.

02:06:34.240 --> 02:06:41.760
[Unknown]: Anyone that you'd want to sit down with today, whether it's on or off your show and chat and why?

02:06:42.720 --> 02:06:46.800
[Amit Varma]: Great question and a tough question. I don't really know. I mean, the easy answer and the

02:06:46.800 --> 02:06:50.000
[Amit Varma]: name that pops to mind, and I hope you haven't written it down and you're going to wave it at

02:06:50.000 --> 02:06:56.320
[Amit Varma]: the screen in front of me, but you have it ready. Okay. It's probably, I mean, Bastia is obviously,

02:06:56.320 --> 02:07:00.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, the first name that comes to mind. I mean, the name of my show, the scene in the unseen

02:07:00.800 --> 02:07:06.400
[Amit Varma]: is inspired by Bastia's great essay, that which is seen and that which is not seen. And his works

02:07:06.400 --> 02:07:10.560
[Amit Varma]: are remarkable. The law is beautiful. His essays are great. The law is just a masterpiece. And

02:07:11.280 --> 02:07:15.680
[Amit Varma]: in so many ways, I mean, the law contains so much of what, you know, it almost anticipates

02:07:15.680 --> 02:07:22.640
[Amit Varma]: public choice theory in so many ways. And also I look at Bastia as, you know, I kind of find

02:07:22.640 --> 02:07:27.600
[Amit Varma]: there's a certain sense of both tragedy and inspiration there that he spends those last

02:07:27.600 --> 02:07:33.200
[Amit Varma]: years from forties to, I think he died when he was 49 or 50, much, much like Orwell. And he's

02:07:33.200 --> 02:07:37.920
[Amit Varma]: essentially fighting a lonely battle that it's inevitable that no one agrees with him, but he's

02:07:37.920 --> 02:07:44.720
[Amit Varma]: putting his ideas out there because it is important to do so. And in a sense, he's again, not writing

02:07:44.720 --> 02:07:50.720
[Amit Varma]: across space, he's writing across time, because, which is why someone like me, you know, a century

02:07:50.720 --> 02:07:55.200
[Amit Varma]: and a half later can be inspired by him. And, you know, of course, I've won two prizes named after

02:07:55.200 --> 02:08:01.120
[Amit Varma]: him, but that's orthogonal. And, but someone like me can be inspired by him and can, you know, find

02:08:01.120 --> 02:08:06.240
[Amit Varma]: value in doing just that. And it also tells you that, you know, the fact that that battle was

02:08:06.240 --> 02:08:12.800
[Amit Varma]: never won that, you know, which he was fighting, which is for individual rights and agency and,

02:08:13.520 --> 02:08:17.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, controlling the power of the state and even understanding it was something that

02:08:17.200 --> 02:08:22.720
[Amit Varma]: was never won and may never be won, but you have to keep fighting the good fight and sort of

02:08:23.280 --> 02:08:26.640
[Amit Varma]: working on that. So I find him inspiring for that reason. The thing is, you know,

02:08:26.640 --> 02:08:30.880
[Amit Varma]: when you ask a hypothetical question of if you could talk to someone from the past novelist or

02:08:30.880 --> 02:08:36.000
[Amit Varma]: otherwise, and ask them a question or whatever, the thing is, like I said, I'm so incredibly

02:08:36.000 --> 02:08:40.000
[Amit Varma]: private and introverted and whatever is that I probably wouldn't want to meet them. I would,

02:08:40.000 --> 02:08:45.200
[Amit Varma]: I would just, you know, like, what would one say with Bastia? Of course, I'd love to do an episode

02:08:45.200 --> 02:08:50.000
[Amit Varma]: of the scene and the unseen with Bastia, like what is a French parliament like, do your friends

02:08:50.000 --> 02:08:55.040
[Amit Varma]: mock you for your views, like my friends mock me, and all of that, you know, and I would have tried

02:08:55.040 --> 02:08:59.520
[Amit Varma]: to get a human sense of that battle, sort of the loneliness of the battle, because, you know,

02:08:59.520 --> 02:09:03.520
[Amit Varma]: I can reach out to many other people who think like me across the world, and I have that access

02:09:03.520 --> 02:09:09.520
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. But, you know, Bastia would not have had that. So then what kind of keeps you

02:09:10.080 --> 02:09:13.760
[Amit Varma]: going? In a sense, I think I somehow in some strange way managed to make this about me.

02:09:13.760 --> 02:09:19.600
[Amit Varma]: But yeah, I mean, Bastia is interesting. Adam Smith is, of course, interesting when you just

02:09:19.600 --> 02:09:24.560
[Amit Varma]: see the sort of the breadth of his work in just those two books, a journey from a theory of moral

02:09:24.560 --> 02:09:30.160
[Amit Varma]: sentiments to, you know, the wealth of nations, just in sort of that journey and how much he

02:09:30.160 --> 02:09:34.080
[Amit Varma]: covers. And of course, you know, Russ Roberts, and I spoke a bit about Adam Smith in our episode,

02:09:34.080 --> 02:09:38.080
[Amit Varma]: and he's written a great, lovely book on Adam Smith, which I recommend everyone

02:09:38.080 --> 02:09:43.200
[Amit Varma]: goes out and reads. Adam Smith would have been interesting, Locke would have been interesting.

02:09:43.200 --> 02:09:49.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, and I think had he lived today, he would have refined his ideas to a much

02:09:49.120 --> 02:09:54.480
[Amit Varma]: finer degree. But to think that a man like that wrote, you know, works like that when he did is

02:09:54.480 --> 02:09:59.760
[Amit Varma]: just remarkable. Apart from that, yeah, I should, you know, I'll be accused of being non-Sanskari

02:09:59.760 --> 02:10:05.600
[Amit Varma]: if I can't name Indian figures. I would have loved to hang out with Kabir, just, you know,

02:10:05.600 --> 02:10:12.800
[Amit Varma]: just, you know, talk about poetry and sort of, you know, how he thinks of language, and how

02:10:12.800 --> 02:10:16.880
[Amit Varma]: sort of all of those sort of different things. And I haven't done enough episodes

02:10:17.760 --> 02:10:22.400
[Amit Varma]: on that. I mean, I kind of should, but Kabir would have been fun. Even, you know, I did an

02:10:22.400 --> 02:10:28.240
[Amit Varma]: episode with Amardeep Singh on the travels of Guru Nanak and Nanak Banti. And Nanak is a very

02:10:28.240 --> 02:10:32.400
[Amit Varma]: Kabir like figure, a very interesting person, not just someone who founded a religion, but

02:10:32.400 --> 02:10:37.440
[Amit Varma]: a very interesting, deep thinker. So again, I would have liked to hang out, maybe just be a fly

02:10:37.440 --> 02:10:41.440
[Amit Varma]: on the wall and maybe travel around a little bit with someone like that, not necessarily do an

02:10:41.440 --> 02:10:46.080
[Amit Varma]: episode and get gyan, because I think there is something beyond intellectual gyan and just

02:10:46.080 --> 02:10:52.400
[Amit Varma]: discussing ideas. But, you know, just maybe travel around and, you know, as far as travels are

02:10:52.400 --> 02:10:57.360
[Amit Varma]: concerned, I am notorious for being the kind of person who, you know, I don't like to walk very

02:10:57.360 --> 02:11:02.400
[Amit Varma]: much. And I don't, I'm not the explorer kinds. I'm like, you know, book me into a comfortable

02:11:02.400 --> 02:11:07.120
[Amit Varma]: place. I want to chill and relax, because that is what vacations are for. But I think it would

02:11:07.120 --> 02:11:12.640
[Amit Varma]: be different if I was hanging out with either Nanak or Kabir or any of these guys. And maybe

02:11:12.640 --> 02:11:18.080
[Amit Varma]: I'd be live blogging while I was with them. Like, you know, after the tsunami had struck in 2004,

02:11:18.080 --> 02:11:23.200
[Amit Varma]: I'd, as you'd know, I'd gone along the coast of Tamil Nadu and those were early days in my blog,

02:11:23.200 --> 02:11:28.960
[Amit Varma]: and I was posting updates every day. And that was in a different way or sort of a very, it was

02:11:28.960 --> 02:11:33.280
[Amit Varma]: interesting. And I'm glad I did that. It was difficult also, you know, like at Nagapattinam,

02:11:34.000 --> 02:11:38.560
[Amit Varma]: and I wrote about this for Rediff also, but, you know, just in a field where you have dead

02:11:38.560 --> 02:11:43.200
[Amit Varma]: bodies all around you and kind of walking through them. And at some point it normalizes in your

02:11:43.200 --> 02:11:48.800
[Amit Varma]: brain and you don't think of them as, you know, former people, so to say. But it's interesting.

02:11:48.800 --> 02:11:53.680
[Guest]: I don't know if I've told you this before, but that's how I found you, through the tsunami

02:11:53.680 --> 02:11:58.480
[Guest]: coverage on your blog. Because I was there at the same time in Nage district.

02:12:00.240 --> 02:12:04.800
[Guest]: Yeah, I had a break from, you know, as you know, it happened between Christmas and New Year. And

02:12:04.800 --> 02:12:09.360
[Guest]: there is, you know, the term break, and just figured out that, you know, things need to be

02:12:09.360 --> 02:12:16.320
[Guest]: done. So I got on an unreserved ticket and just went to Tamil Nadu. And then, you know, figured

02:12:16.320 --> 02:12:21.840
[Guest]: it out from there and joined a volunteer group. And they placed me in a tiny village called Kutty

02:12:21.840 --> 02:12:28.080
[Guest]: Andir, which is in Nage district. And so not very far from where you were blogging. And your blog

02:12:28.080 --> 02:12:33.440
[Guest]: was really lovely. It was one of the very few sort of, you know, I mean, now we have all the blogs

02:12:33.440 --> 02:12:38.960
[Guest]: and the live tweets and all those things going on. But at that time, it was very unique to get that,

02:12:38.960 --> 02:12:45.040
[Guest]: you know, instant, not just news, but also reflections, you know, that was an odd thing

02:12:45.040 --> 02:12:47.520
[Guest]: that was going on at the time. So that's how I found you.

02:12:47.520 --> 02:12:52.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And I was also trying to, I think, look in a different way, if that makes sense,

02:12:52.080 --> 02:12:57.680
[Amit Varma]: like not just look at events and talk to people and ask about the experience. But like, I remember

02:12:57.680 --> 02:13:02.800
[Amit Varma]: when we went through village after village, and I found that in different places, the watches,

02:13:02.800 --> 02:13:09.120
[Amit Varma]: the clock stopped at a different time. And you could make out by the last time on these time

02:13:09.120 --> 02:13:15.200
[Amit Varma]: pieces across all these villages across the shore, when the waves had hit. And that's so incredibly

02:13:15.200 --> 02:13:20.160
[Amit Varma]: poignant and almost heartbreaking, because it carries with it the loss of life and the loss

02:13:20.160 --> 02:13:25.600
[Amit Varma]: of so much, you know, it's just so yeah, and at some level, I wish I'd done a little bit more of

02:13:25.600 --> 02:13:30.160
[Amit Varma]: that, that kind of reporting. And in that sense, you could say I didn't take the initiative enough

02:13:30.160 --> 02:13:36.000
[Amit Varma]: in some ways, that I was just like a death bound person per se, which is what I even am for the

02:13:36.000 --> 02:13:40.480
[Amit Varma]: seen in the unseen, right? I'm just like, you know, sitting in a studio or during the lockdown

02:13:40.480 --> 02:13:45.520
[Amit Varma]: at a mic in my room, and just talking to people and not really out there. But perhaps in this case,

02:13:45.520 --> 02:13:53.040
[Amit Varma]: I think this is the value that I can create now. So it sort of makes sense. And I was but at that

02:13:53.040 --> 02:13:57.120
[Amit Varma]: time, I think I should have gone out more and I was probably too lazy.

02:13:57.120 --> 02:14:02.640
[Guest]: You know, the the timepiece part that you mentioned another really poignant moment I had,

02:14:02.640 --> 02:14:08.160
[Guest]: when this was happening is, you know, one, the first act of, you know, any kind of relief work

02:14:08.160 --> 02:14:12.080
[Guest]: is obviously clearing rubble and making sure you know, people have food and things like that.

02:14:12.640 --> 02:14:19.920
[Guest]: And by the time I reached the village, most of the, you know, sort of the dead had been found

02:14:19.920 --> 02:14:25.520
[Guest]: and sort of disposed in whatever manner was, you know, possible or appropriate at the time.

02:14:26.160 --> 02:14:31.920
[Guest]: But there was this one place where the dwelling structure had really caved in. And clearly,

02:14:31.920 --> 02:14:35.280
[Guest]: someone had been trapped in there, and they hadn't found the body. But obviously, it had

02:14:35.280 --> 02:14:38.800
[Guest]: decomposed to such an extent that there was a stench. And then, you know, people were called

02:14:38.800 --> 02:14:43.360
[Guest]: in to move the rubble and things like that. And the only thing that hadn't decomposed was the

02:14:43.360 --> 02:14:49.760
[Guest]: polyester sari, you know, and the thought that someone's, you know, I mean, this must have cost

02:14:49.760 --> 02:14:56.080
[Guest]: 100 rupees or less, right. And the idea that this polyester sari is in some sense more durable

02:14:56.080 --> 02:15:01.920
[Guest]: than human life, which can just be so fragile in a disaster like this, that like that that picture

02:15:01.920 --> 02:15:06.720
[Guest]: has never left me. And you know, I can if I close my eyes, I can just I can see that rubble and I

02:15:06.720 --> 02:15:10.960
[Guest]: can, I can see the sari. So that was an eye opening experience for sure.

02:15:10.960 --> 02:15:15.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah. And so you know, one of the things that you know, so I mentioned this watches thing

02:15:15.200 --> 02:15:19.440
[Amit Varma]: in a recent episode, I think with Nilesh Mishra. And then when I was linking that post from my

02:15:19.440 --> 02:15:24.080
[Amit Varma]: show notes, I went back to all the posts I'd written during that period. And I'd realized

02:15:24.080 --> 02:15:29.360
[Amit Varma]: and I'd realized how unformed my thinking otherwise was, how naive I was in my faith that,

02:15:29.920 --> 02:15:33.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, the state could have sorted this out with better regulation, there would have been

02:15:33.840 --> 02:15:40.480
[Amit Varma]: less life lost, and we needed sterner coastal laws and a bunch of other things, which over time I,

02:15:40.480 --> 02:15:44.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, I had reason to think about deeper and say that, okay, that was misformed that I just

02:15:44.640 --> 02:15:48.880
[Amit Varma]: sort of intentions and not probable outcomes and the way the political economy actually works and

02:15:48.880 --> 02:15:54.480
[Amit Varma]: blah, blah, blah. So it's interesting also to see one's own journey through that past and realize

02:15:54.480 --> 02:15:59.760
[Amit Varma]: how about, you know, one's opinions were just wrong about so many things, but, you know, and

02:15:59.760 --> 02:16:04.080
[Amit Varma]: even during the scene in the unseen, I think there's a sort of a mirroring of that where I

02:16:04.080 --> 02:16:09.360
[Amit Varma]: remember I did that episode with Akar Patel on, you know, the intellectual foundations of Hindutva,

02:16:09.360 --> 02:16:13.200
[Amit Varma]: which I remember you saying at the time that you really loved that as well. And that was a great

02:16:13.200 --> 02:16:18.400
[Amit Varma]: episode. But both of us were of the opinion at the time of that episode. And, you know, my view

02:16:18.400 --> 02:16:23.200
[Amit Varma]: before it, in fact, very firmly was that there is nothing there, there is no intellectual tradition.

02:16:23.200 --> 02:16:27.840
[Amit Varma]: And whatever claims to be an intellectual tradition is just a cover for a Makota for

02:16:28.640 --> 02:16:33.360
[Amit Varma]: bigotry and all of those other things. And later in the course of doing episodes with

02:16:33.360 --> 02:16:37.840
[Amit Varma]: people like Akshay Mukul, you know, that episode then tells you that there is a tradition. And the

02:16:37.840 --> 02:16:42.000
[Amit Varma]: reason many people like me are missing that tradition is because we read in English,

02:16:42.000 --> 02:16:46.240
[Amit Varma]: where those arguments aren't made in English, but there is a rich tradition in Hinduism.

02:16:46.240 --> 02:16:51.120
[Amit Varma]: Now, you may not agree with that intellectual tradition, but it is coherent and cogent and it

02:16:51.120 --> 02:16:59.280
[Amit Varma]: exists. And, you know, chatting with people like Akshay Mukul and Rahul Verma, and others sort of

02:16:59.280 --> 02:17:03.520
[Amit Varma]: made me realize that in that regard, I was I was wrong. And I needed to have a more nuanced view.

02:17:03.520 --> 02:17:08.000
[Amit Varma]: And that that view reflected my own shortcomings as someone who read mainly in English,

02:17:08.000 --> 02:17:11.360
[Amit Varma]: rather than, you know, something that was actually the truth.

02:17:11.360 --> 02:17:18.000
[Guest]: You know, I want to since you talk both about the blogging days and now, I want to play the

02:17:18.000 --> 02:17:24.240
[Guest]: next question from again, one of our common friends and, you know, ace podcaster and writer.

02:17:24.240 --> 02:17:29.600
[Guest]: This is Pranay Kothasthani. And, you know, he's been on on your show multiple times.

02:17:29.600 --> 02:17:36.880
[Guest]: He's just a wonderful thinker and intellectual. I always enjoy reading him. I love listening to him.

02:17:36.880 --> 02:17:43.120
[Guest]: So, I'm going to play this next question from Pranay and then take this conversation forward.

02:17:43.840 --> 02:17:47.760
[Unknown]: Hey, Amit, Pranay here. Many, many congratulations for doing what you do

02:17:47.760 --> 02:17:53.200
[Unknown]: and for inspiring so many of us to get into podcasting. Now, here's my question for you.

02:17:53.200 --> 02:17:58.320
[Unknown]: You've been both a podcaster and a writer. So, what do you think are the comparative

02:17:58.320 --> 02:18:05.120
[Unknown]: advantages of both? Similarly, from the consumer's end, what do you think are the

02:18:05.120 --> 02:18:10.160
[Unknown]: comparative advantages of podcast listening over reading, if any?

02:18:10.160 --> 02:18:16.560
[Amit Varma]: Fantastic question. And I share your admiration of Pranay and I know him fairly well, because,

02:18:16.560 --> 02:18:20.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, when I all the times when I was editing Pragati, he's, of course, part of

02:18:20.000 --> 02:18:25.200
[Amit Varma]: Takshashila and he wrote a lot for me and just a wonderful, warm human being, you know, such a

02:18:25.200 --> 02:18:29.760
[Amit Varma]: good person that you think that, you know, it's, you know, the correlation of great thinker and

02:18:29.760 --> 02:18:35.200
[Amit Varma]: good person is surely not common. And so you imagine that such a nice guy cannot possibly be

02:18:35.200 --> 02:18:40.160
[Amit Varma]: a fine thinker. But I think he's just one of the finest, sharpest thinkers about policy that I

02:18:40.160 --> 02:18:45.520
[Amit Varma]: personally know, you know, really, you know, he's such a humble, down to earth guy that it's hard

02:18:45.520 --> 02:18:50.880
[Amit Varma]: to sort of think of him as someone on a pedestal. But as an intellectual, he is on a pedestal for

02:18:50.880 --> 02:18:58.560
[Amit Varma]: me. And he does a great Hindi podcast, Pulya Bazi, which is wonderful. I have been a guest

02:18:58.560 --> 02:19:04.640
[Guest]: I have been a guest on that show. And I had, I was just sweating and so nervous, because I've

02:19:04.640 --> 02:19:08.880
[Guest]: never thought about property rights concepts in Hindi, I didn't even know the right words.

02:19:08.880 --> 02:19:14.080
[Guest]: And he and Saurabh sort of held my hand through it. But I feel like I interact with Pranay a lot

02:19:14.080 --> 02:19:19.680
[Guest]: because of the newsletter and the sub stack. And it's, I just look forward to it every time it,

02:19:19.680 --> 02:19:23.440
[Guest]: you know, shows up in my inbox. I think he's doing an incredible job.

02:19:23.440 --> 02:19:30.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, I was also in Pulya Bazi talking in Hindi about Hayek. So yeah, that was that was

02:19:30.160 --> 02:19:33.520
[Amit Varma]: good fun. Pranay is great. And his newsletter is great, co-written with Raghu Jaitley,

02:19:33.520 --> 02:19:36.960
[Amit Varma]: whose real name I know, but shall not reveal, though I never met him.

02:19:36.960 --> 02:19:38.480
[Amit Varma]: Oh, yes. Okay.

02:19:38.480 --> 02:19:42.480
[Amit Varma]: Oh, really? You didn't know that? Okay. Yes. Yeah, bragging rights.

02:19:43.600 --> 02:19:44.800
[Amit Varma]: So I have bragging rights.

02:19:44.800 --> 02:19:50.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. So these, these great questions. And I think the short answer to the difference between

02:19:50.080 --> 02:19:56.160
[Amit Varma]: writing and podcasting is really breadth versus depth, in the sense that, you know, as far as

02:19:56.160 --> 02:20:00.560
[Amit Varma]: reading, writing is concerned, you can just read a lot. And you can read a lot about a bunch of

02:20:00.560 --> 02:20:05.360
[Amit Varma]: different subjects, and you can get breadth that way. Whereas the best podcasts go deep into one

02:20:05.360 --> 02:20:08.640
[Amit Varma]: specific thing. And obviously, if you're listening to different episodes or different podcasts,

02:20:08.640 --> 02:20:13.360
[Amit Varma]: you're getting a certain amount of breadth that way. But writing doesn't allow you to go as deep

02:20:13.360 --> 02:20:21.360
[Amit Varma]: as podcasting does. Like I said, my episode with on education with Karthik Muralitharan was 43,000

02:20:21.360 --> 02:20:26.560
[Amit Varma]: words when it was transcribed, which at double speed, you could have listened to in one and a

02:20:26.560 --> 02:20:31.040
[Amit Varma]: half hours. You know, that's almost a short book. That's a monograph. You know, how are you going

02:20:31.040 --> 02:20:37.440
[Amit Varma]: to consume that and get, you know, that many words, you know, in that much time? And where

02:20:37.440 --> 02:20:43.840
[Amit Varma]: are you? And that's like a sharp, focused kind of discussion that is happening. You know, an

02:20:43.840 --> 02:20:49.440
[Amit Varma]: interview of Karthik in a newspaper would be 800 words, even in a long interview in something like

02:20:49.440 --> 02:20:55.280
[Amit Varma]: caravan would be 7-8000 words at most. And here you have 43,000 words. And I think in one word,

02:20:55.280 --> 02:21:00.480
[Amit Varma]: I think that's the main difference, which is why one has to sort of embrace length. And I'll

02:21:01.280 --> 02:21:05.200
[Amit Varma]: pat myself on the back a little bit for this. Because I think when I started growing long,

02:21:05.200 --> 02:21:11.840
[Amit Varma]: you could say, I shifted the Overton window of length in Indian podcasting, that, you know, now,

02:21:12.480 --> 02:21:18.400
[Amit Varma]: interviews, which last one, one and a half hours are perfectly common, especially, you know, among

02:21:18.960 --> 02:21:23.360
[Amit Varma]: the policy podcasts and all of that. And that really wasn't the case. You know, it's like a

02:21:23.360 --> 02:21:28.480
[Amit Varma]: string that I remember that I just kept lifting it. And I have so many three hour episodes now,

02:21:28.480 --> 02:21:33.360
[Amit Varma]: including presumably this one by the time it's out, that a one hour episode feels like nothing

02:21:33.360 --> 02:21:37.840
[Amit Varma]: at all. And I'm sort of happy about that. The other aspect of that, and I don't know what the

02:21:37.840 --> 02:21:42.480
[Amit Varma]: related stat for other Indian podcasts is, but the one part, I don't look at metrics. But the

02:21:42.480 --> 02:21:47.200
[Amit Varma]: one interesting metric that I have sort of, that gives me satisfaction about my podcast is that

02:21:47.200 --> 02:21:52.400
[Amit Varma]: most people listen, most regular listeners listen to podcast apps on listen to podcasts on their

02:21:52.400 --> 02:21:59.840
[Amit Varma]: podcast apps, while I still get about 30 to 40% of my listens from Chrome, which means that these

02:21:59.840 --> 02:22:04.960
[Amit Varma]: are not regular listeners from the browser, rather. And this means these are not regular listeners.

02:22:04.960 --> 02:22:10.400
[Amit Varma]: These are people for whom that episode of mine has acted as a gateway drug of sorts. And that's

02:22:10.400 --> 02:22:15.360
[Amit Varma]: how they've come into it, which you know, and hopefully I'm kind of, I managed to convert some

02:22:15.360 --> 02:22:19.840
[Amit Varma]: of them. So that gives me a lot of happiness, because I think the ecosystem is very young.

02:22:19.840 --> 02:22:25.520
[Amit Varma]: And we are at a stage where nobody's competing with anybody else. We just want to grow the

02:22:25.520 --> 02:22:31.280
[Amit Varma]: listening habit among people. And we all benefit from that. And that's something that we need. And

02:22:31.280 --> 02:22:36.880
[Amit Varma]: which is why I go out of my way to help people do podcasts. I've sort of, you know, as the editor of

02:22:36.880 --> 02:22:42.320
[Amit Varma]: Pragati, I, you know, started the Pragati podcast, which Pawan Srinath does so well. And he did that

02:22:42.320 --> 02:22:47.440
[Amit Varma]: with Hamsini for a while, she started her own podcast. And so I sort of tried to keep that

02:22:47.440 --> 02:22:52.480
[Amit Varma]: tradition going. Even now with my podcasting course, what I sort of stressed on in the first

02:22:52.480 --> 02:22:56.320
[Amit Varma]: class that I did, was that I don't want this to be like taking a gym membership,

02:22:58.320 --> 02:23:03.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, I want to podcast at the end of this, I want to, you know, so let's work at that.

02:23:03.840 --> 02:23:08.560
[Amit Varma]: So initially, I thought that the first two webinars, the total three webinars, the first two

02:23:08.560 --> 02:23:12.480
[Amit Varma]: can be kind of conceptual, and then we get down to the nitty gritties that this is your basic

02:23:12.480 --> 02:23:17.520
[Amit Varma]: equipment, this is how you record, blah, blah, blah. But I devoted half of my first webinar to

02:23:17.520 --> 02:23:22.400
[Amit Varma]: the nitty gritties because I said that you got to kind of, you know, get down to it right now that

02:23:22.400 --> 02:23:26.640
[Amit Varma]: we can't stay at the level of the abstract, we have to get down to the concrete and actually

02:23:26.640 --> 02:23:32.640
[Amit Varma]: get things done. And I feel strongly about this because, you know, I am in a limited space in

02:23:32.640 --> 02:23:38.000
[Amit Varma]: the sense that right now podcasts in India seem to be heard a lot by English speaking elites.

02:23:38.000 --> 02:23:44.240
[Amit Varma]: And I think the real scope is in the languages, because there is so much more hunger for knowledge

02:23:44.240 --> 02:23:48.880
[Amit Varma]: and information in the languages. If you if you read in English today, you can go on the internet,

02:23:48.880 --> 02:23:52.720
[Amit Varma]: and the world of knowledge is at your fingertips, you can go to YouTube, watch the best videos,

02:23:52.720 --> 02:23:57.600
[Amit Varma]: blah, blah, blah. But supply of that kind of knowledge and insight is so limited in the

02:23:57.600 --> 02:24:03.120
[Amit Varma]: languages. And there is much greater hunger and scope for it. And I'd really like to see

02:24:03.120 --> 02:24:09.680
[Amit Varma]: young entrepreneurs start podcasts, which may not cater to the same use cases, because beyond a

02:24:09.680 --> 02:24:13.760
[Amit Varma]: certain class of society, people may not have the time to actually be working out for an hour a day.

02:24:13.760 --> 02:24:18.000
[Amit Varma]: So when are they going to listen, but, you know, figure out different ways of distributing

02:24:18.000 --> 02:24:22.720
[Amit Varma]: podcasts, maybe not a podcast app, maybe on WhatsApp, a guy is getting a five minute update

02:24:22.720 --> 02:24:27.520
[Amit Varma]: every morning in Hindi, which gives perspective on what happened that day, not just news,

02:24:27.520 --> 02:24:32.400
[Amit Varma]: or things like that, just throw things at the wall, try interesting things. Because that's where

02:24:32.400 --> 02:24:38.160
[Amit Varma]: I think podcasts will kind of really explode and really make a difference in our society.

02:24:38.160 --> 02:24:42.480
[Guest]: You know, the thing you mentioned about language, that's the other thing I really love about

02:24:42.480 --> 02:24:49.600
[Guest]: podcasts, which is that even people who don't speak English as fluently, maybe as you and me,

02:24:49.600 --> 02:24:53.760
[Guest]: because we we have the privilege of, you know, being English medium or whatever,

02:24:54.480 --> 02:25:00.560
[Guest]: they can listen to the podcast at their own pace in their own time, you know, they can actually

02:25:00.560 --> 02:25:04.960
[Guest]: hear how the words are said in what context they are used. Whereas, you know, normally,

02:25:04.960 --> 02:25:10.400
[Guest]: the only access to these ideas would be through the written word, which is much harder to access

02:25:10.400 --> 02:25:16.720
[Guest]: if, if your fluency levels are not that high. So I think, even for non English speakers, or those

02:25:16.720 --> 02:25:22.000
[Guest]: who are perhaps less fluent, I think the podcast medium does something really interesting and

02:25:22.000 --> 02:25:27.920
[Guest]: really special. And and you told me not to use jargon, you admonished me a few minutes, or was

02:25:27.920 --> 02:25:33.920
[Guest]: it a few hours ago, I lost track of time. But I think there is some value to that, right? Like

02:25:33.920 --> 02:25:39.200
[Guest]: people are also learning, we might make fun of drinking games and talking about incentives and

02:25:39.200 --> 02:25:45.040
[Guest]: liberalism. But with us, the listeners are also learning the language of how to think about these

02:25:45.040 --> 02:25:49.600
[Amit Varma]: ideas and how to communicate them. Yeah, first of all, let me correct you, I did not admonish you,

02:25:49.600 --> 02:25:54.640
[Amit Varma]: I scolded you. So let us use sort of simpler words. But no, that's a that's a great point.

02:25:54.640 --> 02:26:00.480
[Amit Varma]: And that brings me to a related sort of I thought it was little more gentle than scolding. Well,

02:26:00.480 --> 02:26:06.960
[Amit Varma]: I mean, yeah. So I mean, there are surely simpler synonyms of admonished. So you know,

02:26:06.960 --> 02:26:11.120
[Amit Varma]: but that's absolutely true. Because you know, a good friend of mine, I don't know if you met him,

02:26:11.120 --> 02:26:16.480
[Amit Varma]: Yogesh Dashrath, who runs Storytel. Yeah, you haven't met Yogesh. So Yogesh who runs Storytel,

02:26:16.480 --> 02:26:20.960
[Amit Varma]: and I've done some work for Storytel in the past. And they have this, and it's, you know,

02:26:20.960 --> 02:26:25.760
[Amit Varma]: sponsored many episodes of the scene and scene in the unseen in the past. So friends of the podcast,

02:26:25.760 --> 02:26:32.720
[Amit Varma]: in a sense, early sponsors. So Yogesh once told me and they have a great bank of Marathi and Hindi

02:26:32.720 --> 02:26:37.040
[Amit Varma]: audiobooks. So a lot of the listeners are people who are listening to Marathi and Hindi. In fact,

02:26:37.040 --> 02:26:41.920
[Amit Varma]: I, you know, I heard Raag Darbari there, because I'd read it in English, and I wanted to read it

02:26:41.920 --> 02:26:46.480
[Amit Varma]: in Hindi. But I thought, let me listen to it in Hindi and it's such a masterpiece. And he told

02:26:46.480 --> 02:26:51.280
[Amit Varma]: me that many of those listeners, we think people who listen to audio listen at higher speeds,

02:26:51.280 --> 02:26:56.160
[Amit Varma]: he said many of his listeners, listen to the English content of Storytel at lower speeds,

02:26:56.160 --> 02:27:02.800
[Amit Varma]: 0.75, 0.5, because that's how they understand. And that also opened my eyes. And another similar sort

02:27:02.800 --> 02:27:07.840
[Amit Varma]: of eye opening thing that I learned recently, is that when I heard someone complaining about,

02:27:07.840 --> 02:27:15.120
[Amit Varma]: oh, Netflix now allows you to play videos slower or faster. And he was appalled by that, because he

02:27:15.120 --> 02:27:19.680
[Amit Varma]: said, why should someone speed it up or whatever it is made for natural speed. But then I looked

02:27:19.680 --> 02:27:24.880
[Amit Varma]: into why that was. And I'm very impressed by the reason and why Netflix has done it. And the reason

02:27:24.880 --> 02:27:30.080
[Amit Varma]: is that when blind people are watching shows, in a sense, they're not really watching the shows,

02:27:30.080 --> 02:27:34.160
[Amit Varma]: they're listening to a description of what is happening, which is how they consume the content.

02:27:34.160 --> 02:27:39.600
[Amit Varma]: And they like to speed it up, because they comprehend audio faster. So the higher speeds

02:27:39.600 --> 02:27:45.760
[Amit Varma]: help blind people watch shows, which is such a, you know, remarkable thing. And what people who

02:27:45.760 --> 02:27:51.040
[Amit Varma]: can't hear what they do is that they are reading the subtitles, because they can't follow the

02:27:51.040 --> 02:27:55.680
[Amit Varma]: dialogue. And so they like to slow it down, because it takes them longer to read. So it makes

02:27:55.680 --> 02:28:01.920
[Amit Varma]: perfect sense. And those of us who can see and hear perfectly well, don't realize this. And we

02:28:01.920 --> 02:28:06.720
[Amit Varma]: think of our experience of the world as a normal experience. And this is the way things should be.

02:28:07.360 --> 02:28:13.760
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, so you know, credit to Netflix for building this stuff into the software and just

02:28:13.760 --> 02:28:18.000
[Amit Varma]: suddenly expanding that universe of content in such a, you know, heartwarming way.

02:28:18.000 --> 02:28:22.320
[Guest]: No, absolutely. And I mean, one is, of course, people who are differently abled,

02:28:22.320 --> 02:28:28.240
[Guest]: or visually impaired and things like that. But the other thing is also, we are all differently abled.

02:28:29.840 --> 02:28:34.800
[Guest]: Also, in the sense of the background that we come from, right? I mean, when we're talking,

02:28:34.800 --> 02:28:41.040
[Guest]: I consume monetary economics, as I learned while I researched for Viral Acharya's episode,

02:28:41.760 --> 02:28:46.560
[Guest]: so much slower than any other subfield of economics, which is applied micro,

02:28:46.560 --> 02:28:50.640
[Guest]: right? And I'm a professional economist, but there are capabilities I have built,

02:28:50.640 --> 02:28:54.320
[Guest]: there are words I have learned, there are shorthands I have learned. And I think we

02:28:54.320 --> 02:28:58.800
[Guest]: don't pay enough attention to this as we communicate, right? And the nicest thing

02:28:58.800 --> 02:29:03.600
[Guest]: about technology, especially one that is asynchronous, like podcasting, is that people

02:29:03.600 --> 02:29:08.160
[Guest]: can do this. And they can also do this in the privacy of their own home. Because normally,

02:29:08.160 --> 02:29:12.640
[Guest]: when we do it in the classroom, when we do community viewing, or community listening,

02:29:12.640 --> 02:29:19.200
[Guest]: or community education, as we do in schools, people are routinely made fun of for pronouncing

02:29:19.200 --> 02:29:25.120
[Guest]: a word wrong, or not understanding a question the first time it is posed. Many people who lack

02:29:25.120 --> 02:29:29.600
[Guest]: fluency skills in a particular language need that question to be posed, maybe multiple times,

02:29:29.600 --> 02:29:35.520
[Guest]: maybe a little bit more slowly. I mean, for me, when it comes to Tamil, anything other than food

02:29:35.520 --> 02:29:39.280
[Guest]: needs to be said, you know, a little bit more carefully and gently for me,

02:29:39.280 --> 02:29:43.280
[Guest]: you know, especially if it's something like economics. And I think that is a lesser

02:29:43.280 --> 02:29:50.800
[Guest]: appreciated aspect of how podcasting and video streaming can really crack open the education

02:29:50.800 --> 02:29:56.000
[Guest]: space, even with shows that are not intending to educate, but they can educate because they've

02:29:56.000 --> 02:30:00.000
[Guest]: built in the infrastructure to do so. No, and it's out there, because you know,

02:30:00.000 --> 02:30:05.040
[Amit Varma]: just being out there, just being available at a certain depth is important, because we are

02:30:05.040 --> 02:30:09.360
[Amit Varma]: surrounded today by mass media, which for a number of different reasons, and they're responding to

02:30:09.360 --> 02:30:14.320
[Amit Varma]: different incentives and being rational, unnecessarily being shallow. Like if you look at

02:30:14.320 --> 02:30:18.400
[Amit Varma]: the Indian news TV channels, I had a brief episode on this with Ashok Malik a long time back when I

02:30:18.400 --> 02:30:23.360
[Amit Varma]: did short episodes. And his point was great. His point was that one, they have paid such

02:30:23.360 --> 02:30:28.800
[Amit Varma]: license fees that the investment in a TV channel is massive. And two, you know, government

02:30:28.800 --> 02:30:33.440
[Amit Varma]: regulations have price controls on how much they can charge subscribers. Therefore, the bulk of

02:30:33.440 --> 02:30:37.760
[Amit Varma]: the revenue comes from advertisers. And so they need to dump it down, which is why you have the

02:30:37.760 --> 02:30:42.640
[Amit Varma]: shouty nonsense that you see, and which is or Bollywood or Bollywood, which is why all our

02:30:42.640 --> 02:30:47.280
[Amit Varma]: channels are functioning at a lowest common denominator, and you cannot get into any niche.

02:30:47.280 --> 02:30:51.840
[Amit Varma]: And here is where podcast has an advantage, even over something like radio, where you can cater

02:30:51.840 --> 02:30:56.080
[Amit Varma]: to any niche, right? And anybody can start not having an entry barrier. Like imagine if they

02:30:56.080 --> 02:31:02.720
[Amit Varma]: were giving licenses for podcasts. One, I would never have got a license. And two, even if I

02:31:02.720 --> 02:31:06.560
[Amit Varma]: wouldn't have applied, I wouldn't have applied. And I would never have got one. And even if I

02:31:06.560 --> 02:31:10.240
[Amit Varma]: got one, it would have been for a different show. And some babu would have shown up at my door

02:31:10.240 --> 02:31:14.640
[Amit Varma]: saying, you wanted to do 20 minute episodes on public policy. Now you're doing three hour

02:31:14.640 --> 02:31:20.000
[Amit Varma]: interviews with known dissenters, what is going on. So not having an entry barrier is interesting

02:31:20.000 --> 02:31:23.920
[Amit Varma]: in the sense is important in the sense that people can then follow their own interests,

02:31:23.920 --> 02:31:28.320
[Amit Varma]: and often surprise themselves with how many people share those interests. And just having

02:31:28.320 --> 02:31:35.440
[Amit Varma]: the knowledge available out there is really kind of important. So yeah, I agree with you. It's just

02:31:35.440 --> 02:31:40.240
[Guest]: stunning. You know, one element we've been talking about is the technological infrastructure,

02:31:40.240 --> 02:31:46.720
[Guest]: which makes us more able communicators using the podcast medium. The other is content. And here I

02:31:46.720 --> 02:31:52.080
[Guest]: want to, you know, talk about another question from our guest or rather queue another question

02:31:52.080 --> 02:31:59.680
[Guest]: from one of your guests and one of our common friends, who is Kumar Anand. Right. And I think,

02:31:59.680 --> 02:32:04.480
[Guest]: you know, we've had some fantastic conversations one on one and the three of us together. And he's

02:32:04.480 --> 02:32:10.000
[Guest]: been on your show. And he's talked about especially agriculture, and agricultural reforms,

02:32:10.000 --> 02:32:16.400
[Guest]: which is more recently an area which after, you know, so many years has cracked open. So maybe

02:32:16.400 --> 02:32:20.880
[Guest]: you and Kumar had a little bit of something to do with cracking open that space. I don't know

02:32:20.880 --> 02:32:27.440
[Guest]: how far and wide the podcast reach can go. But I just want you to hear this question from Kumar

02:32:27.440 --> 02:32:32.240
[Guest]: on the content and communication. Hi, Amit. Congratulations on this

02:32:32.240 --> 02:32:36.800
[Unknown]: great milestone. I used to think of you as the Dan Carlin of Indian podcasting,

02:32:36.800 --> 02:32:41.120
[Unknown]: but I've changed my mind. I now think Dan Carlin is the Amit Verma of podcasting.

02:32:42.000 --> 02:32:47.280
[Unknown]: Anyways, here's my question. You have now done 199 episodes of the seen and unseen

02:32:47.280 --> 02:32:51.360
[Unknown]: in your episodes. On several occasions, you have dealt with issues with elements

02:32:51.360 --> 02:32:56.080
[Unknown]: that are difficult to communicate to an average common person. Issues like the concentrated

02:32:56.080 --> 02:33:02.080
[Unknown]: benefit and disperse costs, the free rider problem, unintended consequences, a public myopia

02:33:02.080 --> 02:33:06.320
[Unknown]: where only the short term cost of a policy is visible and the long term benefits are not,

02:33:06.960 --> 02:33:12.400
[Unknown]: spontaneous order of things, a majority preference for a grand central plan rather than the invisible

02:33:12.400 --> 02:33:17.680
[Unknown]: hand of voluntary exchange and cooperation. So given these and similar challenges in communicating

02:33:17.680 --> 02:33:22.560
[Unknown]: the unseen, in your experience, what do you think are the best ways in which we can overcome this

02:33:22.560 --> 02:33:28.000
[Amit Varma]: challenge? Thank you. Yeah, very, very powerful question. And I'm kind of embarrassed at the

02:33:28.560 --> 02:33:33.200
[Amit Varma]: comparison with Dan Carlin because no one can be like Dan Carlin. I really got turned on to

02:33:33.200 --> 02:33:38.880
[Amit Varma]: podcast as a medium when I heard hardcore history by Dan Carlin, which is just next level. You know,

02:33:38.880 --> 02:33:44.640
[Guest]: it's amazing. I fell asleep. You told me to listen to it. And I think about halfway through the first

02:33:44.640 --> 02:33:49.600
[Guest]: couple of episodes, I just like fell asleep. He had a lovely voice. But also it might be a lack

02:33:49.600 --> 02:33:54.560
[Unknown]: of interest in that kind of a deep dive. So it wasn't for me. I think also spare attention and

02:33:54.560 --> 02:33:58.080
[Amit Varma]: capacity because you might have been listening to him at normal speed and he is rather slow.

02:33:58.880 --> 02:34:03.120
[Amit Varma]: So I listened to him at 2.5 at least. And I got turned on for those of my listeners who want to

02:34:03.120 --> 02:34:07.920
[Amit Varma]: know to this incredible episode called blueprint for Armageddon, which was on World War One. And

02:34:07.920 --> 02:34:13.520
[Amit Varma]: I think it's like 25 hours of content spread over five episodes of five hours each or something like

02:34:13.520 --> 02:34:17.520
[Amit Varma]: that. And it's just him talking. It's nothing else. There's no sound effects, there's no music,

02:34:17.520 --> 02:34:21.920
[Amit Varma]: it's just him talking. It's so pure and beautiful and incredible and thought provoking. And

02:34:22.800 --> 02:34:28.000
[Amit Varma]: that's kind of just brilliant. And I've always since then wanted to do a solo history

02:34:28.720 --> 02:34:34.160
[Amit Varma]: podcast at some point, but that you know, requires resources far beyond anything I might have right

02:34:34.160 --> 02:34:40.240
[Amit Varma]: now. So maybe someday in the future. But to answer Kumar's perceptive question, and it's something

02:34:40.240 --> 02:34:46.640
[Amit Varma]: that I have, you know, we all three of us have lamented this, that our brains are wired in

02:34:46.640 --> 02:34:52.320
[Amit Varma]: prehistoric times, where we lived in different realities. And therefore, many of the truths

02:34:52.320 --> 02:34:57.360
[Amit Varma]: about the world, the way it really works are unintuitive. Because, you know, in prehistoric

02:34:57.360 --> 02:35:03.440
[Amit Varma]: times, we used to live in, you know, where things were scarce, and there was brutal competition,

02:35:03.440 --> 02:35:08.080
[Amit Varma]: as it were, as Hobbes would put it harsh and brutish competition. And therefore, our brain

02:35:08.080 --> 02:35:12.480
[Amit Varma]: evolved to think of the world in zero sum ways, that the only way somebody can benefit is if you

02:35:12.480 --> 02:35:17.680
[Amit Varma]: take it away from somebody else. And we don't intuitively understand the positive some nature

02:35:17.680 --> 02:35:22.480
[Amit Varma]: of voluntary interaction is what John Strassel calls a double thank you moment, that, you know,

02:35:22.480 --> 02:35:26.880
[Amit Varma]: when I buy a cup of coffee at a cafe, when the coffee is handed to me, I say thank you. And

02:35:27.600 --> 02:35:31.760
[Amit Varma]: the person at the other person says thank you. And the thing is, I value the coffee more than

02:35:31.760 --> 02:35:36.080
[Amit Varma]: the money and they value the money more than the coffee. And it's a mutually beneficial interaction,

02:35:36.720 --> 02:35:40.160
[Amit Varma]: which is why you know, both of us saying thank you, double thank you moment, it's it's,

02:35:41.120 --> 02:35:46.080
[Amit Varma]: it's a positive some game. But our brains think of the world in zero sum ways that if the rich

02:35:46.080 --> 02:35:50.320
[Amit Varma]: are getting richer, the poorer must be getting poorer. And that's a difficult truth to communicate

02:35:50.320 --> 02:35:54.640
[Amit Varma]: communicating something like spontaneous order is very hard to communicate that you don't need a

02:35:54.640 --> 02:36:02.160
[Amit Varma]: grand central planner, that really complex systems like evolution, like markets like the like

02:36:02.160 --> 02:36:08.160
[Amit Varma]: languages cannot happen by central committee, you know, that they, you know, that they happen in

02:36:08.160 --> 02:36:12.160
[Amit Varma]: different ways. And there's a great episode called the evolution of everything that I read with Matt

02:36:12.160 --> 02:36:18.640
[Amit Varma]: Ridley, where we spoke about this at some length. So this is a challenge. And I've I've thought

02:36:18.640 --> 02:36:23.920
[Amit Varma]: about this. And I've recently sort of come to realize that the reason for this also lies in

02:36:23.920 --> 02:36:28.160
[Amit Varma]: the distinction between the abstract and the concrete, that the reason these things have

02:36:28.160 --> 02:36:34.000
[Amit Varma]: evolved is that if you're living in a time where you are in a little tribe, and you have to,

02:36:34.000 --> 02:36:39.520
[Amit Varma]: everything is scarce, then your concrete reality has scarcity in it. And you will see the world

02:36:39.520 --> 02:36:44.160
[Amit Varma]: in zero sum ways, because that is what you're doing for you to, you know, get the meaty part

02:36:44.160 --> 02:36:51.120
[Amit Varma]: of that deer, you have to sort of, you know, win it over somebody else, that means someone else

02:36:51.120 --> 02:36:55.600
[Amit Varma]: doesn't get it, and so on and so forth, that tribes of 100 people are best handled from the

02:36:55.600 --> 02:37:00.000
[Amit Varma]: top down, perhaps, and spontaneous order is not necessary, because that level of complexity is

02:37:00.000 --> 02:37:06.880
[Amit Varma]: not there. So I think perhaps the way to getting closer to communicating some of these things

02:37:06.880 --> 02:37:11.440
[Amit Varma]: is by getting concrete, what is the problem, for example, with concentrated benefits and

02:37:12.480 --> 02:37:16.640
[Amit Varma]: with concentrated benefits and diffuse costs. Now, I'll quickly go over the concept. And

02:37:16.640 --> 02:37:20.480
[Amit Varma]: obviously, Shruti, you've thought about it and taught it a million times. But the concept

02:37:20.480 --> 02:37:26.960
[Amit Varma]: basically is that, let's say in the case of Air India, that every year, Air India basically,

02:37:28.080 --> 02:37:33.520
[Amit Varma]: a failing dying airline is kept alive by infusions of taxpayers money. And let's say each citizen is

02:37:33.520 --> 02:37:37.520
[Amit Varma]: paying two rupees for it, I'm just picking a hypothetical number. Now, the point is that

02:37:38.080 --> 02:37:42.160
[Amit Varma]: the benefit is concentrated, Air India gets it, and therefore they will lobby for it. And they

02:37:42.160 --> 02:37:46.320
[Amit Varma]: will do all kinds of things. And if the beneficiary was a private party, they would contribute to

02:37:46.320 --> 02:37:50.720
[Amit Varma]: party coffers, they would buy politicians, all of that, the benefits are concentrated. But the

02:37:50.720 --> 02:37:55.920
[Amit Varma]: costs are diffused, that all of us are losing only two rupees, it is unseen, we don't even know that

02:37:55.920 --> 02:38:01.040
[Amit Varma]: we are losing it. And therefore, why should we protest? And this becomes a dilemma. And the

02:38:01.040 --> 02:38:09.360
[Amit Varma]: problem that therefore arises from this is that how can we therefore make it, you know, make this

02:38:09.360 --> 02:38:16.640
[Amit Varma]: concrete aspect of the situation more explicit, so that the abstract principle then becomes obvious,

02:38:16.640 --> 02:38:21.360
[Amit Varma]: and then that kind of comes across like, I remember once in a conversation with Kumar,

02:38:21.360 --> 02:38:25.440
[Amit Varma]: when we were chatting about this, I spoke about it as flicking a light switch, that, you know,

02:38:25.440 --> 02:38:28.800
[Amit Varma]: once you flick the switch, and you turn it on, it's fine, the light is there, but you have to

02:38:28.800 --> 02:38:33.680
[Amit Varma]: flick it. And, you know, even for me, I suffered from all these misconceptions, because that's how

02:38:33.680 --> 02:38:38.240
[Amit Varma]: we are wired. And then you gradually flick the switches, and you see the world in a different

02:38:38.240 --> 02:38:43.600
[Amit Varma]: way, because there is that. So as communicators of these ideas, which we care so deeply about,

02:38:43.600 --> 02:38:48.400
[Amit Varma]: we have to find ways to flick these switches. And we cannot do that at the level of the idea

02:38:48.400 --> 02:38:53.040
[Amit Varma]: at an abstract level, we can't do that at the level of abstraction, we have to get concrete,

02:38:53.040 --> 02:38:59.120
[Amit Varma]: and we have to relate it to their own lives. And that becomes a complicated challenge.

02:38:59.120 --> 02:39:03.840
[Amit Varma]: Like if the garbage outside your house has not been collected, you know, there are so many like

02:39:03.840 --> 02:39:07.760
[Amit Varma]: you and I had done an episode on urban governance, where we spoke about the disconnect between power

02:39:07.760 --> 02:39:13.040
[Amit Varma]: and accountability. And, you know, why that affects the governance in our cities. And all of

02:39:13.040 --> 02:39:18.000
[Amit Varma]: that is abstract. How do you make it real by talking about why the person's garbage outside

02:39:18.000 --> 02:39:23.200
[Amit Varma]: his house is not being collected? Or why, you know, whatever, whatever problems that

02:39:24.880 --> 02:39:29.520
[Amit Varma]: citizens face in their everyday lives. And I think as communicators, that is a challenge that we have

02:39:29.520 --> 02:39:34.960
[Amit Varma]: to sort of communicate at that level and not an abstract level. Because if we just talk about

02:39:34.960 --> 02:39:40.800
[Amit Varma]: stuff at an abstract level, we will fail utterly. And I think this is something that, you know,

02:39:40.800 --> 02:39:46.000
[Amit Varma]: the extreme right wing does this very well. They are wrong, but they are wrong in that they talk

02:39:46.000 --> 02:39:50.320
[Amit Varma]: about concrete things. So they build simple narratives. Like one of the reasons I wrote a

02:39:50.320 --> 02:39:54.880
[Amit Varma]: column on this once about why Trump succeeded in 2016. And it wasn't because he was right,

02:39:54.880 --> 02:40:00.080
[Amit Varma]: because he was basically wrong about everything, then, as he is now, which is not to say his

02:40:00.080 --> 02:40:06.240
[Amit Varma]: opponents aren't also wrong, but he was wrong. But the stories he sold were simple stories,

02:40:06.240 --> 02:40:09.840
[Amit Varma]: which are easy to understand. So when you're speaking to people in the Midwest, who don't

02:40:09.840 --> 02:40:14.640
[Amit Varma]: have jobs anymore, it is easy to sell the narrative that immigrants are taking your jobs,

02:40:14.640 --> 02:40:19.600
[Amit Varma]: therefore, immigration is bad, and that your jobs are being shipped overseas to China. So,

02:40:19.600 --> 02:40:23.600
[Amit Varma]: you know, China is bad. Now, both those narratives are wrong, but they are simple.

02:40:23.600 --> 02:40:30.640
[Amit Varma]: So similarly, if you want to sort of communicate any kind of ideas at a mass level, you have to

02:40:30.640 --> 02:40:35.040
[Amit Varma]: find a way to make it simple and relatable. And you do that at the level of the concrete.

02:40:35.040 --> 02:40:40.960
[Guest]: No, and also, you know, you don't have to do it just once, right. So there's this great quote

02:40:40.960 --> 02:40:46.960
[Guest]: by Frank Knight, who is also one of my intellectual heroes. And he said, it takes varied

02:40:46.960 --> 02:40:56.000
[Guest]: reiterations to force alien concepts upon reluctant minds. Right. So it's not just about

02:40:56.000 --> 02:41:01.040
[Guest]: putting it out there, or even as you said, though, it's very important of making it less abstract.

02:41:01.040 --> 02:41:06.960
[Guest]: I think it's also story after story, example after example. So the way you gave the example

02:41:06.960 --> 02:41:12.560
[Guest]: of Air India, I think if you gave 100 such examples, then you know, the broader public

02:41:12.560 --> 02:41:18.240
[Guest]: choice principle of concentrated benefits and diffused costs might penetrate. And this is also

02:41:18.240 --> 02:41:22.800
[Guest]: where I really enjoyed your conversation with Nilesh Mishra, you know, I mean, it was

02:41:23.760 --> 02:41:30.240
[Guest]: the importance of storytelling, the value of sentiment, the value of nostalgia, you know,

02:41:30.240 --> 02:41:35.760
[Guest]: of course, there are broader themes, they invoke certain emotions, which make you connect or make

02:41:35.760 --> 02:41:40.640
[Guest]: things more intimate. And it's related to the art of conversation. But it's also related to the art

02:41:40.640 --> 02:41:47.520
[Guest]: of education, right? Everything is not passion and information. It is also sentiment, it is also

02:41:47.520 --> 02:41:52.720
[Guest]: nostalgia, it is also storytelling and fitting things within a broader tradition. I didn't ask

02:41:53.680 --> 02:41:58.000
[Guest]: him for a question, though, I would have loved to because by the time we planned this episode,

02:41:58.000 --> 02:42:04.480
[Guest]: that one wasn't out. So to the listeners who are disappointed, I apologize. I want to take a break

02:42:04.480 --> 02:42:10.800
[Guest]: at this point, because in good, you know, seen and unseen tradition, we have breached many,

02:42:10.800 --> 02:42:16.400
[Guest]: many barriers, we are now almost at like the two and a half hour mark, I think. So I want to take

02:42:16.400 --> 02:42:22.800
[Guest]: a little commercial break, we're going to talk a little bit more, mainly about some of the policy

02:42:22.800 --> 02:42:28.320
[Guest]: ideas that you have. And I know your love for books. So you know, I'd love to talk to you more

02:42:28.320 --> 02:42:34.640
[Guest]: about books. So more for the listeners when we come back from this commercial break.

