[Unknown]: epidemic situation. Amit held that a lockdown was justified, while I didn't see any justification

02:46:06.480 --> 02:46:13.520
[Unknown]: in penalizing every citizen in search for the virus. So the question that has been making me

02:46:13.520 --> 02:46:20.880
[Unknown]: think for the past few months is, why our framework didn't lead us to a common policy position,

02:46:21.520 --> 02:46:27.040
[Unknown]: as had been the case for all the years? Yeah, well, what a fantastic question. And

02:46:27.040 --> 02:46:30.800
[Amit Varma]: Barunda, of course, is again, one of my favorite people on the world, such a

02:46:32.560 --> 02:46:36.240
[Amit Varma]: delightful gentleman, I've learned so much from over the years. I think our frameworks are pretty

02:46:36.240 --> 02:46:40.480
[Amit Varma]: common in the sense that I also care about means and the ends in the sense that I care about

02:46:40.480 --> 02:46:46.880
[Amit Varma]: means to not include coercion. And I value consent a lot. And I agree with Barun and indeed,

02:46:46.880 --> 02:46:53.600
[Amit Varma]: the Mahatma Gandhi that, you know, the no end is ever justified by unjust means. And therefore,

02:46:53.600 --> 02:46:57.760
[Amit Varma]: we should be careful. Now, in this particular case, I also think that look, and I could be

02:46:57.760 --> 02:47:03.200
[Amit Varma]: wrong here. This is one of those areas where one is never sure and I'm open to accepting I could

02:47:03.200 --> 02:47:08.160
[Amit Varma]: be wrong. And I think, and I hope Barun will also share that sentiment. But I think that

02:47:08.160 --> 02:47:12.640
[Amit Varma]: and I hope Barun will also share that sentiment, not am I being wrong, but either of us could be

02:47:12.640 --> 02:47:18.000
[Amit Varma]: wrong. But that, you know, I think the purpose of the state is to protect the rights of citizens.

02:47:18.000 --> 02:47:24.000
[Amit Varma]: And that includes, say, protesting the rights of citizens against external invaders, for example,

02:47:24.000 --> 02:47:28.080
[Amit Varma]: which is why libertarians will say that you have to have rule of law so that rights are protected

02:47:28.080 --> 02:47:34.080
[Amit Varma]: within a country. And you have to have, you know, an army or some kind of defense, which of course

02:47:34.080 --> 02:47:38.720
[Amit Varma]: should be voluntary, which protects you from external invaders. How do we classify a virus?

02:47:39.360 --> 02:47:44.960
[Amit Varma]: I think that, you know, the point is that when it comes to public health, I think, for example,

02:47:45.920 --> 02:47:52.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, not wearing a mask in public can create externalities for others. For example, this is why

02:47:52.320 --> 02:47:57.280
[Amit Varma]: in general anti-vaxxers have it so wrong. Vaccines are important. You don't take a vaccine just for

02:47:57.280 --> 02:48:02.640
[Amit Varma]: yourself, you take it to protect others as well. And if enough people refuse to get vaccinated,

02:48:02.640 --> 02:48:08.400
[Amit Varma]: you are putting everybody else at risk. And we all agree that there is this liberal paradox,

02:48:08.400 --> 02:48:15.200
[Amit Varma]: right, that to protect everyone's rights, that is to protect everyone's consent for that matter,

02:48:15.200 --> 02:48:19.840
[Amit Varma]: you have to infringe on them a little bit. The very existence of the state is an infringement

02:48:19.840 --> 02:48:25.200
[Amit Varma]: on individual freedom because, you know, a state can only exist based on taxes. And therefore,

02:48:25.200 --> 02:48:29.600
[Amit Varma]: there is some amount of coercion. And we all agree that the state is a necessary evil,

02:48:29.600 --> 02:48:34.880
[Amit Varma]: the night watchman state, as the old classical liberals put it, is a necessary evil. Now,

02:48:34.880 --> 02:48:41.760
[Amit Varma]: I think all ideological discussion comes down to how much coercion is justified by the state.

02:48:41.760 --> 02:48:46.640
[Amit Varma]: That's all it comes down to. I think anyone who denies that every act of government is an act of

02:48:46.640 --> 02:48:51.040
[Amit Varma]: violence, I wrote a column with that headline once, or that the state depends on coercion,

02:48:51.040 --> 02:48:56.800
[Amit Varma]: is deluded. It is obvious that the existence of the state depends on coercion. And the only

02:48:56.800 --> 02:49:02.640
[Amit Varma]: line of argument is about how much coercion is necessary, and what justifies coercion. So,

02:49:02.640 --> 02:49:07.200
[Amit Varma]: does like everything that the government does, whether in terms of spending money or whatever

02:49:07.200 --> 02:49:13.280
[Amit Varma]: it does, has a cost. And that cost is coercive. So, that's the question. And therefore,

02:49:13.280 --> 02:49:19.120
[Amit Varma]: the argument would be about, you know, you can argue, does a statute justify that coercion?

02:49:19.120 --> 02:49:26.160
[Amit Varma]: Does, you know, keeping a failing airline alive with all the other associated costs that you have

02:49:26.160 --> 02:49:31.520
[Amit Varma]: that you have of crowding out and all of that, does that justify the coercion? Do roads and bridges

02:49:31.520 --> 02:49:36.000
[Amit Varma]: justify the coercion because of the positive externalities they have? And I think in this

02:49:36.000 --> 02:49:42.320
[Amit Varma]: case, there are reasonable arguments to be made at both ends. So, similarly, does a lockdown justify

02:49:42.320 --> 02:49:46.320
[Amit Varma]: the coercion? And it's a very difficult question. You know, you and I did an episode in April where

02:49:46.320 --> 02:49:51.360
[Amit Varma]: we spoke about the policy trade-offs involved here. And the point is that no matter what you

02:49:51.360 --> 02:49:57.280
[Amit Varma]: do, it will seem like the wrong decision because the cost, which is the lives that were lost and

02:49:57.280 --> 02:50:01.680
[Amit Varma]: what happened to the economy, the cost will be visible and the benefits, which is the lives that

02:50:01.680 --> 02:50:07.120
[Amit Varma]: were saved because of the measures you took, will be invisible. And this is regardless of whether

02:50:07.120 --> 02:50:11.600
[Amit Varma]: there is a lockdown or no lockdown or whatever. Now, this question becomes extremely complicated

02:50:11.600 --> 02:50:15.840
[Amit Varma]: because even if you say that a lockdown is necessary, you then look at the state capacity.

02:50:15.840 --> 02:50:20.960
[Amit Varma]: Even if you argue that our lockdown was necessary at the time the Prime Minister called it,

02:50:22.000 --> 02:50:26.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, you look at state capacity and you think that, okay, there's still going to be

02:50:26.480 --> 02:50:31.200
[Amit Varma]: enormous suffering because state capacity can't handle what is required. And added to that,

02:50:31.200 --> 02:50:35.760
[Amit Varma]: you have, say, political apathy, as in the case of the migrant workers, which was a humanitarian

02:50:35.760 --> 02:50:40.960
[Amit Varma]: tragedy that played out at scale. And you have all these other things going wrong. And I just

02:50:40.960 --> 02:50:46.880
[Amit Varma]: think that this is a really difficult kind of question. And we argued about this, we discussed

02:50:46.880 --> 02:50:50.560
[Amit Varma]: it rather, I don't think you and I really argued about it. I think both of us agreed that to some

02:50:50.560 --> 02:50:54.720
[Amit Varma]: extent, you had to have a lockdown at that point or, you know, public health could have fallen

02:50:54.720 --> 02:51:00.160
[Amit Varma]: apart. At the same time, I get Barun's point that, you know, it's coming in the way of the

02:51:00.160 --> 02:51:06.400
[Amit Varma]: voluntary interactions, which make us prosperous as a society in the first place. And if Amit

02:51:06.400 --> 02:51:11.440
[Amit Varma]: wants to trade with Barun, who is the government to say that he cannot leave his house and do that

02:51:11.440 --> 02:51:15.680
[Amit Varma]: and meanwhile, both of them starve at home. And that is, of course, a problem. And in a sense,

02:51:15.680 --> 02:51:21.200
[Amit Varma]: I'm not even disagreeing with him. I agree with his concerns. And I think he would agree with

02:51:21.200 --> 02:51:26.080
[Amit Varma]: mine as well. And where the policy decision should fall, I don't know. I still think that

02:51:26.080 --> 02:51:31.040
[Amit Varma]: a lockdown was necessary. I think it was completely botched. But I think it was necessary. Otherwise,

02:51:31.040 --> 02:51:35.920
[Amit Varma]: our hospitals could have been overwhelmed. And we could just have had a disaster that spiraled out

02:51:35.920 --> 02:51:40.880
[Amit Varma]: of nowhere. Now the point is, the lockdown was badly botched in terms of what happened to migrant

02:51:40.880 --> 02:51:45.200
[Amit Varma]: workers and the implementation and the fact that I'm not sure that the government managed to use

02:51:45.200 --> 02:51:49.920
[Amit Varma]: that time wisely to get in the state of readiness that they should have managed. But all those

02:51:49.920 --> 02:51:54.560
[Amit Varma]: questions apart, I think it's very complicated and nuanced. And I'm completely open to realizing

02:51:54.560 --> 02:51:58.480
[Amit Varma]: three years later that I was completely wrong. Had there been no lockdown, it would have been

02:51:58.480 --> 02:52:06.960
[Amit Varma]: better for all of us. But at the time you make the sort of, you know, it's complicated and messy.

02:52:06.960 --> 02:52:11.360
[Amit Varma]: But I don't think I would say that the state should not have the right to call something like

02:52:11.360 --> 02:52:17.920
[Amit Varma]: a lockdown. Because if like, for example, okay, the you know, the Coronavirus is what it is,

02:52:17.920 --> 02:52:23.520
[Amit Varma]: but imagine a far deadlier virus, you know, imagine a virus that is both extremely contagious

02:52:23.520 --> 02:52:28.720
[Amit Varma]: and kill 60% of the people who get it. Is a lockdown justified then? Where do you draw?

02:52:28.720 --> 02:52:29.360
[Unknown]: Ebola?

02:52:29.360 --> 02:52:35.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. Ebola was different because it wasn't so contagious. It was much more fatal. You know,

02:52:36.000 --> 02:52:41.600
[Amit Varma]: this Coronavirus was hyped up as being in that sweet spot where it is both very contagious and

02:52:41.600 --> 02:52:46.960
[Amit Varma]: sufficiently fatal to be problematic in that sense, almost a game theory optimal virus. But

02:52:48.000 --> 02:52:52.880
[Amit Varma]: Ebola wasn't there. But imagine a virus that is as deadly as Ebola and as contagious

02:52:52.880 --> 02:52:57.280
[Amit Varma]: as any Coronavirus. What do you do then? Is a lockdown justified? If it is not, what are you,

02:52:57.280 --> 02:53:02.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, I don't know how you can justify a lockdown not being necessary in those circumstances.

02:53:02.160 --> 02:53:07.440
[Amit Varma]: And if you think it is justified then but not justified now, where do you draw the line? Based

02:53:07.440 --> 02:53:11.680
[Amit Varma]: on what information do you draw the line, especially when we are in the kind of epistemic

02:53:11.680 --> 02:53:18.320
[Amit Varma]: fog, if I may use jargon again. So I think that's it. It's a deep and nuanced question. But I think

02:53:18.320 --> 02:53:24.720
[Amit Varma]: Varun and I have the same kind of framework. And you could say that I am in fact being hypocritical

02:53:24.720 --> 02:53:29.360
[Amit Varma]: here because I am sort of, you know, turning away from the question of consent that the government

02:53:29.360 --> 02:53:34.880
[Amit Varma]: did not take the consent of all the people that it forcibly locked down. But I think we also accept

02:53:34.880 --> 02:53:40.720
[Amit Varma]: that there is a state that has a certain minimum sort of role to play. And the real argument then

02:53:40.720 --> 02:53:44.720
[Amit Varma]: is that does something like this fall within that role?

02:53:44.720 --> 02:53:49.120
[Guest]: You know, I'd add a couple more things to this. So one, of course, I mean, I like you,

02:53:49.120 --> 02:53:52.400
[Guest]: I'm completely open to realizing I'm wrong about this a few years from now.

02:53:53.200 --> 02:53:58.560
[Guest]: I already have a more nuanced view than maybe in, you know, early April when we talked about this,

02:53:58.560 --> 02:54:02.720
[Guest]: which is, of course, you know, some kind of intervention I thought is necessary. But is

02:54:02.720 --> 02:54:07.680
[Guest]: it necessary in rural Bihar? Is it necessary in Arunachal Pradesh, for instance, where there are

02:54:07.680 --> 02:54:12.720
[Guest]: no cases, at least at the time of the lockdown, there were no cases, right? It's important to,

02:54:12.720 --> 02:54:17.360
[Guest]: you know, maybe come down really hard on the Mumbai locals where you can think of them as

02:54:17.360 --> 02:54:22.720
[Guest]: super spreaders, right? Is it really that important to come down on rural areas or farm activity?

02:54:22.720 --> 02:54:28.080
[Guest]: So, you know, that is one kind of, you know, aspect of the lockdown for which I completely

02:54:28.080 --> 02:54:34.400
[Guest]: understand why someone like Barun and even us would just be, you know, think not twice,

02:54:34.400 --> 02:54:39.600
[Guest]: but many, many times over this kind of an imposition of government over liberty.

02:54:39.600 --> 02:54:46.320
[Guest]: But there is another aspect to it. Now, normally, the public choice economist in me takes over,

02:54:46.320 --> 02:54:49.840
[Guest]: and we talk about government failure and, you know, the incentives and how government does

02:54:49.840 --> 02:54:54.640
[Guest]: things badly. Does that mean government should not do it at all? Right? And this is a question

02:54:54.640 --> 02:54:59.600
[Guest]: for which I honestly don't have a good answer. Now, I think policing is an incredibly important

02:54:59.600 --> 02:55:03.600
[Guest]: function of government. I think India is under-policed. I think the people who pay the

02:55:03.600 --> 02:55:08.560
[Guest]: most because it's under-policed is minorities and, you know, Dalits and women and things like that.

02:55:08.560 --> 02:55:13.360
[Guest]: Now, because we haven't figured out policing and how to do it right, does that mean the state

02:55:13.360 --> 02:55:18.960
[Guest]: shouldn't be in the business of policing? Right? Some libertarian friends we have would say yes,

02:55:19.520 --> 02:55:24.800
[Guest]: right? Some would say absolutely not. There are very, very minimal areas like, you know,

02:55:24.800 --> 02:55:30.160
[Guest]: this is probably someone like Ajay Shah, right? Or someone like Niranjan Rajyadhyak, right?

02:55:30.160 --> 02:55:35.520
[Guest]: These are critical state functions, night watchman state functions, and it's very important to

02:55:35.520 --> 02:55:40.800
[Guest]: to slowly give the chance and allow the state to build capacity in these areas. Now, I know the

02:55:40.800 --> 02:55:46.880
[Guest]: lockdown is not the same thing as, you know, policing, nor do I want the government to get

02:55:46.880 --> 02:55:52.160
[Guest]: very good at imposing lockdowns, because then we are in Kashmir and China, and that's a horror

02:55:52.160 --> 02:55:59.120
[Guest]: scenario in itself. But to me, the fact that the government doesn't do the lockdown well,

02:55:59.920 --> 02:56:04.480
[Guest]: is normally a good argument. In this instance, I think it weakens just a little bit,

02:56:04.480 --> 02:56:09.920
[Guest]: because usually when we say the government is not good at providing, you know, telephones,

02:56:09.920 --> 02:56:15.440
[Guest]: you know, let the market solve it, the market actually solves it pretty well, okay? In this

02:56:15.440 --> 02:56:20.000
[Guest]: particular instance, I'm not sure how voluntary interactions, because we're not talking about a

02:56:20.000 --> 02:56:26.000
[Guest]: market for viruses, but how voluntary interactions or that they necessarily solve it well, right?

02:56:26.000 --> 02:56:30.160
[Guest]: We know people who've continued having big events, super spreader events, there are people

02:56:30.160 --> 02:56:35.440
[Guest]: who continue having weddings, right, political rallies, Chief Minister Adityanath was planning

02:56:35.440 --> 02:56:41.680
[Guest]: this huge event, just before the lockdown was called for Ram Navami, and they would have

02:56:41.680 --> 02:56:48.480
[Guest]: probably gone ahead with that, you know, had some kind of a mandate not come in. So it's not that

02:56:48.480 --> 02:56:55.520
[Guest]: private citizens are in a place to act in the same way as they do when they are buying telephones

02:56:55.520 --> 02:57:00.480
[Guest]: and bread and butter, either relative to, you know, let's say the government running Modern

02:57:00.480 --> 02:57:06.160
[Guest]: Bakery, or the government running Lodhi Hotel or Air India. So there is also that comparison,

02:57:06.160 --> 02:57:11.040
[Guest]: did the government botch the lockdown? Absolutely. Was it necessary? To me, some

02:57:11.040 --> 02:57:14.720
[Guest]: intervention was necessary, this kind of a horrific lockdown, especially I thought it

02:57:14.720 --> 02:57:19.760
[Guest]: would go on for three weeks, it went on for like, whatever 70-80 days, right? So there is that

02:57:19.760 --> 02:57:24.800
[Guest]: element of that trade off. And there is also, do we need a lockdown? The question is compared to

02:57:24.800 --> 02:57:32.080
[Guest]: what and I honestly do not see private citizens acting that responsibly, right, as one would

02:57:32.080 --> 02:57:36.480
[Guest]: require in this kind of a pandemic. Because for everyone, it's important to get married, it's

02:57:36.480 --> 02:57:41.360
[Guest]: important to have a family event, it is important to have a political rally, right, and the and the

02:57:41.360 --> 02:57:45.040
[Guest]: losses are passed on to someone else or the externalities passed on to someone else. So I

02:57:45.040 --> 02:57:50.960
[Guest]: think, even within, you know, the libertarian classical liberal framework of thinking,

02:57:50.960 --> 02:57:56.400
[Guest]: there's obviously a lot of things to consider. But this is how I have started to think about

02:57:56.400 --> 02:58:01.280
[Guest]: issues of the lockdown. Now, I know, it doesn't get me to the exact same point as

02:58:01.280 --> 02:58:06.800
[Guest]: Barun. And I keep wondering why, because like you, I, I hugely admire him. And maybe, you know,

02:58:06.800 --> 02:58:12.400
[Guest]: over a period of time, we all kind of figure out where we are on this. But, you know, epistemic

02:58:12.400 --> 02:58:18.480
[Guest]: fog is real. I thought the dead bodies would just be piling up in India, based on my experience with

02:58:18.480 --> 02:58:22.480
[Guest]: the healthcare system in Italy, when I lived there. And, you know, then when they had like,

02:58:22.480 --> 02:58:26.960
[Guest]: you know, this kind of crazy fatality rate in Italy, I was like, if this is happening in Italy,

02:58:26.960 --> 02:58:31.520
[Guest]: what will happen in India. But at that time, when I was imagining those horrifying things,

02:58:32.320 --> 02:58:38.240
[Guest]: we didn't know that it disproportionately affects older people, or that younger people are not,

02:58:38.240 --> 02:58:42.560
[Guest]: you know, affected quite the same, and the fatality rates are much lower. You know,

02:58:42.560 --> 02:58:48.080
[Guest]: we just didn't have this, this information in March, early April, or at least, you know, the

02:58:48.080 --> 02:58:53.120
[Guest]: really good studies from the cruise ship and things like that hadn't come out yet. So I think

02:58:53.840 --> 02:59:02.320
[Guest]: the epistemic fog lifting also genuinely helps our understanding of, hey, only 7% or 6.5% of

02:59:02.320 --> 02:59:08.080
[Guest]: Indians are above 65 years of age. So you know, maybe this wasn't that necessary. Also, Indians

02:59:08.080 --> 02:59:14.560
[Guest]: don't overwhelmingly, you know, put the elderly in old age homes or nursing homes, which means you

02:59:14.560 --> 02:59:19.120
[Guest]: don't have this kind of huge impact where one event and you know, you suddenly have lots and

02:59:19.120 --> 02:59:23.840
[Guest]: lots of people dead in a particular area or a particular county. So, you know, those things

02:59:23.840 --> 02:59:30.480
[Guest]: have helped us understand why India wasn't as badly affected. But at the time, I still believe

02:59:30.480 --> 02:59:36.720
[Guest]: some intervention was necessary. Should it have been all India? Should it have been as a grave as

02:59:36.720 --> 02:59:42.480
[Guest]: it was? Should it have, you know, been extended three times over those things, I would agree with

02:59:42.480 --> 02:59:47.360
[Amit Varma]: Varun were quite unnecessary. I mean, I'll say a couple of things. I mean, one is a fairly trivial

02:59:47.360 --> 02:59:56.640
[Amit Varma]: point almost that people I have noticed worryingly, often come up with responses to policy based on

02:59:56.640 --> 03:00:00.640
[Amit Varma]: where it is coming from, who is a politician in charge, for example, it's almost interesting to

03:00:00.640 --> 03:00:05.520
[Amit Varma]: see here that we had the right wing government of Modi calling a lockdown in India and a right

03:00:05.520 --> 03:00:11.280
[Amit Varma]: wing government of Trump opposing a lockdown in the US. So I don't like to use words like right

03:00:11.280 --> 03:00:15.520
[Amit Varma]: wing and left wing because I don't think those frameworks are correct. But regardless, and

03:00:15.520 --> 03:00:20.480
[Amit Varma]: similarly, the opposition breaks out along those lines that those who oppose Modi here will say,

03:00:20.480 --> 03:00:25.120
[Amit Varma]: array, the lockdown was too strict. And those who oppose Trump there will say that we need a

03:00:25.120 --> 03:00:30.160
[Amit Varma]: stricter lockdown and more of a lockdown and all of that. But I'm not saying that's why Varun

03:00:30.880 --> 03:00:35.360
[Amit Varma]: opposed it at all. I mean, he of course opposes Modi, but this is perfectly law opposing the

03:00:35.360 --> 03:00:40.880
[Amit Varma]: lockdown is very cogent according to his framework. So I respect that. But the deeper point I want to

03:00:40.880 --> 03:00:46.160
[Amit Varma]: make is a point that I think every libertarian will agree with. And again, I don't really like

03:00:46.160 --> 03:00:53.840
[Amit Varma]: to use these sort of tribal classifications. But I think anyone who uses these to describe themselves

03:00:53.840 --> 03:01:00.640
[Amit Varma]: will agree with anyway, which is that what went wrong in India, the botched lockdown also speaks

03:01:00.640 --> 03:01:05.040
[Amit Varma]: to a fundamental structural problem. And I'm not even referring to the flailing state. And I wrote

03:01:05.040 --> 03:01:09.920
[Amit Varma]: a column about how India's great disasters as shown is, you know, even worse than the

03:01:09.920 --> 03:01:17.200
[Amit Varma]: viruses are flailing state, which, you know, causes far more suffering than the virus can or

03:01:17.200 --> 03:01:22.720
[Amit Varma]: has. But rather, that our structure of governance is true top down. And if it was far more local,

03:01:22.720 --> 03:01:27.600
[Amit Varma]: the responses would have been better. Like as you just said, that the policy that you carry out in

03:01:27.600 --> 03:01:32.400
[Amit Varma]: Mumbai is not something that really fits in Arunachal Pradesh or rural Bihar or whatever.

03:01:32.400 --> 03:01:38.560
[Amit Varma]: So if governance is really local, and responsive to what the actual needs on the ground of local

03:01:38.560 --> 03:01:45.920
[Amit Varma]: citizens are, then better decisions can be taken that way at a local level. Now, there will be

03:01:45.920 --> 03:01:50.400
[Amit Varma]: places where people get it wrong. But there will also be places where people get it right. And the

03:01:50.400 --> 03:01:56.240
[Amit Varma]: point is, a bad decision will not scale in the way that it can, when there is just one guy in Delhi,

03:01:56.240 --> 03:02:03.440
[Amit Varma]: who is making a bad decision, and then it just percolates down. So I would have preferred that.

03:02:03.440 --> 03:02:08.720
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, those sort of... I've just written a paper on this with

03:02:08.720 --> 03:02:13.200
[Guest]: G.P. Manish and Abhishek Chaturgupta. So I will send this paper to you talking about

03:02:13.200 --> 03:02:17.520
[Guest]: the reason we had such a terrible lockdown imposing these horrible, you know, unintended

03:02:17.520 --> 03:02:23.760
[Guest]: consequences and costs on the poor is because India's federalism is too centripetal, which has

03:02:23.760 --> 03:02:28.080
[Guest]: made our governance structure very top heavy and very dysfunctional. So I'll send this paper to

03:02:28.080 --> 03:02:36.080
[Guest]: you. I'm already intimidated, centripetal. Let's move. I'm sorry, there is no easier word to

03:02:36.080 --> 03:02:45.280
[Guest]: describe that. You can admonish me again, or scold if you shall. But it's hard to come up

03:02:45.280 --> 03:02:51.680
[Guest]: with another word for centripetal, right? Because we're supposed to be federal, we're not centralized,

03:02:51.680 --> 03:02:57.440
[Guest]: right? But we have a bias towards the center, we gravitate towards the center. So if you have a

03:02:57.440 --> 03:03:01.520
[Guest]: better word for that, you should tell me. We can change the title of our paper, we still have time.

03:03:02.640 --> 03:03:06.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's move on to the next question. I don't want to change the title of your paper.

03:03:07.120 --> 03:03:13.600
[Guest]: Yes. So the next question, I mean, these are just, you know, it just so happens that some very

03:03:13.600 --> 03:03:19.440
[Guest]: brilliant women have asked a lot of policy questions. And, you know, all great economic

03:03:19.440 --> 03:03:26.000
[Guest]: thinkers. So I'm going to start with one of our favorite, you know, books in the last few years,

03:03:26.000 --> 03:03:32.960
[Guest]: which is Pooja Mehra, and her book, The Lost Decade. She's, I think, one of the best, you know,

03:03:32.960 --> 03:03:38.960
[Guest]: economics covering journalists that we have in India. And that book was really an eye opener for

03:03:38.960 --> 03:03:45.600
[Guest]: me, again, because as a public choice person, we always, you know, think less about a particular

03:03:45.600 --> 03:03:51.360
[Guest]: individual or their role and think always in terms of incentives and institutions and structures.

03:03:51.360 --> 03:03:56.080
[Guest]: But her book simultaneously, I mean, while illuminating that her book also illuminates

03:03:56.080 --> 03:04:01.200
[Guest]: the importance of good leadership, the importance of accidents, the importance of personalities and

03:04:01.200 --> 03:04:06.960
[Guest]: histories of people getting together and not getting along and things like that. So it was,

03:04:06.960 --> 03:04:12.640
[Guest]: again, one of my favorite episodes that you have done. And I don't know, was this before 100?

03:04:12.640 --> 03:04:15.200
[Guest]: Or after 100? Well, after 100.

03:04:15.200 --> 03:04:20.400
[Guest]: Okay, well, after 100. So definitely, we haven't discussed this before. And so I'm going to play

03:04:20.400 --> 03:04:21.760
[Guest]: Pooja Mehra's question for you.

03:04:22.640 --> 03:04:28.480
[Unknown]: Hi, Shruti and Amit. Many congratulations on the 200th episode milestone. Wish you

03:04:28.480 --> 03:04:35.200
[Unknown]: hundreds more. So the question for me for Amit is this. What I'd like to know, Amit,

03:04:35.200 --> 03:04:40.960
[Unknown]: is if you feel optimistic, cautiously optimistic, or, like me, pessimistic about the future.

03:04:41.840 --> 03:04:45.600
[Unknown]: I feel India's made a hash of the window of opportunity it had when a lot of good

03:04:45.600 --> 03:04:51.040
[Unknown]: things came together for it. First, a prime minister who's a good economist and understands

03:04:51.040 --> 03:04:57.200
[Unknown]: rather well how the system functions and how the system resists change. Then a prime minister who

03:04:57.200 --> 03:05:03.040
[Unknown]: enjoys tremendous popular support, favorable demographics with a large young population

03:05:03.040 --> 03:05:09.760
[Unknown]: and a global openness for trade, etc. A corporate sector that is chasing excellence for a change.

03:05:09.760 --> 03:05:16.160
[Unknown]: This window and its many positives are now closing. Many negatives, among them increasing

03:05:16.160 --> 03:05:21.600
[Unknown]: cussedness in politics, policy, and in general, dominate the scene now.

03:05:22.960 --> 03:05:28.000
[Unknown]: So, what is the economic and socio-economic future for India look like to you?

03:05:28.960 --> 03:05:32.400
[Unknown]: Should we still hold on to our dreams of a vastly improved future,

03:05:32.400 --> 03:05:36.960
[Unknown]: or should we brace for a prolonged period of difficulties of all sorts?

03:05:36.960 --> 03:05:42.240
[Unknown]: Thank you. Her question almost made me sad. That was a lovely episode, by the way. And her book is

03:05:42.240 --> 03:05:46.800
[Amit Varma]: really an eye-opener into what goes on behind the scenes in government and politics and all of that.

03:05:46.800 --> 03:05:51.120
[Amit Varma]: And a very nuanced book, which shows you that it's wrong to blame one party or the other,

03:05:51.120 --> 03:05:56.080
[Amit Varma]: one per person or the other, that everyone's responding to incentives. And this is how kind

03:05:56.080 --> 03:05:59.680
[Amit Varma]: of things work out. And Pooja is, of course, a very nuanced thinker. And you did mention that

03:05:59.680 --> 03:06:06.880
[Amit Varma]: she has this podcast, which we'll link from the show notes. Of course. Yeah, you've cracked open

03:06:06.880 --> 03:06:12.800
[Unknown]: the space right now. All your guests have had spin-off series of their own. I'm not going to

03:06:12.800 --> 03:06:18.080
[Amit Varma]: take any credit for it at all. And Pooja's podcast. I think you should. I think you should. There is,

03:06:18.080 --> 03:06:22.080
[Guest]: you've cultivated an audience for it. So that's pretty, pretty special. But I'll let you answer

03:06:22.080 --> 03:06:27.360
[Guest]: Pooja's question first. Yeah. So yeah, this is almost like the hope and despair question.

03:06:27.360 --> 03:06:33.840
[Amit Varma]: I asked so many of my guests. And I think I've answered it somewhere or the other, but it's,

03:06:33.840 --> 03:06:40.960
[Amit Varma]: it's, yeah, it's tough. I mean, you know, one, I think that it's going to get worse before it gets

03:06:40.960 --> 03:06:45.360
[Amit Varma]: better, if it gets better. So it's going to get worse before it gets better is actually a hopeful

03:06:45.360 --> 03:06:51.520
[Amit Varma]: statement, not a despairing one. That, you know, our discourse is very polluted. And what has

03:06:51.520 --> 03:06:56.640
[Amit Varma]: happened is that we are inevitably getting more and more polluted. And I think, you know,

03:06:56.640 --> 03:07:01.680
[Amit Varma]: we're getting more and more polarised, because the worst angels of our nature, as it were,

03:07:01.680 --> 03:07:09.120
[Amit Varma]: the worst demons of our nature are given scale by social media and technology. And that, you know,

03:07:09.120 --> 03:07:14.720
[Amit Varma]: that makes me feel fairly sad sometimes about the way things are going. And I don't know what

03:07:14.720 --> 03:07:20.400
[Amit Varma]: one can really do. You know, politics has become, politics has always been not about governance,

03:07:20.400 --> 03:07:26.560
[Amit Varma]: but about narrative. And all narratives that are out there are in some way reductive and toxic to

03:07:26.560 --> 03:07:32.080
[Amit Varma]: different levels. So what do you kind of do about that? And that's what I've always said has given

03:07:32.080 --> 03:07:37.520
[Amit Varma]: me hope is that I've and I think, you know, while I despair of what is happening in the larger,

03:07:37.520 --> 03:07:44.800
[Amit Varma]: broader scheme where abstract ideas rule, what I do take hope from is the small concrete ways in

03:07:44.800 --> 03:07:49.680
[Amit Varma]: which our lives are improved, especially by technology. Like I think where politics has

03:07:49.680 --> 03:07:55.520
[Amit Varma]: failed liberalism, technology has succeeded by empowering individuals in many different ways by

03:07:55.520 --> 03:08:01.840
[Amit Varma]: empowering them with choice by empowering them with access to information, and so on and so forth.

03:08:01.840 --> 03:08:06.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, maybe there is hope there. I mean, anyone who is listening to this is listening to

03:08:06.000 --> 03:08:10.480
[Amit Varma]: this because of technology that didn't exist 10 years ago. And you could have podcast 10 years

03:08:10.480 --> 03:08:16.560
[Amit Varma]: ago, but the precise confluence of technologies that has brought my voice to your ears right now,

03:08:16.560 --> 03:08:23.280
[Amit Varma]: didn't really exist or not, not at the circumstances. And so, and I think the future

03:08:23.280 --> 03:08:29.600
[Amit Varma]: is largely a sea of unknown unknowns. So, you know, we can't tell in what ways good things

03:08:29.600 --> 03:08:34.800
[Amit Varma]: will happen or even bad things will happen. And there will be domains in which things will get

03:08:34.800 --> 03:08:39.840
[Amit Varma]: worse. And the arc of history will bend towards injustice as it were, or it will seem like that

03:08:39.840 --> 03:08:46.400
[Amit Varma]: in the short term. But, you know, I have hoped that in the long run, it will sort of, and maybe

03:08:46.400 --> 03:08:51.040
[Amit Varma]: I'm being delusional. So here is again, this is something somewhere where I could realize that

03:08:51.040 --> 03:08:55.520
[Amit Varma]: I should have been more pessimistic in the future. Who knows? You know, for me, I try,

03:08:56.160 --> 03:09:00.880
[Amit Varma]: these days, I try not to think about what's happening in the broader political space or in

03:09:00.880 --> 03:09:05.200
[Amit Varma]: the economic space, because it is, it makes me angry and frustrated, and there's nothing I can

03:09:05.200 --> 03:09:10.480
[Amit Varma]: do about it. So I want to keep exploring ideas and keep, you know, keep keep the discourse going

03:09:10.480 --> 03:09:14.800
[Amit Varma]: about all of these things, but there's nothing I can do about it. So at a personal level,

03:09:14.800 --> 03:09:19.840
[Amit Varma]: my personal philosophy really comes down to cherishing small joys, like the good conversations

03:09:19.840 --> 03:09:28.560
[Amit Varma]: I get to have, or just, you know, the kachoris I had earlier today. And which makes it sound

03:09:28.560 --> 03:09:35.040
[Amit Varma]: very trivial. But you know, I wish I had kachoris today. Yeah, there you go. I have just darkened

03:09:35.040 --> 03:09:43.120
[Amit Varma]: your world. I have. Yeah. So yeah, so I think, you know, so you do what you can at an individual

03:09:43.120 --> 03:09:50.560
[Amit Varma]: level, both for yourself, for your, you know, own mental enrichment, and, and all of that,

03:09:50.560 --> 03:09:56.480
[Amit Varma]: and whatever you can throw at the wall of ideas out there, you throw it, you know, the point is,

03:09:56.480 --> 03:10:00.960
[Amit Varma]: you don't, you don't, I mean, I think of Bastia again, you know, no chance of success, but he

03:10:00.960 --> 03:10:05.200
[Amit Varma]: writes all those great books, like the law and all his essays like that, which is seen and that

03:10:05.200 --> 03:10:09.520
[Amit Varma]: which is not seen. So you just got to do what you got to do. The future is unknown unknowns,

03:10:09.520 --> 03:10:15.760
[Amit Varma]: you increase the probability of good outcomes, if you can continue doing good things now,

03:10:15.760 --> 03:10:20.880
[Amit Varma]: without hoping for, you know, good outcomes later. So, you know, you just increase that

03:10:20.880 --> 03:10:25.600
[Amit Varma]: probability, you add your voice to the mix, you kind of do what you can, but you also I think,

03:10:25.600 --> 03:10:29.440
[Amit Varma]: I think all of us also need to sort of look us look after ourselves as well.

03:10:29.440 --> 03:10:36.400
[Guest]: No. And, you know, on this aspect, I feel like also there are things we are optimistic about.

03:10:36.400 --> 03:10:43.360
[Guest]: And the one thing I'm optimistic about, the older I get, is I think most people are fundamentally

03:10:43.360 --> 03:10:50.480
[Guest]: good, decent people. Right. And in that I have a very large amount of hope for the future of India,

03:10:50.480 --> 03:10:54.960
[Guest]: right? I know everyone thinks everyone hates everyone. And there is all this right wing

03:10:54.960 --> 03:10:58.800
[Guest]: anger and left wing anger and people think Twitter is what the real world looks like.

03:10:58.800 --> 03:11:04.080
[Guest]: The real world in my sense, I mean, I know India is remarkably violent and remarkably difficult and

03:11:04.080 --> 03:11:10.720
[Guest]: all of those things, you know, casteist, racist, misogynistic, but it's also full of remarkable

03:11:10.720 --> 03:11:18.960
[Guest]: kindness, you know, in the face of extreme shortages and, you know, some really difficult

03:11:18.960 --> 03:11:24.320
[Guest]: circumstances for a lot of people. And the more I travel in India, the more I see that kind of,

03:11:24.320 --> 03:11:29.280
[Guest]: you know, individual level kindness, that gives me a lot of hope. The other thing that gives me a

03:11:29.280 --> 03:11:34.880
[Guest]: lot of hope is I, you know, also do Emergent Ventures, right, which is one of the Mercatus

03:11:34.880 --> 03:11:42.000
[Guest]: Center platforms with which we support moonshot ideas. And just reading the applications from

03:11:42.000 --> 03:11:48.320
[Guest]: really young people, their ambition, you know, their imagination, their creativity. I,

03:11:49.360 --> 03:11:55.440
[Guest]: anytime I work on Emergent Ventures applications on a given day, you know, the next few hours are

03:11:55.440 --> 03:12:01.120
[Guest]: very bright and optimistic for that particular reason. So I'm also hugely optimistic of the

03:12:01.120 --> 03:12:08.960
[Guest]: younger people in India. I want to now move on to the other favorite resident economist that we have,

03:12:08.960 --> 03:12:16.720
[Guest]: and that is Rajeshwari Sengupta, right? I mean, she is just such a great thinker. Again, you know,

03:12:16.720 --> 03:12:22.960
[Guest]: our fields of specialization are different. So anytime I read a column or a paper by Rajeshwari,

03:12:22.960 --> 03:12:28.880
[Guest]: immediately it's got like, you know, my brain just expands and opens up a little bit more. So

03:12:28.880 --> 03:12:34.240
[Guest]: I really value her as an academic, but also as, you know, a guest on your podcast as a fellow

03:12:34.240 --> 03:12:39.840
[Guest]: guest, because we, we did one episode together. So I had the pleasure of meeting her. And she also

03:12:39.840 --> 03:12:44.400
[Guest]: has one of these big think questions for you. So I'm not going to say more, I'm just I'm going to,

03:12:44.400 --> 03:12:47.040
[Guest]: you know, play the question then. And then we'll talk about it.

03:12:47.040 --> 03:12:52.800
[Unknown]: Hi, this is Rajeshwari. First of all, heartiest congratulations to Amit and team on completing

03:12:52.800 --> 03:12:58.640
[Unknown]: 200 episodes of a podcast, which I think is one of the best in the country on the topics that it

03:12:58.640 --> 03:13:03.680
[Unknown]: covers. I've thoroughly enjoyed listening to several episodes and learned a lot. I wish you

03:13:03.680 --> 03:13:09.200
[Unknown]: guys all the best as you hopefully continue to enlighten us with more such informative shows.

03:13:10.000 --> 03:13:16.400
[Unknown]: My question for Amit is as follows. The podcast can safely be categorized as one

03:13:16.400 --> 03:13:22.960
[Unknown]: that caters to a highly educated English speaking elite audience. But the word elite

03:13:22.960 --> 03:13:30.080
[Unknown]: now has a negative connotation, it seems, in several societies, including us. All over the

03:13:30.080 --> 03:13:37.120
[Unknown]: world, we are witnessing a sort of a backlash against us elites. The unsaid unwritten criticism

03:13:37.120 --> 03:13:43.360
[Unknown]: seems to be that we the elite, the intellectual thinkers of the country have ignored or

03:13:43.360 --> 03:13:49.920
[Unknown]: marginalized for common man. And in doing so, somewhere we have lost the plot, we have lost

03:13:49.920 --> 03:13:56.960
[Unknown]: the narrative. There seems to be a deep disconnect between what we say or think or write, and what

03:13:56.960 --> 03:14:03.680
[Unknown]: the common man who votes in our democracy believes in. So my question for Amit today is that,

03:14:04.240 --> 03:14:10.480
[Unknown]: is there anything that he thinks that we can or need to do to bridge this ever expanding divide?

03:14:10.480 --> 03:14:16.720
[Unknown]: Or do we risk becoming redundant and reduced to passive observers reminiscing about the past

03:14:16.720 --> 03:14:23.520
[Unknown]: when things were different? Yeah, what a what a fantastic question. No. Yeah, it's it's Rajesh.

03:14:23.520 --> 03:14:28.400
[Unknown]: And it doesn't surprise you that it comes from Rajeshwari, right? Like she, she never thinks

03:14:28.400 --> 03:14:33.760
[Unknown]: narrowly. She just thinks so big and broad. I just, you know, classic macroeconomist thinking

03:14:33.760 --> 03:14:38.160
[Amit Varma]: macro question. Yeah, she's great. I did an episode on GDP with her, which was a fabulous

03:14:38.160 --> 03:14:43.280
[Amit Varma]: episode. And for anyone who wants to understand the concept of the GDP, and the way it's measured

03:14:43.280 --> 03:14:47.600
[Amit Varma]: and the larger conceptual questions as well. That's a great episode. And you Rajeshwari and

03:14:47.600 --> 03:14:51.760
[Amit Varma]: Vivek Kaur were my guests in a four person episode, we did 12 dream reforms, which is

03:14:51.760 --> 03:14:57.280
[Amit Varma]: one of my 10 most popular episodes, I think. And that was great fun. And you and Rajeshwari were,

03:14:57.280 --> 03:15:04.480
[Amit Varma]: of course, fighting all the time. We're not fighting. Economists talk to each other. I

03:15:04.480 --> 03:15:10.400
[Amit Varma]: think we scared everyone. Yeah, very deep question. So let me let me respond to it by

03:15:10.400 --> 03:15:15.280
[Amit Varma]: saying that first of all, I mean, I of course, use the elites in a banal descriptive sense,

03:15:15.280 --> 03:15:19.920
[Amit Varma]: but it's obviously true. We are the elites, right? We have to acknowledge our own good fortune and

03:15:19.920 --> 03:15:25.600
[Amit Varma]: our own privilege and all of that. And it's true. We are the elites by definition, because

03:15:26.400 --> 03:15:32.640
[Amit Varma]: there are so few of us and we are so fortunate. As far as the criticisms of elites are concerned,

03:15:32.640 --> 03:15:38.800
[Amit Varma]: I think they are largely justified. I think they're largely justified because elites too often,

03:15:40.160 --> 03:15:47.280
[Amit Varma]: people like us, and I include you and me, will sit in ivory towers and be sanctimonious about

03:15:47.280 --> 03:15:54.080
[Amit Varma]: what is good for everybody, including what is good for the common person. And, you know, and

03:15:56.080 --> 03:16:00.080
[Amit Varma]: because for so long, elites have controlled the levers of the state and the levers of media and

03:16:00.080 --> 03:16:06.960
[Amit Varma]: all of that. We'll, you know, we can do what we want and we can sort of, our narratives are the

03:16:06.960 --> 03:16:11.520
[Amit Varma]: ones that get through. And you could say in a sense that has started to change in recent times,

03:16:11.520 --> 03:16:16.880
[Amit Varma]: and there are ebbs and flows in that. I think the two, you know, to get back to the constructive

03:16:16.880 --> 03:16:22.880
[Amit Varma]: part of it that what can elites do better, I think there are sort of two important things that we can

03:16:22.880 --> 03:16:29.360
[Amit Varma]: do better. One is at a level of attitude, we need to be open. We don't need to look down on people

03:16:29.360 --> 03:16:35.840
[Amit Varma]: who, you know, are not elites and say that, oh, you know, so-and-so voted for Modi because he's

03:16:35.840 --> 03:16:42.000
[Amit Varma]: bigoted or so-and-so voted for Trump, so he must be a racist. And I think that kind of condescending,

03:16:42.000 --> 03:16:47.040
[Amit Varma]: demeaning attitude doesn't help. People's concerns are different from ours. We have to be

03:16:47.040 --> 03:16:52.240
[Amit Varma]: open to understanding. See, people contain multitudes. Like you said earlier, you know,

03:16:52.240 --> 03:16:57.840
[Amit Varma]: there is much kindness in the common person towards others, even towards those who he would

03:16:57.840 --> 03:17:02.960
[Amit Varma]: consider in an abstract sense to be the other, you know, that abstract term, but there is kindness

03:17:02.960 --> 03:17:09.440
[Amit Varma]: in an actual concrete way towards that. And I had a, I had an episode recently with Anshul Malhotra

03:17:09.440 --> 03:17:18.320
[Amit Varma]: where we discussed the concrete and the abstract a lot and very moving episode for me. And so I

03:17:18.320 --> 03:17:22.720
[Amit Varma]: think that this, we need to do that. We need to stop looking down on people and say that these

03:17:22.720 --> 03:17:27.920
[Amit Varma]: are the unwashed masses. What do they know? We know better and all of that. And we need to be open

03:17:27.920 --> 03:17:34.080
[Amit Varma]: to A, their concerns and open to their concerns, not in a way that we are, you know, giving

03:17:34.080 --> 03:17:40.160
[Amit Varma]: compassion from on top, but actually try to understand where are they coming from? Why are

03:17:40.160 --> 03:17:45.040
[Amit Varma]: they, because the point is, you know, there, but for the grace of God, go, aye, as it were. And,

03:17:46.320 --> 03:17:50.000
[Amit Varma]: and that's actually the wrong quote, because it's not even as if somebody is in an inferior

03:17:50.000 --> 03:17:54.560
[Amit Varma]: position and someone is better or someone is inferior or someone is better. It's not like

03:17:54.560 --> 03:17:59.440
[Amit Varma]: that at all. It's just that everyone is a creature of their circumstances and their thinking. And

03:17:59.440 --> 03:18:04.720
[Amit Varma]: maybe it is some of the elites who are in fact, intellectually hobbled by a narrowness of vision.

03:18:04.720 --> 03:18:11.920
[Amit Varma]: So I think elites need to be open and especially in one good way of doing this is through considering

03:18:11.920 --> 03:18:17.440
[Amit Varma]: what Barun calls means. And I would call consent that if you want to, if you want your ideas to

03:18:17.440 --> 03:18:22.640
[Amit Varma]: percolate through society, kindly do not impose them at the cost of others, but try to make it

03:18:22.640 --> 03:18:27.840
[Amit Varma]: happen in a bottoms up way. Too many of the elites have a particular vision of the world, which they

03:18:27.840 --> 03:18:33.920
[Amit Varma]: want to impose on others out of the best possible intentions. And I sort of have an issue with that.

03:18:33.920 --> 03:18:38.000
[Amit Varma]: So that's one aspect where the elites can do better just in terms of their attitude and their

03:18:38.000 --> 03:18:45.280
[Amit Varma]: approach. Have some humility, be open, don't, you know, try to look at the world in a top down way

03:18:45.280 --> 03:18:51.680
[Amit Varma]: and impose your ideas in that manner. And secondly, I would say that if the elites really have a sense

03:18:51.680 --> 03:18:55.680
[Amit Varma]: of conviction in what their ideas are, like you and I did and going back to Kumar's question,

03:18:56.240 --> 03:19:02.640
[Amit Varma]: then focus on a narrative where you're not talking at someone, but you're actually talking to

03:19:02.640 --> 03:19:06.560
[Amit Varma]: someone, you're respecting their concerns, and you're trying to convince them in a respectful

03:19:06.560 --> 03:19:11.440
[Amit Varma]: way, instead of lecturing to them, and judging them because they don't agree with you. So they

03:19:11.440 --> 03:19:18.560
[Amit Varma]: must be bad people, and so on and so forth, which is happening too much. And yeah, so these two

03:19:18.560 --> 03:19:24.800
[Amit Varma]: things, I think a lot of criticisms of and anger at elites are justified, and we should have the

03:19:24.800 --> 03:19:31.280
[Amit Varma]: humility to accept that and the capacity to then think about how do we communicate better. And I

03:19:31.280 --> 03:19:37.040
[Amit Varma]: think a lot of the answer comes in learning from others who are not like us. And some of the answer

03:19:37.040 --> 03:19:43.280
[Amit Varma]: comes from being able to have the sort of dialogue with them that we can convince them of our ideas.

03:19:43.840 --> 03:19:48.480
[Guest]: I would add one more thing. And maybe this is because I have been in the academy my whole life

03:19:48.480 --> 03:19:54.160
[Guest]: that I feel this particularly, I think elites, not just Indians everywhere in the world, but also

03:19:54.160 --> 03:19:59.840
[Guest]: very cliquish. And, you know, it's like a club with a secret handshake, right? Because if you

03:19:59.840 --> 03:20:04.800
[Guest]: didn't know how to pronounce that French word correctly, or you know, you know, you said Rodin

03:20:04.800 --> 03:20:09.600
[Guest]: instead of Rodin, then you know, oh, you are you are not you don't know the secret handshake,

03:20:09.600 --> 03:20:15.680
[Guest]: right? So there is, there is a very cliquish nature, we use pronunciation, we use schooling,

03:20:15.680 --> 03:20:22.480
[Guest]: we use brands, you know, what you wear, things like that, right? Like how you speak as proxies

03:20:22.480 --> 03:20:27.760
[Guest]: for whether you are part of the club or not part of the club. I find that particularly disturbing.

03:20:28.640 --> 03:20:33.200
[Guest]: And I never realized this about Indian elites while I was living in India, I was probably one

03:20:33.200 --> 03:20:37.600
[Guest]: of them who would have made fun of someone, you know, I hope I wouldn't have been that unkind.

03:20:37.600 --> 03:20:42.320
[Guest]: But you know, I can easily imagine myself being one of those people, either openly making fun of

03:20:42.320 --> 03:20:45.840
[Guest]: someone or at least like thinking in my head, I can't believe they don't know how to say that.

03:20:46.640 --> 03:20:54.480
[Guest]: But I think one thing that has changed me is also being an immigrant, right? So once you leave

03:20:54.480 --> 03:21:00.240
[Guest]: the place that you were raised in, and you come to a new world, which was open enough to accept

03:21:00.240 --> 03:21:06.320
[Guest]: you, even though I'm not one of them, right? I'm not, I'm not American. And being welcomed with

03:21:06.320 --> 03:21:11.280
[Guest]: open arms, people engaging with you, people mentoring you, teaching you so on so forth.

03:21:11.280 --> 03:21:18.160
[Guest]: And now suddenly, the lens with which I look at my own community or childhood or my own people,

03:21:18.160 --> 03:21:24.400
[Guest]: so to speak, people like us just flipped. So you know, ever since I left India, I have had

03:21:24.400 --> 03:21:31.440
[Guest]: actually, I guess, a more harsh view of this club nature of elites, like I just despise,

03:21:31.440 --> 03:21:36.240
[Guest]: you know, I mean, the people in a very pejorative way, say, you know, Khan Market,

03:21:36.240 --> 03:21:41.760
[Guest]: Kabal or something like that. But I grew up in Khan Market, you know, Bari Bookstores

03:21:41.760 --> 03:21:47.840
[Guest]: was my bookstore, right? Like, India International Center is where we had family dinner. So I have

03:21:47.840 --> 03:21:54.800
[Guest]: also been in that sort of, you know, Kabal to know enough that it is very much an in group,

03:21:54.800 --> 03:21:59.600
[Guest]: you know, you are one of us or out sort of environments. And I think that is something

03:21:59.600 --> 03:22:05.360
[Guest]: Indian elites really need to change as an at an individual and at a group level. I think this,

03:22:05.360 --> 03:22:13.440
[Guest]: there's also a value in networks, right? Thanks to Twitter, I have been speaking to more people

03:22:13.440 --> 03:22:21.840
[Guest]: who are from different backgrounds, right? Dalits, LGBTQ members, who, who I normally wouldn't have

03:22:21.840 --> 03:22:26.880
[Guest]: met, we would have never been in the same room, you know, given the circumstances in which I grew

03:22:26.880 --> 03:22:32.000
[Guest]: up in India. And one of the things I realized is one of the hardest things for Dalit students to

03:22:32.000 --> 03:22:37.760
[Guest]: get into American universities is letters of recommendation. Right? There aren't enough people

03:22:37.760 --> 03:22:44.480
[Guest]: that they know, who would write a letter for them that would carry weight in an American university

03:22:44.480 --> 03:22:48.080
[Guest]: that, you know, would get them admission. Of course, they know wonderful thinkers, I'm sure

03:22:48.080 --> 03:22:54.160
[Guest]: they have great teachers. But there is this gap, and this gap exists, because we wouldn't let them

03:22:54.160 --> 03:22:59.360
[Guest]: in. Right? So I have made this offer multiple times on Twitter and privately, and I'll make

03:22:59.360 --> 03:23:05.760
[Guest]: it on your show, that, you know, students who need help and help opening doors, opening networks

03:23:05.760 --> 03:23:11.120
[Guest]: within academy in India or abroad, they need people to recommend them or at least people to mentor

03:23:11.120 --> 03:23:19.440
[Guest]: them. And we need to open up a little bit and not say, I'm only going to mentor so and so who came

03:23:19.440 --> 03:23:24.400
[Guest]: from, you know, my father's friend's son, or, you know, someone who grew up in my neighborhood, or

03:23:24.400 --> 03:23:29.680
[Guest]: is the, you know, alumni of my school and things like that. So I think this in group clique behavior

03:23:29.680 --> 03:23:34.640
[Amit Varma]: really needs to end. Yeah. And some of these exclusionary behavior is, of course, the default

03:23:34.640 --> 03:23:39.920
[Amit Varma]: condition of being an elite and not necessarily an intentional, this thing on the part of the

03:23:40.480 --> 03:23:44.960
[Amit Varma]: elites, but it helps to be aware of it. And that self awareness is important. I'll just respond to

03:23:44.960 --> 03:23:49.840
[Amit Varma]: a couple of the things that you said. One is about pronunciations. You know, I read someone make the

03:23:49.840 --> 03:23:54.720
[Amit Varma]: point once which I agree wholeheartedly with, and it's a great point, is that when you hear someone

03:23:54.720 --> 03:24:00.080
[Amit Varma]: pronounce something wrong, you should actually respect the person and applaud him. Because it

03:24:00.080 --> 03:24:04.720
[Amit Varma]: means that he is not in those circles, where people talk about that person or that idea,

03:24:04.720 --> 03:24:09.600
[Amit Varma]: but nevertheless, he has read up on it enough to know about it, but he can't pronounce it,

03:24:09.600 --> 03:24:15.520
[Amit Varma]: which which shows that added sort of work that the person has put in. And therefore, you know,

03:24:15.520 --> 03:24:20.240
[Amit Varma]: if someone says Rodin instead of Rodin, which I'm sure I must have done at the start, the very first

03:24:20.240 --> 03:24:24.560
[Amit Varma]: time I read the word, how would I have thought of it exactly like that, right? So it's, it's

03:24:24.560 --> 03:24:31.040
[Amit Varma]: perfectly fine. And and we need to sort of lose some of that inbuilt snobbishness. The second

03:24:31.040 --> 03:24:36.640
[Amit Varma]: thing I'll say is that, you know, I think I've sort of been an outsider in every sort of community

03:24:36.640 --> 03:24:41.040
[Amit Varma]: that I've been remotely part of in my life, whether it's an intellectual community or writers or poker

03:24:41.040 --> 03:24:45.440
[Amit Varma]: players or whatever, I've kind of been on the fringes one foot in one foot out very different

03:24:45.440 --> 03:24:51.280
[Amit Varma]: kind of view bringing a different lens and all of that. So I've kind of gotten this from the start

03:24:51.280 --> 03:24:56.720
[Amit Varma]: that while I am extremely fortunate and privileged and all that, there's just so many problems with,

03:24:57.600 --> 03:25:02.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, those sort of narrow, constricted worlds. And the other thing I would say is that,

03:25:02.320 --> 03:25:06.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, we know for a fact that this podcast, for example, does have an elite audience,

03:25:06.640 --> 03:25:12.720
[Amit Varma]: it goes out to a lot of the elites, and especially young PhD students, and so on and so forth. And

03:25:12.720 --> 03:25:18.320
[Amit Varma]: if they are listening to that, I just ask that always retain intellectual humility. Because,

03:25:18.320 --> 03:25:23.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, we reflexively fall into certain ways of thinking that are common in our circles,

03:25:23.920 --> 03:25:28.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, depending on where we are being educated or the circles that we talk to and

03:25:28.320 --> 03:25:34.160
[Amit Varma]: whatever. And it's always sort of tempting to harden the ways in which you think to fit in

03:25:34.160 --> 03:25:38.320
[Amit Varma]: with your peers and to gain brownie points for them or whatever. And that's a natural human

03:25:38.320 --> 03:25:45.120
[Amit Varma]: tendency, but always try as far as possible to retain a certain amount of intellectual humility,

03:25:45.120 --> 03:25:50.320
[Amit Varma]: and to not make the mistake of dehumanizing those who disagree with you. Like one thing that is

03:25:50.320 --> 03:25:55.520
[Amit Varma]: so sad about these modern times is that discourse has become so toxic, that if someone disagrees

03:25:55.520 --> 03:25:59.520
[Amit Varma]: with us, we treat them as if they are a bad person, there is a character flaw there.

03:25:59.520 --> 03:26:00.400
[Amit Varma]: They are the enemy.

03:26:00.400 --> 03:26:08.000
[Amit Varma]: They are the enemy and kindly avoid that. But enough of my hectoring as the elites would do.

03:26:08.000 --> 03:26:08.880
[Guest]: And let's move on.

03:26:08.880 --> 03:26:12.800
[Guest]: I think that is a posh word. Amit, you need to find a simpler word for that.

03:26:12.800 --> 03:26:16.800
[Amit Varma]: Hoist by my own petard to use an elite cliche,

03:26:16.800 --> 03:26:19.680
[Amit Varma]: again, something I won against, by the way, in my course. But yeah.

03:26:22.160 --> 03:26:26.160
[Guest]: Now, I want to get to a couple of like more concrete policy.

03:26:26.160 --> 03:26:31.120
[Guest]: So the next question, again, comes from, you know, one of our favorite people and thinkers.

03:26:32.000 --> 03:26:37.440
[Guest]: This is Hamsini Hariharan. I mean, off late, I mean, not that I didn't admire her before,

03:26:37.440 --> 03:26:44.000
[Guest]: but my admiration for her has increased many fold since she got into the world of China.

03:26:44.000 --> 03:26:47.920
[Guest]: Right. And it feels like this different universe, whether it's the language,

03:26:47.920 --> 03:26:53.120
[Guest]: whether it's actually going to China and spending time there, whether it's really trying to

03:26:53.120 --> 03:26:58.240
[Guest]: understand the world from a completely different lens. Right. Seeing India through a different

03:26:58.240 --> 03:27:03.440
[Guest]: culture, through the neighbor's point of view. So Hamsini, if you're listening to this,

03:27:03.440 --> 03:27:09.360
[Guest]: you know, my admiration for you has only increased. And Hamsini has a question for you. So I will

03:27:10.160 --> 03:27:12.000
[Guest]: play the question first and then we'll talk about it.

03:27:12.960 --> 03:27:17.200
[Unknown]: Hi, Amit. Congratulations on 200 episodes of The Seen and The Unseen.

03:27:17.200 --> 03:27:22.800
[Unknown]: Here's my question for you. If the government of India came to you tomorrow

03:27:22.800 --> 03:27:27.600
[Unknown]: and asked you for advice on policy reform, what would be the first on your list that

03:27:27.600 --> 03:27:31.920
[Unknown]: the government needs to reform? Yes, I know you tell the government not to do anything

03:27:31.920 --> 03:27:37.280
[Unknown]: and to butt out, but this is hypothetical. So what's the first thing that you think

03:27:37.280 --> 03:27:41.440
[Unknown]: the government needs to address? Yeah, nice question. I mean, where does one

03:27:41.440 --> 03:27:47.600
[Amit Varma]: even start? Hamsini, of course, was my colleague at Pragati for the time that I was the editor

03:27:47.600 --> 03:27:52.480
[Amit Varma]: there. So we were basically, she and I were the editorial team. She was based out of Bangalore.

03:27:52.480 --> 03:27:56.720
[Amit Varma]: So whenever I went there, we would have our editorial meetings at Blossom's bookstore,

03:27:56.720 --> 03:28:01.120
[Amit Varma]: which is the best possible place to have editorial meetings, I would imagine. And

03:28:01.120 --> 03:28:05.920
[Amit Varma]: she's always been into China, by the way, from the time I knew her, so not recent. Good

03:28:05.920 --> 03:28:10.320
[Guest]: question. Where do I even start? I mean, Oh, no, the recent part is her actually going

03:28:10.320 --> 03:28:14.960
[Amit Varma]: to China, immersing herself in that. Well, that's the recent part.

03:28:14.960 --> 03:28:19.680
[Amit Varma]: She was already a scholar of China before that, and studying and learning Chinese and

03:28:19.680 --> 03:28:25.280
[Amit Varma]: all of that. I think you need an overall mindset shift, right? If you just change one little

03:28:25.280 --> 03:28:28.400
[Amit Varma]: thing that doesn't help, but I don't want to cop out. So okay, what are the specific

03:28:28.400 --> 03:28:36.720
[Amit Varma]: things? I mean, easy answers would be, okay, abolish, you know, all but maybe five or six

03:28:36.720 --> 03:28:42.000
[Amit Varma]: ministries in all the areas where you don't need them. Apart from that, yeah, I mean,

03:28:42.000 --> 03:28:47.760
[Amit Varma]: just sort of, you know, I mean, there's so many policies that I've discussed over a period

03:28:47.760 --> 03:28:54.000
[Amit Varma]: of time. There are, you know, urban development related policies like, you know, FSI and rent

03:28:54.000 --> 03:28:59.680
[Amit Varma]: control, there are policies at the agricultural level, which is, you know, where we have really

03:28:59.680 --> 03:29:05.520
[Amit Varma]: failed our farmers and shackled them for decades. And there are tons of policies with all kinds

03:29:05.520 --> 03:29:09.520
[Amit Varma]: of externalities, you know, you should immediately shut down all PSUs, for example.

03:29:10.800 --> 03:29:14.880
[Guest]: Can I interrupt you for a second? Sure. And prompt you a little bit because I have a feeling

03:29:14.880 --> 03:29:20.000
[Guest]: you'll agree with me. I think the number one thing, if I had been asked that would be on

03:29:20.000 --> 03:29:25.120
[Amit Varma]: Amit Verma's list would have been education. Yeah, allow for profit schools and don't regulate them.

03:29:25.120 --> 03:29:30.560
[Amit Varma]: And I've had different episodes on why this is important. And it's a tragedy. It's what we have

03:29:30.560 --> 03:29:37.120
[Amit Varma]: done to our children for decades is, you know, keeping them poor and uneducated is just a crime,

03:29:37.120 --> 03:29:45.200
[Amit Varma]: but it's so unseen. And it's, it's, it's a crime. And yeah, I mean, I could, I could sort of

03:29:45.200 --> 03:29:50.400
[Amit Varma]: get all emotional and upset over here. And, and I, of course, I'm one of those elites who had

03:29:50.400 --> 03:29:55.440
[Amit Varma]: the privilege of getting a decent education, though our education system is actually completely

03:29:55.440 --> 03:30:01.200
[Amit Varma]: shitty. I consider myself self educated, but regardless of that, whatever base one was given

03:30:01.200 --> 03:30:05.920
[Amit Varma]: just in terms of learning the language, but extremely privileged that way. But yeah, what

03:30:05.920 --> 03:30:11.680
[Amit Varma]: we have done to the children of our country, keeping them poor and uneducated for decades

03:30:11.680 --> 03:30:18.160
[Amit Varma]: is a great tragedy. And every government is to blame for thinking about this the wrong way.

03:30:18.160 --> 03:30:23.520
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, that's, that's, you know, certainly one area that I can think of, but it's like,

03:30:23.520 --> 03:30:30.080
[Amit Varma]: where do you even start if your body has like 80 cancers and, you know, 40 ulcers and all kinds of

03:30:30.080 --> 03:30:35.360
[Amit Varma]: things going wrong and organs are falling apart. And, you know, there are every bacteria and virus

03:30:35.360 --> 03:30:39.680
[Amit Varma]: has infected you and you say, which disease would you like to cure first? Like, you know,

03:30:39.680 --> 03:30:45.600
[Amit Varma]: it's like you feel like saying Bhaskar Pagle Rulaega Kya? It's, yeah, so I know that's not a

03:30:45.600 --> 03:30:50.880
[Guest]: satisfying... I think reincarnation is the only option if we were the religious sorts. If we were

03:30:50.880 --> 03:30:56.640
[Amit Varma]: the religious sorts. Yeah. I mean, the question is, you know, the reason I'm sort of floundering

03:30:56.640 --> 03:31:00.880
[Amit Varma]: is that the question I've just heard the question, maybe if I'd had it a day in advance, I could

03:31:00.880 --> 03:31:06.640
[Amit Varma]: have thought of something eloquent and a good reasoning for that. But education, you know,

03:31:06.640 --> 03:31:10.800
[Amit Varma]: certainly, you're right that that's something that I've written about a lot. And that would

03:31:10.800 --> 03:31:15.360
[Amit Varma]: kind of make sense. But in general, you want a mindset shift where, you know, it shouldn't be

03:31:15.360 --> 03:31:20.560
[Amit Varma]: as if the government owned the people. The fact is, the state is there to serve the citizens and

03:31:20.560 --> 03:31:24.960
[Amit Varma]: not the other way around. We have the opposite mindset. And we need to get past the mindset.

03:31:24.960 --> 03:31:28.720
[Amit Varma]: And I don't know whether it's a problem of the state. I think it's a problem of the people that

03:31:28.720 --> 03:31:34.160
[Amit Varma]: we have normalized it and we have this mindset. If you change the demand end of the political

03:31:34.160 --> 03:31:39.440
[Amit Varma]: marketplace, then the supply end will take care of itself. And but I think that, you know, the

03:31:39.440 --> 03:31:44.080
[Amit Varma]: state is a different beast that is almost insulated from a lot of what happens in the political

03:31:44.080 --> 03:31:48.960
[Amit Varma]: marketplace, partly because of all the mistakes made in designing the state to begin with when

03:31:48.960 --> 03:31:54.320
[Amit Varma]: we gained independence. And that's just a whole new story. And it could have been far worse. So,

03:31:54.320 --> 03:31:56.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, maybe we should just be thankful for what we have.

03:31:56.960 --> 03:32:02.480
[Guest]: I think there is another question along similar lines. And this is by one of your biggest fans.

03:32:02.480 --> 03:32:08.960
[Guest]: This is Sudhir Sarnobat. And I am going to play the question. And now don't say I surprised you,

03:32:08.960 --> 03:32:13.360
[Guest]: because you've had a little bit more time to think about it. But it's basically putting

03:32:13.360 --> 03:32:18.080
[Guest]: Modiji out of a job. So just, you know, let me play Sudhir's question.

03:32:18.080 --> 03:32:24.320
[Unknown]: Hi Amit. Congratulations on 200th episode of Seen and Seen. Over the last 200 episodes,

03:32:24.320 --> 03:32:28.480
[Unknown]: I have learned a lot about states, markets, economics, and Indian political history.

03:32:28.480 --> 03:32:33.200
[Unknown]: There's a lot that's wrong with our society, politics, and overall political structure.

03:32:34.160 --> 03:32:38.800
[Unknown]: Various themes have been discussed on Seen and Seen. Taking that thread forward,

03:32:38.800 --> 03:32:44.000
[Unknown]: I would like to indulge you into a thought experiment. What if you are made a prime

03:32:44.000 --> 03:32:51.840
[Unknown]: minister of India with thumping majority for, let's say, next 10 years, from 2024 till 2034?

03:32:52.880 --> 03:32:57.520
[Unknown]: Then what are the top five initiatives that you would implement which would make India

03:32:57.520 --> 03:33:03.280
[Unknown]: a country and a society that you have dreamed to have? Can you just give us your thoughts on this?

03:33:03.840 --> 03:33:04.340
[Unknown]: Thank you.

03:33:05.360 --> 03:33:11.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, wonderful question. Sudhir is an ardent fan and supporter of the show, which I'm very

03:33:12.720 --> 03:33:18.640
[Amit Varma]: grateful for since I opened up support in April. He also enrolled himself for the writing course

03:33:19.360 --> 03:33:23.760
[Amit Varma]: and all of that and just keeps giving wonderful feedback, which is what I meant when,

03:33:23.760 --> 03:33:28.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, so many of the readers feel like they have a personal stake in the show, so they want to

03:33:28.880 --> 03:33:32.320
[Amit Varma]: constantly, you know, if they don't like something, they'll tell you about it.

03:33:32.320 --> 03:33:35.680
[Amit Varma]: They want something else, they'll tell you about it, which, you know, and I love that.

03:33:36.240 --> 03:33:41.280
[Amit Varma]: Makes me feel like I'm also a custodian of something that belongs to other people and

03:33:41.280 --> 03:33:46.960
[Amit Varma]: means something to them as well. Okay, five things. I don't know. I think, where do you start?

03:33:46.960 --> 03:33:48.240
[Amit Varma]: Now, if you are...

03:33:48.240 --> 03:33:50.400
[Guest]: Let's start with you being elected prime minister.

03:33:50.400 --> 03:33:50.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean...

03:33:51.680 --> 03:33:52.480
[Amit Varma]: So, Varmaji.

03:33:52.480 --> 03:33:56.800
[Amit Varma]: Varmaji. So, obviously, Varmaji is never going to happen. It's absurd, but I love thought

03:33:56.800 --> 03:34:01.920
[Amit Varma]: experiments and I appreciate that Sudhir put a thought experiment. So, I'll respect that and

03:34:01.920 --> 03:34:08.720
[Amit Varma]: let us say that, okay, if I am ever in that kind of position of power, first of all, do an audit,

03:34:08.720 --> 03:34:12.000
[Amit Varma]: rationalize everything the government does and think about should the government do this or

03:34:12.000 --> 03:34:16.880
[Amit Varma]: should the government not do this. And, you know, my sort of rather heuristic for looking at what

03:34:16.880 --> 03:34:21.200
[Amit Varma]: is wrong with the public policy or where the problem is, like if there's a particular outcome

03:34:21.200 --> 03:34:25.440
[Amit Varma]: in the world, why is that outcome there? Where is the problem? And one heuristic I use is to

03:34:25.440 --> 03:34:29.440
[Amit Varma]: ask the question, where is the coercion? So, I would do that in the case of government where

03:34:29.440 --> 03:34:35.040
[Amit Varma]: I would look at different policies and say, okay, where is the coercion? Is it necessary?

03:34:35.040 --> 03:34:40.400
[Amit Varma]: Why is it necessary? What is the impact of this? What are the outcomes that it is having? Do a

03:34:40.400 --> 03:34:44.560
[Amit Varma]: complete audit on everything that the government does, which will immediately knock off a lot of

03:34:44.560 --> 03:34:49.520
[Amit Varma]: the ministries, which will knock off a lot of the spending. Figure out ways to do it because even

03:34:49.520 --> 03:34:55.440
[Amit Varma]: though you can't shift from one equilibrium to the other overnight, there are what I would call

03:34:55.440 --> 03:35:01.360
[Amit Varma]: transaction costs in that and you got to figure out ways to make smooth transitions. But one do

03:35:01.360 --> 03:35:06.320
[Amit Varma]: that, have a clear vision of what the government is to do, you know, and think about that. Like

03:35:06.320 --> 03:35:11.200
[Amit Varma]: one metric that I would love using for this is Gandhiji's metric, where Mahatma Gandhi's metric

03:35:11.200 --> 03:35:16.560
[Amit Varma]: was that for every public policy, think of whether it will help the poor or not, which is actually,

03:35:16.560 --> 03:35:20.560
[Amit Varma]: I'm quite happy for that to be the single metric that I use for everything in terms of outcome,

03:35:20.560 --> 03:35:24.800
[Amit Varma]: when I think about outcome, that will it help the poor or hurt the poor? And the interesting thing

03:35:24.800 --> 03:35:29.920
[Amit Varma]: is that most of the policies that many people think of as being tailored towards the poor

03:35:29.920 --> 03:35:34.400
[Amit Varma]: actually hurt the poor, they don't help them and vice versa. So, think a little deeper,

03:35:34.400 --> 03:35:39.920
[Amit Varma]: think about unseen but entirely foreseeable effects and work according to that. So, rationalize

03:35:39.920 --> 03:35:46.000
[Amit Varma]: according to what the government has no business doing, what it can do to solve poverty, which is

03:35:46.000 --> 03:35:52.880
[Amit Varma]: our number one problem and should be our number one problem and think about it, not at the basic,

03:35:53.600 --> 03:35:58.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, patronizing level of, you know, handouts and schemes and all of that thing.

03:35:58.240 --> 03:36:02.240
[Amit Varma]: But think about structurally, what can we do about our poverty, how the rest of the world has

03:36:02.240 --> 03:36:07.440
[Amit Varma]: tackled it. And therefore, that's what we need to do. So, I really start with these two. And

03:36:07.440 --> 03:36:12.720
[Amit Varma]: the thing is, the problem with the Indian state is that it is too small and too large at the same

03:36:12.720 --> 03:36:18.480
[Amit Varma]: time, that it doesn't do the few things it should do properly, such as maintain the rule of law,

03:36:19.200 --> 03:36:24.000
[Amit Varma]: and so on, where basically in most of the country, there is no rule of law for elites like us,

03:36:24.000 --> 03:36:29.840
[Amit Varma]: we can buy, figure out ways to work the system, but there is no rule of law for most people.

03:36:29.840 --> 03:36:33.920
[Amit Varma]: So, the things that we should do strengthen the state there. And there are so many things that

03:36:33.920 --> 03:36:40.960
[Amit Varma]: we should not do and get the state out of that as smoothly as possible. So, these are the broad

03:36:40.960 --> 03:36:47.120
[Amit Varma]: areas, you know, I, you know, can't really think of five and all of these are in the realm of wild

03:36:47.120 --> 03:36:53.840
[Amit Varma]: fantasy, you know, it's, but, but, yeah, I mean, if you put me in that thought experiment,

03:36:54.800 --> 03:37:00.640
[Amit Varma]: these are the lines I along which I will think you remove restrictions on private enterprise,

03:37:00.640 --> 03:37:05.600
[Amit Varma]: voluntary action is what what makes society grow. Now, with every act of voluntary exchange,

03:37:05.600 --> 03:37:11.040
[Amit Varma]: both people are better off. That's the secret to prosperity. So remove all restrictions on acts

03:37:11.040 --> 03:37:15.840
[Amit Varma]: like that, you know, if you know, there'll be one class of people in India, who will

03:37:16.720 --> 03:37:20.800
[Amit Varma]: say that we should be free to do whatever we want in the marketplace, but not in the bedroom,

03:37:20.800 --> 03:37:24.560
[Amit Varma]: and there'll be another class that says the opposite. And I'll say that no two consenting

03:37:24.560 --> 03:37:29.360
[Amit Varma]: adults should be able to interact with each other in whatever way they want, as long as they're not

03:37:29.360 --> 03:37:34.240
[Amit Varma]: infringing on the rights of someone else, be it in the bedroom or the marketplace. So get out of,

03:37:34.240 --> 03:37:39.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, the regulating people's personal morality or passing judgment on that, and also

03:37:39.840 --> 03:37:43.760
[Amit Varma]: let them interact freely in the marketplace, unless you're doing a deal to get someone

03:37:43.760 --> 03:37:47.680
[Amit Varma]: assassinated, in which case you're obviously infringing those rights. But otherwise respect

03:37:47.680 --> 03:37:51.920
[Amit Varma]: the power of voluntary exchange, we do not do this enough. And this will automatically take

03:37:51.920 --> 03:37:56.880
[Amit Varma]: care of a lot of cronyism, like people often confuse markets with business that what is good

03:37:56.880 --> 03:38:02.080
[Amit Varma]: for markets must be good for business. And it's actually, they are at opposite ends that, you

03:38:02.080 --> 03:38:07.040
[Amit Varma]: know, a pro-business policies will be bad for markets and therefore bad for the people, because

03:38:07.040 --> 03:38:12.160
[Amit Varma]: every big business will want to shut down competition, and, you know, put barriers to

03:38:12.160 --> 03:38:16.080
[Amit Varma]: entry so that their position is protected, and they will want special favors from the government.

03:38:16.080 --> 03:38:21.840
[Amit Varma]: And in the end, this harms the people, and this harms the poor. So, you know, the more we get out

03:38:21.840 --> 03:38:28.800
[Amit Varma]: of regulating voluntary exchange, the less this kind of cronyism becomes possible. So this sort

03:38:28.800 --> 03:38:36.960
[Amit Varma]: of a rambling answer, I hope will satisfy Sudhir. Yeah, I mean, that covers more than five, right?

03:38:36.960 --> 03:38:42.560
[Guest]: That covers like hundreds of potential interventions or initiatives that you could implement.

03:38:43.360 --> 03:38:48.720
[Guest]: So now, we are moving on to, I think, what is going to be one of the most exciting parts of

03:38:48.720 --> 03:38:54.560
[Guest]: this conversation for me. I want to move on to a really exciting area. So you know, one of the

03:38:54.560 --> 03:39:01.120
[Guest]: things I have been so jealous of, pretty much the entire time I have known you, is how broadly you

03:39:01.120 --> 03:39:06.240
[Guest]: read, and more importantly, how quickly you read. You know, by the time I finish one book, you have

03:39:06.240 --> 03:39:12.560
[Guest]: finished five, and I think I read a fair bit, but you just put the rest of us to shame. The other

03:39:12.560 --> 03:39:20.080
[Guest]: thing is, you manage to read, you know, not just the same type of thing over and over again. And

03:39:20.080 --> 03:39:24.640
[Guest]: of course, you know, being in the academy has stunted me in that we specialize in a particular

03:39:24.640 --> 03:39:29.680
[Guest]: discipline and things like that. But you read everything, right? You're not a snob about things.

03:39:29.680 --> 03:39:33.440
[Guest]: You may make fun of Chetan Bhagat, but you will make fun of Chetan Bhagat after reading

03:39:33.440 --> 03:39:39.680
[Guest]: Chetan Bhagat, right? You've read everything. So there are a number of your, you know, guests and

03:39:39.680 --> 03:39:46.400
[Guest]: fans, not surprisingly, who have questions about books. And so I want to start queuing that up and,

03:39:46.400 --> 03:39:52.480
[Guest]: you know, ask you those questions, right? So the very first question comes from, as we have

03:39:52.480 --> 03:39:58.800
[Guest]: discussed this multiple times in this episode, Russ Roberts, the host of Econ Talk, and one of

03:39:58.800 --> 03:40:04.480
[Guest]: my most favorite thinkers. You know, you talked about education, and of course, I am not self

03:40:04.480 --> 03:40:10.560
[Guest]: taught like you. I have had a lot of formal education, you know, which a lot of your listeners

03:40:10.560 --> 03:40:17.040
[Guest]: have also, you know, learned about through various episodes. But I feel like I have learned more from

03:40:17.040 --> 03:40:23.360
[Guest]: Russ Roberts than virtually any other book in economics or any other single professor of mine,

03:40:23.360 --> 03:40:29.360
[Guest]: because I have been listening to his podcast since I think 2006 or 2007, from the very,

03:40:29.360 --> 03:40:32.480
[Guest]: very early days. And he was a professor at George Mason, and that was the pull.

03:40:33.360 --> 03:40:39.360
[Guest]: But you know, I have just learned how to think about the world through his voice. And you know,

03:40:39.360 --> 03:40:46.320
[Guest]: through his eyes. I also think he's a remarkable human being and so incredibly kind and generous.

03:40:46.320 --> 03:40:54.000
[Guest]: I feel like I hope somewhere that has also seeped into me maybe, you know, the I hope I have become

03:40:54.000 --> 03:41:00.480
[Guest]: less judgmental, less critical, less snobbish, you know, more kind, more willing to listen all

03:41:00.480 --> 03:41:05.520
[Guest]: all the things that you know, Russ just embodies. I don't know how he's been doing it for so long.

03:41:05.520 --> 03:41:13.600
[Guest]: And so I, when I emailed Russ, he sent in a question. And in, you know, those of the listeners

03:41:13.600 --> 03:41:18.480
[Guest]: who don't listen to Russ Roberts on Econ Talk, do so immediately. And now I'm going to play the

03:41:18.480 --> 03:41:26.160
[Unknown]: question for you. I meet Russ Roberts here. I want to congratulate you on your 200th episode and to

03:41:26.160 --> 03:41:31.440
[Unknown]: thank you for the opportunity to be one of those 200 on your podcast, The Seen and the Unseen was

03:41:31.440 --> 03:41:37.120
[Unknown]: one of my favorite conversations ever. Here's my question for you. I'm going to ask you to name and

03:41:37.120 --> 03:41:43.040
[Unknown]: recommend three books. One that has influenced your view of the world. One that enthralled you

03:41:43.040 --> 03:41:47.840
[Unknown]: as pure entertainment, perhaps a novel or biography. And finally, one that inspired you,

03:41:47.840 --> 03:41:52.320
[Unknown]: one that made you a better person or that touched you, such as a book of poetry, or maybe even a

03:41:52.320 --> 03:41:59.680
[Unknown]: single poem that's special to you. Again, Amit, congratulations. Yeah, well, it's almost overwhelming

03:41:59.680 --> 03:42:05.760
[Amit Varma]: to be asked the question by Russ Roberts, right? Because he is such a legend of both podcasting and

03:42:05.760 --> 03:42:10.400
[Amit Varma]: and and you know, I've obviously never met him personally, but his humanity shines through his

03:42:10.400 --> 03:42:15.440
[Amit Varma]: writing, and is therefore so inspiring. And that that episode, of course, was such a, you know,

03:42:15.440 --> 03:42:19.280
[Amit Varma]: wonderful conversation that I did with him. I really loved it. And this reading, I mean,

03:42:19.280 --> 03:42:24.880
[Amit Varma]: even his short book on Adam Smith is really, in a sense, a guide to how to be a better person and to

03:42:24.880 --> 03:42:33.120
[Amit Varma]: live a better life. So I kind of love that. A book that changed my view of the world. I'm not going

03:42:33.120 --> 03:42:38.960
[Amit Varma]: to name a libertarian book here, oddly enough, I'm going to name The Blank Slate by Steven Pinker.

03:42:39.520 --> 03:42:46.800
[Amit Varma]: Because and what that book sort of did to me and and was that it made me much more cognizant

03:42:46.800 --> 03:42:53.600
[Amit Varma]: and aware of human nature. And the fact that we aren't blank slates, that we have a hard wiring.

03:42:53.600 --> 03:42:59.680
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, it made me very conscious of the different ways in which our culture is both a

03:42:59.680 --> 03:43:06.080
[Amit Varma]: reflection of the hard wiring, and also an attempt to mitigate it and to fight it, that we are wired

03:43:06.080 --> 03:43:11.040
[Amit Varma]: in certain ways. And we are also wired in certain contradictory ways. But the most remarkable thing

03:43:11.040 --> 03:43:18.160
[Amit Varma]: is that we are the only animal, so to say, that has been given the tools to fight its hard wiring,

03:43:18.160 --> 03:43:23.920
[Amit Varma]: which is the ability to think about the world in conceptual terms, and to make value judgments

03:43:23.920 --> 03:43:28.640
[Amit Varma]: about what is a good way to behave and what is the wrong way to behave. And that awareness of

03:43:28.640 --> 03:43:35.440
[Amit Varma]: our own humanity and sort of the different ways in which you know, we are like I think of the

03:43:35.440 --> 03:43:41.200
[Amit Varma]: brain as a machine that we have to fight, that the machine is wired to do so many things to look at

03:43:41.200 --> 03:43:47.360
[Amit Varma]: the world and, you know, different kinds of toxic ways. And we have to fight that machine and we

03:43:47.360 --> 03:43:53.200
[Amit Varma]: have to fight it even in more everyday mundane things like our brain is wired to be distracted,

03:43:53.200 --> 03:43:58.560
[Amit Varma]: to take the easy way out to preserve cognitive energy and not actually do deep work. And in

03:43:58.560 --> 03:44:04.000
[Amit Varma]: various ways, we have to kind of fight that. And the blank slate is this wonderful book that,

03:44:04.000 --> 03:44:11.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, through this long arc shows one on the different ways in which we are shaped and

03:44:11.040 --> 03:44:17.360
[Amit Varma]: our cultures and our societies are shaped by a wiring and be in the ways in which different fields

03:44:18.080 --> 03:44:24.800
[Amit Varma]: have, you know, are shaped by it and also reflect sort of the different battles that then arise

03:44:24.800 --> 03:44:32.160
[Amit Varma]: when we try to fight this and also how dangerous a view of the world would be that rejects the fact

03:44:32.160 --> 03:44:36.960
[Amit Varma]: that we are wired and treats us as if we are blank slates when we are absolutely not. So,

03:44:36.960 --> 03:44:42.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, it takes a very nuanced view of nature versus nurture. I think in one of his books,

03:44:43.040 --> 03:44:49.920
[Amit Varma]: Pinker writes about how, you know, nature gives us knobs, nurture turns them, which I think is,

03:44:49.920 --> 03:44:53.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, such a powerful line. That's one book, which I think changed the way

03:44:53.840 --> 03:45:02.640
[Amit Varma]: I look at the world. Another great book, which I think sort of moves me a lot and, you know,

03:45:02.640 --> 03:45:08.160
[Amit Varma]: has me sort of connects me deeply with the shared humanity of all of us and the shared tragedy of

03:45:08.160 --> 03:45:14.160
[Amit Varma]: life, as it were, is a book of poems called Almost Invisible by Mark Strand. And I would

03:45:14.160 --> 03:45:18.480
[Amit Varma]: recommend all my listeners to just go and buy Mark Strand's collected poems, because that will

03:45:18.480 --> 03:45:22.960
[Amit Varma]: include this book, obviously. And that's a remarkable volume. And he's a remarkable poet.

03:45:22.960 --> 03:45:27.280
[Amit Varma]: And these poems were written, I think, when he was towards the end of his life, if I'm not mistaken,

03:45:27.280 --> 03:45:34.320
[Amit Varma]: it's his last book of poetry. And it's prose poems. Right. So it's just, it's just prose.

03:45:34.320 --> 03:45:40.000
[Amit Varma]: And, and since Russ said, maybe I should read something out from it. Let me, let me, let me

03:45:40.000 --> 03:45:48.160
[Amit Varma]: quickly find something to sort of read out from this. Yeah, so I'll, I have opened the page, and

03:45:48.960 --> 03:45:52.000
[Amit Varma]: I'll read out a couple of poems are very short, and they're very powerful.

03:45:52.000 --> 03:45:57.360
[Amit Varma]: You can always get there from here by Mark Strand, a traveler returned to the country from where he

03:45:57.360 --> 03:46:01.760
[Amit Varma]: had started many years before. When he stepped down from the boat, he noticed how different

03:46:01.760 --> 03:46:06.000
[Amit Varma]: everything was. There were once many buildings, but now there were few and each of them needed

03:46:06.000 --> 03:46:11.280
[Amit Varma]: repair. In the park where he played as a child, dust filled shafts of sunlight struck the tawny

03:46:11.280 --> 03:46:16.800
[Amit Varma]: leaves of trees and withered hedges. Empty trash bags littered the grass, the air was heavy. He

03:46:16.800 --> 03:46:21.440
[Amit Varma]: sat on one of the benches and explained to the woman next to him that he'd been away a long time.

03:46:21.440 --> 03:46:26.400
[Amit Varma]: He then asked her what season had he come back to. She replied that it was the only one left,

03:46:26.400 --> 03:46:30.720
[Amit Varma]: the one they had all agreed on. I'll read out the next one now.

03:46:31.520 --> 03:46:36.480
[Amit Varma]: Like a leaf carried off by the wind by Mark Strand. After leaving work, where he is not

03:46:36.480 --> 03:46:41.600
[Amit Varma]: known and where his job is a mystery even to himself. He walks down dimly lit streets and

03:46:41.600 --> 03:46:46.880
[Amit Varma]: dark alleys to his room at the other end of town in the rear of a rundown apartment house.

03:46:46.880 --> 03:46:50.480
[Amit Varma]: It is winter and he walks hunched over with the collar of his coat turned up.

03:46:50.480 --> 03:46:55.200
[Amit Varma]: When he gets to his room, he sits at a small table and looks at the book open before him.

03:46:55.200 --> 03:46:59.040
[Amit Varma]: Its pages are blank, which is why he is able to gaze at them for hours.

03:47:00.320 --> 03:47:07.760
[Amit Varma]: And I'll finally read out a third one and this is called Harmony in the Boudoir by Mark Strand.

03:47:07.760 --> 03:47:12.000
[Amit Varma]: After years of marriage, he stands at the foot of the bed and tells his wife that she will never

03:47:12.000 --> 03:47:17.120
[Amit Varma]: know him, that for everything he says there is more that he does not say, that behind each word

03:47:17.120 --> 03:47:22.880
[Amit Varma]: he utters there is another word and hundreds more behind that one. All those unsaid words, he says,

03:47:22.880 --> 03:47:27.440
[Amit Varma]: contain his true self, which has been betrayed by the superficial self before her.

03:47:27.440 --> 03:47:32.320
[Amit Varma]: So you see, he says, kicking off his slippers, I am more than what I have led you to believe.

03:47:33.280 --> 03:47:38.160
[Amit Varma]: Oh, you silly man, says his wife. Of course you are. I find that just thinking of you having so

03:47:38.160 --> 03:47:43.840
[Amit Varma]: many selves receding into nothingness is very exciting, that you barely exist as you are,

03:47:43.840 --> 03:47:47.680
[Amit Varma]: couldn't please me more. And what was the third kind of book?

03:47:47.680 --> 03:47:52.480
[Guest]: I was about to ask you, the third question is one that enthralled you as pure entertainment,

03:47:52.480 --> 03:47:55.200
[Guest]: perhaps a novel or a biography or something like that.

03:47:56.000 --> 03:48:00.880
[Amit Varma]: Fascinating. I mean, as a biography, I love The Power Broker by Robert Caro,

03:48:01.600 --> 03:48:07.200
[Amit Varma]: but not enthralling. It's very insightful and very interesting. I'd say I was sort of maybe,

03:48:08.160 --> 03:48:13.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, enthralled by Lord of the Rings, for example, which is, you know, great fantasy and

03:48:13.520 --> 03:48:18.960
[Amit Varma]: just a world building and everything. And that's a favorite of so many people. And I guess growing

03:48:18.960 --> 03:48:24.640
[Amit Varma]: up, it's one of those books you remember for, you know, the ways in which it enthralls you.

03:48:24.640 --> 03:48:30.800
[Amit Varma]: And I guess at the moment, I'll pick that, you know, at a later point in time, I will sort of

03:48:30.800 --> 03:48:37.360
[Amit Varma]: regret not mentioning, I'm sure so many other books. But yeah, I would say that that certainly

03:48:37.360 --> 03:48:42.960
[Guest]: did enthrall me. Now there are more and more questions on books. So I'm going to ask you,

03:48:42.960 --> 03:48:48.080
[Guest]: Sukhada Choudhury's question next, right, because this is also book related.

03:48:48.880 --> 03:48:56.000
[Unknown]: Hi, Amit. This is Sukhada. I've been a big fan of your podcast and big congratulations

03:48:56.000 --> 03:49:02.640
[Unknown]: on completing 200 episodes of this fabulous show. And the question that I want to ask you is,

03:49:03.440 --> 03:49:08.480
[Unknown]: if you could make sure that everyone in the world could read just one book,

03:49:08.480 --> 03:49:13.760
[Unknown]: which book would that be? Would love to know your answer. Thanks so much and all the best.

03:49:14.640 --> 03:49:23.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, great question. Again, a difficult question, just one book. Yeah, I must say,

03:49:24.640 --> 03:49:28.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, she's a fan of the show in the sense she's a supporter of the show. She keeps

03:49:28.240 --> 03:49:33.120
[Amit Varma]: retweeting all my episodes and has kind words to say about them. I haven't really interacted

03:49:33.120 --> 03:49:37.520
[Amit Varma]: much with her. I think I've just met her once. She organized a Vidarbha Lit Fest earlier this year at

03:49:37.520 --> 03:49:43.200
[Amit Varma]: Nagpur where I went and where I, in fact, met a number of authors who subsequently figured on my

03:49:43.200 --> 03:49:48.560
[Amit Varma]: show, like, you know, Madhavi Menon in that episode about the secret history of desire in

03:49:48.560 --> 03:49:55.680
[Amit Varma]: India, which was great. And, you know, I met Rajat Ubekar there. So yeah, so over a period of time,

03:49:55.680 --> 03:49:59.520
[Amit Varma]: I've taken three or four guests from that festival. Good question. It's also a very

03:49:59.520 --> 03:50:02.240
[Amit Varma]: sad question. Imagine a world where people could read just one book.

03:50:02.240 --> 03:50:07.520
[Guest]: You know, it's also a question that appreciates the opportunity cost of time if one had time just

03:50:07.520 --> 03:50:12.960
[Unknown]: to read one book. So I am with her on this and I'm going to corner you and make sure you don't

03:50:12.960 --> 03:50:17.600
[Amit Varma]: weasel your way out of it. No, no, I won't weasel. But I'll name more than one book because

03:50:17.600 --> 03:50:23.120
[Amit Varma]: there's more than one sort of dimension in which this can play out. And, you know,

03:50:23.120 --> 03:50:29.600
[Amit Varma]: in the realm of ideas, the book that immediately comes to mind is Bastia's The Law because of what,

03:50:29.600 --> 03:50:34.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, the relationship between the state and the individual and the principle stand that it

03:50:34.720 --> 03:50:39.760
[Amit Varma]: takes. But it's a difficult book to read. It's actually very simple, but the language is archaic.

03:50:39.760 --> 03:50:44.080
[Amit Varma]: So it's kind of difficult for that reason. I mean, one could also point out, you know,

03:50:44.080 --> 03:50:48.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, Adam Smith's, both his books, Theory of Moral Sentiments. And though, I mean,

03:50:48.480 --> 03:50:52.080
[Amit Varma]: if you don't have time to read both of them, you could maybe just read Russ Roberts's book on

03:50:52.080 --> 03:50:59.760
[Amit Varma]: Adam Smith. I love Orwell's essays, but I don't know what would be the value of reading them if

03:50:59.760 --> 03:51:06.320
[Amit Varma]: you read nothing else, because where do you get context from? Right. And similarly, you know,

03:51:07.040 --> 03:51:10.960
[Amit Varma]: I wouldn't recommend Mark Stantz's poem if it is the only book in the world, because again,

03:51:10.960 --> 03:51:16.000
[Amit Varma]: there is no, you know, your taste would not have built up to the point where you could appreciate

03:51:16.000 --> 03:51:22.080
[Amit Varma]: it, perhaps it would just. So it's a tough question. I think, you know, I don't know,

03:51:22.080 --> 03:51:28.400
[Amit Varma]: maybe just, yeah. So in nonfiction, like I said, you know, maybe Bastia's Law, maybe Orwell,

03:51:28.400 --> 03:51:33.360
[Amit Varma]: I don't know. In fiction, you could go to Orwell, you could go to something like 1984 or Animal Farm,

03:51:33.360 --> 03:51:40.560
[Amit Varma]: which also are in their own ways, books of ideas and books that kind of contain a lot of

03:51:40.560 --> 03:51:44.800
[Amit Varma]: truth about the world. But I mean, depending on how one is feeling, one could come up with,

03:51:44.800 --> 03:51:50.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, a bunch of different answers. But I can't think of a satisfactory single answer

03:51:50.240 --> 03:51:55.600
[Amit Varma]: for fiction, because the joy of fiction is that with every book, you enter a different world and

03:51:55.600 --> 03:52:01.280
[Amit Varma]: enter other people's lives. And all of it collectively, just increases your empathy and

03:52:01.280 --> 03:52:07.840
[Amit Varma]: makes you a better person. I mean, some book, like if somebody read only one book, you have

03:52:07.840 --> 03:52:12.320
[Amit Varma]: to give them a book, which is also easy enough to read. So I would think... But it's not somebody,

03:52:12.320 --> 03:52:17.600
[Guest]: right? She's asking if everybody in the world could read just one book. So there is a shared

03:52:17.600 --> 03:52:20.560
[Guest]: context, I think, in her question, unless I'm reading too much into it.

03:52:20.560 --> 03:52:25.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but the point is, there are many books, which are great books. But if people haven't

03:52:25.360 --> 03:52:30.000
[Amit Varma]: read any other book, it doesn't have the same impact. Maybe something like A Curious Incident

03:52:30.000 --> 03:52:37.440
[Amit Varma]: of the Dog in the Nighttime by Mark Haddon, which is a delightful book about a specially able child

03:52:37.440 --> 03:52:44.160
[Amit Varma]: solving the murder mystery of his dog, and just beautiful writing. And that also gives you a sense

03:52:44.160 --> 03:52:49.760
[Amit Varma]: of how you can enter someone's else's head and see the world differently, and yet is written in

03:52:49.760 --> 03:52:55.920
[Amit Varma]: simple enough language that everyone can get it. So that's one sort of book that comes to mind.

03:52:55.920 --> 03:53:01.600
[Amit Varma]: But you know, you get the fundamental difficulty with the question. And also, perhaps this is my

03:53:01.600 --> 03:53:08.080
[Amit Varma]: shortcoming that I read so much that I am simply unable to imagine what it must be like to not

03:53:08.080 --> 03:53:14.480
[Amit Varma]: have read anything. It's somewhat like, you know, Thomas Nagel wrote this famous essay about what

03:53:14.480 --> 03:53:20.480
[Amit Varma]: it is to see like a bat. And, you know, which makes a philosophical point that some experiences

03:53:20.480 --> 03:53:28.720
[Amit Varma]: are so outside of our realm that we cannot even imagine what it must be like. So yeah, I mean,

03:53:28.720 --> 03:53:32.720
[Amit Varma]: I think I've kind of edged, but I hope Sukrata will forgive me.

03:53:32.720 --> 03:53:37.760
[Guest]: I'm an economist. And if there was only I mean, I like you can't imagine a world where

03:53:37.760 --> 03:53:43.040
[Guest]: only one book could be read. But I would say Economics in One Lesson by Henry Hazlitt.

03:53:43.040 --> 03:53:47.840
[Guest]: If everybody in the world read that book, then 90% of the remaining economics books don't have

03:53:47.840 --> 03:53:52.720
[Amit Varma]: to be read in some sense. Right? Yeah. And that's, by the way, that's by the way,

03:53:52.720 --> 03:53:57.360
[Amit Varma]: a big book based on Bastia's essay, that which is seen and that which is not seen. So it ties

03:53:57.360 --> 03:54:01.520
[Guest]: in beautifully. It's a great book. It ties in beautifully. It's a great book. It's easy to read

03:54:01.520 --> 03:54:07.520
[Guest]: and, you know, economic imperialism all the way, at least for now for me.

03:54:09.280 --> 03:54:15.120
[Guest]: I have a couple more book related questions. So this is Subrat Mohanty. I don't want to say too

03:54:15.120 --> 03:54:22.160
[Guest]: much. I want to play the question first and then talk about it. Amit. Hi, this is Subrat here.

03:54:22.160 --> 03:54:26.400
[Unknown]: Long time listener. In fact, from the time you dropped your first episode.

03:54:27.600 --> 03:54:35.040
[Unknown]: Congratulations on the 200th episode. Here's my question for you. Why have more people read

03:54:35.600 --> 03:54:41.120
[Unknown]: Das Kapital than Road to Serfdom? Thanks and all the best for future.

03:54:41.120 --> 03:54:42.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, what a great question, isn't it?

03:54:43.600 --> 03:54:47.120
[Guest]: Yeah, so it's not about books, but about reading, which is also a subject on which

03:54:47.120 --> 03:54:52.640
[Guest]: is also a subject on which you have a lot of insight on how people read, how you read yourself,

03:54:52.640 --> 03:54:57.200
[Guest]: you know, how one should read to write better, and so on, so forth. So I think this is a good

03:54:57.200 --> 03:55:00.960
[Guest]: question of why, why the world has gravitated one way instead of another.

03:55:00.960 --> 03:55:04.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, Subrat, by the way, is a host of a brilliant podcast called Haal Chaal Theek

03:55:04.080 --> 03:55:10.240
[Amit Varma]: Tak Hai, which is a lovely podcast, which looks at Hindi films, and Hindi music and indeed,

03:55:10.240 --> 03:55:16.480
[Amit Varma]: our society itself at an earlier time. And I recommend everyone listens to that. Great

03:55:16.480 --> 03:55:21.280
[Amit Varma]: question. And I remember once when I was a teenager, and I remember this memory. And like I

03:55:21.280 --> 03:55:26.080
[Amit Varma]: said, my father had 1000s of books across ideologies and across genres and all of that.

03:55:26.080 --> 03:55:31.040
[Amit Varma]: So I remember once, I was meeting a bunch of friends in college. And in my bag, I took the

03:55:31.040 --> 03:55:35.120
[Amit Varma]: book Das Kapital, which he asked about because I thought it would be cool. I thought it was

03:55:35.120 --> 03:55:40.160
[Amit Varma]: fashionable, it would make me seem intellectual, and all of that when I was a very young kid.

03:55:40.160 --> 03:55:48.640
[Amit Varma]: Young teenager, and I think a lot of what draws us towards ideologies, as also ideological books

03:55:48.640 --> 03:55:54.160
[Amit Varma]: is the desire to fit in and you know, with a cool gang and to be seen as, you know, one of a

03:55:54.800 --> 03:56:00.640
[Amit Varma]: cool bunch of people and all of that, which is why we shall, you know, we will read Das Kapital

03:56:00.640 --> 03:56:06.800
[Amit Varma]: and we'll read Marx and we'll wear t shirts of the mass murdering. Yeah, Sheikh Guwahara,

03:56:06.800 --> 03:56:16.400
[Amit Varma]: which is which just repels me when I see someone wearing that t shirt. But yeah, so it's kind of

03:56:16.400 --> 03:56:21.440
[Amit Varma]: those social currents where you want to fit in with a cool bunch of people. And especially if

03:56:21.440 --> 03:56:26.320
[Amit Varma]: those cool bunch of people seem to be enlightened and they've read a lot and they're compassionate.

03:56:26.320 --> 03:56:32.080
[Amit Varma]: Though, you know, we have seen where compassion can lead society in the 20th century, that kind

03:56:32.080 --> 03:56:40.000
[Amit Varma]: of shallow stated compassion that remains at the level of intention. And I think that's a big reason

03:56:40.000 --> 03:56:46.960
[Amit Varma]: why some ideologies are so fashionable and others don't really take off. Also, I think a lot of

03:56:46.960 --> 03:56:54.880
[Amit Varma]: leftism appeals to simplistic ways of viewing the world, which are inbuilt in us. For example,

03:56:54.880 --> 03:57:01.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, zero sum thinking or thinking of, you know, the world in terms of adversaries

03:57:01.680 --> 03:57:06.560
[Amit Varma]: in an adversarial way that oh, then you know, the workers versus so and so and all of that.

03:57:06.560 --> 03:57:11.840
[Amit Varma]: And, and these sort of simplistic narratives that the way to get rid of poverty is that,

03:57:11.840 --> 03:57:17.120
[Amit Varma]: you know, just redistribute and, you know, all of that. And I can see why those are appealing.

03:57:17.680 --> 03:57:23.600
[Amit Varma]: And so I'm not really surprised why more people have read Das Kapital than, you know, Hayek's

03:57:23.600 --> 03:57:29.040
[Amit Varma]: books. And Hayek also writes in slightly dense language, but so does Marx, of course. And,

03:57:29.040 --> 03:57:34.160
[Amit Varma]: and, of course, I read Marx before I read Hayek, which, you know, tells you something about the

03:57:34.160 --> 03:57:38.800
[Amit Varma]: way the world is that many people will never even move to Hayek, which is why it's a responsibility

03:57:38.800 --> 03:57:44.560
[Amit Varma]: of those of us who read Hayek and, you know, find illumination in him to spread those ideas

03:57:44.560 --> 03:57:51.680
[Amit Varma]: in concrete terms and simple language. Because I think that there is a social cost to reading

03:57:51.680 --> 03:57:55.920
[Amit Varma]: the wrong books, there is a personal cost and a social cost to reading the wrong books.

03:57:55.920 --> 03:58:00.960
[Amit Varma]: And this is possibly the wrong time to sort of elaborate on that. But we are shaped by what we

03:58:00.960 --> 03:58:08.560
[Amit Varma]: read. And what we then become is what shapes society, if enough of us turn out that way.

03:58:09.200 --> 03:58:13.760
[Amit Varma]: No, and also the other thing to note is that besides Das Kapital, a book that has

03:58:13.760 --> 03:58:18.080
[Amit Varma]: been perennially on the bestseller list in India over the years is Mein Kampf by Hitler.

03:58:18.080 --> 03:58:22.560
[Amit Varma]: And you could also ask that that is another toxic, dangerous book. Why are people reading that? But

03:58:22.560 --> 03:58:27.600
[Amit Varma]: because one, because I suppose at some level is enthralling and two, because it speaks to simple

03:58:27.600 --> 03:58:32.480
[Amit Varma]: narratives that you need a strong leader. And all I mean, I used to hear these kind of arguments

03:58:32.480 --> 03:58:37.520
[Amit Varma]: back in the day that India needs a strong leader like that. And, you know, who can get things done

03:58:37.520 --> 03:58:42.320
[Amit Varma]: in the trains will run on time and you still hear arguments like that from people. So these are sort

03:58:42.320 --> 03:58:48.960
[Amit Varma]: of, you know, from different end from different ideological ends, both simplistic, both dangerous,

03:58:48.960 --> 03:58:53.680
[Amit Varma]: we have seen the damage they have caused in the 20th century with Stalin and Mao and, of course,

03:58:53.680 --> 03:59:00.480
[Amit Varma]: Hitler himself and so on and so forth. And both having commonalities in terms of having a simplistic

03:59:00.480 --> 03:59:06.480
[Amit Varma]: vision of the world and believing in the power of the state to shape society as you wish through

03:59:06.480 --> 03:59:12.720
[Amit Varma]: coercive action. And we, of course, haven't learned any lessons. And I think it also, I mean,

03:59:12.720 --> 03:59:17.520
[Guest]: the way the question was phrased, though, I know Subrata and Meena quite as literally,

03:59:17.520 --> 03:59:23.280
[Guest]: I'm not sure so many people have read Das Kapitala, right? It's like, most people think they

03:59:23.840 --> 03:59:29.600
[Guest]: understand the punchline or, you know, the Cliff Notes version of it. And I think that has a lot to

03:59:29.600 --> 03:59:34.960
[Guest]: do with, you know, this lovely article that Hayek wrote called intellectuals and socialism,

03:59:36.000 --> 03:59:43.760
[Guest]: where in a way, you know, the socialists managed to capture an intellectual elite class, who then

03:59:43.760 --> 03:59:48.080
[Guest]: furthered and propagated those ideas, probably for all the reasons that you mentioned, which is,

03:59:48.080 --> 03:59:53.760
[Guest]: you know, the simple narrative, the appeal to tribalism, the appeal to our base instincts of

03:59:53.760 --> 04:00:01.040
[Guest]: thinking in terms of zero sum and things, things like that. But the liberals have not quite as well,

04:00:01.840 --> 04:00:09.520
[Guest]: you know, penetrated the intellectual class, to then convert it into simpler messages,

04:00:09.520 --> 04:00:14.880
[Guest]: you know, which are easy to consume, easy to repeat, easy to turn into a proverb, and, you know,

04:00:15.520 --> 04:00:20.080
[Guest]: so on and so forth. So I think there is something to do with both the content,

04:00:20.080 --> 04:00:26.240
[Guest]: but also the messaging, and who's doing the messaging? I have another question, which is not

04:00:26.240 --> 04:00:31.600
[Amit Varma]: about... Before that, if I may interject, it's also, you know, this is similar of Piketty also,

04:00:31.600 --> 04:00:37.040
[Amit Varma]: that Piketty is very fashionable these days. Almost nobody has actually read Piketty.

04:00:37.040 --> 04:00:41.120
[Amit Varma]: But it's very fashionable, because it makes you seem both intellectual and compassionate at the

04:00:41.120 --> 04:00:46.160
[Amit Varma]: same time. And actually, the man is just profoundly wrong in so many different ways. But you don't

04:00:46.160 --> 04:00:49.760
[Amit Varma]: even want to enter into an argument about it with anyone, because it will seem like you,

04:00:49.760 --> 04:00:58.080
[Amit Varma]: who has no compassion for whatever and all of that. And I would, you know, before people start

04:00:58.080 --> 04:01:01.600
[Amit Varma]: arguing about Piketty with me, I would request them to actually read his full book, and then

04:01:01.600 --> 04:01:06.560
[Guest]: you come and talk. Yeah, I would also recommend they read, you know, Deirdre McCloskey and Phil

04:01:06.560 --> 04:01:11.920
[Guest]: Magnus' critique of the book, which is also not just a substantive critique, but also, you know,

04:01:11.920 --> 04:01:17.120
[Guest]: many issues with the data, and how the data is interpreted and analyzed and so on and so forth.

04:01:17.120 --> 04:01:24.160
[Guest]: Exactly. So now I have another question on books, but this is not about your favorite book.

04:01:25.040 --> 04:01:32.080
[Guest]: This question comes from Ram Guha. Again, one of our, you know, probably favorite writers, thinkers,

04:01:32.080 --> 04:01:38.880
[Guest]: historians, I mean, again, someone who has multitudes, just, I mean, right now, I'm

04:01:38.880 --> 04:01:43.520
[Guest]: excited about Guha for a completely different reason. I was reading something that he had

04:01:43.520 --> 04:01:49.680
[Guest]: written on, you know, forest nationalization and forest rights of tribals. And my husband

04:01:50.800 --> 04:01:54.960
[Guest]: is incredibly excited about Guha, because he's coming out with a new book on cricket,

04:01:54.960 --> 04:02:00.240
[Guest]: right. And in this household, that I think there are very few intellectual figures who

04:02:00.240 --> 04:02:07.120
[Guest]: excite both of us in equal measure on dimensions which are so far apart. So thanks to you. And

04:02:07.120 --> 04:02:14.880
[Guest]: thanks to the 200th episode, I got to say hello to Ram Guha on zoom during the pandemic. And,

04:02:14.880 --> 04:02:20.960
[Guest]: you know, get to ask this question. So I'm first going to play the question and then

04:02:20.960 --> 04:02:26.640
[Unknown]: talk to you more about it. Hi, Abit, this is Ram Guha. And I'm here to wish you on

04:02:26.640 --> 04:02:32.720
[Unknown]: the splendid anniversary of your fabulous program, and to request you to please write

04:02:32.720 --> 04:02:39.440
[Unknown]: accessible book on the relevance of C. Rajagopalachari. You do not have to be a Tamil,

04:02:39.440 --> 04:02:43.760
[Unknown]: you do not need to learn Tamil, you need to understand economics, politics and have an

04:02:43.760 --> 04:02:49.440
[Unknown]: independent point of view, which is exactly what you have. And we need to rescue Rajaji

04:02:49.440 --> 04:02:53.600
[Unknown]: from the fundus who are claiming him as one of their own. So please do it, Abit.

04:02:53.600 --> 04:02:58.640
[Amit Varma]: Please do it, Abit. What a magnificent question and a difficult request.

04:03:00.080 --> 04:03:06.880
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I am possibly not capable of writing a biography. And, you know, and there are so many

04:03:06.880 --> 04:03:11.920
[Amit Varma]: books that have yet been unwritten, the written and the unwritten could be, you know, the story

04:03:11.920 --> 04:03:16.960
[Amit Varma]: of my life, except the first part of that would be very scant, that there are just so many things

04:03:16.960 --> 04:03:21.840
[Amit Varma]: that I want to write, but I'm getting to but I agree with Ram that, you know, Rajaji needs to

04:03:21.840 --> 04:03:30.480
[Amit Varma]: to have a nuanced, deep biography written on him by, you know, someone who is apart from those

04:03:30.480 --> 04:03:34.560
[Amit Varma]: who claim him these days. I mean, it's really tragic to see what has happened, you know,

04:03:34.560 --> 04:03:40.640
[Amit Varma]: the magazine he once founded Swarajya being the filthy rag that it is today. And it's tragic,

04:03:40.640 --> 04:03:46.080
[Amit Varma]: but yeah, and again, it's it's kind of awesome to have to actually have someone like Ram Guha

04:03:46.080 --> 04:03:51.600
[Guest]: ask you a question. I mean, he's asking more than a question. He's asking you to write a book.

04:03:51.600 --> 04:03:56.960
[Amit Varma]: I think that's an even higher level compliment. Yeah, yeah, no, I would you know, I'm going to

04:03:56.960 --> 04:04:02.080
[Amit Varma]: pass the parcel on to my readers and say that this is something that I agree with Ram that it would

04:04:02.080 --> 04:04:08.320
[Amit Varma]: be great if somebody did it. So if one of you is up to it, you know, we have had a lot of great

04:04:08.320 --> 04:04:13.520
[Amit Varma]: biographers on my show talk about their methods of work and all of that. So take inspiration from

04:04:13.520 --> 04:04:23.040
[Guest]: some of that and go do it. I do, however, think that, you know, I think one incredible sort of

04:04:23.040 --> 04:04:31.520
[Guest]: talent that Ram Guha has is to boil down an entire cultural moment into a single question. I mean,

04:04:31.520 --> 04:04:38.160
[Guest]: something that might seem like an innocuous podcast question. But what Ram is saying is

04:04:38.160 --> 04:04:44.880
[Guest]: like a critique on the entire right wing intellectual movement that's going on right

04:04:44.880 --> 04:04:49.040
[Unknown]: now. Right. So that is also one of my favorite things about him. So what is said and what is

04:04:49.040 --> 04:04:55.280
[Guest]: unsaid could be another way to think about that. And I think Pratap has the same quality, you know,

04:04:55.280 --> 04:05:01.520
[Guest]: Ram Guha has the same quality. They're able to think and capture these big ideas and big

04:05:01.520 --> 04:05:07.600
[Guest]: sort of cultural, political life moments and, you know, turn them into something like a question for

04:05:07.600 --> 04:05:14.480
[Guest]: Amit Verma to write a book on Rajaji. No, I mean, Ram has so many great insights and

04:05:14.480 --> 04:05:20.080
[Amit Varma]: thankfully he's one of those public intellectuals who keeps writing columns regularly and not just

04:05:20.080 --> 04:05:24.720
[Amit Varma]: withdrawing to a shell in the face of severe criticism from both sides. And that makes me so

04:05:24.720 --> 04:05:30.720
[Amit Varma]: sad. I mean, one, it does make me sad that one of the things that the troll farms of the BJP

04:05:30.720 --> 04:05:36.000
[Amit Varma]: the BJP did after they came to power was that they sort of, you know, demonize Ram Guha and

04:05:36.000 --> 04:05:42.080
[Amit Varma]: made him out to be, you know, a liberal historian who was against the Hindu cause and just whatever,

04:05:42.080 --> 04:05:47.040
[Amit Varma]: which is a complete misreading of his great body of work. None of these people have read his books

04:05:47.040 --> 04:05:51.440
[Amit Varma]: and to paint him in that manner was really tragic. And what has also happened after that is

04:05:51.440 --> 04:05:55.920
[Amit Varma]: that today you'll have, you know, woke liberals on Twitter also ranting about Ram for different

04:05:55.920 --> 04:06:00.160
[Amit Varma]: reasons. One of which of course is his contempt for the Gandhi family, which I entirely share

04:06:00.160 --> 04:06:04.800
[Amit Varma]: and which we discussed on the show, I think in the Republic Day episode that we did at the start

04:06:04.800 --> 04:06:10.080
[Amit Varma]: of the year. And, and that's really tragic because this is a great story and a great thinker of our

04:06:10.080 --> 04:06:16.640
[Amit Varma]: times and a very nuanced thinker. So, you know, obviously both ideological tribes will reduce

04:06:16.640 --> 04:06:22.560
[Amit Varma]: the world to a binary and anybody who doesn't fit that binary is by default, you know, a bad person,

04:06:22.560 --> 04:06:27.600
[Amit Varma]: a bad thinker or whatever. And it's sad, but his books sell well. And I hope that, you know, and

04:06:27.600 --> 04:06:32.640
[Amit Varma]: I'm sure that, you know, within that silent majority, which is not part of the barking dogs

04:06:32.640 --> 04:06:38.560
[Amit Varma]: of Twitter, you know, Ram has enough people who have the same sort of admiration and reverence

04:06:38.560 --> 04:06:43.840
[Guest]: for him that, you know, you and I do. You know, another thing here is we talked about this a

04:06:43.840 --> 04:06:48.320
[Guest]: little bit earlier when we were talking about intellectual influences and how, you know,

04:06:48.320 --> 04:06:54.160
[Guest]: partly because the, our, you know, school curriculum is so heavily, you know, got this,

04:06:54.160 --> 04:07:00.560
[Guest]: this colonial hangover, you know, sort of thing. We don't read whether it is in literature,

04:07:00.560 --> 04:07:06.080
[Guest]: whether it is non-fiction, we don't read too many of our own, you know, Indian voices,

04:07:06.080 --> 04:07:13.520
[Guest]: Indian thoughts, Indian letter. Right. And I think one thing that India after Gandhi did

04:07:13.520 --> 04:07:20.640
[Guest]: was it just cracked that wide open. Right. It made me at least understand, and I'm a keen

04:07:20.640 --> 04:07:25.440
[Guest]: reader of history. I mean, I'd already almost finished law school by then. You know, the,

04:07:25.440 --> 04:07:29.840
[Guest]: I remember having this conversation with my husband, I'd given him the book, you know,

04:07:29.840 --> 04:07:34.640
[Guest]: so it was, I think, one of the first presents that I gave him. It had released in India,

04:07:34.640 --> 04:07:38.640
[Guest]: but it hadn't released in London. So when I was going to see him, I got the book for him.

04:07:38.640 --> 04:07:42.720
[Guest]: And he said, I had no idea all this happened during the emergency. Right. I, on the other

04:07:42.720 --> 04:07:47.200
[Guest]: hand, had been to law school. And, you know, I knew a lot of it from the litigation point of view,

04:07:47.200 --> 04:07:54.240
[Guest]: but I had no idea what was going on in Nagaland, for instance. Right. And just cracking that open,

04:07:54.240 --> 04:08:00.640
[Guest]: you know, talking about Indian events and Indian intellectual thought from the point of view of

04:08:00.640 --> 04:08:06.800
[Guest]: what was going on with our people. I don't think anyone has done that better, you know, than Ram.

04:08:06.800 --> 04:08:12.480
[Guest]: And in one sense, I hope that, you know, the silent majority and like the lots of people

04:08:12.480 --> 04:08:19.280
[Guest]: who buy and read his books, we are able to create a culture of, you know, Indian thought and writing.

04:08:19.280 --> 04:08:23.040
[Guest]: Now, it doesn't have to be liberal, it doesn't have to be centrist, it doesn't have to be right

04:08:23.040 --> 04:08:28.400
[Guest]: wing. It could be all sorts of things, because India also contains multitudes, right. But I think

04:08:28.400 --> 04:08:33.440
[Guest]: that is a critical piece. And I think that's also where his question is coming from, which is in

04:08:33.440 --> 04:08:39.840
[Guest]: this homegrown intellectual thought or tradition, you know, Rajaji is an incredibly important member.

04:08:39.840 --> 04:08:46.240
[Guest]: And if your listeners are interested in looking for their next book project, maybe one of them

04:08:46.240 --> 04:08:51.280
[Amit Varma]: could write it. No, and more than that, I'd say that, you know, the significance of Ram Goha

04:08:51.280 --> 04:08:56.640
[Amit Varma]: himself, let's leave aside Rajagopalachari for the moment. The significance of Ram Goha himself is,

04:08:56.640 --> 04:09:00.640
[Amit Varma]: I think, something that perhaps he himself would not be aware of, because in a sense,

04:09:01.440 --> 04:09:07.280
[Amit Varma]: his books are like a gateway drug for so many people into reading history, into caring about

04:09:07.280 --> 04:09:12.320
[Amit Varma]: history. You know, would a great historian like Srinath Raghavan, for example, have less readers

04:09:12.320 --> 04:09:17.760
[Amit Varma]: if Ram Goha did not exist? The answer clearly is yes. Maybe Srinath himself would be a different

04:09:17.760 --> 04:09:24.720
[Amit Varma]: kind of writer if, you know, part of that way wasn't sort of laid out for him before that.

04:09:25.520 --> 04:09:30.640
[Amit Varma]: And that's important. And this, you know, things like the books like what Ram writes can then have

04:09:30.640 --> 04:09:35.920
[Amit Varma]: a domino effect on future historians or would be historians or people who would not have thought

04:09:35.920 --> 04:09:41.520
[Amit Varma]: of themselves as possible historians, but who like good stories and who like reading about the past,

04:09:41.520 --> 04:09:47.120
[Amit Varma]: suddenly reading, you know, something historical written by Ram and saying that, damn, this is so

04:09:47.120 --> 04:09:51.760
[Amit Varma]: exciting. I need more of this. And then they read more and then they want to write more and all of

04:09:51.760 --> 04:09:57.200
[Amit Varma]: that. And these are all unseen effects, which will, you know, play out across generations.

04:09:57.200 --> 04:10:02.960
[Amit Varma]: And one may never know where it kind of ends up. And I wish more people express their admiration

04:10:02.960 --> 04:10:08.400
[Amit Varma]: for him, you know, on Twitter and elsewhere, rather than the sort of vituperative space that

04:10:08.400 --> 04:10:12.560
[Amit Varma]: it's become. And forgive me, I keep going back to that, but it's just disturbing that I know that

04:10:12.560 --> 04:10:17.440
[Amit Varma]: I know people like, you know, Ram and Barkha Dutt and all of those probably ignored their

04:10:17.440 --> 04:10:23.200
[Amit Varma]: Twitter notifications completely. But it just disturbs me to see the amount of sort of abuse

04:10:23.200 --> 04:10:28.400
[Amit Varma]: and hatred that they get that what is wrong with us as a society when we cannot, you know,

04:10:28.400 --> 04:10:33.840
[Guest]: cherish people who do such remarkable work? Yeah. And on this, I think both the left and the right

04:10:34.560 --> 04:10:39.280
[Guest]: are pretty similar. Maybe the left has slightly better grammar and punctuation,

04:10:39.920 --> 04:10:44.400
[Guest]: their hate and vitriol on Twitter, but I think they're about the same. I think this is where

04:10:44.400 --> 04:10:49.280
[Guest]: conversations like yours and people like you and Russ, you know, things like that. I don't know

04:10:49.280 --> 04:10:54.720
[Guest]: if you've noticed this, but all the people we've talked about, you know, who've asked the question,

04:10:54.720 --> 04:10:58.800
[Guest]: I mean, one of the first few things we've said about every one of them is how kind and wonderful

04:10:58.800 --> 04:11:03.760
[Guest]: they are. Right. And we're not just doing this as platitudes. A lot of these people I, you know,

04:11:03.760 --> 04:11:09.680
[Guest]: we know them. When I come to India, I have lunch with you and Prem. And you know, like, we're

04:11:09.680 --> 04:11:15.200
[Guest]: talking about you, me, Prem and Pranay at a table together is one of the nicest conversations,

04:11:15.200 --> 04:11:19.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, that I've ever had. I've immediately remembered those dosas that we had at MTR,

04:11:19.680 --> 04:11:25.680
[Guest]: right? Wasn't it in Bangalore? At MTR. Oh, my God, that was so good. I just, I think I killed

04:11:25.680 --> 04:11:33.040
[Amit Varma]: your keto. And I'm not on keto. I'm not on keto, as you can probably see. I envy Bangalore people

04:11:33.040 --> 04:11:39.680
[Amit Varma]: for that reason. You have MTR, you have Blossoms and you have Ram Guha. Speaking of that, you know,

04:11:39.680 --> 04:11:46.800
[Unknown]: migration is always a possibility. Since we started with that theme. I have two more, you know,

04:11:46.800 --> 04:11:52.320
[Guest]: I mean, this I know we're like way past breaking classic scene and the unseen episode records.

04:11:53.120 --> 04:12:00.480
[Guest]: But I have a couple more sort of, you know, broad themes. One is just something you and I have

04:12:00.480 --> 04:12:06.800
[Guest]: talked about more recently, as we have grown older, which is gratitude. Right. And so I mean,

04:12:06.800 --> 04:12:11.600
[Guest]: I should just say out there, I'm very grateful to have the opportunity to do this. But I'm

04:12:11.600 --> 04:12:17.520
[Guest]: particularly grateful, you know, all the guests and everyone I wrote to just instantly said,

04:12:17.520 --> 04:12:22.320
[Guest]: Oh, my God, this is such a wonderful idea. Some of them took a little bit extra glee in saying,

04:12:22.320 --> 04:12:26.320
[Guest]: finally, Amit will get to know how hard it is to be a guest and answer questions.

04:12:26.880 --> 04:12:32.800
[Guest]: All of them sent their questions really promptly. Your sound engineer and producer Vijay Doipade,

04:12:32.800 --> 04:12:38.000
[Guest]: I think I've just like, I think I've traumatized him. You know, if he quits after this,

04:12:38.000 --> 04:12:45.440
[Amit Varma]: I apologize. But he has been wonderful. He could quit because he's my editor. There's no sound

04:12:45.440 --> 04:12:50.320
[Amit Varma]: engineer per se, because we are recording remotely ourselves. And I'm the producer.

04:12:50.320 --> 04:12:54.880
[Amit Varma]: But he's the editor. And as I mentioned in the introduction, a lot of the shaping of the show

04:12:54.880 --> 04:13:01.760
[Amit Varma]: and the fact that, you know, it sounds, you know, as good as it does. And it's also smooth is all

04:13:01.760 --> 04:13:06.400
[Amit Varma]: because of Vijay. So yeah, credit to him. But sorry, I had to interrupt. Yeah, I have to add

04:13:06.400 --> 04:13:12.160
[Guest]: on this episode, he's also the sound engineer, because, you know, so many different clips,

04:13:12.160 --> 04:13:17.760
[Guest]: all in different formats, all with different levels and volumes. And I just I'm very, very

04:13:17.760 --> 04:13:24.880
[Guest]: thankful to Vijay for doing this. I'm incredibly grateful to all the guests and fans who responded

04:13:24.880 --> 04:13:30.240
[Guest]: so warmly, and sent in questions. And I kept asking for lots of questions, because I thought,

04:13:30.240 --> 04:13:35.760
[Guest]: you know, we have so much time. But as always, there are more ideas and thoughts and interesting

04:13:35.760 --> 04:13:40.720
[Guest]: conversation than there is time. So, you know, we've, we've sort of covered all of it. But more

04:13:40.720 --> 04:13:46.480
[Guest]: generally, one of the things I have, I have personally experienced being a guest on your show,

04:13:46.480 --> 04:13:53.280
[Guest]: and I'm incredibly grateful for is two things. I have never had the kind of engagement that I get

04:13:53.280 --> 04:14:00.240
[Guest]: from your listeners to pretty much anything else that I do. Right? I write academic papers, which

04:14:00.240 --> 04:14:05.280
[Guest]: we all know nobody reads, right? I write columns, which people read, but you know, it's a very quick

04:14:05.280 --> 04:14:11.360
[Guest]: and dirty, sometimes not even past the headline or the first couple of paragraphs. I've had I have

04:14:11.360 --> 04:14:17.920
[Guest]: students who pay money to listen to me and learn from me, but not all of them are quite as engaged.

04:14:17.920 --> 04:14:21.440
[Guest]: But there is something incredible about your listeners. And obviously, there's a selection

04:14:21.440 --> 04:14:26.800
[Guest]: bias here, because only the most engaged reach out. But their questions are so penetrating. They

04:14:26.800 --> 04:14:34.480
[Guest]: are so, you know, they're critical, but they are so civil. They're really like a model in my mind

04:14:34.480 --> 04:14:39.840
[Guest]: of, you know, how discourse should be conducted. I think the way you conduct your discourse has a

04:14:39.840 --> 04:14:45.440
[Guest]: lot to do with how your listeners respond. But I have, you know, immense gratitude for the

04:14:45.440 --> 04:14:51.680
[Guest]: engagement from your listeners. And the second is the love. I mean, they are just ridiculous. I, I'm

04:14:51.680 --> 04:14:58.000
[Guest]: both envious and also still quite astounded because when people are that sort of profuse in their

04:14:58.000 --> 04:15:03.920
[Guest]: praise and warmth, I'm always like, wait a second. I mean, what do they want? Or what is going on

04:15:03.920 --> 04:15:09.920
[Guest]: here? Is this normal? This just feels very awkward and uncomfortable. But I wanted to talk to you a

04:15:09.920 --> 04:15:15.440
[Guest]: little bit about that. How, you know, what are you grateful for? Now that you do the show, I know how

04:15:15.440 --> 04:15:22.160
[Guest]: much work it is to put it together. But I also know that you feel so happy and so much gratitude

04:15:22.160 --> 04:15:23.360
[Guest]: for how it's turned out.

04:15:23.360 --> 04:15:29.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, two things. I mean, one, of course, to begin with gratitude towards my guests that

04:15:29.120 --> 04:15:33.680
[Amit Varma]: they trust me, that they trust me to come on the show. They are generous with their time and their

04:15:33.680 --> 04:15:38.240
[Amit Varma]: insights. And it's okay, you and I were friends before and people who've come on the show have

04:15:38.240 --> 04:15:42.080
[Amit Varma]: come on the show have been friends. But there are many people who don't know me from Adam, who will

04:15:42.080 --> 04:15:47.840
[Amit Varma]: still come on the show, and who will still sit and they will still speak with intellectual honesty,

04:15:47.840 --> 04:15:55.120
[Amit Varma]: assuming goodwill, in good faith, and have that kind of conversation that is so enriching. So

04:15:55.120 --> 04:15:59.840
[Amit Varma]: obviously, you know, that that's part of the whole thing that you're trusting yourself in the hands

04:15:59.840 --> 04:16:05.360
[Amit Varma]: of a stranger, in a sense. And that's, you know, one essential thing, which is actually one reason

04:16:05.360 --> 04:16:11.440
[Amit Varma]: why I've sort of taken it easy on having foreign guests, because I could, you know, write to

04:16:11.440 --> 04:16:15.280
[Amit Varma]: foreign guests and get them, but they may not know me, they may not have heard that show. So that

04:16:15.280 --> 04:16:20.800
[Amit Varma]: same level of trust isn't there, it can become a bit like a q&a, which, you know, a couple of

04:16:20.800 --> 04:16:26.480
[Amit Varma]: episodes in the distant past have have gone that way. And it just doesn't feel like that relaxed

04:16:26.480 --> 04:16:32.640
[Amit Varma]: conversation. So I feel much more comfortable doing an episode with someone who's probably,

04:16:32.640 --> 04:16:36.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, heard me at some point, or at least heard of me or is willing to take that step and

04:16:36.800 --> 04:16:42.640
[Amit Varma]: maybe listen to an episode or, you know, engage. So that's great. And the other thing, obviously,

04:16:42.640 --> 04:16:46.960
[Amit Varma]: is like you said, the listeners, the listeners are incredible, and I don't even know what to say. And

04:16:46.960 --> 04:16:50.640
[Amit Varma]: like you said, one of the things is not just the depth of engagement, and very often, they'll

04:16:50.640 --> 04:16:56.240
[Amit Varma]: disagree with me, but they'll be very polite. I mean, it's a you understand the dual meaning of

04:16:56.240 --> 04:17:02.160
[Amit Varma]: the term civil society, that they are just neatly Yeah, that they're just so polite. And you know,

04:17:02.160 --> 04:17:06.240
[Amit Varma]: when they're engaging with you on Twitter, it seems like it seems like a world within a world

04:17:06.240 --> 04:17:11.680
[Amit Varma]: because Twitter is otherwise so shouty and adversarial and all of that. And then you have

04:17:11.680 --> 04:17:17.520
[Amit Varma]: this sort of very polite, reasoned engagement from folks, which I really value. I mean, the

04:17:17.520 --> 04:17:21.600
[Amit Varma]: one thing I block for on Twitter is actually rudeness. Anyone is rude, I just block them.

04:17:22.560 --> 04:17:27.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, and but, you know, so many of the listeners and they'll disagree with me and

04:17:27.440 --> 04:17:32.240
[Amit Varma]: they'll say they disagree and they'll say where they disagree and whatever. And they're just so

04:17:32.240 --> 04:17:36.800
[Amit Varma]: polite. And, and it's also kind of struck me that, you know, since I opened up support for,

04:17:37.440 --> 04:17:41.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, when I asked people to buy me a cup of coffee from April onwards, if they enjoyed listening

04:17:41.680 --> 04:17:46.080
[Amit Varma]: to an episode of the show, so many people were so generous. And I just want to say here that,

04:17:46.080 --> 04:17:50.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, I didn't have time to sort of, I couldn't write to each of them in person and

04:17:50.560 --> 04:17:55.920
[Amit Varma]: thank them for it. But also, because I procrastinate, and I'm really bad at this stuff and

04:17:55.920 --> 04:18:00.640
[Amit Varma]: email and all that. And I have literally 1000s of 100 emails and all of that. But I was blown

04:18:00.640 --> 04:18:06.480
[Amit Varma]: away by it. It's really been enough to keep the show independent. And I appreciate that, because

04:18:06.480 --> 04:18:11.440
[Amit Varma]: that means I don't have to, I don't have to tailor it for anybody else. But just keep going in the

04:18:11.440 --> 04:18:15.760
[Amit Varma]: directions that I want to go. And like this episode, I think is already well over four hours.

04:18:15.760 --> 04:18:19.520
[Amit Varma]: And I can do this, no one's going to say, you know, no one's going to come up with old fangled

04:18:19.520 --> 04:18:26.960
[Amit Varma]: notions of who listens to something so long. And all of that. So yeah, so I'm kind of, you know,

04:18:27.760 --> 04:18:32.960
[Amit Varma]: I'm just, in a sense, grateful to even beyond these two categories of people to guests and

04:18:32.960 --> 04:18:38.160
[Amit Varma]: listeners to, to just dumb luck that's brought me in a situation where I've discovered something

04:18:38.160 --> 04:18:43.440
[Amit Varma]: that gives me satisfaction and that I'm enjoying for however long it lasts. I mean, I've reached

04:18:43.440 --> 04:18:49.040
[Amit Varma]: 200. And I think one of the questions said, may you do hundreds more. And I don't think it's going

04:18:49.040 --> 04:18:54.000
[Amit Varma]: to happen. But it's nice to get this far and to feel that I'm still part of the journey. And,

04:18:54.000 --> 04:18:58.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, while putting together my course for podcasting, I started thinking deeper about it and

04:18:58.880 --> 04:19:03.280
[Amit Varma]: realized that I'm still learning so much about it. And then that makes it so exciting. And that

04:19:03.840 --> 04:19:07.760
[Amit Varma]: one can kind of go ahead and do that. Yeah, but that that's, that's broadly,

04:19:08.640 --> 04:19:12.960
[Guest]: you know, on gratitude, I know you are grateful to your guests, but there's something incredible

04:19:12.960 --> 04:19:16.480
[Guest]: you've done for the community, right? I spoke about this before a little bit,

04:19:16.480 --> 04:19:21.120
[Guest]: you've cracked open an audience for a policy podcast, right? Things that people thought

04:19:21.120 --> 04:19:25.120
[Guest]: were just impossible, you yourself thought anything longer than 20 minutes is going to,

04:19:25.120 --> 04:19:30.400
[Guest]: you know, just not work. And you are brave enough to experiment, right? You're brave enough to put

04:19:30.400 --> 04:19:34.320
[Guest]: it out there and say, I'm going to do this. And let's see if it works. Or if it doesn't work,

04:19:34.320 --> 04:19:40.640
[Guest]: I'll change it. And so that is incredible. And what you've done is you've created a very keen

04:19:40.640 --> 04:19:45.840
[Guest]: listening audience, which is different from a keen reading audience, right? It's a little bit

04:19:45.840 --> 04:19:51.360
[Guest]: different. And there's a lot of overlap. But you've created this entire space for policy podcasts,

04:19:51.360 --> 04:19:56.160
[Guest]: and whether it is Pawan, who's been a guest on your show, whether it's Pranay, you know,

04:19:56.160 --> 04:20:02.880
[Guest]: whether it is Hamsini, myself, Srinath, Pooja Mehra, we've all launched our own podcast,

04:20:02.880 --> 04:20:09.520
[Guest]: I'm sure I'm missing a few people. And so much of our initial audience has come from the seen

04:20:09.520 --> 04:20:14.400
[Guest]: and the unseen, or because of some recall value, right? That, oh, I heard them on the seen and the

04:20:14.400 --> 04:20:18.880
[Guest]: unseen, and I enjoyed that episode. And I would love to listen to them. And in that sense, you

04:20:18.880 --> 04:20:26.080
[Guest]: know, you really are sort of a model for how to create a market, how to expand it. And it also

04:20:26.080 --> 04:20:30.640
[Guest]: takes generosity and mentorship. I know you've mentored each one of us, I've never heard you say,

04:20:31.200 --> 04:20:36.160
[Guest]: hey, I'm doing this. So I don't want you to do the same thing, you would be as generous,

04:20:36.160 --> 04:20:42.160
[Guest]: you know, to someone who is launching the seen and the unseen part two versus, you know, someone

04:20:42.160 --> 04:20:46.560
[Guest]: who's doing something very remote from what you're doing, or someone who's doing it in a different

04:20:46.560 --> 04:20:52.720
[Guest]: language. And, and I think that policy podcast space, you know, at least I'm very grateful,

04:20:52.720 --> 04:20:58.160
[Guest]: and a lot of us are grateful that you exist. The other thing I think people are grateful for is

04:20:58.880 --> 04:21:05.440
[Guest]: the books, right? I mean, I watch this on Twitter all the time, there are people who have shelves

04:21:05.440 --> 04:21:09.920
[Guest]: in their homes, which are the seen and the unseen shelf, right? Which is all the book recommendations

04:21:09.920 --> 04:21:13.680
[Guest]: that they got from your show, and then they picked up those books, and they enjoyed reading it.

04:21:13.680 --> 04:21:17.840
[Guest]: And that, of course, creates this whole other ecosystem, whether it is, you know, publishers,

04:21:18.720 --> 04:21:24.160
[Guest]: I know many publishers are vying to get their next book launched on your show and things like that.

04:21:24.160 --> 04:21:27.520
[Guest]: But even book authors, you know, someone who spent a couple of years writing a book,

04:21:28.400 --> 04:21:33.840
[Guest]: the kind of very sympathetic and generous profiling you'll give, you know, like you said,

04:21:33.840 --> 04:21:39.440
[Guest]: you're not one of those literary festival spiels, where you talk to five people for 10 minutes,

04:21:39.440 --> 04:21:45.120
[Guest]: and they come with this programmed spiel about their book. This is a very different kind of

04:21:45.120 --> 04:21:50.160
[Guest]: conversation, whether it's profiling the author. So I think all of these things I am very grateful

04:21:50.160 --> 04:21:54.560
[Guest]: for, like there are so many books, I wouldn't have discovered, I never read as much history,

04:21:54.560 --> 04:21:58.960
[Guest]: you know, before I started listening to the show, it was more policy and economics and things like

04:21:58.960 --> 04:22:04.240
[Guest]: that. You know, I mean, something like, you know, I mean, Chitmai, of course, is an economist,

04:22:04.240 --> 04:22:08.000
[Guest]: so I would have, you know, read him, but something like Ira Mukherjee's book, right,

04:22:08.000 --> 04:22:13.120
[Guest]: would have not been anywhere on my radar, for instance, right, or the book with Anshul Malhotra

04:22:13.120 --> 04:22:16.640
[Guest]: on partition, right, I would have just, you know, thought, oh, this is a sentimental,

04:22:16.640 --> 04:22:22.560
[Guest]: sweet memoir sort of thing, you know, I'll read it later. And, and the way I have the discovery

04:22:22.560 --> 04:22:28.160
[Guest]: process is another thing I'm grateful for. It's not getting an annoying mailer. It is not a

04:22:28.160 --> 04:22:33.200
[Guest]: publisher, like bombarding you with things. It's someone really thoughtful, who is carefully

04:22:33.200 --> 04:22:38.560
[Guest]: putting this together, you know, for an entire community building out other ecosystems. So that's

04:22:38.560 --> 04:22:43.120
[Guest]: another thing I'm very grateful for, as far as your podcast is concerned. I'll just say a couple

04:22:43.120 --> 04:22:48.400
[Amit Varma]: of things. One is that, you know, it's, you make me sound like a great sort of philanthropist,

04:22:48.400 --> 04:22:52.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, doing so much for the world, but actually, it's all out of self interest, right.

04:22:52.240 --> 04:22:56.480
[Amit Varma]: And it's a great way of how self interest and altruism are really the same thing. They come

04:22:56.480 --> 04:23:03.120
[Amit Varma]: together. You know, when you have voluntary interactions, so so so yeah, it's not like a grand

04:23:03.120 --> 04:23:07.280
[Amit Varma]: plan, or that I'm going to do this, I'm going to do that I'm going to make people read more,

04:23:07.280 --> 04:23:11.920
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to do whatever, whatever that has happened has happened, you know, has been an

04:23:11.920 --> 04:23:18.160
[Amit Varma]: unseen and actually unforeseen effect. It has been organic has been an unforeseen effect of my just

04:23:18.160 --> 04:23:23.120
[Amit Varma]: following my own intellectual journey and my curiosities and kind of getting there. So I feel

04:23:23.120 --> 04:23:29.600
[Amit Varma]: as I feel blessed. And the other side of it is as far as helping others is concerned, is that I think

04:23:29.600 --> 04:23:34.560
[Amit Varma]: there was a time when I was much younger, when I might have been competitive about it. What helps

04:23:34.560 --> 04:23:40.960
[Amit Varma]: me not be competitive at all, is the sense that I am making something across time, which is,

04:23:40.960 --> 04:23:46.480
[Amit Varma]: I think, you know, and broadly, like I said, I'm also making the show for listeners of 30 years

04:23:46.480 --> 04:23:53.200
[Amit Varma]: later. And that approach is something I come to almost out of necessity. Because I think I have

04:23:53.200 --> 04:23:57.760
[Amit Varma]: realized that as far as the ways I think about the world and my ideas and all of that, it's

04:23:57.760 --> 04:24:03.360
[Amit Varma]: basically, you know, it's, it's, it's kind of a lonely road. And even in terms of success,

04:24:03.360 --> 04:24:08.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, I might not achieve any kind of success with anything I do immediately or in the short

04:24:08.880 --> 04:24:13.760
[Amit Varma]: run. That's the default attitude I've taken after all these years of doing whatever I have done,

04:24:13.760 --> 04:24:18.960
[Amit Varma]: because I have sort of been on the margins of every community I've been sort of involved with,

04:24:19.680 --> 04:24:24.560
[Amit Varma]: in a sense, and I'm used to people not taking me seriously. So I figured that, okay, I'm not going

04:24:24.560 --> 04:24:29.040
[Amit Varma]: to bother about all that and think about present day validation and riches and all of that. I'm

04:24:29.040 --> 04:24:32.880
[Amit Varma]: just going to do something I love. And maybe, you know, 30 years later, people can look back and

04:24:32.880 --> 04:24:37.440
[Amit Varma]: say, okay, these were great conversations. And I know that sounds very vain and arrogant for

04:24:37.440 --> 04:24:42.240
[Amit Varma]: anyone to imagine that he can create something of value, even for the present moment as an act of

04:24:42.240 --> 04:24:47.760
[Amit Varma]: arrogance. But to say that 30 years later, people will be listening to this or reading me is even

04:24:47.760 --> 04:24:55.280
[Amit Varma]: more so. But, you know, what do you do? That's what you do, right? So, no, I don't, I don't

04:24:55.280 --> 04:25:00.080
[Guest]: completely agree on this, probably because I've known you a long time. Even when there were real

04:25:00.080 --> 04:25:06.080
[Guest]: space constraints, like say, you know, columnness, you know, and things like that, whether you were

04:25:06.080 --> 04:25:11.760
[Guest]: a blogger, which was a little bit less constrained, I have seen this quality in you across all the

04:25:11.760 --> 04:25:17.040
[Guest]: things that you have done or engaged in, you immediately build a community, you reach out to

04:25:17.040 --> 04:25:21.680
[Guest]: other people doing the same thing, you encourage them, you have honest discussions about how to do

04:25:21.680 --> 04:25:27.520
[Guest]: it better, right? You you don't compete on those margins, you may, you may compete on quality,

04:25:27.520 --> 04:25:32.640
[Guest]: or, you know, making a better argument or writing a better post, but you've never really competed on

04:25:32.640 --> 04:25:37.360
[Guest]: those margins. I think so many of us got our first break, you're the first person who ever told me

04:25:37.360 --> 04:25:41.920
[Guest]: to write, you're the person who introduced me to Niranjan Rajyadheek, who was my first editor,

04:25:41.920 --> 04:25:46.800
[Guest]: who told me to write in a newspaper, and you know, so on and so forth. And I know I'm not the only

04:25:46.800 --> 04:25:52.800
[Guest]: one who has benefited either from that generosity or that mentorship. So I don't think I think this

04:25:52.800 --> 04:25:58.960
[Guest]: is something a little bit more inherent in your personality. I'm this is the last nice thing I'm

04:25:58.960 --> 04:26:03.280
[Amit Varma]: going to say. So you know, take it, you know, I remember, I remember, you know, Hamsini once

04:26:03.280 --> 04:26:08.000
[Amit Varma]: said something nice about me at one point in time. And I told her that she was committing the Salman

04:26:08.000 --> 04:26:12.720
[Amit Varma]: Khan fallacy. Have I told you about the Salman Khan fallacy? No, but I must suffer through it.

04:26:12.720 --> 04:26:16.480
[Amit Varma]: So go for it. Yeah, you must suffer through it. The Salman Khan fallacy is that just because

04:26:16.480 --> 04:26:21.760
[Amit Varma]: someone is nice to you, you imagine they're nice people. I didn't say you're a nice person. Yeah,

04:26:21.760 --> 04:26:32.960
[Unknown]: but I mean, no, no, no, no, no. For our listeners, Amit is very grumpy. Amit can be really like a

04:26:32.960 --> 04:26:40.800
[Guest]: annoying, grumpy, he can be very, very irritable about so many things. He lacks patience, he doesn't

04:26:40.800 --> 04:26:47.760
[Guest]: travel well. You know, he will complain about traffic and New York City restaurants. So yes,

04:26:47.760 --> 04:26:52.880
[Guest]: so the long list of things about how annoying Amit is and how he's not a very nice person exists.

04:26:52.880 --> 04:27:02.640
[Guest]: Having said that, no, but there is something very generous about you. And there is a great

04:27:02.640 --> 04:27:07.600
[Guest]: mentorship model that you have created. And this is not because you've been personally kind to me,

04:27:07.600 --> 04:27:12.240
[Guest]: it's because I know lots of people like me who benefited from it. It's a matter of creating

04:27:12.240 --> 04:27:17.360
[Guest]: an ecosystem. It's about creating a community. I think this community creation is underrated.

04:27:17.920 --> 04:27:22.480
[Guest]: You know, whether it is talking about the mailing lists you create, the WhatsApp groups that you've

04:27:22.480 --> 04:27:27.520
[Guest]: created, all of this, you've always brought people who I normally wouldn't have encountered and put

04:27:27.520 --> 04:27:32.240
[Guest]: us in a space together. That obviously also creates friction and we have arguments and

04:27:32.240 --> 04:27:36.160
[Guest]: intellectual disagreements. Sometimes we are complaining behind each other's backs,

04:27:36.160 --> 04:27:40.480
[Guest]: can you believe so-and-so wrote that or so-and-so said that on Twitter. But still,

04:27:40.480 --> 04:27:44.640
[Guest]: the value of creating that community and engagement is incredible. And I will give

04:27:44.640 --> 04:27:49.360
[Guest]: you credit for doing that. By the way, the most annoying thing about you is that you don't like

04:27:49.360 --> 04:27:55.760
[Amit Varma]: sugar. May I just put that out there? No, I don't like sugar at an abstract level. Sugar is poison,

04:27:55.760 --> 04:28:00.880
[Amit Varma]: I know that. But at a concrete level, I keep getting drawn back to it time and time again.

04:28:00.880 --> 04:28:05.760
[Amit Varma]: So you know, I had a very successful period on keto where I lost 20 kgs. But after that,

04:28:05.760 --> 04:28:10.960
[Amit Varma]: I went off keto and put back 22. So in fact, I've been sort of by the time you listen to this,

04:28:10.960 --> 04:28:16.000
[Amit Varma]: hopefully I'd be like at least a week into my new discipline routine. But then you know,

04:28:16.000 --> 04:28:20.880
[Amit Varma]: so there are, you know, people seem to think from my output that you must be so disciplined and all

04:28:20.880 --> 04:28:26.000
[Amit Varma]: of that. I'm just a freaking opposite. So... No, you are disciplined on certain

04:28:26.000 --> 04:28:29.680
[Guest]: intellectual margins. You have a lot of discipline when you write, when you teach,

04:28:29.680 --> 04:28:33.760
[Guest]: when you engage. I mean, those are incredible qualities. But you're also a very annoying person

04:28:33.760 --> 04:28:37.760
[Unknown]: to go to lunch with because you'll immediately talk about how many carbs there are in the

04:28:37.760 --> 04:28:42.480
[Amit Varma]: MTR masala dosa and things like that. Noted. I did eat all the MTR masala

04:28:42.480 --> 04:28:47.680
[Unknown]: dosas the last time we were at lunch. While complaining loudly instead of just

04:28:47.680 --> 04:28:53.360
[Unknown]: quietly enjoying the moment. We'll put a picture out, you know, maybe on Twitter or in the show

04:28:53.360 --> 04:28:58.240
[Unknown]: notes. There's a great photograph of this lovely event of, you know, Amit and me enjoying masala

04:28:58.240 --> 04:29:04.480
[Guest]: dosas just pre pandemic. We have reached the end. And I have three quick questions for you.

04:29:05.040 --> 04:29:10.560
[Guest]: These come from guests and fans. And I think, you know, they're, they're sort of like the perfect

04:29:10.560 --> 04:29:16.240
[Guest]: questions to end on. So I want you, you know, the first we're going back to Chinmay. Chinmay is like

04:29:16.240 --> 04:29:24.480
[Guest]: having this, you know, Salman Khan style stardom on this episode. Very much well deserved. But he

04:29:24.480 --> 04:29:29.520
[Guest]: asked another great question in addition to the first one. So, you know, let me play Chinmay's

04:29:29.520 --> 04:29:35.760
[Unknown]: question and everyone will know why when we discuss it. Hi Amit, this is Chinmay Tumbe here.

04:29:35.760 --> 04:29:41.120
[Unknown]: Congrats on your 200th episode. We all know how much you love TikTok. And so my question for you

04:29:41.120 --> 04:29:48.480
[Unknown]: is, if you had to record a TikTok video for 20 seconds, what would it be? Wow, fantastic question.

04:29:48.480 --> 04:29:54.480
[Guest]: There's so many different. Yeah. So let me first preface with Amit, as you all know, loves TikTok

04:29:54.480 --> 04:29:59.920
[Guest]: or, you know, before it got banned. And another lovely thing about Amit is he always knows what

04:29:59.920 --> 04:30:07.040
[Guest]: the future looks like and he's not at all snobbish or elitist or classist about it. He used to send

04:30:07.040 --> 04:30:11.760
[Guest]: me TikTok videos all the time. And at one point it was so many that I couldn't keep up with them.

04:30:11.760 --> 04:30:16.560
[Guest]: The first time he told me about TikTok, Amit sent me 45 videos on WhatsApp. And I was like,

04:30:16.560 --> 04:30:19.360
[Guest]: are you kidding me? You want me to watch all of them? And he said, yeah, this is going to be

04:30:19.360 --> 04:30:25.120
[Guest]: great for you. And it again, opened my mind into another subculture. So two things, you know,

04:30:25.120 --> 04:30:29.120
[Guest]: before you answer Chinmay's question, tell us a little bit about your fascination with TikTok

04:30:29.120 --> 04:30:34.240
[Guest]: and then tell us what TikTok video you would make. Yeah. So I'm glad you asked that first

04:30:34.240 --> 04:30:38.480
[Amit Varma]: question because it gives me some time to sort of get away from us answering the second one,

04:30:38.480 --> 04:30:43.120
[Amit Varma]: which I don't yet have an answer for. But no, my fascination for TikTok is because of,

04:30:44.160 --> 04:30:49.760
[Amit Varma]: I think, one, of course, the quality of the creativity within TikTok, if you look at it.

04:30:49.760 --> 04:30:54.400
[Amit Varma]: And two, I think it, like I taught a course called, I put together a course called TikTok

04:30:54.400 --> 04:30:58.320
[Amit Varma]: in Indian society. I taught only one batch of it because TikTok was banned by then. So there was

04:30:58.320 --> 04:31:02.640
[Amit Varma]: no way for, I mean, I had all the videos downloaded and I taught it on WhatsApp because that's the

04:31:02.640 --> 04:31:08.800
[Amit Varma]: only way to send people hundreds of vertical format videos. And then I decided no point

04:31:08.800 --> 04:31:13.440
[Amit Varma]: doing it again because people can't actually see TikTok. But the reason I was blown away for it

04:31:13.440 --> 04:31:19.920
[Amit Varma]: is that I think it gave a voice to people who did not otherwise have a voice before that.

04:31:19.920 --> 04:31:25.280
[Amit Varma]: Like, I think a couple of things happened in India simultaneously. One is that broadband

04:31:25.280 --> 04:31:31.040
[Amit Varma]: on smartphones became much more widespread, I won't say ubiquitous, became much more widespread

04:31:31.040 --> 04:31:35.680
[Amit Varma]: at a certain point in time, partly because of what Jio was doing. And forget Jio's means of

04:31:35.680 --> 04:31:40.720
[Amit Varma]: getting there and the cronyism that might or might not be involved. But the bottom line was that

04:31:40.720 --> 04:31:47.360
[Amit Varma]: broadband became much more accessible to many more people. And then along came an app which

04:31:47.360 --> 04:31:52.800
[Amit Varma]: actually empowered them by, you know, allowing them to showcase their own creativity. Now,

04:31:52.800 --> 04:31:58.160
[Amit Varma]: here's the thing. If you think of popular culture in India, you know, popular culture in India has

04:31:58.160 --> 04:32:02.800
[Amit Varma]: gatekeepers and is run by elites. For example, just take Bollywood. I mean, I know there are

04:32:02.800 --> 04:32:06.640
[Amit Varma]: film industries across the country. Let's take one of them. Let's take Bollywood, where if you

04:32:06.640 --> 04:32:10.960
[Amit Varma]: look at the, there are two different kinds of elites which dominate Bollywood today though

04:32:10.960 --> 04:32:15.600
[Amit Varma]: is gradually changing. And one is that old school elite who have their old school regressive

04:32:15.600 --> 04:32:19.920
[Amit Varma]: attitudes, which they bring into everything. And the other is perhaps their kids who have gone

04:32:19.920 --> 04:32:24.080
[Amit Varma]: abroad and studied and come back and they're like the woke elites and they've got a different

04:32:24.080 --> 04:32:28.960
[Amit Varma]: conception of what entertainment is and what they should do with it. But they're both out of touch

04:32:28.960 --> 04:32:33.760
[Amit Varma]: with the real India, which is not a judgment on either of them. But you know, they're in cities

04:32:33.760 --> 04:32:37.920
[Amit Varma]: and they've lived different lives and they're out of touch with the real India. And what TikTok did

04:32:37.920 --> 04:32:43.920
[Amit Varma]: was that it did, it changed this at two levels. One is that it allowed anyone to create anything

04:32:43.920 --> 04:32:49.760
[Amit Varma]: without a gatekeeper being there and put it up. Two, as consumers, it made them realize that

04:32:49.760 --> 04:32:55.040
[Amit Varma]: there is a world of entertainment out there on TikTok, which has not come through these gatekeepers

04:32:55.040 --> 04:33:00.720
[Amit Varma]: and which reflects their lives and their values and their struggles. And you see this in various

04:33:00.720 --> 04:33:07.040
[Amit Varma]: little niches, for example, the LGBTQI community, where you have an outpouring of incredible

04:33:07.040 --> 04:33:14.160
[Amit Varma]: creativity and self-assertion, confident self-assertion from them on TikTok, because suddenly

04:33:14.160 --> 04:33:19.840
[Amit Varma]: so many people realize that they are not alone, that there are so many others like themselves.

04:33:19.840 --> 04:33:24.320
[Amit Varma]: And it's one thing to be an English speaking, marginalized person in a city and to be able to

04:33:24.320 --> 04:33:29.440
[Amit Varma]: go on the internet and see people like yourself and connect with people like yourself. But if you

04:33:29.440 --> 04:33:34.240
[Amit Varma]: don't know English, if you're in a village somewhere or whatever, and you might feel that you are a

04:33:34.240 --> 04:33:38.480
[Amit Varma]: freak, it will affect your self-image and the way you live your life and all of that, which I think

04:33:38.480 --> 04:33:44.240
[Amit Varma]: was, you know, true for marginalized people over decades. And suddenly along comes this app and on

04:33:44.240 --> 04:33:49.040
[Amit Varma]: this app, you see that, you know, that you are not alone in a sense that there are people in identical

04:33:49.040 --> 04:33:55.040
[Amit Varma]: social conditions to yours and identical orientations to yours who are expressing

04:33:55.040 --> 04:34:01.520
[Amit Varma]: themselves powerfully and the kind of sort of create. And obviously, a lot of the creativity

04:34:01.520 --> 04:34:05.760
[Amit Varma]: is the lowest form of humor. There'll be puns and there'll be memes getting played out. But there's

04:34:05.760 --> 04:34:12.640
[Amit Varma]: also a lot of sophisticated humor. There's also a lot of heartbreaking stuff and some insane

04:34:12.640 --> 04:34:20.400
[Amit Varma]: creative talent on TikTok, like, my God, so good, you know, and then it got banned. And it's

04:34:20.400 --> 04:34:26.080
[Amit Varma]: such a tragedy. I feel like it's personal that it's, I mean, I just feel so sad about it. It's

04:34:26.080 --> 04:34:30.720
[Amit Varma]: horrible. And it also tells you the happenstance that if that particular app which worked like that

04:34:30.720 --> 04:34:34.480
[Amit Varma]: didn't come across at that particular time, this would not have happened. And now you've left them

04:34:34.480 --> 04:34:39.200
[Amit Varma]: high and dry again. But the question here for entrepreneurs and for people who, you know, feel

04:34:39.200 --> 04:34:45.600
[Amit Varma]: the way I do is that think of the unknown unknowns of the future, what are the ways in which you can

04:34:45.600 --> 04:34:50.400
[Amit Varma]: sort of fill some of these gaps that even people may not know exist, people in those gaps may not

04:34:50.400 --> 04:34:56.800
[Amit Varma]: know exist. And, you know, and there's so much hope for doing something there. And that moment

04:34:56.800 --> 04:35:03.440
[Guest]: is lost to us. I mean, it's weird to think of it in terms of gaps, right? Like, I mean, a gap exists

04:35:03.440 --> 04:35:08.320
[Guest]: if you know that there is a world that fits in a particular way. And, and there are things like

04:35:08.320 --> 04:35:12.320
[Guest]: Twitter, or, you know, initially, when people said 140 characters, well, you're going to tell

04:35:12.320 --> 04:35:17.120
[Guest]: them I got, you know, a macchiato today morning or something like that. Right. And then Twitter

04:35:17.120 --> 04:35:23.120
[Guest]: became this point of reference for everyone, it became something that can change elections,

04:35:23.120 --> 04:35:28.160
[Guest]: it can be some, it became something where that can lead to revolutions, because people know where to

04:35:28.160 --> 04:35:32.880
[Guest]: congregate on in the middle of the city or something like that. And it's just become this

04:35:32.880 --> 04:35:39.040
[Guest]: extraordinary platform, right. And I think TikTok did something similar. And it goes to show how

04:35:39.040 --> 04:35:45.920
[Guest]: powerful it was, if the biggest threat you can be to the Chinese is to take away a massive audience

04:35:45.920 --> 04:35:52.800
[Guest]: or consumer base from TikTok, then you know how, how much it penetrated and how powerful it was.

04:35:52.800 --> 04:35:56.720
[Amit Varma]: And I don't think the ban was even well thought out in political terms, because this base was not

04:35:56.720 --> 04:36:02.000
[Amit Varma]: a threat to Modiji. This was kind of part of his base. You know, like there were stories after TikTok

04:36:02.000 --> 04:36:08.080
[Amit Varma]: was banned, I think Shortik Biswas did a story on BBC and he, I think we chatted that morning,

04:36:08.080 --> 04:36:12.720
[Amit Varma]: because he took a quote from me and Shortik pointed out how all the TikTok creators he had

04:36:12.720 --> 04:36:17.840
[Amit Varma]: spoken to were actually confident it would be repealed because they were fans of Modiji. And

04:36:17.840 --> 04:36:23.600
[Amit Varma]: they said, okay, he'll repeal it. But the other point that I kind of want to make here is that

04:36:23.600 --> 04:36:28.000
[Amit Varma]: the loss is not just that a niche is not being served, but that it is not being discovered.

04:36:28.000 --> 04:36:31.920
[Amit Varma]: Like one of the points I make in my podcasting course about the difference between radio and

04:36:31.920 --> 04:36:37.360
[Amit Varma]: podcasting is that because radio out of necessity has to be so broad, that not only can it not

04:36:37.360 --> 04:36:41.680
[Amit Varma]: serve certain niches, they don't even discover those niches and those niches don't discover

04:36:41.680 --> 04:36:46.800
[Amit Varma]: themselves. And you see, for example, in the newsletter, if you go to the top paid newsletters

04:36:46.800 --> 04:36:51.360
[Amit Varma]: at Substack, and you'll see so many niches being covered there that Bill Bishop is doing

04:36:51.360 --> 04:36:56.160
[Amit Varma]: cynicism, which is a newsletter on China, and it is such a huge hit and is making him so much money

04:36:56.160 --> 04:37:00.400
[Amit Varma]: and who would have thought that niche existed. Emily Oster is, you know, doing the economics

04:37:00.400 --> 04:37:04.720
[Amit Varma]: of parenthood and pregnancy and all of that. And that's a hugely popular newsletter. And there is

04:37:04.720 --> 04:37:09.360
[Amit Varma]: that niche, you know, even the seen and the unseen serves a particular kind of niche. If I had to

04:37:09.360 --> 04:37:13.840
[Amit Varma]: apply for a license for a podcast, and I told someone I'm going to do three hour interviews

04:37:13.840 --> 04:37:18.640
[Amit Varma]: with intellectuals who write obscure books, like no way, man, it's crazy. I myself would have thought

04:37:18.640 --> 04:37:23.600
[Amit Varma]: it was crazy, crazy. I discovered it by the serendipity of just get being able to do it in

04:37:23.600 --> 04:37:29.440
[Amit Varma]: the technology existing. And I think tiktok served some of that. Yeah. And now I'm not going to let

04:37:29.440 --> 04:37:34.640
[Amit Varma]: you weasel your way out of Chinmay's question. Chinmay's question if I had to do? I don't know,

04:37:34.640 --> 04:37:41.200
[Amit Varma]: man. I've never actually thought about it. Because tiktok is the one sort of medium where I was just

04:37:41.200 --> 04:37:46.720
[Amit Varma]: a pure consumer. I never fantasized about doing something on it. So I have, I have no idea if

04:37:46.720 --> 04:37:53.680
[Amit Varma]: tiktok existed, I would take it up as a challenge and maybe do something. And maybe fulfill Ram

04:37:53.680 --> 04:38:00.960
[Amit Varma]: Guha's request as well and do something on Rajaji. I can't, you know, nothing really comes to mind,

04:38:00.960 --> 04:38:05.600
[Amit Varma]: I guess I'd pick up an existing meme and subvert it in some way and just kind of run with that.

04:38:05.600 --> 04:38:09.440
[Amit Varma]: But I think the thing with tiktok, if I were to start a channel just thinking aloud,

04:38:09.440 --> 04:38:13.680
[Amit Varma]: I think I'd start off doing mundane, boring things, which in retrospect would seem horrible.

04:38:13.680 --> 04:38:18.240
[Amit Varma]: But then over a period of time, it would evolve. And it would probably be my 100 video,

04:38:18.240 --> 04:38:23.760
[Amit Varma]: which would be nice. And my 3000 video, which which would be incredible. And then I would get

04:38:23.760 --> 04:38:28.400
[Guest]: into my groove. So I'm surprised you didn't mention your limerick. I thought that would

04:38:28.400 --> 04:38:32.960
[Guest]: have been perfect for tiktok, right? The limericks that you used to write for Times of India,

04:38:32.960 --> 04:38:37.600
[Guest]: they're almost like crafted for that 20 second video, they have humor,

04:38:37.600 --> 04:38:42.480
[Guest]: they are current, they are political. You don't think that's a good fit? That's just

04:38:42.480 --> 04:38:46.080
[Amit Varma]: completely different. That's kind of you, but they're English. And I don't think that's a

04:38:46.080 --> 04:38:49.840
[Amit Varma]: good fit. I think I'd find out, you know, with my creativity, I'd figure out things to do.

04:38:50.400 --> 04:38:55.360
[Amit Varma]: But I never even thought about it. Because it and also anybody who gets on tiktok,

04:38:55.360 --> 04:39:00.000
[Amit Varma]: their first few videos will always be shit, even the best creators. It's after a period of time

04:39:00.000 --> 04:39:04.160
[Amit Varma]: that you begin to find moments of magic. And I say moments of magic, because tiktok has just

04:39:04.160 --> 04:39:10.080
[Amit Varma]: given me so many moments of transcendent magic and just watching something over and over again

04:39:10.080 --> 04:39:15.200
[Amit Varma]: and saying, like, WTF, like, I have not seen anything like this anywhere else.

04:39:15.200 --> 04:39:20.160
[Guest]: Yeah, for me, the dancing, I mean, the humor and the dancing were the two things which I was

04:39:20.160 --> 04:39:24.960
[Guest]: astounded by one that people could actually move like that. And that, you know, I mean,

04:39:24.960 --> 04:39:30.400
[Guest]: Indian humor is very specific, right? It's not like your typical American stand up comedy humor.

04:39:30.400 --> 04:39:33.840
[Guest]: Some of it, as you mentioned, is quite misogynistic, it can be quite regressive.

04:39:33.840 --> 04:39:39.680
[Guest]: But a lot of the humor there, like some of the satire was just really high quality.

04:39:40.960 --> 04:39:47.440
[Guest]: The other thing you can potentially do on tiktok is tell PJs because you specialize in PJs.

04:39:47.440 --> 04:39:52.720
[Guest]: It is entirely my quality control that no such terrible PJs have occurred on this

04:39:54.000 --> 04:39:57.760
[Unknown]: on this episode. And I say occurred because they are like a disaster.

04:39:57.760 --> 04:40:04.480
[Amit Varma]: No, if I do a video of me telling a PJ, I would you would find me instructing a pajama. See,

04:40:04.480 --> 04:40:07.360
[Amit Varma]: are you happy now? This is what you do. This is what you asked for.

04:40:07.360 --> 04:40:10.480
[Amit Varma]: Let's let's move on to the next question. And apologies to Tinmay.

04:40:10.480 --> 04:40:14.640
[Amit Varma]: If tiktok is ever back in India, I promise that just for Chinmay, I'll

04:40:14.640 --> 04:40:16.560
[Unknown]: make a video of some sort and show him.

04:40:16.560 --> 04:40:21.600
[Guest]: Okay, the next question is probably your big from your biggest fan ever.

04:40:21.600 --> 04:40:27.440
[Guest]: This is Vinayak on Twitter, right? And I know him only from Twitter. He

04:40:27.440 --> 04:40:33.920
[Guest]: absolutely loves your show. I think he he even sometimes beats you before you manage to,

04:40:34.640 --> 04:40:41.120
[Guest]: you know, release the show online and things like that. He's also just really wonderful,

04:40:41.120 --> 04:40:46.240
[Guest]: very engaged, very spirited person on Twitter. I love engaging with him.

04:40:46.240 --> 04:40:50.080
[Guest]: So this is Vinayak's question to you.

04:40:50.080 --> 04:40:53.280
[Unknown]: Question to you. Hi, Mitza. Hi, Shruti.

04:40:54.320 --> 04:40:59.840
[Unknown]: I want to thank you for enriching my life and lives of many other unseen listeners of the show.

04:41:00.880 --> 04:41:04.240
[Unknown]: So many of my great moments in recent times have been from engaging with you

04:41:04.240 --> 04:41:10.080
[Unknown]: and learning from you. So I'd like to know what is the best moment of your life. Also,

04:41:10.800 --> 04:41:16.960
[Unknown]: I have a request. Can you start a publication community like Yashas Persuasion

04:41:16.960 --> 04:41:21.200
[Unknown]: and persuade all the intellectuals from the podcast to come together for the project?

04:41:22.640 --> 04:41:27.840
[Unknown]: And finally, please never stop making episodes for seen and unseen. Thank you.

04:41:28.720 --> 04:41:31.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's that's a really nice question and a nice sentiment. And

04:41:32.560 --> 04:41:36.960
[Amit Varma]: Vinayak is a pseudonym. I do happen to know his real name, but he's got reasons for why he

04:41:36.960 --> 04:41:41.920
[Amit Varma]: calls himself Vinayak. So we shall respect that and call him Vinayak as well. And often I have

04:41:41.920 --> 04:41:46.960
[Amit Varma]: found that he has retweeted a tweet of mine before I have even tweeted it. It almost feels like that

04:41:46.960 --> 04:41:52.800
[Amit Varma]: he is so incredibly prompt. Best moment of my life? I don't really know. I have sort of now

04:41:53.360 --> 04:41:58.480
[Amit Varma]: one our memory is sort of tainted by who we become at any particular point in time. So

04:41:58.480 --> 04:42:04.480
[Amit Varma]: we look at memories differently. And do I have come to the point where I have learned to

04:42:04.480 --> 04:42:10.640
[Amit Varma]: consciously think about taking joy from small things. So the best moment in my life might have

04:42:10.640 --> 04:42:14.480
[Amit Varma]: been a little thing that happened today, for example. So it's really hard to say.

04:42:15.360 --> 04:42:21.440
[Amit Varma]: But as he's the Kachori, but as he's gone to the effort of asking the question.

04:42:23.680 --> 04:42:27.440
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I won't go into the personal happy moments because I like to keep the personal

04:42:27.440 --> 04:42:33.040
[Amit Varma]: out of the podcast and all of that. So I'll leave that aside. But apart from that, you know,

04:42:33.040 --> 04:42:38.240
[Amit Varma]: I think winning the two Bastia prizes was great, especially because I had friends around me when I

04:42:38.240 --> 04:42:43.200
[Amit Varma]: won them. And the second time I got to celebrate with you and Nandu and Yazad and all the other

04:42:44.000 --> 04:42:50.960
[Amit Varma]: friends who were there. But I don't, I don't know. I think that somehow, you know,

04:42:52.320 --> 04:42:58.480
[Amit Varma]: how does one even define happiness? It's, you know, and does happiness exist when you

04:42:58.480 --> 04:43:04.320
[Amit Varma]: consciously think about a moment and you say, I am happy now? If you just experience it without

04:43:04.320 --> 04:43:10.880
[Amit Varma]: without classifying it like that, is it happiness? Can there be, for example, the quiet happiness of

04:43:10.880 --> 04:43:16.560
[Amit Varma]: enjoying a sunset without my thinking about it and therefore classifying it as a happy moment?

04:43:17.120 --> 04:43:22.560
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, so there are, as usual, I've got a little meta and ask these meta questions. So

04:43:23.200 --> 04:43:27.840
[Amit Varma]: I don't really know, maybe happiness is would be personal moments that I wouldn't want to share

04:43:27.840 --> 04:43:35.360
[Amit Varma]: here. But, you know, even in terms of my sort of professional career or whatever, I don't know,

04:43:35.360 --> 04:43:40.880
[Amit Varma]: it's very hard to say. And, you know, I know that tomorrow, I'm going to regret this. And I'll think,

04:43:40.880 --> 04:43:44.880
[Amit Varma]: oh, I should have given this answer. And you, of course, did not give me time to prepare

04:43:45.520 --> 04:43:51.760
[Amit Varma]: answer as much as I do to so many of my guests, they could say, so this is a sweet revenge.

04:43:51.760 --> 04:43:56.880
[Guest]: I think there's a trade off between being genuinely surprised and spontaneous and being

04:43:56.880 --> 04:44:02.800
[Guest]: very prepared. Let me rephrase, you know, when I expressed a little bit differently, maybe I

04:44:02.800 --> 04:44:08.240
[Guest]: don't know if you want to put pressure on yourself for that one single happy moment when you know,

04:44:08.240 --> 04:44:12.720
[Guest]: something like the Bastiat prize, especially the second time stands out. But what I've noticed

04:44:12.720 --> 04:44:18.800
[Guest]: about you is that you're a really grumpy, irritable, introverted person who wants to

04:44:18.800 --> 04:44:24.560
[Guest]: complain about everything. But it's the smallest things that make you happy. Right? I mean,

04:44:24.560 --> 04:44:31.120
[Guest]: you get really happy if you eat good luchi at O'Calcutta and break your keto diet. Or you get

04:44:31.120 --> 04:44:35.680
[Guest]: really happy if you've read a beautiful poem. And you're like, oh, my God, this was amazing.

04:44:35.680 --> 04:44:40.320
[Guest]: Or you get really happy if you've had a fantastic class or workshop and someone said amazing and

04:44:40.320 --> 04:44:43.840
[Guest]: something amazing in that class. And you're like, that made me think or you know, like that

04:44:43.840 --> 04:44:48.720
[Guest]: conversation with Karthika that you mentioned at the top of the show. So what I've noticed is that

04:44:48.720 --> 04:44:54.400
[Guest]: I have observed about your happiness is that it's very spontaneous and fleeting. And it's always in

04:44:54.400 --> 04:44:59.600
[Guest]: the little things. It's not in like some grand prize and design and things like that. You're

04:44:59.600 --> 04:45:06.800
[Guest]: quite a happy person in everyday life, despite your middle aged grumbling. Yeah, that's a middle

04:45:06.800 --> 04:45:12.400
[Amit Varma]: aged grumbling is a nice description. I'd say I broadly have a pessimistic view of the world in

04:45:12.400 --> 04:45:16.960
[Amit Varma]: the sense that life has no meaning and we're all going to die. And that's it. But within that,

04:45:16.960 --> 04:45:20.480
[Amit Varma]: therefore, how do you cope with that? What is your coping mechanism? Maybe at some point,

04:45:20.480 --> 04:45:25.920
[Amit Varma]: the coping mechanism doesn't work. But right now, it would be to, you know, just find joy in your

04:45:25.920 --> 04:45:31.280
[Amit Varma]: work and happiness in the small things. I mean, I'm sounding very much like a self help guru and

04:45:31.280 --> 04:45:35.680
[Amit Varma]: all of that now. And I'm also sounding I'm sure incredibly ungrateful to all the people who've

04:45:35.680 --> 04:45:42.640
[Amit Varma]: given me happy moments that I don't think of those or they don't kind of automatically come to mind.

04:45:42.640 --> 04:45:46.320
[Amit Varma]: But I mean, conceptually, what is happy, I can look back on a memory that has happened and

04:45:46.320 --> 04:45:51.920
[Amit Varma]: classify it in retrospect as happy, even if in that particular moment, it might have been some

04:45:51.920 --> 04:45:57.120
[Amit Varma]: other elation, such as an unseemly pride or whatever, going through me. I mean, memory is

04:45:57.120 --> 04:46:01.760
[Amit Varma]: a strange thing, right? Like, you know, the way memory works is, and of course, I discussed memory

04:46:01.760 --> 04:46:06.480
[Amit Varma]: in great detail in with Anshul in the episode I did with her, which another episode I enjoyed a

04:46:06.480 --> 04:46:11.280
[Amit Varma]: lot. But, you know, memory strange in the sense that the way our brain works is that the first

04:46:11.280 --> 04:46:15.280
[Amit Varma]: time we remember, remember something, we remember it. But the second time we remember it, we are

04:46:15.280 --> 04:46:21.920
[Amit Varma]: remembering the remembering. And across time, therefore, memory becomes fiction. It becomes

04:46:21.920 --> 04:46:26.480
[Amit Varma]: fiction. So in that sense, and we are inventing our own fiction and adding to it as we go along.

04:46:26.480 --> 04:46:32.880
[Amit Varma]: So in that sense, I can I can look back on past events on my life as either happy or unhappy in

04:46:32.880 --> 04:46:38.400
[Amit Varma]: retrospect. And maybe then that happiness that I remember is a happiness now of remembering it,

04:46:38.400 --> 04:46:43.600
[Amit Varma]: which makes this the happy moment, rather than that itself. Okay, you're a terrible guest on

04:46:43.600 --> 04:46:49.120
[Unknown]: your own show. We can't get a straight answer out of you. Everything becomes very meta, meta,

04:46:49.120 --> 04:46:55.280
[Unknown]: meta. And so I'm just yeah, I'm you're a terrible, terrible guest. I'm glad you picked the job of

04:46:55.280 --> 04:47:00.240
[Amit Varma]: the host. You know, I'll tell you something. Meta is the only damn thing I'm good at.

04:47:06.640 --> 04:47:10.560
[Amit Varma]: So and now to move on to Vinayak's second question, which was about why don't I start a

04:47:10.560 --> 04:47:17.200
[Amit Varma]: publication like Yashamong's Persuasion? It's you know, so I was editor of Pragati, which is a

04:47:18.080 --> 04:47:22.640
[Amit Varma]: magazine of ideas and policy and whatever. And one of the problems with something like that is

04:47:23.600 --> 04:47:29.280
[Amit Varma]: just finding enough writers that do we have such a rich ecosystem full of intellectuals where

04:47:29.280 --> 04:47:34.720
[Amit Varma]: you can get enough content out regularly? And, you know, and if I were to make a list of just

04:47:34.720 --> 04:47:38.320
[Amit Varma]: a guest on my show, the answer would seem like yes, but then you have to get them to write

04:47:38.320 --> 04:47:44.880
[Amit Varma]: regularly and all of that. And it just didn't feel at that time, like it would be worthwhile,

04:47:44.880 --> 04:47:49.120
[Amit Varma]: maybe when the ecosystem is richer, maybe 20 years later, or 10 years later, maybe someone

04:47:49.120 --> 04:47:53.920
[Amit Varma]: could do that. But if I were to do that, I think that there's a danger that it would just fizzle

04:47:53.920 --> 04:47:59.840
[Amit Varma]: out that they wouldn't be that I'd be working much harder than I would like to, to try and

04:47:59.840 --> 04:48:06.640
[Amit Varma]: get people to write for it. And there just wouldn't be enough of them. And I think that that's kind of

04:48:06.640 --> 04:48:11.440
[Amit Varma]: the thing with the intellectual ecosystem. That is one thing that you know, people can have the

04:48:11.440 --> 04:48:15.840
[Amit Varma]: generosity to come on my show for three hours and have a relaxed conversation and all that.

04:48:15.840 --> 04:48:20.960
[Amit Varma]: But actually writing and then writing regularly is a whole different ballgame. So just speaking

04:48:20.960 --> 04:48:28.320
[Amit Varma]: from my own experience of trying to do a version of it, it's difficult. I have had various ideas

04:48:28.320 --> 04:48:33.360
[Amit Varma]: at times for media startups in the sense that I think that the way people consume and discover

04:48:33.360 --> 04:48:37.840
[Amit Varma]: content in India has changed radically over the last 10 years and no publication mainstream or

04:48:37.840 --> 04:48:41.760
[Amit Varma]: otherwise gets it. So I've often thought that why don't I try to fill the gap and

04:48:42.640 --> 04:48:47.600
[Amit Varma]: do interesting things, but I just don't have the appetite to be an entrepreneur. And the thing is,

04:48:47.600 --> 04:48:51.840
[Amit Varma]: everything has an opportunity cost. The scene in the unseen takes some time and I want to get down

04:48:51.840 --> 04:48:57.680
[Amit Varma]: to writing books, which is what I'm trying to do now. And you know, which is the one thing I've

04:48:57.680 --> 04:49:01.440
[Amit Varma]: always wanted to do. And if I don't do more of that, I'll sort of that's the one thing I'll

04:49:01.440 --> 04:49:06.560
[Amit Varma]: regret. So that's what I'm trying to get down to. So I'm not sure I really have the time and that,

04:49:07.200 --> 04:49:11.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, yeah, so that that's kind of a short answer. And as to the third thing,

04:49:11.360 --> 04:49:15.680
[Amit Varma]: when I said that, he hopes I keep doing it forever. Look, I love doing it. So I'll keep

04:49:15.680 --> 04:49:21.280
[Amit Varma]: doing it for as long as I can. But, you know, one doesn't even live forever. So who is to say?

04:49:21.280 --> 04:49:27.280
[Guest]: Now we are finally I promise the listeners at the very end. And here is the last question.

04:49:27.280 --> 04:49:32.320
[Guest]: And it's quite fitting. It's from one of our mutual friends, Mohit Satyanand. We talked about,

04:49:32.320 --> 04:49:38.320
[Guest]: you know, the that voice or a great voice is not important for podcast the way it is for radio.

04:49:38.880 --> 04:49:43.600
[Guest]: But Mohit is one of those people. I mean, he's an incredible person and entrepreneur,

04:49:43.600 --> 04:49:49.200
[Guest]: just such a kind, wonderful person and mentor, but has the most remarkable voice,

04:49:49.200 --> 04:49:55.360
[Guest]: which is completely wasted in his day job in his regular life. And I feel like, you know,

04:49:55.360 --> 04:50:00.960
[Guest]: he could read, I don't know the yellow pages and, and it would still be amazing to listen to him.

04:50:01.760 --> 04:50:06.000
[Guest]: So here's Mohit's question. And you are going to complain I didn't give you more time,

04:50:06.000 --> 04:50:08.160
[Guest]: but for what it's worth, here it is.

04:50:08.880 --> 04:50:11.920
[Unknown]: Amit, how would you like your epitaph to read?

04:50:13.440 --> 04:50:18.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah. Mohit is, of course, a dear friend. I almost think of him as family in a sense,

04:50:18.880 --> 04:50:25.360
[Amit Varma]: like when I go to Delhi, I stay over at Mohit and Premi's place and just I have great love for him.

04:50:25.920 --> 04:50:30.240
[Amit Varma]: He asked me this question on WhatsApp a few days ago, by the way. And it's not such a difficult

04:50:30.240 --> 04:50:34.240
[Amit Varma]: question to answer because and the answer will seem like a cop out. But it's a genuine answer

04:50:34.240 --> 04:50:42.320
[Amit Varma]: that I don't care. I mean, I'll be gone. So what difference does it make what my epitaph

04:50:43.360 --> 04:50:46.960
[Amit Varma]: reads? I mean, I don't have the vanities of leaving a legacy and all and this might seem

04:50:46.960 --> 04:50:51.200
[Amit Varma]: at odds with what I said earlier about creating a show for 30 years later and all of that. But

04:50:51.200 --> 04:50:56.480
[Amit Varma]: it gives me pleasure to think that I'm sort of, I might be able to create that kind of content.

04:50:56.480 --> 04:51:01.200
[Amit Varma]: But once you're gone, you're gone. So it doesn't really matter. You know, the thing is,

04:51:01.840 --> 04:51:08.240
[Amit Varma]: I don't anymore have the vanities that I did as a much younger person that I will imagine that I

04:51:08.240 --> 04:51:13.280
[Amit Varma]: can change the world in some way or that my ideas have great meaning or resonance or whatever.

04:51:13.280 --> 04:51:19.040
[Amit Varma]: So I don't know, I'm kind of, I'm kind of pessimistic about, you know, any epitaph. It's

04:51:19.040 --> 04:51:23.440
[Amit Varma]: just, you know, one does what one does. But I think you're thinking of it too literally,

04:51:23.440 --> 04:51:27.040
[Guest]: right? An epitaph has two purposes. One, of course, it's you're leaving something behind

04:51:27.040 --> 04:51:31.840
[Guest]: in the world to be remembered by and things like that. The other is, it's also a very pithy way

04:51:31.840 --> 04:51:38.640
[Guest]: of summing up a very rich, large, fulfilled life. So I will ask you Mohit's question from the

04:51:38.640 --> 04:51:43.440
[Guest]: second point of view, not from a point of view of vanity, but like, what would you want to be known

04:51:43.440 --> 04:51:48.960
[Guest]: for? What would you like the life to add up to? Okay, tough question. Like you said, no preparation.

04:51:48.960 --> 04:51:53.440
[Amit Varma]: There are different aspects to it. I mean, one can break it down and say that what would you,

04:51:53.440 --> 04:51:57.520
[Amit Varma]: like the way you phrased it, what would you like to be remembered for? Or the other way of looking

04:51:57.520 --> 04:52:02.000
[Amit Varma]: at it is like, what would you have liked to achieve, have achieved in your own life? Like

04:52:02.000 --> 04:52:07.200
[Amit Varma]: if I am on my deathbed and I look back, what is my epitaph to myself? And the thing is, the answers

04:52:07.200 --> 04:52:12.960
[Amit Varma]: would be completely different. And in the first case, at some level, when people look back,

04:52:12.960 --> 04:52:18.000
[Amit Varma]: it's fleeting. Yeah. You know, maybe as someone who, you know, engaged with the world with

04:52:18.000 --> 04:52:23.840
[Amit Varma]: intellectual honesty, or made people think about the world a little differently. That would be

04:52:23.840 --> 04:52:28.960
[Amit Varma]: nice. You know, the things I want to be remembered for are things that I want to go ahead and do,

04:52:28.960 --> 04:52:33.680
[Amit Varma]: such as in the books I write, and not anything that I have done yet. So if you're expecting me

04:52:33.680 --> 04:52:39.760
[Amit Varma]: to say that in someone who had great conversations on a podcast, that's not my answer. I'm very happy

04:52:39.760 --> 04:52:44.960
[Amit Varma]: to have done this. But I don't think it's that memorable that people will remember. It's not

04:52:44.960 --> 04:52:50.560
[Amit Varma]: the iconic status of econ talk, for example, 750 episodes or whatever. But even otherwise,

04:52:50.560 --> 04:52:55.040
[Amit Varma]: I, you know, what one would like to do in an ideal world is that you want to sort of

04:52:56.400 --> 04:53:02.640
[Amit Varma]: let your ideas reach far and wide, you know, the way Bastia's ideas reach me,

04:53:02.640 --> 04:53:08.400
[Amit Varma]: but it is such vanity to expect to have that kind of an impact on people. And also, I grew

04:53:08.400 --> 04:53:14.160
[Amit Varma]: less and less hopeful of that happening. But I want to sort of increase the probability of that

04:53:14.160 --> 04:53:19.440
[Amit Varma]: happening by at least doing everything I can to that end, which involves writing the books and

04:53:19.440 --> 04:53:27.440
[Amit Varma]: continuing this podcast, so that when I can others can enjoy listening to it. So I guess that's it.

04:53:27.440 --> 04:53:32.960
[Amit Varma]: I mean, this is just, you know, I don't know. What's your answer, dude? To my epitaph? Yeah.

04:53:32.960 --> 04:53:39.520
[Guest]: Or your epitaph? No, to your epitaph. It's a good question. See, and I did have lead time. See,

04:53:40.720 --> 04:53:46.240
[Guest]: I think my epitaph is gonna say something like, tell your dog I said hi. You know, it's gonna be

04:53:46.240 --> 04:53:52.400
[Guest]: something very simple, something that brings me joy. You know, this is the perfect spot for your

04:53:52.400 --> 04:53:59.840
[Guest]: dog to be. That's probably what the tombstone and the epitaph is worth, if I was being facetious.

04:53:59.840 --> 04:54:05.600
[Guest]: But it would be something really simple. I don't, I mean, I certainly don't think of myself as like

04:54:05.600 --> 04:54:11.520
[Guest]: a public intellectual of your caliber or anything like that. But I think, you know, the, the

04:54:11.520 --> 04:54:16.800
[Guest]: bigness and the richness of my life is always in the personal, you know, that, you know, you know,

04:54:16.800 --> 04:54:22.480
[Guest]: enough about me and my life and my private life and my family to know that. So it would probably

04:54:22.480 --> 04:54:29.040
[Guest]: be something very, very personal, like here lies Cole and Trane's human mom, you know,

04:54:29.040 --> 04:54:33.440
[Amit Varma]: Cole and Trane, by the way, for the benefit of the listeners are her dogs. And she is, of course,

04:54:33.440 --> 04:54:36.320
[Amit Varma]: a big fan of John Coltrane. Maybe you should get a cat called John.

04:54:38.480 --> 04:54:44.640
[Guest]: Yeah. I think we are enough of a zoo right now. You know, I think that there's there's enough

04:54:44.640 --> 04:54:50.240
[Guest]: people in this in this apartment of multiple species. I think we're done for a while. Once

04:54:50.240 --> 04:54:55.680
[Guest]: we're done housebreaking the new puppy, maybe we'll think about, you know, other animals.

04:54:55.680 --> 04:54:59.120
[Amit Varma]: I think my epitaph could easily be finally we are done with the bad jokes.

04:55:01.120 --> 04:55:08.320
[Guest]: No, I think the amount you have griped about not writing your novel, it should say something like

04:55:08.320 --> 04:55:14.000
[Amit Varma]: herein lies many manuscripts. Yeah, I hope not because I hope to get some of them out.

04:55:14.000 --> 04:55:21.360
[Amit Varma]: So I really hope not. But that's really the only thing that I will regret if I don't do.

04:55:21.360 --> 04:55:27.120
[Amit Varma]: And that's, you know, the one thing I should have done. I mean, the scene in the unseen

04:55:27.120 --> 04:55:31.520
[Amit Varma]: just kind of happened accidentally. And I'm glad it happened. But you know,

04:55:31.520 --> 04:55:35.840
[Guest]: you're incredibly young, right? Like you could write lots of novels. It's not like you're an

04:55:35.840 --> 04:55:40.800
[Guest]: old person and you're dying. And we're actually discussing your epitaph. Like get to work, dude.

04:55:40.800 --> 04:55:45.840
[Amit Varma]: I know. Why did Mohit ask that question? It's very sad. Yeah, though I am just a little short

04:55:45.840 --> 04:55:51.360
[Amit Varma]: of the ages when my two heroes Bastia and Orville both died. But I hope to continue for another.

04:55:51.360 --> 04:55:56.400
[Guest]: They didn't have the benefit of modern medicine or the hockey stick prosperity that you have

04:55:56.400 --> 04:56:01.600
[Amit Varma]: been part of. Listen, I would love to give Vinayak 2000 more episodes of the scene in the unseen.

04:56:01.600 --> 04:56:07.760
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, so yeah, so that's what one aims for. You try to live the sort of you try to look

04:56:07.760 --> 04:56:11.120
[Amit Varma]: after yourself, the world can be going to hell, as I said earlier, but you try to look after

04:56:11.120 --> 04:56:18.320
[Amit Varma]: yourself the best that you can and do work that kind of makes you happy, which could be an epitaph

04:56:18.320 --> 04:56:23.440
[Guest]: also, I guess. Yeah, thank you for doing this, Amit. Thank you for letting me take over your show.

04:56:24.240 --> 04:56:30.640
[Guest]: This was the scene and the unseen from, you know, Amit as a guest and someone else as a host.

04:56:30.640 --> 04:56:37.440
[Guest]: I must say that you're a terrible guest. Because you you find it very difficult to answer questions

04:56:37.440 --> 04:56:43.840
[Guest]: and I find it very hard to pin you down. But on the other hand, you're a fantastic host. So you

04:56:43.840 --> 04:56:49.200
[Guest]: so you chose the profession correctly. And thank you for doing this. And thank you for giving us

